    ("What does it mean to be a U.S. citizen? Do kids count or only grown-ups?", "Being a U.S. citizen means you are a legal member of the United States, officially recognized by the government, with certain rights and responsibilities. Citizens have rights like living and working anywhere in the U.S., getting a U.S. passport, asking the government for help when abroad, and being protected by U.S. laws; they also have responsibilities like following the laws, paying taxes, and (for men) registering for Selective Service when they turn 18, and many citizens can vote in elections once they are 18. Kids absolutely count as U.S. citizens if they meet the rules, because citizenship is a legal status, not something you ‚Äúearn‚Äù by being an adult: many people are citizens from birth if they are born in the United States (with a few special exceptions, such as children of certain foreign diplomats), and some are citizens at birth if they are born abroad to U.S.-citizen parent(s) and meet legal requirements. People who were not citizens at birth can become citizens later through naturalization, which is a process that generally requires being an adult (usually 18 or older), meeting residency and other requirements, and taking an oath; children can sometimes become citizens automatically when a parent naturalizes and the child is a permanent resident living with that parent. So, both children and grown-ups can be U.S. citizens, but voting and some other civic actions are only for adults."),

