    ("Is this sentence correct grammar: ‚ÄúMe and my friend went to the park.‚Äù If not, how do I fix it?", "The sentence is understandable, but in formal English it‚Äôs considered incorrect because ‚Äúme‚Äù is an object pronoun and you need a subject pronoun in the subject position, so the standard correction is ‚ÄúMy friend and I went to the park.‚Äù A quick way to check is to remove the other person: you would say ‚ÄúI went to the park,‚Äù not ‚ÄúMe went to the park,‚Äù which shows why ‚ÄúI‚Äù is correct; also, many style guides prefer putting yourself second (‚Äúmy friend and I‚Äù) in more formal writing, though in casual speech ‚ÄúMe and my friend went to the park‚Äù is common. If the phrase comes after a verb or preposition, then ‚Äúme‚Äù is correct (for example, ‚ÄúThey invited my friend and me‚Äù or ‚Äúbetween my friend and me‚Äù)."),

