    ("What are atoms and molecules? Explain it like I‚Äôm 9 please because the book is confusing.", "Everything around you is made of tiny building blocks called atoms, so small you can‚Äôt see them even with a regular microscope; an atom is the smallest piece of an element (like oxygen, carbon, or gold) that still acts like that element, kind of like a single LEGO piece. Atoms can stick together to make molecules, which are groups of two or more atoms bonded together, like snapping LEGO pieces into a small model; for example, oxygen in the air is often a molecule made of two oxygen atoms (O2), water is a molecule made from two hydrogen atoms and one oxygen atom (H2O), and carbon dioxide is one carbon atom joined to two oxygen atoms (CO2). So the simple idea is: atoms are the tiny pieces, and molecules are what you get when atoms join hands to make something new, and different combinations of atoms make different substances you see and use every day."),

