    ("What do you put in a database table? I‚Äôm making a simple website for a club and I don‚Äôt understand rows vs columns.", "A database table is like a spreadsheet that stores one kind of thing, and you decide what ‚Äúkind of thing‚Äù the table represents first (for a club website, common tables are Members, Events, and Payments). Columns are the fields/attributes you store about that thing and each column has a name and a type, like member_id (a unique number), first_name (text), last_name (text), email (text), join_date (date), and is_active (true/false); every row is one complete record, meaning one actual member with values filled in for those columns (for example, member_id 42, ‚ÄúAmina‚Äù, ‚ÄúPatel‚Äù, ‚Äúamina@example.com‚Äù, 2025-09-01, true). A good rule is ‚Äúone row per item, one column per fact about that item,‚Äù and you usually include a primary key column (like member_id) so each row can be uniquely identified; when two things relate, you store the key from one table in another table as a foreign key (for example, an Events table with event_id, title, start_time, location, and an Attendance table with attendance_id, event_id, member_id, status so you can record which members attended which events without repeating all the member details in every event row)."),

