    ("Precalc help: how do I know if a function is one-to-one and how do I find the inverse if it is?", "A function is one-to-one (injective) if different inputs always give different outputs, meaning f(a) = f(b) can only happen when a = b; in precalc you can check this three common ways: (1) the horizontal line test on the graph, where every horizontal line intersects the graph at most once (if some horizontal line hits it twice, two different x-values share the same y-value, so it‚Äôs not one-to-one), (2) algebraically by assuming f(a) = f(b) and showing that forces a = b, and (3) by monotonicity on an interval (if the function is strictly increasing everywhere on its domain or strictly decreasing everywhere, then it‚Äôs one-to-one). If it is one-to-one, you find the inverse by writing y = f(x), swapping x and y (because inverse functions reverse the input/output roles), then solving for y, and finally writing y as f‚Åª¬π(x); you should also state the correct domain and range: the domain of f becomes the range of f‚Åª¬π, and the range of f becomes the domain of f‚Åª¬π, and you can verify by checking f(f‚Åª¬π(x)) = x and f‚Åª¬π(f(x)) = x on the appropriate domains. Example: f(x) = 3x ‚àí 5 is one-to-one (it‚Äôs a line with nonzero slope, so it passes the horizontal line test); start with y = 3x ‚àí 5, swap to x = 3y ‚àí 5, solve 3y = x + 5 so y = (x + 5)/3, hence f‚Åª¬π(x) = (x + 5)/3. Example where you must restrict the domain: f(x) = x¬≤ is not one-to-one on all real numbers (a horizontal line like y = 4 hits at x = ‚àí2 and x = 2), but if you restrict to x ‚â• 0 it becomes one-to-one; then y = x¬≤, swap to x = y¬≤, solve y = ‚àöx (choose the positive root to match x ‚â• 0), so the inverse of x¬≤ on x ‚â• 0 is f‚Åª¬π(x) = ‚àöx with domain x ‚â• 0."),

