    ("I‚Äôm stuck on sequences/series: what‚Äôs the difference between arithmetic and geometric sequences, and how do I find the explicit formula?", "An arithmetic sequence changes by adding or subtracting the same constant each step, called the common difference d, so you can spot it because consecutive terms have the same difference (for example, 3, 7, 11, 15 has d = 4); its explicit formula (nth term) is a_n = a_1 + (n ‚àí 1)d, which comes from starting at the first term and adding d a total of n ‚àí 1 times, and you can quickly check it by plugging in n = 1 to get a_1 and n = 2 to get a_1 + d. A geometric sequence changes by multiplying by the same constant each step, called the common ratio r, so you can spot it because consecutive terms have the same ratio (for example, 2, 6, 18, 54 has r = 3); its explicit formula is a_n = a_1 ¬∑ r^(n ‚àí 1), which comes from starting at a_1 and multiplying by r a total of n ‚àí 1 times, and you can check it the same way by plugging in n = 1 and n = 2. In practice, to find an explicit formula from given terms, first decide arithmetic vs. geometric by testing differences (subtract consecutive terms) or ratios (divide consecutive terms, as long as terms aren‚Äôt zero), then compute d or r, identify a_1 (the first listed term), and substitute into the matching formula; for instance, if the sequence is 10, 7, 4, 1, ‚Ä¶ then d = ‚àí3 so a_n = 10 + (n ‚àí 1)(‚àí3) = 13 ‚àí 3n, while if the sequence is 81, 27, 9, 3, ‚Ä¶ then r = 1/3 so a_n = 81 ¬∑ (1/3)^(n ‚àí 1)."),

