    ("How does the U.S. citizenship test work? Like what kinds of questions do they ask and what do people have to do?", "The U.S. citizenship test is part of the naturalization interview with U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS), and it checks three main things: your ability to read, write, and speak basic English (unless you qualify for an age-and-time-in-the-U.S. exemption), and your knowledge of U.S. civics (U.S. history and government). First, an officer interviews you under oath and reviews your N-400 application, asking questions to confirm your identity, your background, and whether you meet requirements like continuous residence, physical presence, good moral character, and attachment to the U.S. Constitution; they may also ask yes/no eligibility questions from the form (for example about taxes, arrests, or membership in certain organizations). The English portion includes speaking during the interview plus a short reading test where you read one sentence out loud correctly and a writing test where you write one sentence correctly; you must pass one reading sentence and one writing sentence. The civics portion uses the USCIS civics question list: the officer asks up to 10 questions orally, covering topics like the Constitution, the branches of government, rights and responsibilities, elections, and important historical events and leaders, and you need at least 6 correct to pass; if you don‚Äôt pass a test the first time, USCIS usually gives one retest opportunity on the parts you failed within about 60‚Äì90 days. If you pass and your application is approved, the final step is attending a naturalization ceremony where you take the Oath of Allegiance, and only after taking the oath do you become a U.S. citizen."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-25 22:50 - Category: stem_tech_web_dev:database_basics
    ("I‚Äôm designing a tiny database for a class project‚Äîhow do I decide a primary key, and what‚Äôs a foreign key (in simple terms)?", "A primary key is the column (or set of columns) you choose to uniquely identify each row in a table, like a student_id for a Students table; to pick one, choose something that is guaranteed unique for every record, never blank (NOT NULL), and ideally stable over time (names and emails can change, so they‚Äôre often a poor choice), and if no natural unique value exists, add an auto-incrementing ID. A foreign key is a column in one table that stores the primary key value from another table to create a relationship between them, like an Enrollments table having student_id and course_id that point to Students(student_id) and Courses(course_id); this lets the database enforce ‚Äúreferential integrity,‚Äù meaning you can‚Äôt enroll a student_id that doesn‚Äôt exist in Students, and it makes joining tables reliable when you query data. In simple terms, the primary key is a row‚Äôs ‚ÄúID card,‚Äù and a foreign key is the ‚Äúreference‚Äù that links one table‚Äôs row to the matching row in another table."),

