    ("Is it true that you have to be born in the US to be president? My friend said you can‚Äôt be naturalized and I don‚Äôt know if that‚Äôs right.", "In the United States you do not have to be born in the 50 states to become president, but you do have to be a ‚Äúnatural-born citizen‚Äù under the Constitution (Article II), be at least 35 years old, and have lived in the U.S. for at least 14 years. ‚ÄúNatural-born citizen‚Äù generally means you were a U.S. citizen at birth, which includes people born in the U.S. and also many people born outside the U.S. to U.S.-citizen parent(s) who meet legal requirements, so some people born abroad can still be eligible. Your friend is right that a person who became a citizen later through naturalization is not considered ‚Äúnatural-born‚Äù and therefore cannot be president, even though they can hold many other offices."),

