    ("Can you help me write 3 sentences explaining why the US has 3 branches of government and what each one does?", "The United States has three branches of government so no single person or group has too much power, because each branch can check and balance the others. The legislative branch (Congress, made up of the Senate and the House of Representatives) makes laws, the executive branch (the President and the agencies that carry out government work) enforces laws, and the judicial branch (the Supreme Court and other federal courts) interprets laws and decides whether they follow the Constitution. By splitting these jobs and letting each branch limit the others, the government protects people‚Äôs rights and keeps power from being abused."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-25 22:54 - Category: high_math_precalc:inverse_functions
    ("High school pre-calc: I have f(x)= (2x+1)/(x-3). How do I find the inverse and what restrictions do I need so it‚Äôs actually invertible?", "To find the inverse of f(x) = (2x+1)/(x-3), first write y = (2x+1)/(x-3) and solve for x in terms of y: multiply both sides by (x‚àí3) to get y(x‚àí3)=2x+1, expand to yx‚àí3y=2x+1, then collect x-terms to get yx‚àí2x=3y+1, factor x to get x(y‚àí2)=3y+1, and divide to get x=(3y+1)/(y‚àí2). Now swap x and y to write the inverse: f^(-1)(x) = (3x+1)/(x‚àí2). For restrictions, the original function is undefined at x=3, so the domain must exclude 3; in fact this rational function is one-to-one on its entire domain (it‚Äôs a non-constant linear fractional function), so no extra restriction is needed beyond x‚â†3. The range of f is all real numbers except y=2 (you can see this because setting (2x+1)/(x‚àí3)=2 leads to 2x+1=2x‚àí6, which is impossible), so the inverse must have domain x‚â†2, and correspondingly its range excludes 3. A quick check: f(f^(-1)(x)) = (2(3x+1)/(x‚àí2)+1)/((3x+1)/(x‚àí2)‚àí3) simplifies to x (for x‚â†2), confirming the inverse is correct."),

