    ("Physics help: what‚Äôs the electric field at a point 0.20 m away from a +3.0 ŒºC charge? And how do I know which direction the field points?", "For a point charge, the electric field magnitude is E = k|q|/r^2, where k = 8.99 √ó 10^9 N¬∑m^2/C^2, q = +3.0 ŒºC = 3.0 √ó 10^-6 C, and r = 0.20 m, so E = (8.99 √ó 10^9)(3.0 √ó 10^-6)/(0.20)^2 = (2.697 √ó 10^4)/0.040 ‚âà 6.7 √ó 10^5 N/C (equivalently V/m). The direction of the electric field is defined as the direction a positive test charge would be pushed, so because the source charge is positive, the field points radially outward, meaning away from the +3.0 ŒºC charge along the line connecting the charge to the point. If the charge were negative, the field would point inward toward the charge."),

