    ("Work-energy theorem question: if a 5 kg cart starts at rest and a constant 20 N force pushes it for 3 m on a frictionless track, what speed does it have at the end?", "Use the work-energy theorem: the net work done on the cart equals its change in kinetic energy. On a frictionless track with a constant force in the direction of motion, the work is W = Fd = 20 N √ó 3 m = 60 J, and since it starts from rest its initial kinetic energy is 0, so 60 J = (1/2)mv^2 = (1/2)(5 kg)v^2. Solving gives v^2 = 120/5 = 24, so v = sqrt(24) ‚âà 4.9 m/s, which is the cart‚Äôs speed at the end."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-25 22:57 - Category: stem_math_applied:data_science_math
    ("Data science math: what‚Äôs the difference between correlation and causation? My teacher keeps saying r doesn‚Äôt mean it causes it and I don‚Äôt get it.", "Correlation means two variables tend to move together in a predictable way, and the correlation coefficient r (from ‚àí1 to +1) measures how strong and in what direction that ‚Äúmove together‚Äù pattern is; causation means changing one variable actually produces a change in the other. The key difference is that correlation is just an observed association in the data, while causation is a cause-and-effect claim about what would happen if you intervened, and you can have a strong correlation without causation because of coincidence, reverse causation, or a third ‚Äúconfounding‚Äù factor that affects both. For example, ice cream sales and drowning deaths are often positively correlated in summer, but ice cream doesn‚Äôt cause drowning; hot weather increases swimming (raising drowning risk) and also increases ice cream buying, so temperature is the confounder. That‚Äôs why your teacher says ‚Äúr doesn‚Äôt mean it causes it‚Äù: r can tell you a relationship exists, but to argue causation you usually need a study design that rules out other explanations, like a randomized experiment, or careful causal methods and strong assumptions in observational data."),

