    ("Set theory basics: can you explain union vs intersection using like real-life examples? Also what does that upside-down U symbol mean?", "In set theory, a set is just a collection of things, like a set of students who play soccer or a set of students who play basketball. The union of two sets, written A ‚à™ B (the ‚ÄúU-shaped‚Äù symbol), means ‚Äúin A or in B (or in both),‚Äù so if A is the students who play soccer and B is the students who play basketball, then A ‚à™ B is everyone who plays at least one of those sports; for a simple number example, if A = {1, 2, 3} and B = {3, 4}, then A ‚à™ B = {1, 2, 3, 4}. The intersection of two sets, written A ‚à© B (the upside-down U symbol), means ‚Äúin both A and B,‚Äù so with the sports example A ‚à© B is the students who play both soccer and basketball; with the numbers above, A ‚à© B = {3}. So the upside-down U, ‚à©, specifically means intersection, the overlap shared by the two sets."),

