    # Auto-added 2025-12-25 23:00 - Category: college_computer_science:software_engineering
    ("In software engineering, can you explain the difference between unit tests and integration tests like I‚Äôm new to it? And where would mocking fit in?", "Unit tests and integration tests both check that your software works, but they focus on different scopes: a unit test targets one small piece of code in isolation (like a single function or method) and verifies it behaves correctly for various inputs, while an integration test checks that multiple pieces work together (like your service talking to a database layer, an HTTP client, or another module) and catches problems that only appear when components interact, such as mismatched data formats, incorrect wiring, configuration issues, or unexpected side effects. Mocking fits in as a technique most commonly used in unit tests to replace real dependencies (like databases, network calls, clocks, or third-party APIs) with controlled ‚Äúfake‚Äù objects so the test is fast, deterministic, and focused on the unit‚Äôs logic; for example, instead of calling a real payment provider, you mock it to return ‚Äúapproved‚Äù or ‚Äúdeclined‚Äù so you can test how your code responds without relying on the network. In integration tests you typically mock less because you want realism, but you might still mock external systems you don‚Äôt control or that are too slow/expensive/unreliable (for instance, using a sandbox or a stubbed payment service) while keeping the internal components real, so you‚Äôre testing the actual integration you care about."),

