    ("Real talk: I get jealous when my best friend hangs with other people and then I act weird. How do I deal with that without being controlling?", "Jealousy in a close friendship is common, and it usually comes from a fear of being replaced or left out, not from you being a ‚Äúbad‚Äù friend, so the goal is to notice the feeling early and respond in a way that protects the friendship instead of trying to control it. Start by naming what‚Äôs happening in your head when you feel that spike (for example, ‚ÄúThey‚Äôre having more fun without me‚Äù or ‚ÄúI‚Äôm not important anymore‚Äù) and remind yourself that a friend spending time with others is normal and doesn‚Äôt automatically mean you‚Äôre losing them; then do something that calms your body before you act (slow breathing, a short walk, putting your phone down for ten minutes) so you don‚Äôt send cold texts, act distant, or test them. Next, choose a healthy action that meets the real need underneath the jealousy: if you need reassurance, ask directly and kindly instead of hinting or guilt-tripping, like ‚ÄúSometimes I get insecure when I‚Äôm not included, and I‚Äôm working on it‚Äîcould we plan a hangout this week?‚Äù If you need more connection, make concrete plans, build your own routines and friendships so your best friend isn‚Äôt your only source of closeness, and focus on being warm when you do see them rather than ‚Äúpunishing‚Äù them for having other plans. A good boundary to keep yourself out of controlling behavior is this: you can ask for what you want (time together, honesty, reassurance), but you can‚Äôt demand who they‚Äôre allowed to see, monitor them, or make them feel guilty for having a life; if you catch yourself wanting to do that, treat it as a signal to self-soothe and communicate your needs instead. If the jealousy feels intense, leads to constant anxiety, or makes you act in ways you regret, talking it through with a counselor can help you build stronger self-worth and coping skills, which makes friendships feel safer and more enjoyable."),

