    ("Dance help: I‚Äôm trying to learn a basic hip-hop routine for the school talent show‚Äîwhat‚Äôs a good way to practice so I don‚Äôt look stiff?", "A great way to stop looking stiff in a basic hip-hop routine is to practice in layers: first learn the moves slowly with relaxed shoulders and slightly bent knees, then add groove by keeping a gentle ‚Äúbounce‚Äù in your knees and letting your chest and hips move naturally with the beat instead of locking your body. Use the music in counts (try ‚Äú5-6-7-8‚Äù) and drill short chunks (4 or 8 counts at a time) until they feel automatic, then connect the chunks; when you drill, repeat each chunk several times without stopping so your body learns the flow, not just the steps. Record yourself from the front and side and check for common stiffness signs like raised shoulders, straight knees, tight hands, or frozen face; fix one thing at a time (for example, ‚Äúshoulders down‚Äù or ‚Äúhands relaxed‚Äù) and try marking the routine at 50% energy first, then 80%, then full-out. Before practicing, do a quick warm-up (neck/shoulder rolls, hip circles, light bouncing, and a few body rolls) and stretch your ankles/hips so your movement has range; during the routine, think ‚Äúloose and grounded‚Äù by staying low, breathing out on hits, and adding small textures like a head nod, a shoulder roll, or a clean pause on the beat. Finally, run the whole routine like a performance at least once a day: start in your ending spot, do your entrance, smile, and commit to the rhythm even if you mess up‚Äîconfidence and groove read as ‚Äúnot stiff‚Äù more than perfect steps."),

