    ("Ecosystems question (middle school): what‚Äôs the difference between a habitat and a niche? My notes make them sound the same.", "A habitat is the place an organism lives and the physical conditions around it, like a frog‚Äôs habitat being a pond with shallow water, plants, and mud. A niche is the organism‚Äôs role or ‚Äújob‚Äù in that habitat‚Äîhow it gets food, what it eats, when it‚Äôs active, what eats it, and how it affects other living things; for example, the frog‚Äôs niche might be a predator that eats insects and helps control mosquito populations while also serving as prey for snakes and birds. A quick way to remember it is: habitat is the organism‚Äôs address, and niche is its profession and relationships, and two species can share a habitat but usually can‚Äôt have exactly the same niche for long because they would compete for the same resources."),

