    ("Limits intro: can you give me a real-world example of a limit (not just math symbols) that would make sense for a precalc student?", "Imagine you‚Äôre driving toward a red light and you start braking smoothly: at 30 mph you‚Äôre still far away, at 10 mph you‚Äôre closer, at 2 mph you‚Äôre very close, and as time passes your speed gets closer and closer to 0 mph; the ‚Äúlimit‚Äù idea is that even before you‚Äôre completely stopped, your speed is approaching 0, and we can describe that approaching behavior without needing the exact instant it becomes 0. In precalc terms, you can think of your speed as a function of time, and the limit is the value the speed is heading toward (0 mph) as time gets closer to the moment you stop, which matches how limits describe what a quantity is approaching in real life when you can get arbitrarily close to a value even if you don‚Äôt focus on one exact moment."),

