    # Auto-added 2025-12-25 23:08 - Category: how_things_work:light
    ("Why is the sky blue and sunsets orange? My friend said it‚Äôs because of light scattering but I want the real reason.", "Sunlight looks white, but it‚Äôs really a mix of many colors (different wavelengths), and Earth‚Äôs atmosphere is full of tiny molecules like nitrogen and oxygen that interact with that light; these molecules scatter shorter-wavelength light much more strongly than longer-wavelength light, a process called Rayleigh scattering, so blue and violet light get scattered in all directions across the sky while red light mostly travels straight through. Even though violet scatters even more than blue, our eyes are less sensitive to violet and some violet is absorbed higher in the atmosphere, so the scattered light we notice most is blue, making the daytime sky look blue from almost every direction you look. At sunset and sunrise the Sun is low, so its light has to pass through a much longer path of atmosphere; along that long path, most of the blue light gets scattered out of the direct beam before it reaches your eyes, leaving the remaining sunlight richer in longer wavelengths like orange and red, which is why the Sun and the sky near it look warm-colored. If there are extra particles like dust, smoke, or pollution, they can add another kind of scattering (often called Mie scattering) that doesn‚Äôt favor blue as strongly and can make sunsets look even deeper orange or red, or sometimes more whitish if the particles are large and numerous."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-25 23:08 - Category: us_history:founding_fathers
    ("Who were the Founding Fathers and why are they important? Like I‚Äôm in 5th grade and we have a quiz tomorrow.", "The Founding Fathers were a group of leaders in the American colonies who helped the United States become an independent country and then helped create its new government in the late 1700s, especially during the American Revolution (1775‚Äì1783) and the writing of the U.S. Constitution in 1787. Some of the most famous Founding Fathers are George Washington (led the Continental Army and became the first president), Thomas Jefferson (wrote most of the Declaration of Independence), John Adams (important leader for independence and later the second president), Benjamin Franklin (helped win support from France and was a key problem-solver), James Madison (often called the ‚ÄúFather of the Constitution‚Äù and helped write the Bill of Rights), and Alexander Hamilton (helped set up the nation‚Äôs financial system). They are important because they helped the colonies break away from Great Britain, wrote the Declaration of Independence in 1776 to explain why, and then created the Constitution and Bill of Rights to set up how the government works and protect people‚Äôs freedoms, like freedom of speech and religion; even today, the rules and ideas they wrote are the foundation of the U.S. government and many of the rights you learn about in school."),

