    # Auto-added 2025-12-25 23:15 - Category: academic_english:grammar
    ("What‚Äôs the difference between \'their\', \'there\', and \'they‚Äôre\'? Can you give me easy examples?", "Their, there, and they‚Äôre sound the same, but they mean different things: their shows ownership (it answers ‚Äúwhose?‚Äù), as in ‚ÄúTheir dog is barking‚Äù or ‚ÄúI like their new house‚Äù; there refers to a place or position (it answers ‚Äúwhere?‚Äù) or is used to start a sentence like ‚ÄúThere is/There are,‚Äù as in ‚ÄúPut the book over there,‚Äù ‚ÄúWe‚Äôre going there tomorrow,‚Äù or ‚ÄúThere are three cookies left‚Äù; they‚Äôre is a contraction that means ‚Äúthey are,‚Äù so you can check it by replacing it with ‚Äúthey are,‚Äù as in ‚ÄúThey‚Äôre playing outside‚Äù (They are playing outside) and ‚ÄúI think they‚Äôre happy‚Äù (I think they are happy). A quick memory trick is that their has ‚Äúheir‚Äù in it (someone who owns/inherits), there has ‚Äúhere‚Äù in it (a place), and they‚Äôre has an apostrophe because it‚Äôs shortening two words (they are)."),

