    ("I don‚Äôt get climate zones. Why do deserts happen around 30¬∞ latitude and why is it colder near the poles? Can you explain it without using super advanced words?", "Earth‚Äôs climate zones mostly come from two big ideas: how sunlight hits Earth and how air moves. Near the equator, sunlight is more direct, so the ground warms strongly and heats the air above it; warm air is lighter, so it rises, and as it rises it cools, water vapor turns into clouds, and lots of rain can fall (that‚Äôs why many tropical places are wet). After that air rises, it spreads out high in the sky and eventually sinks back down around about 30¬∞ north and 30¬∞ south; sinking air gets squeezed by higher air pressure, which warms it up and makes it able to ‚Äúhold‚Äù more water vapor, so clouds have a harder time forming and rain is less likely, leading to dry regions and many of the world‚Äôs deserts (like the Sahara and the deserts of Australia). Near the poles it‚Äôs colder mainly because sunlight arrives at a low angle: the same amount of sunlight is spread over a larger area, it passes through more atmosphere (so more energy is lost on the way), and snow and ice reflect a lot of the sunlight back to space, so less heat is absorbed; also, the air circulation tends to keep cold air pooled near the poles, which helps them stay cold."),

