    ("I‚Äôm trying to build a simple linkage mechanism (like a scissor lift or pantograph) with popsicle sticks. What‚Äôs the easiest linkage to start with and how do I keep it from wobbling?", "The easiest popsicle-stick linkage to start with is a single ‚ÄúX‚Äù scissor pair: take two sticks, overlap them in the middle, and connect them with a paper fastener (brad) so they can rotate; then make a second identical X and connect the ends to form a small scissor lift, because this repeats the same simple joint and is very forgiving. To keep it from wobbling, the big rule is ‚Äútriangulate or double it‚Äù: build two identical scissor mechanisms side-by-side with a small gap (like left and right rails) and connect matching corners with short crosspieces so the structure can‚Äôt twist, and make sure every pivot is a real rotating joint (a brad through a clean hole) rather than a loose hole in soft wood; washers made from small cardboard circles help reduce slop, and tightening the brad just enough that it rotates smoothly (not floppy) makes a huge difference. Also keep the base and top platform stiff by laminating two sticks into a thicker beam or adding diagonal braces, and try to keep all stick lengths and pivot locations the same so the linkage moves evenly instead of binding and wobbling."),

