    ("If an ecosystem loses all its predators (like wolves), what happens to the rest of the food web? Can you give a real example in North America?", "When an ecosystem loses its top predators, prey animals (often deer or elk) usually increase because fewer are being hunted, and that can trigger a trophic cascade: the larger prey population eats more plants, young trees and shrubs decline, habitats for other species change, and even soil and stream conditions can shift because vegetation that stabilizes banks and provides shade is reduced; as plant communities shrink or change, animals that depend on them (songbirds, beavers, insects, and small mammals) can also decline or move away, and the whole food web becomes less balanced. A well-known North American example is Yellowstone National Park: after wolves were eliminated from the park by the 1920s, elk numbers and browsing pressure rose in many areas, which contributed to declines in willow and aspen regeneration in some valleys and reduced habitat quality for species like beavers that rely on willows; when gray wolves were reintroduced in 1995‚Äì1996, elk behavior and numbers changed and some places saw increased willow and aspen growth and more beaver activity, showing how predators can indirectly shape plants and many other parts of the food web (even though the size of these effects varies by location and other factors like climate and hunting)."),

