    ("What‚Äôs the difference between U.S. citizenship and being a permanent resident? And what are like 3 responsibilities citizens have?", "U.S. citizenship is a permanent legal status that makes you a full member of the United States with the strongest set of rights, including the right to vote in federal elections, the ability to get a U.S. passport, and eligibility for certain government jobs and benefits, and citizens generally cannot be deported for ordinary immigration reasons; a lawful permanent resident (often called a green card holder) is allowed to live and work in the U.S. long-term but is still a citizen of another country, cannot vote in federal elections, usually cannot serve on a federal jury, may have limits on certain jobs or benefits, and can lose permanent residence and be removed from the U.S. for certain serious crimes or by abandoning U.S. residence (for example, moving away or taking very long trips without keeping ties). Three common responsibilities of U.S. citizens are to obey the law, to pay taxes honestly and on time, and for men who live in the U.S. ages 18 through 25 to register with the Selective Service (and citizens may also be called for jury duty and are expected to participate in civic life, like voting and staying informed)."),

