    ("My class is arguing: can states make their own laws that go against federal laws? Who wins and why? (We‚Äôre on the Constitution unit.)", "Under the U.S. Constitution, states can make their own laws on many issues, but they cannot enforce a state law that conflicts with a valid federal law, because the Supremacy Clause in Article VI says the Constitution and federal laws made under it are ‚Äúthe supreme Law of the Land,‚Äù meaning judges must follow federal law over state law when the two directly clash. This doesn‚Äôt mean the federal government always wins on every topic: states keep many powers under the Tenth Amendment, and if Congress tries to regulate something the Constitution doesn‚Äôt give it power to regulate, or if a federal law violates constitutional rights, then the federal law can be struck down by the courts; also, if there is no conflict, both state and federal laws can exist at the same time (for example, states can add extra safety rules as long as they don‚Äôt contradict federal rules). In practice, when people argue ‚Äúwho wins,‚Äù the key questions are whether the federal government had constitutional authority to pass the law and whether the state law actually conflicts with it; if both are true, federal law wins because the Constitution makes it supreme."),

