    ("I‚Äôm confused about how someone becomes a U.S. citizen if they weren‚Äôt born here. What are the main steps and how long does it usually take?", "If you weren‚Äôt born in the United States, the most common way to become a U.S. citizen is through naturalization, which usually starts with first becoming a lawful permanent resident (getting a ‚Äúgreen card‚Äù) through a family member, an employer, refugee/asylee status, or certain other categories; after you have a green card, you generally must live in the U.S. as a permanent resident for 5 years (or 3 years if you‚Äôre married to and living with a U.S. citizen) and meet other requirements like being at least 18, showing ‚Äúgood moral character,‚Äù demonstrating continuous residence and enough physical presence in the U.S., and being able to read, write, and speak basic English and pass a civics test (with some age/disability exceptions). The main steps are: confirm you‚Äôre eligible, file Form N-400 with U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS) and pay the fee or request a fee waiver if you qualify, attend a biometrics appointment for fingerprints and a photo, go to an interview where USCIS reviews your application and gives the English and civics tests, receive a decision, and then take the Oath of Allegiance at a naturalization ceremony‚Äîonly after the oath are you officially a U.S. citizen and able to get a Certificate of Naturalization and apply for a U.S. passport. Timing varies a lot by where you live and USCIS workload, but a typical naturalization case after filing the N-400 often takes roughly 6 to 18 months; the bigger time commitment for many people is the required 3 or 5 years of permanent-resident residence before they can even apply, plus however long it took them to get the green card in the first place. There are also faster or different paths in special situations, such as some members of the U.S. military, and some people become citizens automatically through ‚Äúderivative‚Äù or ‚Äúacquired‚Äù citizenship (for example, certain children of U.S. citizens, or some children who automatically become citizens when a parent naturalizes and the child is under 18, is a permanent resident, and lives in the U.S. in that parent‚Äôs legal and physical custody), so the exact steps and timeline depend on the person‚Äôs starting status."),

