    ("I keep mixing up Boyle‚Äôs law and Charles‚Äôs law‚Ä¶ can you explain the difference and when to use each on a gas law problem?", "Boyle‚Äôs law and Charles‚Äôs law each describe how one gas variable changes when a different variable is held constant, so the key is to ask ‚Äúwhat stays the same?‚Äù Boyle‚Äôs law is the pressure‚Äìvolume relationship at constant temperature and constant amount of gas (n): if temperature doesn‚Äôt change, pressure and volume are inversely proportional, so P1V1 = P2V2; use it for problems like a syringe or piston where you compress a gas (volume goes down, pressure goes up) without heating or cooling it. Charles‚Äôs law is the volume‚Äìtemperature relationship at constant pressure and constant amount of gas: if pressure doesn‚Äôt change, volume is directly proportional to absolute temperature, so V1/T1 = V2/T2 with temperature in Kelvin; use it for problems like a balloon that expands when warmed or shrinks when cooled while the external pressure stays essentially the same. A quick memory check is ‚ÄúBoyle = B for ‚Äòsqueeze‚Äô: squeeze volume smaller, pressure gets bigger,‚Äù and ‚ÄúCharles = C for ‚Äòchange in temperature‚Äô: warmer means larger volume,‚Äù and if a problem changes both pressure and temperature (or mentions moles changing), neither law alone is enough and you should switch to the combined gas law P1V1/T1 = P2V2/T2 (or the ideal gas law PV = nRT if moles are involved)."),

