    ("Evaluate this limit without a calculator and explain the steps: lim (x‚Üí2) (x^2 4)/(x 2).", "To evaluate lim (x‚Üí2) (x^2 ‚àí 4)/(x ‚àí 2), notice that direct substitution gives 0/0, so we simplify the expression first: factor the numerator as a difference of squares, x^2 ‚àí 4 = (x ‚àí 2)(x + 2). Then (x^2 ‚àí 4)/(x ‚àí 2) = (x ‚àí 2)(x + 2)/(x ‚àí 2) = x + 2 for all x ‚â† 2, so the limit as x approaches 2 is the same as the limit of x + 2 as x approaches 2. Now substitute x = 2 into the simplified expression: 2 + 2 = 4, so the limit equals 4."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-25 23:32 - Category: stem_math_foundations:set_theory_basics
    ("Can you explain set theory basics like I‚Äôm a beginner: what do ‚à™, ‚à©, and the complement mean, and what‚Äôs the difference between subset and element?", "A set is just a collection of distinct objects, like A = {1, 2, 3} and B = {3, 4}. The union symbol ‚à™ means ‚Äúeverything in either set,‚Äù so A ‚à™ B = {1, 2, 3, 4}; the intersection symbol ‚à© means ‚Äúonly what they share,‚Äù so A ‚à© B = {3}. The complement of a set means ‚Äúeverything not in that set,‚Äù but you must first know the universe (the ‚Äúall possible choices‚Äù you‚Äôre working within), for example if U = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5} and A = {1, 2, 3}, then the complement of A (often written A·∂ú) is {4, 5}. An element is a single thing inside a set, written with ‚àà, so 2 ‚àà A is true, while 5 ‚àà A is false; a subset is a whole set whose every element is contained in another set, written with ‚äÜ, so {1, 2} ‚äÜ A is true, and {2, 5} ‚äÜ A is false because 5 is not in A. A quick way to remember the difference is that ‚àà compares ‚Äúthing to set,‚Äù while ‚äÜ compares ‚Äúset to set.‚Äù"),

