    ("Electric fields are confusing me‚Äîif you put a positive test charge near a negative charge, which direction is the electric field and why?", "The electric field at a point is defined as the direction a positive test charge would be pushed (the force per unit positive charge), so you always imagine placing a tiny positive test charge there and asking which way it would accelerate. Near a negative charge, a positive test charge is attracted, so the force on it points toward the negative charge; therefore the electric field vectors point toward the negative charge (they ‚Äúend‚Äù on negatives). More generally, electric field lines point away from positive charges and toward negative charges, because a positive test charge is repelled by positives and attracted to negatives."),

