    ("I have two datasets with different scales‚Äîshould I standardize them (z-scores) before doing k-means? Why or why not?", "Yes, in most cases you should standardize (z-score) features before k-means when they are on different scales, because k-means assigns points to clusters by minimizing distances (typically Euclidean distance), and a feature with a larger numeric range or units (for example, income in dollars versus age in years) will dominate the distance calculation and effectively ‚Äúdecide‚Äù the clusters even if it is not more important. Z-scoring puts each feature on a comparable scale (mean 0, standard deviation 1), so each contributes more equally to the distance and the resulting clusters reflect patterns across all features rather than just the biggest-magnitude one. You might not standardize only when the features are already in the same units/scale, or when you intentionally want one variable to have more influence because its scale meaningfully represents importance; in that case you can also use deliberate feature weighting instead of leaving scale differences accidental. Also note that if your variables are highly skewed or have outliers, a robust scaler (using median and IQR) or a log transform before scaling can produce more stable k-means results, since k-means is sensitive to outliers."),

