    ("What is the Liberty Bell and why is it such a big deal in US history? Also where is it now?", "The Liberty Bell is a large historic bell that was made in 1752 for the Pennsylvania State House (now called Independence Hall) in Philadelphia, and it became famous because it is closely connected to the ideas of American freedom and independence. It is a big deal in U.S. history because it was associated with the early government of Pennsylvania and later became a powerful symbol for liberty movements, especially after abolitionists in the 1800s used it as an emblem in the fight to end slavery; it also has an inscription from the Bible that reads, ‚ÄúProclaim Liberty Throughout All the Land Unto All the Inhabitants Thereof.‚Äù The bell is also well known for its crack, which grew over time and eventually made it impossible to ring properly, and today it is preserved and displayed at the Liberty Bell Center in Independence National Historical Park in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, across the street from Independence Hall."),

