    ("For a quick US civics thing: what‚Äôs the difference between a symbol like the Liberty Bell and an actual law/document like the Constitution?", "A symbol like the Liberty Bell is an object people use to represent an idea or value‚Äîlike freedom and independence‚Äîso it teaches history and inspires feelings, but it does not create rules anyone must follow. A law or founding document like the U.S. Constitution is a written set of official rules that sets up the government, lists its powers and limits, and can be enforced by courts, so it actually determines what the government can and cannot do. In other words, the Liberty Bell reminds Americans of what the country stands for, while the Constitution is the legal blueprint that makes the government work and has real legal force."),

