    ("Reading comp help: can you give me a strategy to answer inference questions? I always miss the ones that are like ‚Äúwhat can you conclude‚Äù", "For inference questions like ‚Äúwhat can you conclude,‚Äù treat them as ‚Äúwhat must be true based on the passage,‚Äù not ‚Äúwhat might be true,‚Äù and use a strict evidence-first routine: reread the exact lines connected to the question, paraphrase the key facts in your own words, then combine only those facts into a small, logical statement that doesn‚Äôt add new information. A reliable test is to ask, ‚ÄúCan I point to specific words or sentences that support every part of my answer?‚Äù and ‚ÄúWould this still be true even if I remove my opinions and outside knowledge?‚Äù‚Äîthe correct inference will be the most conservative choice that is fully supported, while wrong answers usually go too far (strong words like always/never), bring in assumptions, or sound reasonable but aren‚Äôt directly backed by the text. When choosing between options, eliminate anything that contradicts a detail, is more extreme than the passage, or answers a different question, and pick the one that you could defend by quoting or paraphrasing the passage in one or two sentences."),

