    ("Ecosystems: what‚Äôs the difference between a food chain and a food web, and why do people say energy ‚Äúdecreases‚Äù at each trophic level?", "A food chain is a simple, linear pathway showing who eats whom in an ecosystem, such as grass ‚Üí rabbit ‚Üí fox, while a food web is a more realistic network of many interconnected food chains because most organisms eat (and are eaten by) more than one species, such as a rabbit eating several plants and being eaten by foxes, hawks, or snakes. People say energy ‚Äúdecreases‚Äù at each trophic level because when an organism eats, only a fraction of the energy stored in the food becomes new biomass that the next level can eat; much of the energy is used for life processes like movement, growth, and maintaining body temperature and is released as heat during respiration, and some is lost in waste or in parts that aren‚Äôt eaten or digested. As a result, higher trophic levels have less usable energy available, which is why energy pyramids narrow toward the top and why there are usually fewer top predators than producers; a common rule of thumb is that only about 10% of energy is transferred from one trophic level to the next, though the exact percent can vary by ecosystem and organism."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-25 23:35 - Category: academic_science:ecosystems
    ("If wolves get removed from an ecosystem, what happens to the rest of the organisms? I need an example of a trophic cascade for my bio notes.", "Removing wolves, a top predator, often triggers a trophic cascade because the animals wolves normally keep in check (like elk or deer) increase in number and change their behavior, which then affects plants and many other species. A classic example comes from Yellowstone: when wolves were absent for decades, elk populations grew and spent more time browsing in river valleys, heavily eating young willows, aspens, and cottonwoods; with fewer young trees and shrubs, streamside habitat declined, which reduced food and building material for beavers, so beaver colonies and their ponds became less common, and that in turn lowered wetland habitat for fish, amphibians, and water birds. Overbrowsing also left riverbanks with less vegetation to hold soil, increasing erosion and simplifying stream channels; when wolves were reintroduced in 1995‚Äì1996, elk numbers and browsing pressure decreased and elk avoided some risky areas, allowing willows and aspens to recover in many places, which supported more beavers and helped stabilize some streamside ecosystems. This chain of indirect effects‚Äîwolves affecting elk, elk affecting plants, and plants shaping habitat for many other organisms‚Äîis what biologists mean by a trophic cascade."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-25 23:35 - Category: us_government:civics_basics
    ("US government question for homework: what does the Supreme Court actually DO, and how is that different from Congress?", "The Supreme Court is the highest court in the United States, and its main job is to decide legal disputes by interpreting the Constitution and federal laws, which often means answering questions like whether a law or government action is constitutional and how a law should be applied in a real case; when the Court rules, its decision becomes a precedent that lower courts must follow, and it can strike down federal or state laws that violate the Constitution (a power called judicial review). Congress is different because it is the lawmaking branch: it writes, debates, and passes bills that can become federal laws, controls federal spending and taxes, and has other legislative powers like declaring war and overseeing the executive branch through hearings and investigations. In short, Congress creates the rules for the country, while the Supreme Court does not write laws at all‚Äîit settles cases and explains what the Constitution and laws mean, sometimes invalidating laws that conflict with the Constitution."),

