    ("I‚Äôm confused about checks and balances‚Äîcan you give me one real example where each branch stops another branch?", "A clear real-world set of examples is: the legislative branch (Congress) can stop the executive branch by overriding a presidential veto with a two-thirds vote in both the House and Senate, like when Congress overrode President George W. Bush‚Äôs veto of the Water Resources Development Act on November 8, 2007; the executive branch (the President) can stop the legislative branch by vetoing a bill passed by Congress, like when President Barack Obama vetoed the Keystone XL Pipeline Approval Act on February 24, 2015; and the judicial branch (the Supreme Court) can stop the legislative branch by declaring a law unconstitutional, like in United States v. Lopez (1995), when the Court struck down the Gun-Free School Zones Act as beyond Congress‚Äôs power under the Commerce Clause. Each example shows one branch using a specific constitutional power to limit another branch so no single part of government can act without checks."),

