    # Auto-added 2025-12-25 23:36 - Category: stem_tech_data_science:regression_models
    ("Data science question: when would you choose ridge vs lasso vs elastic net for a regression model? I get the idea of regularization but I‚Äôm not sure how to explain it in a report.", "Ridge, lasso, and elastic net are all linear regression models that add a penalty to the usual least-squares loss to reduce overfitting, especially when you have many predictors or strong multicollinearity; the practical difference is how they shrink coefficients and whether they can set some exactly to zero. Choose ridge (L2 penalty, sum of squared coefficients) when you believe many predictors have small-to-moderate effects and you mainly want stable predictions in the presence of correlated features: ridge shrinks coefficients toward zero but typically keeps all variables in the model, and when predictors are highly correlated it tends to distribute weight across them rather than picking just one. Choose lasso (L1 penalty, sum of absolute coefficients) when you want a simpler, more interpretable model and you suspect only a subset of predictors truly matter: lasso can drive some coefficients exactly to zero, effectively performing feature selection, but with strongly correlated predictors it may behave ‚Äúpick-one‚Äù and be less stable (small data changes can swap which correlated variable is kept). Choose elastic net (a mix of L1 and L2) when you want sparsity like lasso but also want better behavior with correlated predictors and high-dimensional settings (p can be comparable to or larger than n): the L2 part encourages grouped selection so correlated variables can enter together, while the L1 part still allows some coefficients to become exactly zero. In a report, a clear way to explain it is: ‚ÄúWe used regularization to trade a small increase in bias for a larger reduction in variance, improving generalization; ridge was preferred for prediction stability under multicollinearity, lasso for automatic variable selection and interpretability, and elastic net as a compromise that selects variables while handling correlated features more robustly,‚Äù and you can add that the penalty strength (and the elastic-net mixing parameter) should be chosen via cross-validation so the choice is driven by out-of-sample performance rather than in-sample fit."),

