    ("Geometry help (calc-based maybe): how do you find the volume of a solid generated by rotating the region between y = x and y = x^2 from 0 to 1 around the x-axis? I keep mixing up washers and shells.", "To find the volume when the region between y = x and y = x^2 on 0 ‚â§ x ‚â§ 1 is rotated about the x-axis, first note which curve is on top: for 0 < x < 1 we have x > x^2, so y = x is the outer radius and y = x^2 is the inner radius. Using the washer method (cross-sections perpendicular to the x-axis), the volume is V = œÄ‚à´0^1[(outer radius)^2 ‚àí (inner radius)^2] dx = œÄ‚à´0^1[(x)^2 ‚àí (x^2)^2] dx = œÄ‚à´0^1(x^2 ‚àí x^4) dx = œÄ[(x^3/3) ‚àí (x^5/5)]0^1 = œÄ(1/3 ‚àí 1/5) = 2œÄ/15. If you want to see the shell setup to avoid mixing them up: shells are parallel to the axis of rotation, so you‚Äôd integrate with respect to y; rewrite as x = y (from y = x) and x = ‚àöy (from y = x^2), with y from 0 to 1, giving V = 2œÄ‚à´0^1(radius)(height) dy = 2œÄ‚à´0^1(y)(‚àöy ‚àí y) dy = 2œÄ[(2/5) ‚àí (1/3)] = 2œÄ/15, matching the washer result."),

