    ("How does light actually work as both a wave and a particle? Like, what does it mean in the double-slit experiment without getting super hand-wavy?", "Light isn‚Äôt ‚Äúsometimes a wave and sometimes a particle‚Äù in the everyday sense; in quantum physics it‚Äôs an electromagnetic field that comes in discrete chunks of energy called photons, and the most accurate description is a quantum state (a wavefunction) that tells you the probability of different detection outcomes. In the double-slit experiment, you send very weak light (even one photon at a time) toward two narrow slits and put a detector screen behind them; each photon is always detected as a single localized hit (that‚Äôs the particle-like part), but if you repeat the experiment many times the hits build up into an interference pattern of bright and dark fringes (that‚Äôs the wave-like part), which happens because the quantum state has probability amplitudes for ‚Äúgoing through slit A‚Äù and ‚Äúgoing through slit B‚Äù and those amplitudes add, and when you square the total amplitude to get a probability (the Born rule) you get cross-terms that can be positive (bright fringes) or cancel (dark fringes). The key non-hand-wavy point is that what interferes is not little pellets colliding with each other but probability amplitudes for different paths, and you only see the fringes when the two paths remain coherent, meaning nothing in the setup records which slit the photon took; if you add a which-path detector (or any interaction that leaves reliable which-slit information in the environment), the photon becomes entangled with that detector/environment, the relative phase between the two path amplitudes becomes inaccessible, the interference terms effectively vanish, and the pattern turns into the simple sum of two single-slit patterns even though each detection is still a single hit. So ‚Äúwave‚Äù refers to the spread-out, phase-carrying probability amplitude that can interfere, while ‚Äúparticle‚Äù refers to the quantized, localized detection events and discrete energy/momentum transfer, and the double-slit shows both in one experiment depending on whether the alternatives remain coherent or are distinguished by measurement."),

