    ("What is a food chain? Like can you give me an easy example with a hawk and a mouse and what happens if one of them disappears?", "A food chain is a simple way to show who eats whom in nature, which is how energy from the Sun moves through living things: plants use sunlight to grow, animals eat plants or other animals, and each step passes energy along. An easy example is grass grows, a mouse eats the grass (or seeds), and a hawk eats the mouse, so the chain is grass ‚Üí mouse ‚Üí hawk. If the hawk disappears, more mice may survive and their numbers can grow, which can lead to mice eating more grass and seeds and reducing those plants; if the mouse disappears, hawks have less food so their numbers may drop or they may have to switch to eating other prey, and the plants the mice used to eat may increase because fewer mice are eating them."),

