    # Auto-added 2025-12-25 23:41 - Category: stem_science_earth:renewable_resources
    ("Renewable resources: what‚Äôs the difference between renewable and nonrenewable resources, and why do people say some renewables still have environmental costs?", "Renewable resources are natural resources that can be replaced by nature on a human timescale, meaning they replenish as fast as (or faster than) we use them, such as sunlight, wind, flowing water (hydropower), and sustainably managed biomass like trees grown and replanted; nonrenewable resources exist in limited amounts or take millions of years to form, so using them depletes the supply, such as coal, oil, natural gas, and uranium. People say some renewables still have environmental costs because ‚Äúrenewable‚Äù describes how quickly the resource is replenished, not that it is impact-free: building and running renewable energy systems can require mining and manufacturing (for metals, concrete, and batteries), can change habitats and landscapes (dams can block fish migration and alter river ecosystems; wind turbines can harm some birds and bats; large solar farms can disturb desert or grassland habitats), and biomass can cause air pollution and carbon emissions if burned or if forests are cut faster than they regrow. The key idea is that renewables usually have much lower greenhouse-gas emissions and pollution over their full life cycle than fossil fuels, but they still involve trade-offs, so careful siting, better technology, recycling materials, and sustainable management are important to reduce those impacts."),

