    ("Why do we have national parks in the United States? Like what‚Äôs the point of them?", "National parks exist in the United States to protect special places‚Äîspectacular scenery, unique wildlife and plants, important ecosystems, and historic or cultural sites‚Äîso they don‚Äôt get damaged or used up by logging, mining, heavy development, or uncontrolled tourism, and so people can enjoy them in a responsible way. The idea is often summed up as preserving these lands ‚Äúfor the benefit and enjoyment of the people,‚Äù meaning you can visit, hike, camp, learn, and be inspired, while the government manages the area to keep it healthy for the long term; the National Park Service, created in 1916, is the agency that runs most of them. National parks also help science and education by protecting natural ‚Äúoutdoor laboratories,‚Äù they support local economies through tourism, and they safeguard parts of America‚Äôs natural and cultural heritage‚ÄîYellowstone (established in 1872) is famous as the first U.S. national park and helped set the precedent for protecting extraordinary places for everyone, not just for private profit."),

