    # Auto-added 2025-12-25 23:52 - Category: academic_science:atoms_molecules
    ("what\'s the difference between mitosis and meiosis? i keep mixing them up", "Mitosis and meiosis are both ways cells divide, but they have different jobs and different outcomes. Mitosis is for growth, repair, and asexual reproduction: one cell divides once to make two genetically identical daughter cells, keeping the same number of chromosomes as the original (in humans, 46 stays 46), which is why your skin cells and other body (somatic) cells can replace themselves without changing your DNA. Meiosis is for making sex cells (gametes) like sperm and eggs: one cell divides twice to make four genetically different cells, cutting the chromosome number in half (in humans, 46 becomes 23) and shuffling genes through crossing over and independent assortment, which creates variation and is a key reason offspring differ and populations can evolve. An easy memory trick is ‚ÄúMitosis = Make More of the same‚Äù and ‚ÄúMeiosis = Makes gametes and mixes genes,‚Äù and you can check yourself by asking: does it produce 2 identical cells with the same chromosome number (mitosis) or 4 different cells with half the chromosomes (meiosis)?"),

