    # Auto-added 2025-12-25 23:56 - Category: stem_engineering_design:problem_definition
    ("For an engineering design project, what does ‚Äúproblem definition‚Äù actually include? Like what should I write for criteria + constraints?", "In an engineering design project, ‚Äúproblem definition‚Äù is the clear, testable statement of what needs to be solved and the boundaries you must work within, so it typically includes the user or stakeholder need, the specific goal (what the solution must accomplish), who will use it and where it will be used, the context and assumptions, and how success will be measured. In that write-up, criteria are the measurable requirements used to judge whether a solution is good enough or better than alternatives, so you should write them as performance targets with units and a way to test them (for example, ‚Äúmust support a 500 N load with a safety factor of 2,‚Äù ‚Äúmust reduce temperature to 40¬∞C within 10 minutes,‚Äù ‚Äúmust fit within a 200 mm √ó 150 mm √ó 80 mm envelope,‚Äù ‚Äúmust be assembled in under 15 minutes by one person,‚Äù ‚Äúmust cost under $25 in materials,‚Äù or ‚Äúmust achieve at least 90% accuracy compared to a reference measurement‚Äù), and you can also include ‚Äúwants‚Äù that improve the design (lighter, quieter, more comfortable) as long as you still define how you‚Äôll measure them. Constraints are the non-negotiable limits that restrict the design space, so you should list the fixed conditions you cannot violate, such as budget caps, deadlines, available tools and manufacturing processes, allowed materials, size/weight limits, power availability, environmental conditions (rain, dust, temperature range), compatibility with existing parts, safety and legal requirements (relevant codes/standards), ethical or accessibility requirements, and any resource limits like maximum energy use or limited component availability; a good check is that criteria are what you optimize to make the design successful, while constraints are the hard ‚Äúmust not exceed/ must comply‚Äù boundaries, and both should be written so someone else could verify them by calculation, inspection, or a test procedure."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-25 23:56 - Category: stem_math_applied:mathematical_modeling
    ("I have to make a mathematical model for how fast a candle melts. What variables should I pick and how would I write a basic equation?", "A good candle-melting model starts by choosing a clear ‚Äúoutput‚Äù variable and the main physical drivers. Let m(t) be the candle‚Äôs wax mass remaining (or h(t) the candle height remaining) at time t, and define the melt/burn rate r(t) = ‚àídm/dt (grams per second) or v(t) = ‚àídh/dt (cm per second). The most important variables that affect r are the heat released by the flame (related to wick size and wax type), how efficiently that heat reaches and melts wax (candle diameter/shape and container vs freestanding), and heat losses to the air (ambient temperature, airflow/drafts). A simple first model assumes a constant burn rate under steady conditions, giving dm/dt = ‚àík so m(t) = m0 ‚àí kt (and similarly h(t) = h0 ‚àí vt), where k (or v) is a constant you estimate from data by measuring mass (or height) at several times and fitting a straight line; the candle ‚Äúfinishes‚Äù when m(t) reaches 0. If you want one step more realistic, let the rate depend on airflow or temperature, for example dm/dt = ‚àík0(1 + aU)(1 + b(T0 ‚àí Tair)), where U is a measure of draft speed and Tair is room temperature, with k0, a, and b found by experiments; the key idea is to pick measurable variables, state assumptions (steady flame, constant geometry, no dripping), write the differential equation for the rate of change, and then validate by comparing predicted m(t) or h(t) to your measurements."),

