    ("College calc question: if f(x,y)=x^2y+sin(y), can you walk me through finding the gradient and the directional derivative at (1,0) in direction <3,4>?", "For f(x,y)=x^2y+sin(y), the gradient is ‚àáf(x,y)=<‚àÇf/‚àÇx, ‚àÇf/‚àÇy>. Compute the partial derivatives: ‚àÇf/‚àÇx=2xy (because x^2y differentiates to 2xy and sin(y) has no x), and ‚àÇf/‚àÇy=x^2+cos(y) (because x^2y differentiates to x^2 and sin(y) differentiates to cos(y)), so ‚àáf(x,y)=<2xy, x^2+cos(y)>. At (1,0), this becomes ‚àáf(1,0)=<2¬∑1¬∑0, 1^2+cos(0)>=<0, 2> since cos(0)=1. For the directional derivative in the direction <3,4>, first make it a unit direction vector: its length is sqrt(3^2+4^2)=5, so the unit vector is u=<3/5, 4/5>. The directional derivative is D_u f(1,0)=‚àáf(1,0)¬∑u=<0,2>¬∑<3/5,4/5>=0¬∑(3/5)+2¬∑(4/5)=8/5, meaning f increases at a rate of 8/5 per unit of distance when you move from (1,0) in the direction of <3,4>."),

