    ("For social studies: what‚Äôs the difference between naturalized citizen and someone who‚Äôs a citizen by birth? Do they have the same rights?", "In the United States, a citizen by birth is someone who becomes a U.S. citizen automatically at birth, usually because they were born in the United States and under U.S. jurisdiction (this is called birthright citizenship), or because they were born abroad to U.S.-citizen parent(s) and met the legal requirements for citizenship at birth; a naturalized citizen is someone who was not a U.S. citizen at birth but later chose to become one by going through the legal naturalization process, which typically includes meeting residency and other eligibility rules, applying, passing an English and civics test (with some exceptions), and taking the Oath of Allegiance. In everyday life, naturalized citizens and citizens by birth have the same basic rights and responsibilities, including the right to vote in federal elections, run for most public offices, serve on a jury, get a U.S. passport, and receive full protection under U.S. law. The main difference in rights is that only a ‚Äúnatural-born citizen‚Äù can be President or Vice President of the United States under the Constitution, while naturalized citizens can hold nearly all other jobs and elected offices; also, citizenship obtained through naturalization can be taken away in rare cases if it was gained through serious fraud or certain illegal acts during the process, while citizenship by birth is generally much harder to lose."),

