    ("I‚Äôm 5th grade and we‚Äôre learning about the Constitution‚Äîwhat are the first 10 amendments (Bill of Rights) in super simple terms?", "The Bill of Rights is the first 10 changes (amendments) added to the U.S. Constitution to protect people‚Äôs freedoms and limit government power: The 1st Amendment says you can practice any religion (or none), speak your opinions, write and publish ideas, meet peacefully, and ask the government to fix problems; the 2nd says people can own guns (the right to ‚Äúkeep and bear arms‚Äù); the 3rd says soldiers can‚Äôt be forced to live in your home during peace; the 4th says police usually need a good reason and often a warrant to search you or your stuff or take it; the 5th says you don‚Äôt have to answer questions that would get you in trouble, you must get fair legal steps (due process), you can‚Äôt be tried twice for the same serious crime, and the government can‚Äôt take your property without paying; the 6th says if you‚Äôre accused of a crime you get a speedy, public trial with a jury, a lawyer, and the chance to question witnesses; the 7th says you can have a jury trial in many civil (non-criminal) lawsuits; the 8th says no cruel or unusual punishments and no extreme bail or fines; the 9th says people have other rights too, even if they aren‚Äôt all written down; and the 10th says powers not given to the national government belong to the states or the people."),

