    ("Precalc limits intro: how do you evaluate lim(x‚Üí3) (x^2 ‚àí 9)/(x ‚àí 3) without just plugging in 3? Step-by-step pls.", "To evaluate lim(x‚Üí3) (x^2 ‚àí 9)/(x ‚àí 3) without plugging in 3 right away, first notice that direct substitution gives 0/0, which means you need to simplify the expression. Factor the numerator as a difference of squares: x^2 ‚àí 9 = (x ‚àí 3)(x + 3). Then the expression becomes (x ‚àí 3)(x + 3)/(x ‚àí 3), and for x not equal to 3 you can cancel the common factor (x ‚àí 3), leaving just x + 3. Now take the limit of the simpler function: lim(x‚Üí3) (x + 3) = 3 + 3 = 6, and you can sanity-check this by plugging in values close to 3 (like 2.9 gives 5.9 and 3.1 gives 6.1), which approach 6 from both sides."),

