    ("Is it true that if the left-hand limit and right-hand limit match, the limit exists even if the function value is different? Can you give a quick example?", "Yes: for a real-valued function, the (two-sided) limit lim(x‚Üía) f(x) exists and equals L exactly when both one-sided limits exist and match, meaning lim(x‚Üía‚àí) f(x) = lim(x‚Üía+) f(x) = L, and this is true even if the actual function value f(a) is different (or even undefined). For example, define f(x) = (x^2 ‚àí 1)/(x ‚àí 1) for x ‚â† 1 and set f(1) = 7; for x ‚â† 1 the expression simplifies to f(x) = x + 1, so as x approaches 1 from either side the values approach 2, giving lim(x‚Üí1‚àí) f(x) = lim(x‚Üí1+) f(x) = 2, hence lim(x‚Üí1) f(x) = 2 even though f(1) = 7. This shows the limit depends on nearby values of the function, not necessarily the value at the point itself."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 00:02 - Category: stem_science_physics:electric_fields
    ("Can you help me understand electric field lines like‚Ä¶ why do they spread out and what does ‚Äòfield strength‚Äô actually mean?", "Electric field lines are a drawing tool physicists use to visualize the electric field, which is the ‚Äúpush or pull per unit charge‚Äù that a positive test charge would feel at each point in space; by definition the field points in the direction a tiny positive charge would accelerate, so field lines start on positive charges and end on negative charges (or go off to infinity if there‚Äôs no opposite charge nearby), and they never cross because the field at any one point can only point in one direction. They ‚Äúspread out‚Äù because of how the field from a point charge depends on distance: the same total influence from the charge has to pass through larger and larger imaginary spherical surfaces as you move away, and since a sphere‚Äôs area grows like 4œÄr¬≤, the field strength must drop like 1/r¬≤, so the lines are drawn farther apart to show that weakening; near the charge the lines are crowded, farther away they‚Äôre sparse, which matches the inverse-square law. ‚ÄúField strength‚Äù means the magnitude of the electric field, written E, and it has a precise quantitative meaning: E = F/q, the force F experienced by a small positive test charge divided by the charge q, with units newtons per coulomb (N/C), which is the same as volts per meter (V/m); in field-line pictures, stronger field means more lines per area (higher line density), and weaker field means fewer lines per area, just like how closely spaced contour lines on a map indicate a steeper slope. For example, between two large parallel plates with opposite charge, the lines are straight, parallel, and evenly spaced because the field is nearly uniform (same strength everywhere between the plates), while around a single charged sphere or point charge the lines radiate outward and spread because the field gets weaker with distance."),

