    ("My plant bio lab asked: why do stomata close during hot/dry conditions, and how does that affect photosynthesis? I need a paragraph answer.", "Stomata are tiny pores in the leaf surface that open to let carbon dioxide (CO2) diffuse in for photosynthesis, but when they are open, water vapor also escapes by transpiration; during hot and/or dry conditions the air is often dry and evaporation is fast, so leaving stomata open would cause excessive water loss, loss of cell turgor, and risk of wilting or hydraulic failure. To prevent dehydration, plants signal the guard cells to close the stomata (a key signal is the hormone abscisic acid, ABA, produced during water stress), which reduces transpiration and conserves water. The trade-off is that closing stomata also restricts CO2 entry into the leaf, lowering the internal CO2 concentration, which slows the Calvin cycle and reduces the overall rate of photosynthesis; at the same time, bright light and heat can keep the light reactions supplying energy, so with less CO2 available the plant is more likely to divert energy into photorespiration and protective processes rather than sugar production, further decreasing photosynthetic efficiency."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 00:03 - Category: stem_math_applied:data_science_math
    ("Data science math: my teacher says correlation doesn‚Äôt mean causation‚Äîcan you give a real example and explain what a confounding variable is?", "‚ÄúCorrelation doesn‚Äôt mean causation‚Äù means two things can move together in the data without one actually causing the other. A real example is that ice cream sales and drowning deaths often rise and fall together: they‚Äôre both higher in summer and lower in winter, so they are correlated, but buying ice cream doesn‚Äôt cause drowning. The hidden third factor is the confounding variable, which is a variable that affects both the supposed cause and the outcome and can trick you into thinking there‚Äôs a direct causal link; here, hot weather (or ‚Äúseason‚Äù) increases swimming (raising drowning risk) and also increases ice cream buying, creating the correlation. If you ‚Äúcontrol for‚Äù the confounder by comparing similar temperatures or the same season, the relationship between ice cream and drowning largely disappears, which is a clue that the original correlation was not causal."),

