    ("I‚Äôm making a tiny data project for stats: what‚Äôs the difference between mean vs median when there are outliers, and which one should I report?", "The mean is the arithmetic average (add all values and divide by how many), while the median is the middle value after sorting (or the average of the two middle values if there‚Äôs an even count), and the key difference with outliers is that the mean is pulled toward extreme values whereas the median is much more resistant. For example, in 2, 3, 3, 4, 100 the mean is (2+3+3+4+100)/5 = 22.4, which makes the ‚Äútypical‚Äù value look far larger than most of the data, but the median is 3, which matches where the bulk of values sit; that‚Äôs why with skewed data or clear outliers (like income, house prices, or response times) the median usually better represents a typical observation. Which to report depends on your goal: report the mean when you care about the total or overall level and the distribution is roughly symmetric without extreme outliers (means are also what many statistical methods model), but report the median when you want a robust ‚Äútypical‚Äù value in the presence of outliers or heavy skew; in practice, it‚Äôs often best to report both along with a simple spread measure (like the interquartile range for the median, or standard deviation for the mean) and briefly note that outliers make the mean less representative."),

