    ("I‚Äôm stuck on set theory basics: what‚Äôs the difference between an element and a subset? Like is 2 in {2,4,6} the same as {2}?", "An element is a single object that belongs to a set, and we write that with the symbol ‚àà, while a subset is itself a set whose every element is contained in another set, and we write that with ‚äÜ. For your example A = {2, 4, 6}, the statement 2 ‚àà A is true because 2 is one of the members listed, but {2} is not the same thing as 2: {2} is a set whose only element is 2, so {2} ‚äÜ A is true (everything in {2} is in A), yet {2} ‚àà A is false because A‚Äôs elements are numbers (2, 4, 6), not sets. A good way to remember it is that ‚àà asks ‚Äúis this object in the set?‚Äù while ‚äÜ asks ‚Äúis this whole set contained inside that set?‚Äù and confusing 2 with {2} is like confusing a single book with a one-book library."),

