    ("Set theory help: if A = {1,2,3,4} and B = {3,4,5}, what are A‚à©B and A‚à™B and A\\B? I think I‚Äôm mixing up the symbols.", "Intersection A‚à©B means the elements that are in both sets, so since 3 and 4 appear in A = {1,2,3,4} and also in B = {3,4,5}, you get A‚à©B = {3,4}. Union A‚à™B means all elements that are in A or in B (combine them and remove duplicates), so A‚à™B = {1,2,3,4,5}. The difference A\\B (also written A ‚àí B) means the elements in A that are not in B, so remove 3 and 4 from A and you get A\\B = {1,2}."),

