    ("I‚Äôm doing a group project in my software engineering class‚Äîany tips for using Git without constantly breaking each other‚Äôs code? (merge conflicts are killing us)", "To stop merge conflicts from derailing your group, agree on a simple Git workflow and make it a habit: keep main (or master) always deployable, do all work on short-lived feature branches named clearly (like feature/login or fix/null-check), and merge back through pull requests so at least one teammate reviews before code hits main. Pull often and integrate early by rebasing or merging your branch on top of the latest main at least daily (git fetch then git rebase origin/main, or merge origin/main into your branch if your class prefers), because conflicts get exponentially worse the longer branches drift; after you resolve conflicts, run tests and the app locally before pushing. Make conflicts rarer by dividing work along module boundaries (one person owns a file or folder at a time), avoiding ‚Äúeveryone edits the same giant file‚Äù patterns, and keeping changes small and focused so each PR does one thing; also format code consistently with an auto-formatter (Prettier, Black, gofmt, etc.) and commit the config, since inconsistent formatting creates noisy diffs that trigger conflicts. When conflicts do happen, treat them like a debugging task: use git status to see what‚Äôs conflicted, open the file and understand both sides (HEAD vs incoming), choose the correct logic rather than blindly keeping one side, then git add the resolved files and continue the rebase/merge; tools like VS Code‚Äôs merge editor, IntelliJ‚Äôs diff tool, or git mergetool make this much easier. Finally, protect yourselves with process: enable branch protection so nobody pushes directly to main, require PR reviews and passing CI (at minimum unit tests and a build), write clear commit messages, and communicate before big refactors‚Äîif someone must rename/move lots of files, do it in its own PR and merge it quickly so everyone can rebase right away."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 00:05 - Category: us_symbols:liberty_bell
    ("US symbols: what‚Äôs the Liberty Bell and why is it important? I need 6-8 sentences for a history assignment.", "The Liberty Bell is a famous American symbol that was made in 1752 for the Pennsylvania State House in Philadelphia, which is now called Independence Hall. It is important because it became closely connected with the ideas of freedom and self-government during the American Revolution, and it later became a powerful symbol for people fighting for equal rights. The bell is traditionally associated with July 8, 1776, when the Declaration of Independence was publicly read in Philadelphia, although historians are not certain the bell actually rang on that exact day. It has a large crack, and while the bell was used for years, it cracked badly in the 1800s and could no longer be rung. An inscription on the bell reads, ‚ÄúProclaim Liberty Throughout All the Land Unto All the Inhabitants Thereof,‚Äù a Bible verse that helped inspire its meaning as a liberty symbol. In the 1800s, abolitionists used the name ‚ÄúLiberty Bell‚Äù to connect the bell to the movement to end slavery, and later it was also linked to women‚Äôs suffrage and civil rights. Today the Liberty Bell is displayed at the Liberty Bell Center in Philadelphia, where visitors learn how its history reflects the ongoing struggle to expand freedom in the United States."),

