    ("Is the crack in the Liberty Bell actually from when it was rung, or is that like a myth? What‚Äôs the real story?", "The crack in the Liberty Bell isn‚Äôt a made-up myth, but the ‚Äúit cracked from one dramatic ring‚Äù version is oversimplified; the real story is that the bell had trouble almost from the start and the famous crack grew over time. The bell was cast in 1752 in London for Philadelphia, but it cracked on one of its first test rings, so it was melted down and recast twice in Philadelphia by John Pass and John Stow, whose names are on the bell. For decades it was rung for public events, but by the early 1800s a small crack had formed, and in 1846‚Äîwhen it was rung for George Washington‚Äôs Birthday‚Äîthe crack spread badly. To keep it from breaking further, workers cut the crack into the wide, visible ‚Äúkeyhole‚Äù shape you see today, but the bell still couldn‚Äôt be rung safely afterward, so it became a symbol rather than a working bell."),

