    ("Ecosystems: can you explain the difference between a food chain and a food web, and what happens if you remove a top predator?", "A food chain is a simple, linear pathway that shows who eats whom in an ecosystem, such as grass being eaten by a rabbit and the rabbit being eaten by a fox, while a food web is a more realistic network of many connected food chains because most organisms have more than one food source and more than one predator (for example, a fox might eat rabbits, mice, and birds, and those prey animals eat different plants or insects). If you remove a top predator (an apex predator like a wolf, shark, or big cat), prey populations often increase because there is less predation, and that can trigger a trophic cascade: the overabundant prey may overgraze plants or reduce smaller animals, which can lower plant cover, change habitats, reduce biodiversity, and even affect soil and water conditions; a well-known example is that fewer wolves can allow deer or elk to grow in number, leading to heavier browsing of young trees and shrubs and fewer places for other species to live. Food webs help explain why these changes can spread widely, because when one important species is removed, many feeding relationships are disrupted at once, not just a single chain."),

