    ("I wanna get better at dancing for pep rallies but I‚Äôm super awkward. What‚Äôs a realistic practice plan for learning a short routine in 2 weeks?", "A realistic two-week plan is to practice a little every day, focusing on repetition and confidence instead of trying to ‚Äúnot be awkward‚Äù all at once. First, get the routine video (or have a friend record it) and spend Day 1 watching it several times, then learn it in small chunks: on Days 2‚Äì4, practice just the first 15‚Äì30 seconds until you can do it without stopping, using a slow speed (like 0.75x) and counting the beats out loud (‚Äú1-and-2-and‚Ä¶‚Äù) so your body learns the timing; on Days 5‚Äì7, learn the next chunk the same way, then connect the two chunks and do three clean run-throughs in a row before you end each session. In Week 2, shift from ‚Äúlearning‚Äù to ‚Äúperforming‚Äù: on Days 8‚Äì10, do the full routine at least 5 times per practice, first slowly and then at full speed, and record yourself once per day so you can pick one specific fix (like sharper arms, bigger steps, or cleaner turns) instead of trying to fix everything; on Days 11‚Äì13, practice like it‚Äôs the pep rally by doing a quick warm-up (march in place, shoulder rolls, light stretching), then two full-energy run-throughs with your face up and eyes forward, then one ‚Äúperformance‚Äù take on video, and finish by drilling the two hardest 8-counts three times each. On Day 14, keep it light: one warm-up, two confident run-throughs, and stop before you‚Äôre tired so you don‚Äôt build sloppy habits. Keep sessions short and consistent (about 20‚Äì30 minutes on school days, 45 minutes on weekend days), and use simple confidence tricks that make a big difference fast: practice in front of a mirror for arms and posture, mark the moves smaller when you‚Äôre learning and go full-size once you know them, pick one ‚Äúanchor‚Äù move you always hit hard (like a clap, punch, or head turn) to look intentional, and if you mess up, keep moving and rejoin on the next obvious beat because the crowd notices energy more than perfection."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 00:08 - Category: high_chemistry:periodic_trends
    ("In gen chem, can you explain why atomic radius decreases across a period but increases down a group? I get the trend but not the actual ‚Äúwhy.‚Äù", "Across a period (left to right), atomic radius decreases because each step adds a proton to the nucleus while the added electron usually goes into the same principal energy level (same n shell), so shielding doesn‚Äôt increase much; the result is a higher effective nuclear charge (often written Zeff), meaning the valence electrons feel a stronger net pull toward the nucleus and the electron cloud contracts. Down a group (top to bottom), atomic radius increases because each step adds a new principal energy level, placing valence electrons in a shell that is farther from the nucleus and much more shielded by the inner electrons; even though nuclear charge increases, the increased distance and shielding dominate, so the outer electrons are held less tightly and the atom gets larger. A helpful way to picture it is ‚Äúacross: stronger pull on the same floor, so the cloud shrinks; down: you add a whole new floor farther out, so the atom expands,‚Äù and this is why trends in ionization energy and electronegativity generally move opposite to radius across a period and similarly to radius down a group."),

