    ("In my mechanics class we‚Äôre doing dynamics: if a car is taking a flat turn, how do you set up the free-body diagram to find the max speed before it slips? Assume a coefficient of friction and a turn radius.", "For a car of mass m making a level (unbanked) turn of radius r on a flat road, draw the free-body diagram with three forces: the weight mg acting straight down, the normal force N from the road acting straight up, and the static friction force fs acting horizontally toward the center of the turn (this friction is what provides the needed centripetal acceleration). Choose axes with x pointing radially inward and y vertical; then write Œ£Fy = 0 because there‚Äôs no vertical acceleration, giving N ‚àí mg = 0 so N = mg, and write Œ£Fx = m v^2/r inward, giving fs = m v^2/r. The car is just about to slip when the required friction reaches the maximum available static friction, fs,max = Œºs N = Œºs mg, so set m v^2/r = Œºs mg and solve for the maximum speed: vmax = sqrt(Œºs g r); if the speed is higher than this, the needed centripetal force exceeds what friction can supply and the car will start to skid outward."),

