    ("Web dev: I built a React app and an Express API. What‚Äôs the simplest way to deploy both so my professor can actually test it (domain not required)? Like, what goes on Vercel vs Render vs AWS?", "The simplest ‚Äúprofessor can test it today‚Äù setup is to deploy the React front end as a static site on Vercel (or Netlify) and deploy the Express API as a separate web service on Render (or Railway/Fly.io), then point the React app at the API‚Äôs public URL via an environment variable; concretely, you push both projects to GitHub, import the React repo into Vercel (it auto-builds with npm run build and hosts the static output, giving you a vercel.app URL), import the Express repo into Render as a Web Service (set the start command like npm start or node server.js, make sure your server listens on process.env.PORT, and add any env vars like DATABASE_URL or JWT_SECRET), then in Vercel set something like VITE_API_URL or REACT_APP_API_URL to https://your-api.onrender.com and use that in fetch/axios calls. For local dev you might have used a proxy, but in production you must handle CORS: in Express enable CORS for your Vercel origin (e.g., allow https://your-frontend.vercel.app) and allow credentials only if you truly need cookies; also avoid hardcoding localhost anywhere. If you want it to feel like ‚Äúone site,‚Äù you can optionally add a rewrite on Vercel so requests to /api/ are forwarded to the Render API, but it‚Äôs not required for grading‚Äîtwo URLs is fine as long as the front end calls the right API URL. Vercel is best for the React front end because it‚Äôs optimized for static/Next.js hosting, instant previews, and free HTTPS; Render is best for Express because it runs a long-lived Node process and can attach databases; AWS can do everything but is usually overkill for a class demo because you‚Äôd need to choose and configure services (S3/CloudFront for React, and Elastic Beanstalk/ECS/Lambda+API Gateway for Express) plus IAM, networking, and more setup. Before submitting, test the deployed front end in an incognito window, confirm API endpoints work from the browser (no CORS errors), and include both URLs plus any test credentials or seed data instructions so your professor can click and verify quickly."),

