    ("Can you explain what an atom is in kid words? Is an atom smaller than a cell?", "An atom is the tiniest building block that makes up everything around you, like a super-tiny LEGO piece that can join with other atoms to make bigger things such as water, air, your desk, and even your body; atoms are made of an even tinier center called the nucleus (with protons and neutrons) and electrons that move around it. Yes, an atom is much smaller than a cell: a cell is a living ‚Äúroom‚Äù in your body (or in plants and animals) that does jobs to keep you alive, and it is made of an enormous number of atoms. To picture the size difference, if a cell were as big as a sports stadium, an atom would be far too small to see even then, because a typical cell is about 10 to 100 micrometers across while a typical atom is about 0.1 nanometer across, meaning a cell is roughly 100,000 to 1,000,000 times wider than an atom."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 00:36 - Category: academic_science:atoms_molecules
    ("What are molecules made of? I keep mixing up atom vs molecule and it\'s driving me crazy.", "Molecules are made of atoms that are chemically bonded together, so an atom is a single basic unit of an element (like one oxygen atom O or one carbon atom C), while a molecule is a group of two or more atoms stuck together in a specific arrangement (like oxygen gas O2, water H2O, or carbon dioxide CO2). If the atoms in a molecule are all the same element, it‚Äôs still a molecule (O2 is a molecule made of only oxygen atoms), and if the atoms are different elements, it‚Äôs a compound (H2O is a compound because it contains hydrogen and oxygen). A helpful way to remember it is: atoms are like individual LEGO bricks, and molecules are the structures you build when bricks snap together; the type and number of atoms determine what the molecule is and what properties it has."),

