    ("In a tundra biome, what adaptations help animals survive? Give examples like 2 animals + how they cope.", "Animals in the tundra survive extreme cold, strong winds, and long, dark winters by having adaptations like thick insulation (dense fur or feathers and a layer of fat called blubber), compact bodies with small ears and short legs to reduce heat loss, seasonal color change for camouflage, and behaviors such as burrowing, huddling, or migrating when food is scarce. For example, the Arctic fox grows a very thick winter coat and has furry foot pads that act like warm ‚Äúsnow boots,‚Äù and its fur turns white in winter to blend into snow while it hunts small animals and scavenges; in summer it becomes brown or gray to match the tundra ground. Another example is the caribou (reindeer), which has a thick coat with hollow hairs that trap air for insulation, wide hooves that work like snowshoes and also help it dig through snow to reach lichens, and it migrates in large herds to find better feeding areas as seasons change."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 00:38 - Category: us_civics:citizenship
    ("What does it mean to be a U.S. citizen vs a permanent resident? I‚Äôm writing a paragraph and don‚Äôt want to mess it up.", "A U.S. citizen is a person who has full membership in the United States, usually by being born in the U.S. or certain U.S. territories, being born to U.S.-citizen parent(s) in some situations, or by naturalizing after meeting legal requirements; a lawful permanent resident (often called a ‚Äúgreen card‚Äù holder) is not a citizen but has permission to live and work in the U.S. permanently. Citizens can vote in federal elections, serve on juries, hold many government jobs that require citizenship, and run for most elected offices (the President and Vice President must be natural-born citizens), and they cannot be deported for most reasons; permanent residents generally cannot vote in federal elections, may be limited from certain jobs and offices, and can lose their status and be removed from the U.S. if they commit certain crimes, commit immigration fraud, or abandon U.S. residence by staying away too long. Both citizens and permanent residents can live and work in the U.S. and must follow U.S. laws and pay taxes, but only citizens automatically pass citizenship to their children in all cases and have the strongest right to re-enter the country, while permanent residents must carry proof of status and should keep the U.S. as their main home; many permanent residents can later apply to become citizens, often after 5 years (or 3 years if married to a U.S. citizen) if they meet the rules."),

