    ("I‚Äôm in Algebra 2 and sequences are killing me. If a1=7 and the common difference is -3, what‚Äôs a5 and the explicit formula?", "This is an arithmetic sequence because it has a common difference d = -3, so each term is 3 less than the one before it. Use the arithmetic formula an = a1 + (n ‚àí 1)d: for a5, plug in n = 5 to get a5 = 7 + (5 ‚àí 1)(‚àí3) = 7 + 4(‚àí3) = 7 ‚àí 12 = ‚àí5, and the explicit formula is an = 7 + (n ‚àí 1)(‚àí3), which can also be simplified to an = 10 ‚àí 3n. You can quickly check: a1 = 10 ‚àí 3(1) = 7 and then the terms go 7, 4, 1, ‚àí2, ‚àí5, so the answer is consistent."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 00:39 - Category: high_math_precalc:functions_advanced
    ("Precalc help: how do I find the inverse of f(x)= (2x-3)/(x+4) and what restrictions do I need?", "To find the inverse of f(x) = (2x ‚àí 3)/(x + 4), first note the domain restriction for the original function: x + 4 ‚â† 0, so x ‚â† ‚àí4. Now set y = (2x ‚àí 3)/(x + 4) and solve for x in terms of y: multiply both sides by (x + 4) to get y(x + 4) = 2x ‚àí 3, expand to yx + 4y = 2x ‚àí 3, then collect x-terms on one side: yx ‚àí 2x = ‚àí3 ‚àí 4y, factor x: x(y ‚àí 2) = ‚àí(3 + 4y), and divide to get x = ‚àí(3 + 4y)/(y ‚àí 2). Swap x and y to write the inverse: f‚Åª¬π(x) = ‚àí(3 + 4x)/(x ‚àí 2), which can also be written as (3 + 4x)/(2 ‚àí x). For restrictions, the inverse‚Äôs domain equals the original function‚Äôs range, so you must exclude the value that would make the inverse undefined: x ‚àí 2 ‚â† 0, so x ‚â† 2. (Indeed, f(x) can never equal 2 because (2x ‚àí 3)/(x + 4) = 2 would imply 2x ‚àí 3 = 2x + 8, which is impossible.) The inverse‚Äôs range equals the original function‚Äôs domain, so f‚Åª¬π(x) will never output ‚àí4, matching the original restriction x ‚â† ‚àí4."),

