    ("What do surveyors actually measure on construction sites? Like how do they make sure a road is built in the right place?", "Surveyors on construction sites measure position and elevation so everything is built in the correct horizontal location (x and y) and at the correct height (z) compared to the design. They start by tying the project to a known coordinate system using control points and benchmarks (permanent reference marks with known coordinates and elevations), then they use instruments like total stations (measuring angles and distances), GNSS/GPS receivers (measuring coordinates from satellites), and levels (measuring height differences) to check existing ground, map features, and set out the design. To make sure a road is built in the right place, they ‚Äústake out‚Äù the alignment by marking the designed centerline and edges on the ground, placing stakes or paint at specific stations/chainages and offsets, and setting grade stakes that tell the crew how high or low the surface should be at that location; during construction they repeatedly verify that the built work matches the plan by measuring the as-built centerline, lane widths, curb lines, slopes (crossfall/superelevation), and elevations, and they also monitor tolerances and settlement so the finished road ends up exactly where the drawings and legal right-of-way require."),

