    ("Do you have any test-taking tips for multiple choice when two answers look right? I always second-guess myself.", "When two multiple-choice answers both seem right, slow down and turn the question into a ‚Äúprove it‚Äù challenge: cover the choices, restate what the question is truly asking in your own words, and predict what a correct answer must include (a key word, a definition, a unit, a time period, a cause, or a detail). Then compare the two ‚Äúgood‚Äù options and look for what makes one more precise: one choice often has a small mistake, is too broad, uses absolute words like ‚Äúalways‚Äù or ‚Äúnever‚Äù (which are often wrong unless the topic is truly absolute), or answers a different question than the one asked; also watch for choices that are true statements but not the best answer. Go back to the passage, chart, or problem and force each option to match the evidence: if you can‚Äôt point to a specific line, number, or rule that supports it, treat it as weaker. If you‚Äôre stuck, use elimination by asking, ‚ÄúWhich option would a teacher mark wrong, and why?‚Äù and choose the one that fits every part of the question with no extra assumptions; finally, if you already chose an answer, only change it if you find clear evidence you misread something or you can explain exactly why the new choice is better‚Äîotherwise your first well-reasoned pick is usually your best."),

