    ("I‚Äôm in 5th grade‚Äîwhat‚Äôs the difference between a citizen and a resident in the United States? My homework sheet is confusing.", "In the United States, a citizen is a person who legally belongs to the country and has the full set of rights and responsibilities that come with that, while a resident is someone who lives in the United States but may or may not be a citizen. U.S. citizens can vote in federal elections, can get a U.S. passport, can serve on a jury, and cannot be deported; they also have duties like following laws and paying taxes. Residents also must follow laws and pay taxes, and they can live, work, and go to school here, but most residents cannot vote in federal elections and do not get a U.S. passport; some residents are ‚Äúlawful permanent residents‚Äù (often called green card holders) who can live and work here long-term but can still lose that status and be deported if they break certain immigration rules. People can become U.S. citizens by being born in the United States, being born to U.S. citizen parent(s) in some cases, or by going through a process called naturalization after meeting requirements, and a simple way to remember it is that ‚Äúresident‚Äù means you live here, but ‚Äúcitizen‚Äù means you officially belong to the country with the strongest legal rights."),

