    ("I have a civics quiz: what‚Äôs the difference between the House and the Senate, and why do we have two parts of Congress?", "The House of Representatives and the Senate are the two chambers of Congress, and they differ mainly in how they represent people and how long members serve. The House is based on population, so states with more people get more representatives, for a total of 435 voting members, and House members serve 2-year terms, which makes the House more closely tied to voters and more likely to respond quickly to public opinion; the House also has special powers like starting bills that raise taxes and impeaching federal officials. The Senate gives equal representation to every state, with 2 senators per state for a total of 100, and senators serve 6-year terms with elections staggered so only about one-third are up at a time; the Senate has special powers like confirming presidential appointments, approving treaties by a two-thirds vote, and holding impeachment trials. We have two parts of Congress because the Constitution created a compromise between big states and small states: the House represents the people based on population, while the Senate represents the states equally, and requiring both chambers to pass the same bill also adds a check that encourages debate and prevents laws from being made too quickly."),

