    ("I keep mixing up the Bill of Rights and the Constitution. Can you explain how they relate, with 2 examples of rights we have?", "The Constitution is the main rulebook that created the U.S. government, explained how it works (Congress makes laws, the President enforces them, and courts interpret them), and listed what powers the federal government has, while the Bill of Rights is the name for the first ten amendments that were added to the Constitution in 1791 to protect individual freedoms and to limit what the federal government can do to people. A simple way to remember it is that the Constitution sets up the system, and the Bill of Rights adds specific ‚Äúyou can‚Äôt do that to me‚Äù protections inside that same document. For example, the First Amendment protects freedoms like speech and religion, meaning the government generally cannot punish you just for expressing an opinion or for practicing a faith (or no faith), and the Fourth Amendment protects you from unreasonable searches and seizures, meaning police usually need a lawful reason and often a warrant from a judge to search your home or take your property."),

