    ("We‚Äôre doing a mock election in class. What are the steps of the U.S. presidential election process in a simple timeline?", "A simple timeline of the U.S. presidential election goes like this: First, people who want to run become candidates and campaign, and each party holds state primaries and caucuses to choose its nominee, then the parties officially pick their nominees at national conventions and the nominees choose running mates for vice president. Next comes the general election campaign, and on Election Day in early November voters in each state cast ballots; those votes decide which candidate wins that state‚Äôs Electoral College electors (in almost all states it‚Äôs winner-take-all). After that, in mid-December the electors meet in their states and vote for president and vice president, Congress counts those electoral votes in early January, and the winner is inaugurated and takes office on January 20."),

