    ("In algebra 2, how do you find the inverse of f(x)=3x-7 and how do you know you did it right?", "To find the inverse of f(x)=3x‚àí7, start by writing y=3x‚àí7, then swap x and y because an inverse switches inputs and outputs: x=3y‚àí7. Now solve for y: add 7 to both sides to get x+7=3y, then divide by 3 to get y=(x+7)/3, so f^(-1)(x)=(x+7)/3. You know it‚Äôs right by composing the functions and getting back x: f(f^(-1)(x))=3((x+7)/3)‚àí7=x+7‚àí7=x, and f^(-1)(f(x))=((3x‚àí7)+7)/3=3x/3=x; since both compositions simplify to x, the inverse is correct (and because the slope 3 is not zero, the original function is one-to-one, so an inverse function exists)."),

