    ("I‚Äôm confused on scientific notation‚Äîhow do you write 0.0000471 and 6,300,000 in scientific notation and then multiply them?", "To write 0.0000471 in scientific notation, move the decimal 5 places to the right to make a number between 1 and 10: 4.71, so 0.0000471 = 4.71 √ó 10^-5 (the exponent is negative because the original number is less than 1). To write 6,300,000 in scientific notation, move the decimal 6 places to the left to make 6.3, so 6,300,000 = 6.3 √ó 10^6. Now multiply: (4.71 √ó 10^-5)(6.3 √ó 10^6) = (4.71 √ó 6.3) √ó 10^(-5+6) = 29.673 √ó 10^1, and since scientific notation needs the front number to be between 1 and 10, rewrite 29.673 √ó 10^1 as 2.9673 √ó 10^2 (move the decimal one place left and increase the exponent by 1). A quick check: 0.0000471 √ó 6,300,000 should be a few hundredths times a few million, so a few hundred makes sense, and 2.9673 √ó 10^2 = 296.73."),

