    ("Gas laws help pls: A gas is 2.0 L at 1.0 atm and 300 K. What volume would it be at 0.80 atm and 350 K? (Show steps so I can do similar ones.)", "Use the combined gas law (same amount of gas): P1V1/T1 = P2V2/T2. Write what you know: P1 = 1.0 atm, V1 = 2.0 L, T1 = 300 K, and P2 = 0.80 atm, T2 = 350 K, with V2 unknown. Solve for V2 by rearranging: V2 = (P1V1T2)/(P2T1). Substitute numbers with units: V2 = (1.0 atm √ó 2.0 L √ó 350 K)/(0.80 atm √ó 300 K) = (700 atm¬∑L¬∑K)/(240 atm¬∑K) = 2.916‚Ä¶ L, and atm and K cancel leaving liters, so V2 ‚âà 2.9 L (or 2.92 L); quick reasonableness check: pressure goes down (so volume should go up) and temperature goes up (so volume should go up), so a final volume larger than 2.0 L makes sense."),

