    ("My class is weirdly divided into cliques and group projects always turn into drama. Any advice on handling classroom dynamics without sounding like a teacher‚Äôs pet?", "Start by aiming to be ‚Äúneutral and useful‚Äù rather than trying to fix the whole class: in group projects, suggest simple, practical structures that reduce drama without calling anyone out, like agreeing on one shared goal, splitting the work into clear roles (research, writing, slides, speaking), and setting a quick check-in time so nobody feels ignored or bossed around. When cliques make things tense, use low-key bridge moves that don‚Äôt look like sucking up to the teacher, such as sitting with different people occasionally, asking specific classmates for their opinion (‚ÄúYou‚Äôre good at visuals‚Äîwhat do you think would look best?‚Äù), and giving credit out loud when someone contributes, because that builds trust fast. If conflict starts, keep your language calm and specific: describe the problem in terms of the task (‚ÄúWe‚Äôre stuck because we don‚Äôt know who‚Äôs doing the intro‚Äù) and offer two choices (‚ÄúI can draft the intro or make the slide outline‚Äîwhat do you want?‚Äù), and if someone is being rude, set a boundary without escalating (‚ÄúI‚Äôm happy to work, but I‚Äôm not doing insults; let‚Äôs stick to the project‚Äù). To avoid ‚Äúteacher‚Äôs pet‚Äù vibes, try solving it within the group first, then only involve the teacher when there‚Äôs a clear project-impacting issue like someone refusing to work, repeated disrespect, or you‚Äôre worried about safety; when you do talk to the teacher, frame it as wanting the project to run smoothly and ask for a neutral fix (like clearer roles, a peer-evaluation form, or switching groups) rather than blaming a person. Over time, being the person who stays calm, shares the workload fairly, and keeps things organized makes you respected, not labeled, and it usually lowers the drama because people know you‚Äôre focused on getting it done.")