    ("We‚Äôre doing a mini design challenge: build a cardboard chair that holds 20 lbs. Can you give me a quick brainstorming method and 5 design ideas to test?", "Start with a fast ‚ÄúDefine‚ÄìDiverge‚ÄìDecide‚ÄìDetail‚Äù brainstorm: define the goal and constraints in one sentence (hold 20 lb, cardboard only, size limits, time, allowed tape/glue), then diverge for 5 minutes by sketching lots of tiny thumbnail chairs while forcing variety using prompts like ‚Äúchange the load path,‚Äù ‚Äúchange the shape,‚Äù and ‚Äúchange the joints,‚Äù then decide by circling the 2‚Äì3 sketches that clearly send the weight straight down into the floor with the fewest weak bends, and finally detail those by labeling where the forces go (compression in legs, bending in seat, shear at joints) and what you‚Äôll reinforce (folds, ribs, gussets). Five design ideas to test are: a folded ‚ÄúU-beam‚Äù chair where the seat and two side legs are one continuous piece folded into a U shape with doubled layers at the bends to prevent buckling; a corrugated ‚ÄúI-beam seat‚Äù chair that uses two flat seat skins separated by vertical cardboard ribs (like an I-beam/box beam) so the seat resists bending while four simple legs carry compression; a honeycomb/egg-crate core chair where the seat is a grid of interlocking slotted strips (like a cardboard lattice) topped with a thin skin, spreading the load across many small cells; a triangular truss chair where the sides are made from repeated triangles (trusses) with a flat seat on top, because triangles keep their shape and turn bending into compression/tension along members; and a cantilever ‚Äúbox column‚Äù chair where each leg is a rectangular tube (box column) made by rolling/folding cardboard into closed sections, since closed tubes resist buckling much better than flat panels, with gusseted corners under the seat to stop wobble."),

