    ("In 4th grade reading, my teacher says I need to use transition words. What are some good ones for sequencing events (like first/then/after that) and when do I use them?", "Transition words are ‚Äútime-order‚Äù words that help your reader follow the order of events in a story or explanation, and you use them when you want to show what happened first, next, and last. For starting an event sequence, you can use ‚Äúfirst,‚Äù ‚Äúto begin with,‚Äù or ‚Äúin the beginning‚Äù; for the middle steps, use ‚Äúnext,‚Äù ‚Äúthen,‚Äù ‚Äúafter that,‚Äù ‚Äúlater,‚Äù ‚Äúsoon,‚Äù ‚Äúmeanwhile‚Äù (when two things are happening at the same time), or ‚Äúduring‚Äù (to show something happening within the same time); for showing something happens right away, use ‚Äúimmediately‚Äù or ‚Äúat once‚Äù; for showing something happens after a long time, use ‚Äúeventually‚Äù; and for ending, use ‚Äúfinally,‚Äù ‚Äúat last,‚Äù or ‚Äúin the end.‚Äù For example: ‚ÄúFirst, I packed my bag. Next, I got on the bus. After that, we arrived at the museum. Meanwhile, my friend bought tickets. Finally, we went inside,‚Äù and you can add these words at the beginning of a sentence or in the middle to make the timeline clear."),

