    ("In precalc I‚Äôm stuck on polar coordinates‚Äîhow do I convert r = 4cos(Œ∏) into a Cartesian equation and sketch it? I keep getting the wrong graph.", "To convert r = 4cos(Œ∏) to Cartesian, use the identities x = rcos(Œ∏), y = rsin(Œ∏), and r^2 = x^2 + y^2, and also note that cos(Œ∏) = x/r (as long as r ‚â† 0, and the final equation will still include the origin correctly). Starting with r = 4cos(Œ∏), substitute cos(Œ∏) = x/r to get r = 4(x/r), then multiply both sides by r to get r^2 = 4x; now replace r^2 with x^2 + y^2 to obtain x^2 + y^2 = 4x. Complete the square in x: x^2 ‚àí 4x + y^2 = 0 becomes (x ‚àí 2)^2 + y^2 = 4, which is a circle centered at (2, 0) with radius 2, so it touches the origin and extends to (4, 0). To sketch it, draw the x- and y-axes, plot the center at (2, 0), mark points 2 units left and right of the center along the x-axis (at x = 0 and x = 4), and 2 units up and down (at (2, 2) and (2, ‚àí2)), then draw the circle through those points; a quick polar check also helps: at Œ∏ = 0, r = 4 gives (4, 0), at Œ∏ = œÄ/2, r = 0 gives the origin, and at Œ∏ = œÄ, r = ‚àí4 gives the same point (4, 0), confirming the circle is entirely on or to the right of the y-axis."),

