    ("Can you show me step-by-step how to factor this polynomial: 2x^3 3x^2 8x + 12? Also how do you know which grouping to try?", "To factor 2x^3 ‚àí 3x^2 ‚àí 8x + 12 by grouping, first group the four terms into two pairs: (2x^3 ‚àí 3x^2) + (‚àí8x + 12). Now factor out the greatest common factor from each pair: from 2x^3 ‚àí 3x^2 you can factor x^2 to get x^2(2x ‚àí 3), and from ‚àí8x + 12 you can factor ‚àí4 to get ‚àí4(2x ‚àí 3). Because both groups now share the same binomial factor (2x ‚àí 3), you can factor that out: x^2(2x ‚àí 3) ‚àí 4(2x ‚àí 3) = (2x ‚àí 3)(x^2 ‚àí 4). Finally, factor the difference of squares x^2 ‚àí 4 as (x ‚àí 2)(x + 2), giving the complete factorization (2x ‚àí 3)(x ‚àí 2)(x + 2). You know which grouping to try by aiming to create a common binomial after factoring each pair: a practical strategy is to group the first two terms and last two terms (or sometimes first and third, second and fourth) and then factor out the GCF from each group; if the leftover parentheses match (up to a sign), the grouping works, and if they don‚Äôt match, you try a different pairing or factor out a negative to make them match. As a quick check, multiply back: (x^2 ‚àí 4)(2x ‚àí 3) = (2x^3 ‚àí 3x^2) + (‚àí8x + 12) = 2x^3 ‚àí 3x^2 ‚àí 8x + 12, so the factorization is correct."),

