    ("What does my city council actually do vs the mayor? Explain it like I‚Äôm in 3rd grade because I‚Äôm making a worksheet for my cousin.", "Your city council and your mayor are both in charge of helping run your city, but they have different jobs. The city council is like a team of rule-makers: they listen to what people in different neighborhoods need, they vote on local laws (often called ordinances), they decide how the city‚Äôs money is spent by approving the budget, and they can approve big plans like building parks, fixing roads, or setting rules for things like noise and trash pickup. The mayor is like the team leader: the mayor helps make sure the city‚Äôs workers and departments (like police, fire, parks, and public works) do their jobs, can suggest ideas and a budget for the council to vote on, represents the city at events, and may be able to sign or veto (say ‚Äúno‚Äù to) a law the council passes, depending on the city. A simple way to remember it is: the council decides and votes on the rules and the money, and the mayor helps carry out the plan and manage the city day-to-day."),

