    ("Thermochemistry question: If I dissolve NH4NO3 in water and the temperature drops, how do I decide if ŒîH is positive or negative, and what‚Äôs happening at the particle level?", "If dissolving NH4NO3 in water makes the temperature of the solution drop, the dissolving process is absorbing heat from its surroundings (the water and container), so the enthalpy change for the process NH4NO3(s) ‚Üí NH4+(aq) + NO3‚àí(aq) is positive (ŒîHsolution > 0), meaning it is endothermic; a quick sign check is: temperature decreases implies the system took in heat, so qsurroundings < 0 and qsystem > 0, and at constant pressure ŒîH ‚âà qsystem, so ŒîH is positive. At the particle level, two main energy changes compete: energy is required to pull NH4NO3‚Äôs ions apart from the crystal lattice (breaking ion‚Äìion attractions, which costs energy), and energy is released when water molecules surround and stabilize the separated NH4+ and NO3‚àí ions (forming ion‚Äìdipole attractions, called hydration, which releases energy); for ammonium nitrate, the lattice-breaking cost is larger than the hydration energy released, so the net result is energy absorbed from the water, the average kinetic energy of the water molecules decreases, and you observe a lower temperature even though the salt is dissolving."),

