    ("Precalc inverse functions: how do I find f^{-1}(x) for f(x) = (3x 5)/(2x + 1) and what restrictions do I need on the domain?", "Let y = (3x ‚àí 5)/(2x + 1); the original function is undefined when 2x + 1 = 0, so its domain must exclude x = ‚àí1/2. Solve for x in terms of y: y(2x + 1) = 3x ‚àí 5, so 2yx + y = 3x ‚àí 5, then bring x-terms together: 2yx ‚àí 3x = ‚àí5 ‚àí y, factor: x(2y ‚àí 3) = ‚àí(y + 5), so x = ‚àí(y + 5)/(2y ‚àí 3). Now swap x and y to get the inverse: f‚Åª¬π(x) = ‚àí(x + 5)/(2x ‚àí 3) (equivalently, (x + 5)/(3 ‚àí 2x)). For restrictions, f(x) cannot equal 3/2 because (3x ‚àí 5)/(2x + 1) = 3/2 would imply 2(3x ‚àí 5) = 3(2x + 1), giving 6x ‚àí 10 = 6x + 3, which is impossible, so the range of f excludes y = 3/2; therefore the domain of f‚Åª¬π must exclude x = 3/2, and correspondingly f‚Åª¬π(x) will never output ‚àí1/2, matching the original domain restriction."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 00:51 - Category: stem_tech_web_dev:backend_basics
    ("I‚Äôm building a simple web app for class‚Äîcan you explain backend basics like routes, controllers, database CRUD, and what an API endpoint is? I‚Äôm using Node/Express.", "In a Node/Express backend, a route is the rule that matches an incoming HTTP request (a method like GET/POST/PUT/DELETE plus a URL path like /students or /students/:id) and decides what code should run; an API endpoint is simply one specific route that clients can call to get or change data, like GET /api/students (fetch a list) or POST /api/students (create a new student). A controller is the function that contains the ‚Äúwhat should happen‚Äù logic for that endpoint: it reads inputs from req.params (URL parts like :id), req.query (query string like ?page=2), and req.body (JSON sent by the client), validates them, calls the database layer, and then sends a response with res.status(...).json(...) (usually JSON plus an HTTP status code like 200 OK, 201 Created, 400 Bad Request, 404 Not Found, 500 Server Error). CRUD means Create, Read, Update, Delete‚Äîthe four basic database operations‚Äîand in a typical REST-style Express app they map cleanly to HTTP methods: Create is POST /resource, Read is GET /resource (many) or GET /resource/:id (one), Update is PUT /resource/:id (replace) or PATCH /resource/:id (partial change), and Delete is DELETE /resource/:id; for example, for a ‚Äústudents‚Äù table/collection you might have POST /api/students to insert a new student record, GET /api/students to select all, GET /api/students/123 to select one, PATCH /api/students/123 to change fields like name, and DELETE /api/students/123 to remove it. In practice, Express wires this up by connecting routes to controllers (for example, app.get(\"/api/students/:id\", getStudentByIdController)), and the controller calls your database code (SQL queries, or an ORM like Prisma/Sequelize, or a MongoDB driver) to perform the CRUD operation, then returns a clear JSON response (like { \"id\": 123, \"name\": \"Ava\" }) so the frontend can use it; keeping routes thin, controllers focused on request/response logic, and database access in a separate model/service layer makes your app easier to read, test, and expand."),

