    ("I LOVE DINOSAURS‚Äîwhat are the main theories for what caused the dinosaur extinction, and what evidence supports each one?", "The leading explanation is the Chicxulub asteroid impact about 66 million years ago at the end of the Cretaceous, supported by a worldwide thin clay layer rich in iridium (rare in Earth‚Äôs crust but common in meteorites), shocked quartz and tiny glass spherules formed by extreme impacts, tsunami and ‚Äúimpact ejecta‚Äù deposits around the Gulf of Mexico, and the Chicxulub crater on the Yucat√°n Peninsula dated to the same time; climate models and geologic evidence indicate the impact lofted dust, sulfate aerosols, and soot high into the atmosphere, sharply reducing sunlight and cooling the planet for months to years (with longer-lasting ecosystem disruption), while acid rain and global wildfires added stress. Another major theory is massive volcanism from the Deccan Traps in India, where enormous eruptions near the same time released large amounts of carbon dioxide and sulfur gases, with evidence including the vast stacked lava flows precisely dated to the late Cretaceous, mercury spikes and other volcanic chemical signals in sediments, and signs of climate swings (short-term cooling from sulfur aerosols and longer-term warming and ocean acidification from CO2) that would strain food webs. Many scientists think the most realistic picture is a combination: ecosystems were already stressed by Deccan-driven climate and ocean changes, and the impact delivered a sudden, global ‚Äúone-two punch,‚Äù which fits the fossil record showing a sharp extinction boundary for non-avian dinosaurs and many marine groups right at 66 million years ago. Other ideas like gradual sea-level change, disease, or competition are discussed but have weaker support because they don‚Äôt match the global, abrupt timing seen in rocks and fossils as well as the impact and volcanism evidence does."),

