    ("why do magnets stick to the fridge but not to my plastic cup?", "Magnets stick to many fridges because the fridge door is made of steel (an iron-based metal), and steel is ferromagnetic, meaning its tiny magnetic regions (called domains) can line up with the magnet‚Äôs field and get strongly attracted, so the magnet ‚Äúgrabs‚Äù the metal and stays put. A plastic cup doesn‚Äôt stick because plastic isn‚Äôt ferromagnetic; it doesn‚Äôt have the kind of iron, nickel, or cobalt atoms that can line up into magnetic domains, so a magnet has almost nothing to pull on, and gravity just makes it fall. A quick way to test this idea is to try the same magnet on different materials: it will usually stick to paper clips, nails, and some metal cans (steel), but not to aluminum foil, copper coins, glass, wood, or most plastics, because not all metals are magnetic and most everyday materials don‚Äôt respond strongly to magnets."),

