    ("what is a simple machine like a lever or pulley? i kinda don‚Äôt get it", "A simple machine is a basic tool that helps you do work more easily by changing how a force is applied, usually by letting you use a smaller force over a longer distance or by changing the direction of the force (you don‚Äôt get ‚Äúfree‚Äù energy; you trade force for distance). A lever is a stiff bar that pivots on a point called a fulcrum, like a seesaw or a crowbar: if you push down on the long side, the short side can lift a heavy object because your force acts through a longer distance, giving you mechanical advantage. A pulley is a grooved wheel with a rope: a single fixed pulley mainly changes the direction of your pull (pull down to lift something up), while using more than one pulley in a block-and-tackle can reduce how hard you have to pull because the weight is shared by multiple rope sections, though you must pull more rope to lift the object the same height. Other common simple machines are the inclined plane (a ramp), wheel and axle (like a doorknob), screw (an inclined plane wrapped around a cylinder), and wedge (like a knife), and they all work by the same idea of making a task easier by trading force, distance, or direction."),

