    ("can you help me understand the work-energy theorem and when to use it vs kinematics", "The work‚Äìenergy theorem says that the net work done on an object equals its change in kinetic energy: Wnet = ŒîK = (1/2)mvf^2 ‚àí (1/2)mvi^2, where ‚Äúwork‚Äù is the component of force along the displacement integrated over the path (for a constant force, W = Fd cosŒ∏). You use it when you care about speeds (or stopping distance) and forces over a distance, especially when acceleration isn‚Äôt constant or when multiple forces act and you‚Äôd rather add their works than solve for acceleration; common examples are a block sliding with friction, a car braking, a spring launching an object, or motion on a track where the normal force does no work. Kinematics (like vf^2 = vi^2 + 2aŒîx, v = vi + at, x = x0 + vit + (1/2)at^2) is best when acceleration is known and constant and you want time, position, or velocity as functions of time; it‚Äôs often the fastest route for free fall with constant g (ignoring air resistance) or any situation with uniform acceleration. A good rule of thumb is: if the problem gives forces and distances and asks for speed, use work‚Äìenergy; if it gives (or implies) constant acceleration and asks for time or position, use kinematics. For instance, if a 2 kg block is pushed 5 m by a 10 N horizontal force with 4 N friction, the net work is (10‚àí4)¬∑5 = 30 J, so ŒîK = 30 J and vf = sqrt(2ŒîK/m) = sqrt(60/2) = sqrt(30) ‚âà 5.48 m/s without ever finding a; but if you also needed how long it took, you‚Äôd then switch to kinematics using a = Fnet/m = 6/2 = 3 m/s^2 and solve for t. Finally, remember energy methods don‚Äôt directly give time, and kinematics becomes messy when forces (and thus acceleration) vary with position or speed; that‚Äôs exactly where work‚Äìenergy (and, when only conservative forces act, conservation of mechanical energy) shines."),

