    ("I don‚Äôt get mean/median/mode. Here‚Äôs my data: 2, 5, 5, 7, 10, 10, 10, 12. Can you find them and explain which one is most useful?", "For your data set 2, 5, 5, 7, 10, 10, 10, 12, the mean (average) is found by adding everything and dividing by how many numbers there are: 2+5+5+7+10+10+10+12 = 61, and there are 8 values, so the mean is 61/8 = 7.625. The median is the ‚Äúmiddle‚Äù value when the data are in order; because you have 8 numbers (an even amount), the median is the average of the 4th and 5th values: the 4th is 7 and the 5th is 10, so the median is (7+10)/2 = 8.5. The mode is the value that appears most often; 10 shows up three times, more than any other number, so the mode is 10. Which one is most useful depends on what you want to describe: the mean uses every value but can be pulled down or up by unusually small or large numbers (here the 2 pulls the mean down), the median is often best for a ‚Äútypical middle‚Äù when there are outliers because it isn‚Äôt affected as much (here it lands between 7 and 10), and the mode is most useful when you care about the most common value (here, 10 is the most frequent result)."),

