    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 01:26 - Category: dna_replication
    ("How does DNA replication work? Like what does helicase do and why is it called semi-conservative?", "DNA replication is the process cells use to copy their DNA before they divide, and it happens by using each original strand as a template to build a new matching strand. It starts at specific places called origins of replication, where helicase acts like a zipper-unzipper: it breaks the hydrogen bonds between the paired bases and unwinds the double helix, creating a replication fork with two single strands exposed. Because the separated strands want to snap back together and can get tangled, single-strand binding proteins help keep them apart and topoisomerase relieves twisting stress ahead of the fork; then primase lays down short RNA primers so DNA polymerase can begin, since DNA polymerase can only add nucleotides to an existing 3‚Ä≤ end and builds new DNA in the 5‚Ä≤‚Üí3‚Ä≤ direction. One new strand (the leading strand) is made smoothly toward the fork, while the other (the lagging strand) is made in short Okazaki fragments away from the fork; the RNA primers are later removed and replaced with DNA, and DNA ligase seals the gaps to make a continuous strand. It is called semi-conservative because each finished DNA double helix conserves (keeps) one original ‚Äúparent‚Äù strand and pairs it with one newly synthesized ‚Äúdaughter‚Äù strand, so after replication you end up with two DNA molecules that are each half old and half new."),

