    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 01:27 - Category: congress
    ("What is Congress and what do they actually do all day? I‚Äôm confused.", "Congress is the lawmaking branch of the U.S. federal government, created by the Constitution, and it has two parts: the House of Representatives (435 voting members based on state population, serving 2-year terms) and the Senate (100 members, 2 per state, serving 6-year terms). What members ‚Äúdo all day‚Äù is a mix of writing and debating bills (proposed laws), working in committees where most detailed work happens (holding hearings, questioning experts, rewriting bill language, and voting on whether a bill should move forward), meeting with other lawmakers to negotiate compromises, and then voting on bills on the House or Senate floor; if both chambers pass the same bill, it goes to the president to be signed into law or vetoed. They also do oversight, which means checking how the executive branch is running programs and spending taxpayer money by requesting reports, holding investigations and hearings, and confirming or blocking certain presidential appointments in the Senate; the House can start impeachment charges and the Senate holds the trial, and Congress controls the ‚Äúpower of the purse‚Äù by writing the federal budget and funding agencies. On top of that, members spend a lot of time meeting with constituents (the people they represent), answering letters and calls, helping residents deal with federal agencies through casework (like Social Security or veterans‚Äô benefits problems), and raising money for reelection; when Congress is ‚Äúin session‚Äù they‚Äôre in Washington, D.C., and when they‚Äôre ‚Äúin recess‚Äù they‚Äôre usually back in their home states or districts doing those local meetings and constituent work."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 01:27 - Category: supreme_court
    ("What does the Supreme Court do and why do people say its decisions are a big deal?", "The Supreme Court is the highest court in the United States, and its main job is to interpret the U.S. Constitution and federal laws by deciding real legal disputes that have worked their way up from lower courts. It chooses a small number of important cases each year, hears arguments from both sides, and then issues written decisions that can either uphold or strike down laws and government actions if they conflict with the Constitution; it also settles disagreements about what federal law means and can resolve conflicts when different lower courts have ruled differently on the same issue. People say its decisions are a big deal because they set nationwide legal rules that every other court must follow, they can change what rights people have in everyday life (like free speech, voting rules, privacy, or how the government can act), and they are usually final because there is no higher court to appeal to; since Supreme Court justices are appointed for life, their rulings can shape the country for decades."),

