    ("I‚Äôm learning complex numbers and it feels fake. Can you explain what i is and solve something like (2+3i)(1-4i)?", "The symbol i is defined to be the number whose square is ‚àí1, so i¬≤ = ‚àí1; it isn‚Äôt ‚Äúfake,‚Äù it‚Äôs a way to extend the real numbers so that equations like x¬≤ + 1 = 0 have solutions, and you can think of a complex number a + bi as a point (a, b) on a plane where the real part a is left-right and the imaginary part b is up-down, with multiplying by i acting like a 90¬∞ rotation because (a + bi)i = ‚àíb + ai. To multiply (2 + 3i)(1 ‚àí 4i), use distributive (FOIL): 2¬∑1 + 2¬∑(‚àí4i) + 3i¬∑1 + 3i¬∑(‚àí4i) = 2 ‚àí 8i + 3i ‚àí 12i¬≤; combine like terms to get 2 ‚àí 5i ‚àí 12i¬≤, and since i¬≤ = ‚àí1 this becomes 2 ‚àí 5i + 12 = 14 ‚àí 5i. You can sanity-check by treating them as (a, b) pairs: (2, 3)(1, ‚àí4) multiplies to (2¬∑1 ‚àí 3¬∑(‚àí4), 2¬∑(‚àí4) + 3¬∑1) = (14, ‚àí5), which matches 14 ‚àí 5i."),

