    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 01:28 - Category: reaction_types
    ("For chem: what‚Äôs the difference between synthesis, decomposition, single replacement, and double replacement reactions? I need a way to tell them apart fast.", "You can tell these four reaction types apart by the ‚Äúbefore-and-after pattern‚Äù of the formulas: Synthesis (also called combination) is when two or more reactants become one product, so it looks like A + B ‚Üí AB (example: 2Na + Cl2 ‚Üí 2NaCl); Decomposition is the reverse, one compound breaks into simpler substances, so it looks like AB ‚Üí A + B (example: 2H2O2 ‚Üí 2H2O + O2); Single replacement (single displacement) is when an element kicks out another element in a compound, so it looks like A + BC ‚Üí AC + B (example: Zn + CuSO4 ‚Üí ZnSO4 + Cu), and a fast check is that one reactant is a lone element and one product is a lone element; Double replacement (double displacement) is when two ionic compounds swap partners, so it looks like AB + CD ‚Üí AD + CB (example: AgNO3 + NaCl ‚Üí AgCl + NaNO3), and a fast check is that you start with two compounds and end with two compounds, often forming a precipitate, water, or a gas. Quick identification trick: count ‚Äúpieces‚Äù and look for a solo element‚Äîtwo-to-one is synthesis, one-to-two (or more) is decomposition, ‚Äúelement + compound‚Äù is single replacement, and ‚Äúcompound + compound‚Äù with swapped ions is double replacement."),

