    ("Calc help: does the limit of sin(x)/x as x‚Üí0 exist, and why?", "Yes, the limit exists and it equals 1: lim(x‚Üí0) sin(x)/x = 1 (with x measured in radians). One standard reason is the squeeze theorem using a unit circle: for small nonzero x, the arc length x is bigger than sin(x) (the vertical chord) but smaller than tan(x) (the tangent segment), giving sin(x) < x < tan(x); dividing by x sin(x) (which is positive for x near 0) yields 1 < x/sin(x) < 1/cos(x), and taking reciprocals gives cos(x) < sin(x)/x < 1. As x‚Üí0, cos(x)‚Üí1, so sin(x)/x is squeezed between two functions that both approach 1, forcing the limit to be 1; the same conclusion holds from the left by symmetry since sin is odd, so the two-sided limit exists."),

