    ("Intro CS question: What‚Äôs a transistor in simple terms, and how does it relate to digital logic (0s and 1s)?", "A transistor is a tiny electronic switch (or valve) that can control the flow of electricity: a small input signal at one part of the transistor can turn a larger current on or off in another part. Computers use billions of transistors wired together so that ‚Äúon‚Äù (current flowing, a higher voltage) represents a 1 and ‚Äúoff‚Äù (little or no current, a lower voltage) represents a 0, which is how digital circuits store and process information. By combining transistors into simple building blocks called logic gates (like NOT, AND, and OR), circuits can take some 0/1 inputs and produce a 0/1 output, and chaining many gates together lets a CPU do everything from adding numbers to making decisions like ‚Äúif this is true, do that.‚Äù"),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 01:29 - Category: congress
    ("How does Congress work? What‚Äôs the difference between the House and the Senate and why do they both have to vote on a bill?", "Congress is the lawmaking branch of the U.S. government, and it has two parts, called chambers: the House of Representatives and the Senate; together they write, debate, change, and vote on bills (proposed laws), and if both chambers pass the same exact text, it goes to the President to be signed into law or vetoed. The House is meant to represent the people more directly: its 435 members are divided among the states based on population, each serves a 2-year term, and the House can start bills that raise taxes and can impeach (formally accuse) federal officials; because House districts are smaller and elections are more frequent, the House tends to respond quickly to what voters want right now. The Senate is meant to represent the states equally: each state gets 2 senators no matter its size (100 total), senators serve 6-year terms, and the Senate confirms many presidential appointments and approves treaties; with longer terms and statewide elections, the Senate is designed to be more steady and to slow things down when needed. Both chambers have to vote on a bill because the Constitution set up this ‚Äútwo-house‚Äù system (bicameralism) as a check inside Congress: it forces agreement between a population-based chamber (House) and an equal-states chamber (Senate), which helps prevent a small group from passing laws too quickly and encourages compromise. In practice, a bill is introduced in one chamber, sent to committees that hold hearings and make changes, debated and voted on, then sent to the other chamber to go through a similar process; if the House and Senate pass different versions, they must negotiate and vote again until both pass the same version, and only then can it become law."),

