    ("AP Physics: can you walk me through using the work-energy theorem on a block sliding down a 25¬∞ incline with friction (mu_k = 0.2) for 3.0 m? I keep messing up the signs.", "Use the work‚Äìenergy theorem in the form W_net = ŒîK, choosing the positive direction down the incline (the same direction as the block‚Äôs displacement). Over a distance d = 3.0 m on a Œ∏ = 25¬∞ incline, gravity‚Äôs component along the ramp is mg sinŒ∏ and it points down the ramp, so its work is W_g = +mgd sinŒ∏. The normal force is perpendicular to the motion, so W_N = 0. Kinetic friction has magnitude f_k = Œº_k N = Œº_k mg cosŒ∏ and it points up the ramp (opposite the displacement), so its work is W_f = ‚àíf_k d = ‚àíŒº_k mgd cosŒ∏; the minus sign is the key sign issue: friction does negative work because it opposes the motion. Therefore W_net = mgd sinŒ∏ ‚àí Œº_k mgd cosŒ∏ = ŒîK = (1/2)mv_f^2 ‚àí (1/2)mv_i^2, and the mass cancels if you solve for speed: v_f^2 = v_i^2 + 2gd(sinŒ∏ ‚àí Œº_k cosŒ∏). Plugging in numbers, sin25¬∞ ‚âà 0.423 and cos25¬∞ ‚âà 0.906, so (sinŒ∏ ‚àí Œº_k cosŒ∏) ‚âà 0.423 ‚àí 0.2(0.906) ‚âà 0.242, giving v_f^2 = v_i^2 + 2(9.8)(3.0)(0.242) ‚âà v_i^2 + 14.2; if it starts from rest, v_f ‚âà ‚àö14.2 ‚âà 3.8 m/s. A quick sign check: if Œº_k were larger than tanŒ∏ (here tan25¬∞ ‚âà 0.466, while Œº_k = 0.2), then sinŒ∏ ‚àí Œº_k cosŒ∏ would still be positive and the block speeds up; if Œº_k exceeded tanŒ∏, the bracket would go negative and friction would remove more energy than gravity adds, so the block would slow down, which matches physical intuition."),

