    ("In algebra 2 we‚Äôre doing polynomial functions‚Äîhow do you tell the end behavior and number of turning points just from the leading term/degree? Can you give an example too?", "For a polynomial, the end behavior is determined just by the leading term a x^n (the coefficient a and the degree n) because for very large |x| that term dominates all the others: if n is even, both ends go the same way (a > 0 means f(x) ‚Üí +‚àû as x ‚Üí ¬±‚àû, and a < 0 means f(x) ‚Üí ‚àí‚àû as x ‚Üí ¬±‚àû); if n is odd, the ends go opposite ways (a > 0 means left end down and right end up: as x ‚Üí ‚àí‚àû, f(x) ‚Üí ‚àí‚àû and as x ‚Üí +‚àû, f(x) ‚Üí +‚àû; a < 0 means left end up and right end down: as x ‚Üí ‚àí‚àû, f(x) ‚Üí +‚àû and as x ‚Üí +‚àû, f(x) ‚Üí ‚àí‚àû). The number of turning points (local maxima/minima where the graph changes from increasing to decreasing or vice versa) is at most n ‚àí 1 for a degree-n polynomial, so a quadratic (n = 2) has at most 1 turning point, a cubic at most 2, a quartic at most 3, and so on; it can be fewer, but it cannot exceed n ‚àí 1. Example: f(x) = ‚àí2x^4 + 5x^2 ‚àí 1 has leading term ‚àí2x^4, so n = 4 is even and a is negative, meaning both ends go down (f(x) ‚Üí ‚àí‚àû as x ‚Üí ¬±‚àû), and it can have at most 3 turning points; in contrast, g(x) = 3x^3 ‚àí x + 1 has leading term 3x^3, so it‚Äôs odd degree with positive leading coefficient, meaning left end down and right end up, and it can have at most 2 turning points."),

