    ("Precalc trig is ruining me: what‚Äôs the difference between radians and degrees, and why does the unit circle make more sense in radians?", "Degrees and radians are just two different ways to measure the same thing: an angle, but they use different ‚Äúsize units.‚Äù Degrees are based on a historical choice that a full turn is 360¬∞, so a right angle is 90¬∞ and a straight angle is 180¬∞. Radians are based on circles themselves: an angle in radians is defined by arc length divided by radius, so Œ∏ (in radians) = s/r, which makes it unitless and directly tied to the geometry of the circle. Because the circumference of a circle is 2œÄr, one full revolution corresponds to s = 2œÄr, so Œ∏ = (2œÄr)/r = 2œÄ radians; that‚Äôs why 180¬∞ equals œÄ radians and 90¬∞ equals œÄ/2 radians. The unit circle (radius 1) makes even more sense in radians because the radius is 1, so Œ∏ = s/1 = s, meaning the radian measure of the angle is literally the length of the arc you‚Äôve traveled around the circle from (1,0); for example, œÄ/2 radians means you‚Äôve moved an arc length of œÄ/2 along the circle, landing at the top point (0,1). This ‚Äúangle equals arc length‚Äù connection is why so many trig facts and formulas are cleaner in radians: the standard unit-circle coordinates are (cos Œ∏, sin Œ∏) with Œ∏ naturally measured by how far you go around the circle, and calculus-based results only work in their simplest true form in radians (like d/dx(sin x) = cos x and the small-angle approximation sin x ‚âà x when x is near 0), whereas degrees would require extra conversion factors. A quick conversion you can memorize is multiply degrees by œÄ/180 to get radians and multiply radians by 180/œÄ to get degrees, so 60¬∞ = œÄ/3 and œÄ/6 = 30¬∞, and once you start thinking ‚Äú2œÄ is a full turn,‚Äù the unit circle becomes a map of distances around the circle rather than an arbitrary 360-part scale."),

