    ("Can you explain the work-energy theorem with an example? Like if I push a box across the floor, how does that connect to kinetic energy?", "The work‚Äìenergy theorem says that the net work done on an object equals the change in its kinetic energy: Wnet = ŒîK = (1/2)mvf^2 ‚àí (1/2)mvi^2, where work is the component of force along the motion times the distance, W = Fd cos(Œ∏). If you push a box of mass m across a level floor a distance d with a steady horizontal push Fpush, and friction opposes the motion with force Ffric, then the net work is (Fpush ‚àí Ffric)d, so the box‚Äôs kinetic energy changes by that amount: (Fpush ‚àí Ffric)d = (1/2)mvf^2 ‚àí (1/2)mvi^2. For a concrete example, suppose the box is initially at rest (vi = 0), you push with 20 N for 5 m, and friction is 12 N; your push does +100 J of work, friction does ‚àí60 J of work, so the net work is +40 J, meaning the box gains 40 J of kinetic energy and ends with speed vf = sqrt(2ŒîK/m) = sqrt(80/m). This also shows the key idea: your push doesn‚Äôt automatically become kinetic energy‚Äîonly the net work does; if friction exactly matches your push, net work is zero and the box can move at constant speed with no change in kinetic energy, while the energy you supply is converted into thermal energy in the box and floor."),

