    ("Stats project: I have a dataset of 30 students‚Äô sleep hours vs. GPA‚Äîwhat statistical test should I run to see if there‚Äôs a relationship? And how do I check assumptions?", "With 30 students and two quantitative variables (sleep hours and GPA), the standard choice is a correlation/regression approach: run a Pearson correlation test (equivalently, a simple linear regression with GPA as the outcome and sleep hours as the predictor) to test whether there is a linear relationship; report the correlation r (or the regression slope), a 95% confidence interval, and a p-value. To check assumptions for Pearson/linear regression, first make a scatterplot of GPA vs sleep to see if the relationship looks roughly linear and to spot outliers; then fit the regression and examine residual diagnostics: a residuals-vs-fitted plot should show no clear curve (linearity) and roughly constant spread (homoscedasticity), and a Q‚ÄìQ plot (or a Shapiro‚ÄìWilk test on residuals) should look approximately normal; also check for influential points with leverage/Cook‚Äôs distance because one unusual student can drive results in a sample of 30. If the scatterplot looks monotonic but not linear, or you have strong outliers or clear non-normality that doesn‚Äôt resolve with a sensible transformation, use Spearman‚Äôs rank correlation as a robust alternative (it tests for a monotonic association without requiring normality), and still visualize the data because interpretation depends on the pattern you see."),

