    ("What does \'polynomial function\' mean in 8th grade terms? And how do you know the degree and what the graph usually looks like?", "A polynomial function is a function where the rule is a sum of terms like ax^n (numbers times x raised to a whole-number power), such as f(x) = 3x^4 ‚àí 2x^2 + 5x ‚àí 7; the powers of x can be 0, 1, 2, 3, and so on, and you can add or subtract these terms, but you do not have x in a denominator (like 1/x), you do not use fractional or negative exponents (like x^(1/2) or x^‚àí1), and you do not have x inside a square root. The degree of a polynomial is the largest exponent of x after you simplify and combine like terms (for example, 5x^3 + 2x^2 ‚àí x + 9 has degree 3; 4x^2 ‚àí 7 is degree 2; a nonzero constant like 6 is degree 0; and the zero polynomial is a special case where the degree isn‚Äôt usually defined in middle school). The graph of a polynomial is smooth and continuous with no breaks, holes, or sharp corners, and its overall ‚Äúend behavior‚Äù is controlled by the leading term (the term with the highest power): if the degree is even (like 2, 4, 6), both ends of the graph go the same way (both up if the leading coefficient is positive, both down if it‚Äôs negative), and if the degree is odd (like 1, 3, 5), the ends go opposite ways (for a positive leading coefficient it goes down on the left and up on the right; for a negative leading coefficient it goes up on the left and down on the right). Also, higher degree usually means the graph can wiggle more: a degree n polynomial can have at most n ‚àí 1 turning points, so a line (degree 1) doesn‚Äôt turn, a parabola (degree 2) turns once, and a cubic (degree 3) can turn up to twice."),

