    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 01:32 - Category: statistical_analysis
    ("We‚Äôre doing statistics in science: what‚Äôs the difference between mean, median, and mode and when is each one better to use?", "Mean, median, and mode are three ways to describe the ‚Äútypical‚Äù value in a set of data, but they behave differently. The mean is the average: add all the values and divide by how many values there are, so it uses every data point and is best when the data are fairly symmetric with no extreme outliers (for example, repeated measurements like plant heights or temperatures where a few weird values aren‚Äôt throwing things off), but it can be pulled up or down a lot by one unusually large or small value. The median is the middle value when you sort the data (or the average of the two middle values if there‚Äôs an even number), and it‚Äôs better when the data are skewed or have outliers (like incomes, reaction times, or a class where one student has an extremely high score), because it stays near the center even if one value is extreme. The mode is the most frequent value, and it‚Äôs especially useful for categorical data or when you care about the most common outcome (like the most common blood type in a sample, the most common species observed, or the most common number of seeds per pod), and it can also be helpful when there are repeated ‚Äúfavorite‚Äù values even if the data aren‚Äôt nicely centered; unlike mean and median, a data set can have no mode or more than one mode. In short, use the mean for balanced numerical data without big outliers, the median for skewed data or when outliers matter, and the mode when you want the most common value or you‚Äôre working with categories."),

