    ("I‚Äôm writing my design thinking reflection‚Äîcan you help me come up with a clear problem statement + user needs for redesigning our cafeteria line so it‚Äôs faster?", "A clear design-thinking problem statement should name the user, the need, and the insight (why it matters), so you could write: ‚ÄúBusy students and staff who eat in the cafeteria need a faster, more predictable lunch line because long, confusing waits reduce their time to eat and relax, increase stress, and sometimes cause them to skip items or arrive late to class.‚Äù If you want it even more specific, add a measurable goal: ‚ÄúRedesign the cafeteria line so most customers can get from entry to checkout in under X minutes during peak lunch.‚Äù User needs you can include in your reflection are: students need to understand exactly where to go next (clear signage, one obvious starting point, and no line-cutting confusion); they need the line to move steadily with fewer bottlenecks (enough serving space, fewer stop-and-start moments, and a layout that prevents crowding at popular stations); they need choices to be easy to make quickly (menus visible before reaching the food, simple options, and the ability to decide while waiting); they need payment to be quick and reliable (enough cashiers or faster checkout methods, clear pricing, and a way to handle issues without stopping the whole line); they need fairness and predictability (one queue or well-managed multiple queues, consistent rules, and a system that feels equitable); they need accessibility and comfort (space for wheelchairs and trays, safe traffic flow, and room to step aside if they‚Äôre not ready); and they need to keep their food correct without slowing everyone down (a clear spot to grab utensils/condiments and a separate ‚Äúhelp‚Äù area for missing items or questions). To make your reflection stronger, you can end by linking needs to evidence you observed, like ‚Äústudents hesitate because they can‚Äôt see the menu until the front,‚Äù or ‚Äúthe line stalls at checkout,‚Äù which shows your problem statement is grounded in real user behavior."),

