    ("Why does ice melt faster in my hand than on the table? Is it because of heat transfer or something?", "Ice melts faster in your hand because your hand is much warmer than the ice and can deliver heat to it quickly, so yes, it‚Äôs mainly about heat transfer. Ice has to absorb a lot of energy just to change phase from solid to liquid (this is called the latent heat of fusion), and your body is a big ‚Äúheat reservoir‚Äù at about 37¬∞C with warm blood constantly flowing in to replace any heat that leaves your skin; that means the spot touching the ice doesn‚Äôt stay cold for long, so heat keeps streaming into the ice and it keeps melting. On a table, the only available heat is the table material and the surrounding air, which are usually much cooler than your hand and don‚Äôt replenish heat as fast; the table surface under the ice quickly cools down toward 0¬∞C and then the temperature difference becomes smaller, so the heat flow slows and the ice melts more slowly. Contact also matters: your fingers can wrap around the ice and press against it, increasing the contact area and squeezing out insulating air gaps, while on a flat table only one side touches and a thin layer of meltwater can sit underneath and act like a slippery, partly insulating barrier. So the short answer is that your hand melts ice faster because it‚Äôs warmer and continuously supplies heat (helped by better contact), whereas the table and air supply heat more slowly."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 01:32 - Category: supreme_court
    ("US Gov: can you explain what the Supreme Court actually does and how judicial review works, but like with a real example case?", "The Supreme Court is the highest court in the United States, and its main job is to interpret the Constitution and federal law by deciding real legal disputes that come to it on appeal; it doesn‚Äôt write laws or enforce them, but it can settle disagreements about what a law means, resolve conflicts between lower courts, and decide whether actions by Congress, the President, or the states are constitutional. Judicial review is the power of courts to declare a law or government action unconstitutional, which means it cannot be enforced; this power isn‚Äôt written as a single sentence in the Constitution, but it was established early in U.S. history and is now a core part of how checks and balances work. A classic real example is Marbury v. Madison (1803): William Marbury asked the Supreme Court to order Secretary of State James Madison to deliver his commission, and the Court said Marbury had a right to the commission but ruled that the specific law Marbury relied on (part of the Judiciary Act of 1789) tried to give the Supreme Court a kind of original jurisdiction the Constitution didn‚Äôt allow, so that part of the law was unconstitutional and the Court couldn‚Äôt grant Marbury‚Äôs request; the key takeaway is that the Court used the case to explain that when a federal law conflicts with the Constitution, the Constitution wins, and the Court can say so. Another easy-to-picture example is Brown v. Board of Education (1954), where the Court used judicial review to hold that state laws requiring racial segregation in public schools violated the Equal Protection Clause of the 14th Amendment, which meant those segregation laws could no longer be treated as valid; in both cases, the Supreme Court wasn‚Äôt making a new law, it was applying the Constitution as the highest legal rule and requiring the rest of government to follow it."),

