    ("I‚Äôm studying US history: what started the Cold War and what were NATO and the Warsaw Pact?", "The Cold War began after World War II (1945) when the United States and the Soviet Union, former allies against Nazi Germany, became rivals because they had fundamentally different goals and systems: the U.S. promoted democratic governments and market economies, while the USSR promoted communist one-party rule and Soviet-style planned economies, and each feared the other would expand its influence. Tensions rose as the USSR established pro-Soviet communist governments across Eastern Europe (often called the ‚ÄúSoviet bloc‚Äù), while the U.S. adopted ‚Äúcontainment‚Äù to limit Soviet expansion, announced the Truman Doctrine in 1947 to support countries resisting communism, and launched the Marshall Plan in 1948 to help rebuild Western Europe; major early flashpoints included disagreements over Germany‚Äôs future, the Berlin Blockade and Airlift (1948‚Äì1949), and the spread of nuclear weapons after the USSR tested an atomic bomb in 1949. NATO, the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, was created in 1949 as a collective defense alliance led by the U.S., Canada, and many Western European countries, built around the idea that an attack on one member would be treated as an attack on all (Article 5), aiming to deter Soviet aggression in Europe. The Warsaw Pact, officially formed in 1955, was the Soviet-led military alliance of the USSR and its Eastern European satellite states, created in response to West Germany joining NATO and to tighten Soviet control over the Eastern bloc; it also operated on a mutual-defense principle and served as the military counterpart to NATO until it dissolved in 1991 as communist governments fell and the Cold War ended."),

