    ("US History: what were the main causes of the Civil War, and how were slavery + states‚Äô rights both part of it? I need this for a paragraph response.", "The main causes of the U.S. Civil War (1861‚Äì1865) centered on the conflict between a growing antislavery North and a slaveholding South, especially over whether slavery would expand into new western territories and states, because that expansion affected political power in Congress and the future direction of the country. Slavery was at the core because the Southern economy and social order depended on enslaved labor, and many Southern leaders explicitly said secession was necessary to protect slavery after Abraham Lincoln‚Äôs election in 1860 signaled that slavery‚Äôs spread could be blocked; key flashpoints included the Missouri Compromise (1820), the Compromise of 1850 and the Fugitive Slave Act, the Kansas‚ÄìNebraska Act (1854) and ‚ÄúBleeding Kansas,‚Äù the Dred Scott decision (1857), and John Brown‚Äôs raid (1859), all of which intensified sectional distrust. ‚ÄúStates‚Äô rights‚Äù was part of the argument because Southerners claimed states had the right to decide slavery for themselves and to leave the Union, but this was closely tied to slavery: they wanted state power used to protect slavery locally while also demanding strong federal enforcement of slavery through laws like the Fugitive Slave Act, showing the debate was less about states‚Äô rights in general and more about which level of government would secure slavery. In short, slavery was the fundamental issue, and states‚Äô rights was a major political framework used to defend slavery and justify secession, leading to war when Southern states formed the Confederacy and the United States refused to accept the breakup of the Union."),

