    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 01:33 - Category: object_oriented_programming
    ("College CS: I‚Äôm learning OOP‚Äîcan you show a simple example of classes/inheritance in Java (like Vehicle -> Car) and explain why we use it?", "In Java, a class is a blueprint for objects (data plus behavior), and inheritance lets you define a general ‚Äúparent‚Äù type and reuse/extend it in more specific ‚Äúchild‚Äù types; for example, you can model a Vehicle with fields and methods common to all vehicles, then make Car inherit those and add car-specific details: class Vehicle { protected int speed; public Vehicle(int speed){ this.speed=speed; } public void accelerate(int delta){ speed+=delta; } public String info(){ return \"Vehicle speed=\"+speed; } } and class Car extends Vehicle { private int doors; public Car(int speed,int doors){ super(speed); this.doors=doors; } @Override public String info(){ return \"Car speed=\"+speed+\", doors=\"+doors; } public void honk(){ System.out.println(\"Beep!\"); } } then you can write Vehicle v = new Car(30,4); v.accelerate(10); System.out.println(v.info()); which prints the Car‚Äôs overridden info even though the variable type is Vehicle (polymorphism). We use this because it reduces duplicated code (accelerate and speed live once in Vehicle), makes designs easier to extend (you can add Truck extends Vehicle later without rewriting shared logic), and enables flexible APIs (methods can accept a Vehicle and work with any subclass), while still allowing each subclass to customize behavior via overriding."),

