    ("In geometry, how do conic sections work? Like how are circles, parabolas, ellipses, and hyperbolas related?", "Conic sections are the curves you get when you slice a cone with a flat plane, and circles, ellipses, parabolas, and hyperbolas are all part of this same family because they come from different angles of the cut: if the plane is perpendicular to the cone‚Äôs axis you get a circle (a special case of an ellipse), if it‚Äôs tilted but still cuts only one ‚Äúnappe‚Äù (one half of the cone) you get an ellipse, if it‚Äôs tilted so it‚Äôs exactly parallel to a slanted side of the cone you get a parabola, and if it‚Äôs tilted so it cuts through both nappes you get a hyperbola (two separate branches). They‚Äôre also related by shared geometry ideas like focus and directrix: an ellipse is the set of points whose distances to two fixed points (foci) add to a constant, a hyperbola is the set of points whose distances to two foci differ by a constant, and a parabola is the set of points equally distant from a focus and a line called the directrix; a circle fits in as the ellipse where the two foci coincide at the center. In coordinate geometry these relationships show up in their standard equations: circle x^2 + y^2 = r^2, ellipse x^2/a^2 + y^2/b^2 = 1, parabola y = ax^2 (or (x ‚àí h)^2 = 4p(y ‚àí k)), and hyperbola x^2/a^2 ‚àí y^2/b^2 = 1, and you can think of the ‚Äúeccentricity‚Äù e as a single knob that changes the shape across the family: e = 0 gives a circle, 0 < e < 1 gives an ellipse, e = 1 gives a parabola, and e > 1 gives a hyperbola."),

