    ("I‚Äôm in college calc and I‚Äôm stuck: can you show how to prove lim(x->0) sin(x)/x = 1 using epsilon-delta (not just a graph)?", "To prove lim(x‚Üí0) sin(x)/x = 1 by an epsilon‚Äìdelta argument, you want to show: for every Œµ > 0 there exists Œ¥ > 0 such that 0 < |x| < Œ¥ implies |sin(x)/x ‚àí 1| < Œµ. The key input is the classical inequality (for x in radians) that holds for all x with 0 < |x| < œÄ/2: cos(x) ‚â§ sin(x)/x ‚â§ 1 (this can be proved geometrically from areas in the unit circle, or analytically; either way it‚Äôs a standard lemma). From cos(x) ‚â§ sin(x)/x ‚â§ 1 you get 0 ‚â§ 1 ‚àí sin(x)/x ‚â§ 1 ‚àí cos(x), hence |sin(x)/x ‚àí 1| = 1 ‚àí sin(x)/x ‚â§ 1 ‚àí cos(x). Next use the identity 1 ‚àí cos(x) = 2 sin¬≤(x/2) and the basic bound |sin(u)| ‚â§ |u| for all real u (which follows, for example, from the Mean Value Theorem applied to sin, since |cos| ‚â§ 1), giving 1 ‚àí cos(x) = 2 sin¬≤(x/2) ‚â§ 2(x/2)¬≤ = x¬≤/2. Therefore, whenever 0 < |x| < œÄ/2, you have |sin(x)/x ‚àí 1| ‚â§ x¬≤/2. Now finish with Œµ‚ÄìŒ¥: given Œµ > 0, choose Œ¥ = min(œÄ/2, ‚àö(2Œµ)). Then if 0 < |x| < Œ¥, automatically |x| < œÄ/2 so the inequality applies, and |sin(x)/x ‚àí 1| ‚â§ x¬≤/2 < Œ¥¬≤/2 ‚â§ (2Œµ)/2 = Œµ, which is exactly the definition of the limit."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 01:34 - Category: machine_learning_basics
    ("I‚Äôm taking intro machine learning and I don‚Äôt really get it: what‚Äôs the difference between training and testing data and what does \'overfitting\' mean?", "Training data is the set of examples you let a machine learning model learn from: it sees the inputs (like features about a house) along with the correct outputs (like the sale price) and adjusts its internal parameters to reduce errors on those examples. Testing data is a separate set of examples you keep hidden during training and only use at the end to measure how well the model generalizes to new, unseen data; the key idea is that a model can look great on the data it practiced on but still perform poorly on fresh cases. Overfitting is when the model learns the training data too specifically, including noise and accidental quirks, so it gets very high training accuracy but worse test accuracy; a simple analogy is memorizing the answers to a practice worksheet instead of learning the underlying skill, so you struggle on a different worksheet with the same topic. In practice you reduce overfitting by using more data, simplifying the model, adding regularization, using techniques like dropout or early stopping, and tuning choices based on a validation set (a third split used during development) while reserving the test set for the final, unbiased evaluation."),

