    ("What does it mean when a gene is \'dominant\' vs \'recessive\' and how do Punnett squares predict traits? Can you do one example with eye color?", "A ‚Äúdominant‚Äù gene version (allele) is one that shows its effect in the trait when you have just one copy of it, while a ‚Äúrecessive‚Äù allele usually shows its effect only when you have two copies of it (one from each parent); for example, if we use a simplified classroom model where B = brown eyes (dominant) and b = blue eyes (recessive), then BB and Bb would both be brown-eyed, and only bb would be blue-eyed. A Punnett square is a simple grid that predicts the possible allele combinations a child could inherit by listing one parent‚Äôs possible alleles across the top and the other parent‚Äôs down the side, then filling in the boxes to see the probabilities. Example: if two brown-eyed parents are both carriers (Bb x Bb), each parent can pass on B or b, so the Punnett square gives BB, Bb, Bb, and bb, meaning a 1 out of 4 (25%) chance of BB (brown), a 2 out of 4 (50%) chance of Bb (brown carrier), and a 1 out of 4 (25%) chance of bb (blue), so overall there is a 75% chance of brown eyes and a 25% chance of blue eyes in their children in this simplified model; in real life, eye color is influenced by multiple genes and can be more complex, but Punnett squares are still a great way to learn how dominant and recessive inheritance works."),

