    ("Digital logic help: I have to minimize a Boolean function using a Karnaugh map, but I‚Äôm not sure how to handle don‚Äôt-care terms. Can you explain the strategy and a quick example?", "In a Karnaugh map, don‚Äôt-care terms (often marked X) represent input combinations that will never occur or outputs you don‚Äôt need to define, so you are allowed to treat each X as either 0 or 1 in whatever way produces the simplest expression; the key strategy is to include an X in a group only if it helps you make a larger power-of-two group (1, 2, 4, 8, ‚Ä¶ cells) or reduces the number of groups, and to ignore it (treat it like 0) if it doesn‚Äôt help. You still must cover every required 1 with at least one group, you should make groups as large as possible (wrapping around edges is allowed), and you should never create a group that includes a required 0; X cells are ‚Äúoptional‚Äù and can be used differently in different groups if that simplifies the result. Quick example: let F(A,B,C) = Œ£m(1,3,7) with don‚Äôt-cares d(0,2); in the 3-variable K-map, the 1s are at minterms 1 (001), 3 (011), and 7 (111), and the Xs are at 0 (000) and 2 (010). If you ignore don‚Äôt-cares, you can group (1,3) to get A‚ÄôC and (3,7) to get BC, so F = A‚ÄôC + BC; but if you use the X at minterm 2, you can form a 4-cell group covering (2,3,6,7), which yields B (because B=1 is the only variable constant across that group), and then you still need to cover minterm 1, which can be grouped with minterm 3 to yield A‚ÄôC, giving the simpler result F = B + A‚ÄôC. The takeaway is: don‚Äôt-cares are ‚Äúfree‚Äù cells you may turn on only when they let you build bigger groups and drop literals, but they never need to be covered and they must never force you to include a real 0 in a group."),

