    ("In geometry, how do polar coordinates work? Like if a point is (r, Œ∏) = (5, 120¬∞), how do I convert it to x,y and sketch it?", "Polar coordinates describe a point by how far it is from the origin and what direction it points: (r, Œ∏) means start at the origin, rotate Œ∏ from the positive x-axis (counterclockwise for positive angles), then go out a distance r. To convert to Cartesian coordinates, use x = r cos(Œ∏) and y = r sin(Œ∏), making sure your calculator is in degrees if Œ∏ is in degrees. For (r, Œ∏) = (5, 120¬∞), cos(120¬∞) = ‚àí1/2 and sin(120¬∞) = ‚àö3/2, so x = 5(‚àí1/2) = ‚àí2.5 and y = 5(‚àö3/2) = (5‚àö3)/2 ‚âà 4.33, giving the point (‚àí2.5, 4.33). To sketch it, draw the axes, locate the 120¬∞ ray (it‚Äôs 60¬∞ above the negative x-axis, in Quadrant II), then mark a point 5 units from the origin along that ray; you can sanity-check the sketch because x should be negative, y positive, and the distance from the origin should be ‚àö(x¬≤ + y¬≤) = ‚àö(6.25 + 18.75) = ‚àö25 = 5."),

