    ("I‚Äôm coding a Java project and I keep getting a NullPointerException when I try to traverse my binary search tree. Can you help me debug what to check first and what a safe recursive traversal looks like?", "A NullPointerException during a BST traversal almost always means you‚Äôre dereferencing a null reference somewhere, so first check that the tree‚Äôs root is not null before starting, that your insert/delete logic never leaves a node with an uninitialized child pointer that you later assume is non-null, and that you‚Äôre not calling methods like node.getLeft().getValue() without verifying node.getLeft() isn‚Äôt null. Also confirm you didn‚Äôt accidentally shadow the root (for example, a local variable named root that stays null while the field root has the real tree), and that your traversal method is being called on the correct tree instance (a common bug is constructing a new BST and traversing it before inserting anything). A safe recursive traversal always treats ‚Äúnull node‚Äù as the base case and returns immediately before touching fields, for example an in-order traversal that won‚Äôt throw is: void inorder(Node node) { if (node == null) return; inorder(node.left); System.out.println(node.value); inorder(node.right); } and you call it with inorder(root); (similarly, pre-order prints before recursing and post-order prints after). If you still get an exception with that structure, the stack trace line number will usually point to the exact dereference (often inside the print line if value is an object and you call value.toString() on a null value), so verify that node.value is initialized too, and add a quick guard like if (node.value == null) to detect unexpected null payloads while you fix the construction logic."),

