    ("Numerical methods question: how do I choose step size for Euler vs RK4 for y‚Äô = -15y with y(0)=1 so it doesn‚Äôt blow up? I‚Äôm confused about stability.", "For y‚Äô = ‚àí15y with y(0)=1 the exact solution is y(t)=e^(‚àí15t), so it decays smoothly to 0 and any ‚Äúblow up‚Äù you see is purely a numerical stability issue. For explicit (forward) Euler, the update is y_{n+1}=y_n+h(‚àí15y_n)=(1‚àí15h)y_n, so the numerical solution behaves like (1‚àí15h)^n; it is stable (doesn‚Äôt grow in magnitude) exactly when |1‚àí15h|‚â§1, which gives 0‚â§h‚â§2/15‚âà0.1333, and it is non-oscillatory (keeps the correct sign and monotone decay) when 0‚â§1‚àí15h‚â§1, i.e., 0‚â§h‚â§1/15‚âà0.0667; if you take h>2/15 then |1‚àí15h|>1 and the method amplifies errors so the computed values grow and ‚Äúblow up‚Äù even though the true solution decays. For classical RK4 applied to y‚Äô=Œªy with Œª=‚àí15, the update is y_{n+1}=R(z)y_n with z=hŒª and stability requires |R(z)|‚â§1 where R(z)=1+z+z^2/2+z^3/6+z^4/24; along the negative real axis the RK4 stability interval is approximately z‚àà[‚àí2.785,0], so with z=‚àí15h you need 15h‚â§2.785, i.e., h‚â§2.785/15‚âà0.1857 to avoid blow-up, which is noticeably larger than Euler‚Äôs limit. In practice you choose h based on both stability and accuracy: a safe rule of thumb is to resolve the decay time scale 1/15‚âà0.0667 by taking several steps per time constant (for example h‚âà0.01‚Äì0.02 gives very reliable results), and remember that RK4 can stay stable with larger h than Euler, but if h is too large it may still be stable yet inaccurate (it will decay at the wrong rate), so ‚Äúnot blowing up‚Äù is necessary but not sufficient for a good solution."),

