    ("My civil engineering lab is about beam bending. If I have a simply supported beam with a central point load P, how do I find the max bending moment and deflection (and what assumptions are we making)?", "For a simply supported prismatic beam of span L with a single concentrated load P applied at midspan, the reactions are equal by symmetry, RA = RB = P/2, and the internal bending moment diagram is triangular with its maximum at the center: Mmax = (P/2)(L/2) = PL/4. The maximum vertical deflection also occurs at midspan and, using Euler‚ÄìBernoulli beam theory, is Œ¥max = PL^3/(48EI), where E is Young‚Äôs modulus and I is the second moment of area about the neutral axis (so EI is the flexural rigidity). The standard assumptions behind these formulas are: the beam is initially straight, slender, and linearly elastic (Hooke‚Äôs law, constant E); deflections and rotations are small so geometry changes can be neglected; cross-sections remain plane and perpendicular to the deflected centerline (shear deformation is neglected, meaning Euler‚ÄìBernoulli rather than Timoshenko behavior); the beam has constant I along the span (prismatic member); the supports are ideal simple supports (a pin and a roller) providing no end moment; and the load is truly a point load at midspan (in real labs a ‚Äúpoint‚Äù load is applied over a small width, which is usually a good approximation if that width is small compared with L). You can quickly sanity-check the results by noting Mmax scales with P and L (PL/4) and deflection scales with P and L^3 and is reduced by larger EI, which matches physical intuition: longer beams deflect much more, and stiffer materials or deeper sections (larger I) deflect less."),

