    ("For my HCI project, how do I make a layout that‚Äôs actually responsive (mobile-first) without everything breaking? I‚Äôm using CSS grid + flexbox but I‚Äôm not sure when to use which.", "Start mobile-first by designing the smallest layout first, then only add complexity as the screen gets wider: set a sensible base like box-sizing: border-box, use relative units (rem, %, vw) instead of fixed pixels for widths, keep images and media fluid (max-width: 100%; height: auto), and let content define height rather than forcing fixed heights that will overflow on small screens. Use CSS Grid when you‚Äôre arranging the page in two dimensions (rows and columns at the same time), like your overall app shell (header, nav, main, aside, footer) or a card gallery that needs consistent alignment; Grid is ideal for defining columns with repeat(auto-fit, minmax(‚Ä¶)) so items wrap naturally without you micromanaging breakpoints. Use Flexbox when you‚Äôre laying items out in one dimension (a row OR a column), like a navbar, a toolbar, a form row, a card‚Äôs internal layout, or aligning and spacing items; Flex shines for distributing space, aligning items, and handling unknown content sizes along a single axis. A reliable pattern is ‚ÄúGrid for the macro layout, Flex for the micro layout‚Äù: make the outer container a grid that changes column structure at breakpoints (for example, one column on phones, two columns on tablets, and a sidebar on desktop), and inside each region use flex to align controls, stack text, or space buttons. To prevent ‚Äúeverything breaking,‚Äù avoid hard-coded widths on components; instead constrain with max-width and let containers wrap (flex-wrap: wrap when needed), and prefer minmax in grid so columns can shrink without overflowing. Add breakpoints only when the design actually starts to look cramped (content-driven breakpoints), and keep them simple: start with a single-column flow, then at a wider width switch the grid template to multiple columns and adjust spacing and typography slightly. Finally, test responsiveness by resizing the browser and using device emulation, and watch for the common culprits: long unbroken strings (fix with overflow-wrap: anywhere), fixed-size images or iframes (make them fluid), and components that assume hover-only interactions (ensure touch-friendly spacing and visible focus states)."),

