    ("Can you explain basic heredity‚Äîlike what does it mean when a trait is dominant or recessive?", "Basic heredity is how living things pass traits from parents to offspring using genes, which are instructions in DNA; for many traits you inherit two versions of a gene (called alleles), one from each parent. A dominant allele is one that shows its effect in the trait when you have just one copy of it, while a recessive allele usually shows its effect only when you have two copies of it, because a dominant allele can ‚Äúmask‚Äù the recessive one in a mixed pair. For example, if we use a simple model where B is a dominant allele and b is a recessive allele, then someone with BB or Bb will show the dominant trait, and only someone with bb will show the recessive trait; this is why two parents who both show the dominant trait can still have a child with the recessive trait if both parents are Bb and each passes on the b allele. It‚Äôs also important to know that dominant does not mean ‚Äúmore common,‚Äù ‚Äúbetter,‚Äù or ‚Äústronger,‚Äù and many real traits (like height, skin color, and risk for many diseases) don‚Äôt follow a single dominant/recessive pattern because they involve multiple genes and environmental influences, but the dominant-versus-recessive idea is a helpful starting point for understanding how traits can be inherited."),

