    ("I‚Äôm in geometry‚Äîwhat are the properties of triangles again? Like scalene/isosceles/equilateral and also the angle sum thing.", "Triangles are 3-sided polygons, and the three interior angles always add up to 180¬∞ (so if you know two angles, the third is 180¬∞ minus their sum); also, an exterior angle of a triangle equals the sum of the two non-adjacent (remote) interior angles. By side lengths, a scalene triangle has all three sides different (and therefore all three angles different), an isosceles triangle has at least two equal sides and the angles opposite those equal sides are equal (the ‚Äúbase angles‚Äù match), and an equilateral triangle has all three sides equal and all three angles equal, which must be 60¬∞ each because 180¬∞ √∑ 3 = 60¬∞. By angles, an acute triangle has all angles less than 90¬∞, a right triangle has one 90¬∞ angle (and the other two must add to 90¬∞), and an obtuse triangle has one angle greater than 90¬∞ (so the other two add to less than 90¬∞). A useful inequality to remember is the triangle inequality: the sum of any two side lengths must be greater than the third side, otherwise a triangle can‚Äôt form."),

