    ("What are Kirchhoff‚Äôs laws and how do you use them to solve a circuit? If you can, do a tiny example with numbers.", "Kirchhoff‚Äôs laws are two rules that come from conservation principles and let you write equations for any electric circuit: Kirchhoff‚Äôs Current Law (KCL) says that at any junction (node) the total current flowing in equals the total current flowing out (because charge doesn‚Äôt pile up), and Kirchhoff‚Äôs Voltage Law (KVL) says that around any closed loop the algebraic sum of voltage rises and drops is zero (because energy is conserved). To solve a circuit, you label currents (or node voltages), choose a sign convention, then write KCL equations at key nodes and KVL equations around independent loops, using Ohm‚Äôs law V = IR to relate voltages and currents; finally you solve the resulting system of equations. Tiny example: a 10 V battery in series with two resistors, 2 ohms and 3 ohms; there is one loop current I, and KVL gives +10 ‚àí (2I) ‚àí (3I) = 0, so 10 ‚àí 5I = 0 and I = 2 A, which means the voltage drops are V2ohm = 2¬∑2 = 4 V and V3ohm = 3¬∑2 = 6 V, and they add to 10 V, confirming KVL."),

