    ("What‚Äôs a food chain vs a food web? Can you make an example with a pond ecosystem?", "A food chain is a single, simple pathway that shows who eats whom for energy, starting with a producer (like a plant or algae) and moving up through consumers; a food web is a more realistic network of many connected food chains because most organisms eat more than one thing and are eaten by more than one predator. In a pond, a food chain example could be algae (producer) ‚Üí zooplankton (primary consumer) ‚Üí small fish such as minnows (secondary consumer) ‚Üí largemouth bass (tertiary consumer) ‚Üí heron (top predator), and when you turn it into a food web you connect multiple paths: algae and pond plants can be eaten by snails, tadpoles, and some insects; zooplankton can be eaten by minnows and dragonfly nymphs; minnows can be eaten by bass, turtles, and herons; frogs may eat insects and be eaten by bass or herons; and when plants and animals die, decomposers like bacteria and fungi break them down and return nutrients to the water so producers can grow again. The key difference is that a food chain is one straight line of energy flow, while a food web shows the many overlapping feeding relationships that make an ecosystem stable and interconnected."),

