    ("Can you help me with statics? I have a 4m beam with a 10 kN downward load at 1m from the left support. How do I find the reaction forces at the supports?", "Assume the 4 m beam is simply supported at the left end (support A at x = 0) and the right end (support B at x = 4 m), with a single 10 kN downward point load located 1 m from A. Let the vertical reactions be Ay at A and By at B (there are no horizontal loads here, so the horizontal reaction is zero). First use vertical force equilibrium: sum of vertical forces equals zero, so Ay + By ‚àí 10 = 0, which means Ay + By = 10 kN. Next use moment equilibrium to solve for one reaction; take moments about A so Ay creates no moment: the 10 kN load produces a clockwise moment of 10 kN √ó 1 m = 10 kN¬∑m, and By produces a counterclockwise moment of By √ó 4 m, so sum of moments about A equals zero gives 4By ‚àí 10 = 0, hence By = 2.5 kN upward. Substitute back into Ay + By = 10 to get Ay = 10 ‚àí 2.5 = 7.5 kN upward. A quick check using moments about B also works: the load is 3 m from B, so Ay √ó 4 = 10 √ó 3 gives Ay = 7.5 kN, consistent; therefore the support reactions are 7.5 kN up at the left support and 2.5 kN up at the right support."),

