    ("I‚Äôm trying to understand decimals: what‚Äôs the difference between 0.3 and 0.30, and why are they the same value?", "0.3 and 0.30 look different, but they represent the same amount because trailing zeros to the right of a decimal don‚Äôt change the value. The digit 3 in 0.3 is in the tenths place, meaning ‚Äúthree tenths,‚Äù or 3/10; in 0.30 the 3 is still in the tenths place and the 0 is in the hundredths place, meaning ‚Äúzero hundredths,‚Äù so it‚Äôs 30/100, and 30/100 simplifies to 3/10, which is exactly 0.3. A helpful way to picture it is money: $0.3 is 30 cents, and $0.30 is also 30 cents‚Äîwriting an extra zero just makes the number look more precise, but it doesn‚Äôt add any value."),

