    ("We‚Äôre learning the periodic table and I‚Äôm confused: what do the groups/columns mean and why are some elements super reactive?", "On the periodic table, a group (a vertical column) is a set of elements that have the same number of valence electrons, meaning electrons in the outermost energy level, and that‚Äôs why elements in the same group tend to have similar chemical behavior; for example, Group 1 (the alkali metals like lithium, sodium, and potassium) all have 1 valence electron, and Group 17 (the halogens like fluorine and chlorine) all have 7 valence electrons. Elements are ‚Äúsuper reactive‚Äù when their outer electron situation makes it very easy to reach a more stable arrangement: atoms are most stable when their outer shell is full (often 8 valence electrons for many main-group elements), so Group 1 metals react strongly because they can lose 1 electron to reach a full shell underneath, while Group 17 halogens react strongly because they can gain 1 electron to fill their outer shell; when a Group 1 metal meets a Group 17 halogen, the metal can transfer an electron to the halogen, forming ions and an ionic compound like sodium chloride (table salt). Reactivity also changes as you go down a group because the outer electrons are farther from the nucleus and more shielded by inner electrons: alkali metals generally get more reactive down the group because that single valence electron is easier to lose, while halogens generally get less reactive down the group because it becomes harder for the larger atoms to attract and gain an extra electron."),

