    ("Can you explain protein synthesis like I‚Äôm in 7th grade? Like what do DNA, mRNA, and ribosomes actually do?", "Protein synthesis is how a cell builds proteins, which are like tiny machines that do jobs in your body (like building muscle, carrying oxygen, or helping you digest food). DNA is the master instruction book stored safely in the cell‚Äôs nucleus, and each gene is a recipe for one protein, but the cell usually doesn‚Äôt take the DNA out where the building happens; instead, it makes a working copy called mRNA (messenger RNA). During a step called transcription, the cell ‚Äúreads‚Äù a gene in the DNA and writes a matching mRNA message (using RNA letters A, U, C, and G instead of DNA‚Äôs A, T, C, and G), and that mRNA leaves the nucleus and goes into the cytoplasm. Ribosomes are the protein-building machines that grab the mRNA and read it three letters at a time (each three-letter ‚Äúcodon‚Äù is like a word that stands for one amino acid), and during translation they use that code to link amino acids together in the correct order; tRNA molecules act like delivery trucks that bring the right amino acid for each codon. When the ribosome reaches a stop signal, the chain is finished and folds into a specific shape, and that folded shape is the working protein. In short: DNA stores the original recipe, mRNA carries a copy of the recipe to the work area, and ribosomes read the recipe and assemble amino acids to make the protein."),

