    ("I‚Äôm doing a poster for class‚Äîcan you explain the water cycle in a way a 3rd grader would get it?", "The water cycle is how water moves around Earth over and over again, like a never-ending trip. First, the Sun warms up water in oceans, lakes, rivers, and even puddles, and some of it turns into an invisible gas called water vapor and rises into the air; this is called evaporation (plants can also release water vapor from their leaves, which is part of the cycle too). Next, high up in the sky where it‚Äôs cooler, the water vapor changes back into tiny drops of water and makes clouds; this is called condensation. When the drops in the clouds get too heavy, the water falls back to Earth as precipitation, like rain, snow, sleet, or hail. Finally, the water collects again in places like rivers, lakes, oceans, and the ground (some soaks in to become groundwater), and then the Sun warms it up and the whole cycle starts again."),

