    ("I have a science fair idea: which paper towel brand absorbs the most water. Can you help me make a fair test and what to write for my hypothesis?", "To make a fair test of which paper towel brand absorbs the most water, keep everything the same except the brand: cut each brand into identical pieces (for example, 10 cm by 10 cm squares or one full sheet each, but use the exact same size for every trial), use the same amount of water each time (measure with a graduated cup or syringe, like 50 mL), use the same container and water temperature, and use the same method and time for absorbing (for example, place the towel flat in the water for 10 seconds, lift it straight up, let it drip for 5 seconds, then measure how much water it held). A simple way to measure absorption is to weigh each dry towel piece on a kitchen scale, do the soaking step, weigh it again, and subtract: absorbed water = wet mass ‚àí dry mass (because 1 gram of water is about 1 milliliter, the mass difference tells you the volume absorbed). Do at least 3‚Äì5 trials per brand and average the results so one ‚Äúlucky‚Äù test doesn‚Äôt decide the winner, and write down any observations like thickness, texture, or if it tears. A strong hypothesis is a clear prediction with a reason, such as: ‚ÄúIf I test equal-sized pieces of several paper towel brands using the same amount of water and the same soaking time, then Brand X will absorb the most water because it feels thicker and has a quilted pattern that may trap more water,‚Äù and you can replace Brand X with the brand you think will win based on what you notice before testing."),

