    ("I‚Äôm building a LEGO car for class and it keeps going slow‚Ä¶ how do gear ratios work and which gears make it faster vs stronger?", "Gear ratios are about trading speed for strength (torque): when a small gear drives a bigger gear, the car gets more pushing power but the wheels turn slower; when a big gear drives a smaller gear, the wheels spin faster but with less power, so it may stall or slip. You can calculate the ratio by dividing the driven gear‚Äôs teeth by the driving gear‚Äôs teeth: if an 8-tooth gear drives a 24-tooth gear, the ratio is 24/8 = 3:1, meaning the motor turns 3 times for 1 wheel turn, which is slower but about 3 times stronger at the wheel (good for starting, climbing, or heavy cars); if a 24-tooth drives an 8-tooth, the ratio is 8/24 = 1:3, meaning the wheel turns 3 times for each motor turn, which is faster but weaker (good only if the car is light and rolls easily). For a LEGO car that feels slow, first make sure it rolls freely (wheels not rubbing the frame, axles straight, bushings not squeezing the wheels, and no extra friction), then choose gearing based on the problem: if it struggles to start, climbs poorly, or the motor bogs down, gear down for strength (small-to-big like 8‚Üí24, 12‚Üí36, or 16‚Üí40); if it accelerates fine but you want higher top speed on flat ground, gear up for speed (big-to-small like 24‚Üí8 or 40‚Üí16), but only after reducing weight and friction because speed gearing needs a low-resistance car. If you use multiple gear stages, multiply the ratios (for example 8‚Üí24 is 3:1 and then 12‚Üí36 is 3:1, together that‚Äôs 9:1 strong but slow), and remember the best ‚Äúfast‚Äù setup is usually a smooth, light car with just a modest speed increase so the motor can still keep spinning quickly."),

