    ("Why does a heavier backpack make it harder to start moving? Is that friction or gravity or both?", "A heavier backpack is harder to start moving mainly because of inertia: when you add mass, the backpack resists changes in motion more, so you must apply a larger force to accelerate it from rest (Newton‚Äôs second law, F = m a). Friction is also involved if the backpack is on the ground, because the backpack‚Äôs weight comes from gravity pulling down, and that increases the normal force from the floor; since friction is roughly proportional to the normal force (F_friction ‚âà ŒºN), a heavier backpack has a larger maximum static friction to overcome before it will start sliding. Gravity itself is not directly ‚Äústopping‚Äù the backpack from moving sideways, but gravity increases the weight, which increases the normal force and therefore increases friction; so the difficulty comes from both inertia (more mass to accelerate) and friction (more force needed to break static friction), with friction mattering most for sliding on a surface and inertia mattering any time you try to start it moving, even if you‚Äôre lifting or carrying it."),

