    ("What are the 3 branches of the US government and what does ‚Äòchecks and balances‚Äô mean with a real example?", "The U.S. government has three branches: the Legislative Branch (Congress‚Äîthe House of Representatives and the Senate) makes laws, the Executive Branch (the President and the agencies that carry out federal programs) enforces laws, and the Judicial Branch (the federal courts, including the Supreme Court) interprets laws and decides whether they follow the Constitution. ‚ÄúChecks and balances‚Äù means each branch has powers that can limit the others so no single branch becomes too powerful; for example, if Congress passes a bill, the President can veto it, but Congress can check that veto by overriding it with a two-thirds vote in both the House and the Senate, and the courts can also check both branches by ruling that a law or executive action is unconstitutional. This system forces cooperation and helps protect citizens‚Äô rights by spreading power across the three branches."),

