    ("Why do we celebrate Juneteenth and what should I include in a 1-minute class presentation about it?", "We celebrate Juneteenth, short for ‚ÄúJune Nineteenth,‚Äù because on June 19, 1865, Union Army General Gordon Granger arrived in Galveston, Texas and announced that enslaved people were free, bringing the news of emancipation to one of the last places in the Confederacy where slavery continued even after the Emancipation Proclamation of 1863; Juneteenth honors the end of slavery in the United States, recognizes the long struggle for freedom and civil rights, and is now a federal holiday (Juneteenth National Independence Day) first observed nationwide in 2021. In a 1-minute class presentation, include the key date and place (June 19, 1865, Galveston, Texas), explain why it mattered (freedom finally being enforced and communicated to many enslaved people in Texas), connect it to the bigger timeline (Emancipation Proclamation in 1863 and the 13th Amendment ending slavery in 1865), and share how people commemorate it today (community gatherings, music, food, parades, and learning about Black history), ending with a simple takeaway like ‚ÄúJuneteenth reminds us that freedom delayed is still worth fighting for, and that knowing history helps us build a more fair future.‚Äù"),

