    ("What were the main causes of World War I vs World War II? I keep mixing them up.", "World War I (1914‚Äì1918) was mainly caused by rising tensions in Europe from militarism (countries building big armies and navies), alliances that promised to pull many nations into any conflict (especially the Triple Alliance and Triple Entente), imperial rivalry over colonies and power, and intense nationalism; the immediate spark was the assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria-Hungary on June 28, 1914, which set off a chain reaction as Austria-Hungary moved against Serbia and alliance commitments drew in Russia, Germany, France, and Britain. World War II (1939‚Äì1945) was mainly caused by the unstable aftermath of World War I, especially resentment and economic strain linked to the Treaty of Versailles, the Great Depression, and the rise of aggressive totalitarian regimes that sought expansion (Nazi Germany under Adolf Hitler, Fascist Italy under Benito Mussolini, and militarist Japan), along with the failure of appeasement and collective security; the immediate trigger in Europe was Germany‚Äôs invasion of Poland on September 1, 1939, which led Britain and France to declare war, while in Asia the war grew out of Japan‚Äôs expansion in China and the Pacific and became truly global after Japan attacked Pearl Harbor on December 7, 1941. A simple way to keep them straight is that World War I began with a single assassination igniting a tightly linked alliance system, while World War II began with deliberate expansion by dictatorships trying to conquer territory and remake the world order after the problems left by World War I."),

