    ("Explain photosynthesis but like, detailed‚Äîwhat goes in, what comes out, and what part of the plant does it?", "Photosynthesis is the process plants use to make their own food (a sugar called glucose) using light energy, and it mostly happens in the leaves inside tiny cell structures called chloroplasts that contain the green pigment chlorophyll. What goes in is sunlight, water (H2O) that the roots absorb from the soil and send up through tubes called xylem, and carbon dioxide (CO2) that enters the leaf through small pores called stomata; what comes out is glucose (C6H12O6), which the plant uses for energy and growth or stores as starch, and oxygen (O2), which leaves the plant through the stomata as a ‚Äúwaste‚Äù product. A helpful overall equation is 6 CO2 + 6 H2O + light energy ‚Üí C6H12O6 + 6 O2, and it happens in two main stages: in the light-dependent reactions (in the thylakoid membranes of the chloroplast) chlorophyll captures light to split water, releasing oxygen and making energy-carrying molecules (ATP and NADPH), and in the Calvin cycle (in the chloroplast stroma) the plant uses CO2 plus that stored energy to build sugar. In short, leaves do most of the work, roots supply the water, stomata let CO2 in and O2 out, and the chloroplasts are the ‚Äúsolar-powered sugar factories‚Äù that turn light, water, and carbon dioxide into glucose and oxygen."),

