    ("I‚Äôm stuck on functions vs relations‚Äîhow do you tell from a set of ordered pairs if it‚Äôs a function?", "From a set of ordered pairs, it‚Äôs a function if every input (the x-value) is matched with exactly one output (the y-value). To check, scan the pairs and look only at the first coordinate in each one: if the same x appears more than once with different y-values, then it‚Äôs not a function (for example, (2, 5) and (2, 7) together break the rule because input 2 would give two outputs), but if repeated x-values always have the same y (like (3, 4) and (3, 4) listed twice), it still counts as a function because the input isn‚Äôt producing a different output. A relation is just any set of ordered pairs, so every function is a relation, but the ‚Äúone output per input‚Äù rule is what makes a relation a function."),

