    ("So like‚Ä¶ why is fire hot? Is it because of atoms moving or something? I‚Äôm genuinely curious.", "Fire feels hot because it‚Äôs a region where a chemical reaction (combustion) is rapidly turning the chemical energy stored in fuel (like wood, paper, or gas) into thermal energy, and ‚Äútemperature‚Äù is basically a measure of how much random kinetic energy the particles have, so yes: it‚Äôs very much about atoms and molecules moving faster. In a flame, fuel molecules react with oxygen and form new molecules such as carbon dioxide and water; making and breaking chemical bonds rearranges energy, and in combustion the products end up with lots of energy in their motion and vibrations, which raises the temperature of the gas. That hot gas then transfers energy to you in three main ways: it radiates infrared light (heat radiation) you can feel even from a distance, it convects by moving hot air toward you (the rising ‚Äúheat‚Äù you feel above a flame), and it conducts heat if you touch something the flame has heated. The flame also glows because some particles are hot enough to emit visible light (and in many flames, tiny soot particles get heated until they glow), but the key idea is that combustion releases energy quickly, making the particles in and around the flame move and vibrate much faster, and that fast microscopic motion is what you experience as ‚Äúhot.‚Äù"),

