    ("In AP Stats we did regression‚Äîcan you explain what it means if r is close to 1, and what residuals tell you?", "If r (the correlation coefficient) is close to 1, it means there is a very strong positive linear relationship between the two quantitative variables: as x increases, y tends to increase in a pattern that lies close to a straight line, so the points on a scatterplot would cluster tightly around an upward-sloping line (r = 1 would be a perfectly straight-line pattern with no scatter). Residuals tell you how far off the regression line‚Äôs predictions are for each data point: a residual is y ‚àí ≈∑ (actual minus predicted), so a positive residual means the point is above the line (the model underpredicted) and a negative residual means it‚Äôs below the line (the model overpredicted); looking at a residual plot helps you judge whether a linear model is appropriate and whether the spread is consistent, because residuals should look randomly scattered around 0 with no clear curve or pattern if a linear regression is a good fit, while patterns (like a U-shape) suggest nonlinearity, and unusually large residuals can flag outliers or influential points."),

