    ("In physics, can you walk me through circular motion? Like why do we feel ‚Äòpulled‚Äô outward on a turning ride if the force is inward?", "In circular motion, an object keeps changing direction, and any change in velocity (even if speed stays the same) requires an acceleration toward the center of the circle called centripetal acceleration, with size a = v¬≤/r, so the required net force is inward, F = m v¬≤/r; on a turning ride, that inward force is provided by the seat, floor, or a harness pushing you toward the center. The reason you feel ‚Äúpulled outward‚Äù is not because there is a real outward force acting on you in an inertial (non-accelerating) frame; it‚Äôs because your body‚Äôs inertia wants to keep moving in a straight line tangent to the circle, while the ride forces you to curve inward, so you press outward against the seat or wall and you feel the seat pushing on you. If you describe the motion from the rotating point of view of someone riding along, you can introduce a ‚Äúcentrifugal‚Äù pseudo-force that points outward to make Newton‚Äôs laws look balanced in that accelerating frame, but it‚Äôs a bookkeeping force, not a new physical interaction; the real interaction forces are still things like the seat‚Äôs normal force and friction, and they point inward to provide the centripetal force. A quick way to picture it is a ball on a string: the string pulls inward to bend the ball‚Äôs path, and if the string breaks the ball flies off in a straight line, not outward from the center, showing that the ‚Äúoutward pull‚Äù feeling comes from your tendency to go straight while something else forces you to turn."),

