    ("For calculus, how do you do this limit: lim(x‚Üí0) (sin x)/x and why does it equal 1?", "To evaluate lim(x‚Üí0) (sin x)/x, you use the key fact that for angles measured in radians, sin x is extremely close to x when x is close to 0, so their ratio approaches 1. A standard geometric proof uses the unit circle: for 0 < x < œÄ/2 (in radians), the area of the triangle formed by the radius and the tangent line is larger than the area of the circular sector, which is larger than the area of the triangle formed by the radius and the chord; translating those area comparisons gives sin x < x < tan x, and dividing by sin x (which is positive here) gives 1 < x/sin x < 1/cos x, then taking reciprocals gives cos x < (sin x)/x < 1. As x‚Üí0, cos x‚Üí1, so by the Squeeze Theorem (something trapped between two expressions that both approach 1 must also approach 1), (sin x)/x‚Üí1; the same conclusion holds for x‚Üí0 from the negative side because sin is an odd function and the ratio stays even, so the two-sided limit is 1."),

