    ("I‚Äôm trying to learn basic frontend stuff‚Äîwhat‚Äôs the difference between HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, and what should I learn first?", "HTML, CSS, and JavaScript are the three core building blocks of most websites, and they each have a different job: HTML (HyperText Markup Language) provides the structure and meaning of content, like headings, paragraphs, links, images, forms, and page sections (it‚Äôs the ‚Äúskeleton‚Äù and the part that makes content understandable to browsers and assistive technologies); CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) controls how that HTML looks, including layout, colors, fonts, spacing, and responsive design for different screen sizes (it‚Äôs the ‚Äúclothes and layout,‚Äù turning a plain document into a designed interface); JavaScript is the programming language that adds behavior and interactivity, like responding to clicks, validating forms, showing/hiding elements, fetching data from a server, and updating the page without reloading (it‚Äôs the ‚Äúmuscles/brain‚Äù that makes the page dynamic). A good learning order is HTML first (learn semantic tags like header, nav, main, section, article, footer; links and images; basic forms), then CSS (the box model, selectors, specificity, flexbox and grid, responsive design with media queries), and then JavaScript (variables, functions, events, DOM manipulation, and basic async concepts like fetch and promises), because you‚Äôll understand what you‚Äôre styling and what you‚Äôre making interactive. As you learn, build tiny projects that combine all three‚Äîstart with a simple personal page in HTML, make it look good with CSS, then add small JavaScript features like a button that toggles a menu or validates a form‚Äîsince real progress comes from seeing how structure, style, and behavior work together in the browser."),

