    ("I have to model a Ferris wheel with a parametric equation but I‚Äôm stuck. Radius = 20 m, center is 22 m above the ground, and it makes one rotation every 40 seconds. Can you write x(t), y(t) and explain what the numbers mean?", "Let t be time in seconds and measure x in meters horizontally and y in meters vertically with y = 0 at the ground; a Ferris wheel of radius 20 m whose center is 22 m above the ground can be modeled by x(t) = 20 cos( (2œÄ/40)t ) and y(t) = 22 + 20 sin( (2œÄ/40)t ). Here 20 is the radius (so the rider is always 20 m from the center), 22 is the vertical shift putting the center at height 22 m, and (2œÄ/40) radians per second is the angular speed because one full turn is 2œÄ radians completed in 40 seconds; at t = 0 this choice starts the rider at the rightmost point at height 22 m, and as t increases the point moves counterclockwise (if you want it to start at the bottom instead, you could use x(t) = 20 cos((2œÄ/40)t ‚àí œÄ/2) and y(t) = 22 + 20 sin((2œÄ/40)t ‚àí œÄ/2), which gives y(0) = 2 m)."),

