    ("Can you explain the difference between a function and just a relation? Like with mapping diagrams and ordered pairs?", "A relation is any set of ordered pairs (x, y) that shows a connection between inputs and outputs, so it can include situations where one input is matched with several different outputs; a function is a special kind of relation where every input x in the domain is paired with exactly one output y (it‚Äôs okay if different inputs share the same output, but a single input cannot point to two different outputs). In ordered pairs, you can check this by looking for repeated first coordinates: if you see (2, 5) and (2, 7) in the same set, that relation is not a function because the input 2 would have two outputs; but (2, 5) and (3, 5) is still a function because each input has one output even though the output repeats. In a mapping diagram, a relation becomes a function only if each input on the left has exactly one arrow leaving it (an input with two arrows means ‚Äúnot a function,‚Äù and an input with no arrow means that input isn‚Äôt actually in the domain of the relation as listed), and this same idea matches the vertical line test on a graph: if any vertical line hits the graph more than once, some x-value has more than one y-value, so it‚Äôs a relation but not a function."),

