    ("I don‚Äôt get limits at ALL. What does lim(x‚Üí2) (x^2-4)/(x-2) actually mean, and how do you solve it without just memorizing tricks?", "lim(x‚Üí2) (x^2‚àí4)/(x‚àí2) means: look at the values of the expression (x^2‚àí4)/(x‚àí2) for x very close to 2 (from either side), and ask what number those values get closer and closer to; it is not the same as ‚Äúplug in x = 2‚Äù when that would cause a division by zero, because a limit is about approaching, not necessarily being equal at the point. If you try plugging in x = 2 you get (4‚àí4)/(2‚àí2) = 0/0, which is an ‚Äúindeterminate form‚Äù that tells you the expression is undefined at x = 2 but might still have a well-defined limiting value nearby. To find it without memorizing, rewrite the expression in a way that makes sense near x = 2: factor the numerator using the difference of squares, x^2‚àí4 = (x‚àí2)(x+2), so for x not equal to 2 the expression becomes (x‚àí2)(x+2)/(x‚àí2) = x+2; this cancellation is valid because we are only looking at x close to 2, not equal to 2. Now the limit is lim(x‚Üí2) (x+2) = 4, because as x gets close to 2, x+2 gets close to 4. A quick reality check using nearby values shows the same idea: at x = 1.9 the original expression equals (1.9^2‚àí4)/(1.9‚àí2) = (3.61‚àí4)/(‚àí0.1) = 3.9, and at x = 2.1 it equals (4.41‚àí4)/(0.1) = 4.1, so from both sides the values squeeze toward 4, which is exactly what the limit is saying."),

