    ("We‚Äôre doing molecular genetics and I‚Äôm confused: how does a frameshift mutation change the protein compared to a point mutation? Can you give an example with a short DNA sequence?", "A point mutation is a change in a single nucleotide (for example, swapping one base for another) and it usually affects only one codon, so it may change just one amino acid (missense), create a stop codon (nonsense), or change nothing at all because of redundancy in the genetic code (silent); a frameshift mutation is caused by inserting or deleting nucleotides in a number that is not a multiple of three, which shifts the reading frame so every codon downstream changes, often producing many wrong amino acids and frequently an early stop codon, making a truncated, usually nonfunctional protein. Example (coding DNA shown 5‚Äô‚Üí3‚Äô): original sequence ATG AAA GGC TTT TAA translates as Met‚ÄìLys‚ÄìGly‚ÄìPhe‚ÄìStop; a point mutation changing the second codon from AAA to AGA gives ATG AGA GGC TTT TAA, translating as Met‚ÄìArg‚ÄìGly‚ÄìPhe‚ÄìStop (only Lys‚ÜíArg changes). Now a frameshift: insert one base C after the start codon, giving ATG CAA AGG CTT TTT AA‚Ä¶ which is read as ATG‚ÄìCAA‚ÄìAGG‚ÄìCTT‚ÄìTTT‚Ä¶ and translates as Met‚ÄìGln‚ÄìArg‚ÄìLeu‚ÄìPhe‚Ä¶ (everything after the insertion is different, and the original stop codon is no longer in the same place, so a stop may appear later or earlier by chance)."),

