    ("What‚Äôs the difference between climate and weather? My uncle says it‚Äôs the same thing and I don‚Äôt know how to explain it", "Weather is what the atmosphere is doing right now or over the next few days in a specific place, like ‚Äúit‚Äôs raining this afternoon,‚Äù ‚Äúit will be windy tomorrow,‚Äù or ‚Äúwe‚Äôre having a heat wave this week.‚Äù Climate is the long-term pattern of weather for a region, usually described using averages and typical ranges over decades (often about 30 years), like ‚Äúthis area has hot, dry summers and mild, wet winters‚Äù or ‚Äúwinters here are usually cold with occasional snow.‚Äù A simple way to explain it to your uncle is: weather is your outfit today, climate is your whole wardrobe‚Äîtoday might be unusual, but the wardrobe tells you what‚Äôs typical over time; that‚Äôs why one cold day doesn‚Äôt disprove global warming, because climate is about long-term trends, not a single day‚Äôs weather."),

