    ("Physics question: can you explain the Doppler effect like I‚Äôm smart but tired? And can you do one example problem with a siren moving toward a stationary observer?", "The Doppler effect is the reason a moving sound source seems higher-pitched as it comes toward you and lower-pitched as it moves away: the source is still making the same sound, but its motion squeezes the sound waves closer together in front of it (shorter wavelength, higher frequency) and stretches them out behind it (longer wavelength, lower frequency), like a moving person making ripples in water that bunch up in front and spread out behind. For a siren moving toward a stationary observer, the observed frequency is f_observed = f_source √ó v/(v ‚àí v_source), where v is the speed of sound and v_source is the source speed toward the observer; example: a siren emits f_source = 800 Hz, the speed of sound is v = 343 m/s, and the siren moves toward you at v_source = 30 m/s, so f_observed = 800 √ó 343/(343 ‚àí 30) = 800 √ó 343/313 ‚âà 800 √ó 1.0958 ‚âà 877 Hz, meaning you hear about 877 Hz while it‚Äôs approaching (and if it were moving away at the same speed you‚Äôd hear f = 800 √ó 343/(343 + 30) ‚âà 728 Hz, which matches the ‚Äúhigher coming, lower going‚Äù idea)."),

