    ("Solve for x: 3(2x 5) = 4x + 7. Also can you show me how to check it after?", "Start by distributing the 3 on the left: 3(2x ‚àí 5) = 6x ‚àí 15, so the equation becomes 6x ‚àí 15 = 4x + 7; subtract 4x from both sides to get 2x ‚àí 15 = 7, then add 15 to both sides to get 2x = 22, and divide by 2 to find x = 11. To check, plug x = 11 back into the original equation: left side is 3(2¬∑11 ‚àí 5) = 3(22 ‚àí 5) = 3¬∑17 = 51, and right side is 4¬∑11 + 7 = 44 + 7 = 51, and since both sides match, x = 11 is correct."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 01:52 - Category: world_wars
    ("What were the main causes of the American Civil War? My teacher keeps saying ‚Äústates‚Äô rights‚Äù but I don‚Äôt get what that means", "The main cause of the American Civil War (1861‚Äì1865) was a long-running conflict over slavery‚Äîespecially whether slavery would be protected and expanded into new U.S. territories and states as the country grew westward‚Äîand ‚Äústates‚Äô rights‚Äù in this context mostly meant that Southern leaders argued individual states should have the right to keep slavery and to ignore or block federal laws that threatened it. The North and many anti-slavery Americans believed the federal government could limit slavery‚Äôs spread and that the Union was permanent, while many white Southerners feared losing political power and an economy deeply tied to enslaved labor; these tensions flared through events like the Missouri Compromise (1820), the Compromise of 1850 and the Fugitive Slave Act (which forced the return of escaped enslaved people even from free states), the Kansas‚ÄìNebraska Act (1854) and violent fighting in ‚ÄúBleeding Kansas,‚Äù the Supreme Court‚Äôs Dred Scott decision (1857) saying Congress couldn‚Äôt ban slavery in the territories, and John Brown‚Äôs raid (1859). The immediate trigger was Abraham Lincoln‚Äôs election in 1860 on a platform opposing the expansion of slavery, after which several Southern states seceded to form the Confederate States of America; when Confederate forces fired on Fort Sumter in April 1861, war began. So when your teacher says ‚Äústates‚Äô rights,‚Äù it helps to ask, ‚ÄúStates‚Äô rights to do what?‚Äù‚Äîin the Civil War era, the central issue behind that phrase was the right to maintain and expand slavery, along with related disputes about federal power, enforcement of slavery laws, and whether a state could leave the Union."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 01:52 - Category: seasons_why
    ("Why do we have seasons? My little brother thinks it‚Äôs because we‚Äôre closer to the sun in summer and I‚Äôm pretty sure that‚Äôs not right but I need an easy way to explain it.", "We have seasons mainly because Earth is tilted, not because we‚Äôre much closer to the Sun in summer. Earth‚Äôs axis is tilted about 23.5 degrees, so as Earth goes around the Sun, each half of the planet takes turns leaning toward the Sun and then away from it; when your hemisphere is tilted toward the Sun, the Sun is higher in the sky and its light hits the ground more directly, so the same sunlight is concentrated on a smaller area and warms things more, and you also get longer days, which means more hours of heating each day‚Äîtogether that makes summer. When your hemisphere is tilted away, the Sun stays lower in the sky so its light is spread out and weaker, and the days are shorter, so there‚Äôs less time to warm up‚Äîso it‚Äôs winter. The ‚Äúcloser to the Sun‚Äù idea sounds reasonable, but it‚Äôs not the main cause: Earth‚Äôs orbit is only slightly oval, and in fact Earth is closest to the Sun in early January and farthest in early July, which is why it can be winter in the Northern Hemisphere while it‚Äôs summer in the Southern Hemisphere at the same time; if distance were the reason, both hemispheres would have summer together. A simple way to show it is to use a flashlight and a tilted ball: shine the light and notice that when the ball is tilted toward the light the bright spot is smaller and brighter (more heating, like summer), and when it‚Äôs tilted away the spot is larger and dimmer (less heating, like winter)."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 01:52 - Category: government
    ("Can you compare the U.S. government branches (legislative/executive/judicial) like I‚Äôm in 7th grade? I keep mixing up what they do", "Think of the U.S. government like a school with three big jobs that are kept separate so no one person gets too powerful. The legislative branch is Congress (the House of Representatives and the Senate), and its main job is to make laws, which is like writing the school rules; it can also vote on the budget, declare war, and the Senate approves important presidential picks like judges and cabinet members. The executive branch is led by the President, and its main job is to carry out and enforce the laws, which is like the principal and staff making sure the rules are followed; the President can sign a bill into law or veto it, runs federal agencies, and is commander in chief of the military. The judicial branch is the court system led by the Supreme Court, and its main job is to interpret the laws and the Constitution, which is like referees deciding what the rules mean in a tricky situation; courts can rule that a law or government action is unconstitutional. A quick way to remember is Make (Congress), Enforce (President), and Explain/Interpret (Courts), and if you‚Äôre mixing them up, picture a law as a note passing through three stations: Congress writes it, the President carries it out, and the courts decide what it really means and whether it breaks the Constitution."),

