    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 01:52 - Category: parametric_equations
    ("In Algebra 2, what‚Äôs a parametric equation? Can you show an example and how it makes a graph?", "A parametric equation (or parametric form) describes a curve by giving both x and y as functions of a third variable called a parameter, usually t, so instead of y = f(x) you write x = x(t) and y = y(t); as t changes, the point (x(t), y(t)) moves and traces out the graph. For example, let x = 2t + 1 and y = t ‚àí 3: if t = 0 the point is (1, ‚àí3), if t = 1 the point is (3, ‚àí2), if t = 2 the point is (5, ‚àí1), and as you keep increasing or decreasing t these points line up to make a straight line; to see what line it is in x-y form, solve x = 2t + 1 for t to get t = (x ‚àí 1)/2, then substitute into y = t ‚àí 3 to get y = (x ‚àí 1)/2 ‚àí 3 = (x ‚àí 7)/2, which is exactly the line the moving point traces. Parametric equations are especially useful for curves that are hard to write as y = f(x) or for showing direction and motion, like a circle: x = 3cos(t), y = 3sin(t) traces the circle x^2 + y^2 = 9, and as t goes from 0 to 2œÄ the point goes once around the circle counterclockwise."),

