    ("AP Calc: can you walk me through finding the limit lim(x->2) (x^2-4)/(x-2) and explain why you can‚Äôt just plug in 2 at first?", "To find lim(x‚Üí2) (x^2‚àí4)/(x‚àí2), you first try direct substitution to see what happens: plugging in x=2 gives (2^2‚àí4)/(2‚àí2) = (4‚àí4)/0 = 0/0, which is undefined, so you can‚Äôt ‚Äújust plug in 2‚Äù because the expression isn‚Äôt defined at x=2 and 0/0 is an indeterminate form that doesn‚Äôt tell you the limit. Instead, simplify the expression for x near 2 by factoring the numerator: x^2‚àí4 is a difference of squares, so x^2‚àí4 = (x‚àí2)(x+2). Then (x^2‚àí4)/(x‚àí2) = (x‚àí2)(x+2)/(x‚àí2) = x+2 for all x‚â†2 (the cancellation is valid only when x‚àí2 isn‚Äôt zero). Now the limit becomes lim(x‚Üí2) (x+2), and you can substitute safely because x+2 is continuous: 2+2 = 4, so the limit is 4; the key idea is that the original function has a ‚Äúhole‚Äù at x=2, but as x gets close to 2 the values follow the simpler expression x+2 and approach 4."),

