    ("I need help finding the derivative of f(x)= (3x^2-5x+1)/(x-2) and then using it to figure out where f is increasing/decreasing.", "To differentiate f(x) = (3x^2 ‚àí 5x + 1)/(x ‚àí 2), use the quotient rule with u = 3x^2 ‚àí 5x + 1 and v = x ‚àí 2, so u‚Ä≤ = 6x ‚àí 5 and v‚Ä≤ = 1; then f‚Ä≤(x) = (u‚Ä≤v ‚àí uv‚Ä≤)/v^2 = [(6x ‚àí 5)(x ‚àí 2) ‚àí (3x^2 ‚àí 5x + 1)]/(x ‚àí 2)^2, which simplifies to f‚Ä≤(x) = (3x^2 ‚àí 12x + 9)/(x ‚àí 2)^2 = 3(x ‚àí 1)(x ‚àí 3)/(x ‚àí 2)^2. The domain excludes x = 2, and since (x ‚àí 2)^2 is always positive for x ‚â† 2, the sign of f‚Ä≤ is determined by 3(x ‚àí 1)(x ‚àí 3): it is positive when x < 1 (both factors negative) and when x > 3 (both factors positive), and negative when 1 < x < 3; splitting at the discontinuity x = 2 gives that f is increasing on (‚àí‚àû, 1) and (3, ‚àû), and decreasing on (1, 2) and (2, 3). The critical points where f‚Ä≤ = 0 are x = 1 and x = 3 (both in the domain), so f has a local maximum at x = 1 (increasing then decreasing) and a local minimum at x = 3 (decreasing then increasing), while x = 2 is not a critical point because f is not defined there."),

