    ("I‚Äôm in my algorithms class and I‚Äôm stuck: can you explain Big-O vs Big-Theta in plain English, and then analyze the runtime of this pseudocode with two nested loops where the inner loop runs up to i each time?", "Big-O and Big-Theta are both ways to describe how an algorithm‚Äôs running time grows as the input size n gets large, but they mean slightly different things: Big-O is an upper bound, meaning the runtime grows no faster than some function (it‚Äôs a ‚Äúno worse than‚Äù guarantee, like saying a trip will take at most 2 hours), while Big-Theta is a tight bound, meaning the runtime grows at the same rate both above and below (it‚Äôs a ‚Äúthis is the true growth rate‚Äù statement, like saying the trip consistently takes about 2 hours, not just at most 2). For pseudocode with two nested loops where the outer loop runs i from 1 to n and the inner loop runs from 1 to i each time, the total number of inner-loop iterations is 1 + 2 + 3 + ‚Ä¶ + n, which equals n(n+1)/2; since n(n+1)/2 grows proportionally to n^2 (constants and lower-order terms don‚Äôt matter for asymptotic growth), the runtime is Theta(n^2), and therefore it is also O(n^2) (and, in fact, also Omega(n^2) because it really does take on the order of n^2 steps)."),

