    ("How do you do regression analysis from scratch? Like if I have (x,y) data points from a lab, how do I get the line of best fit and R^2 without just using a calculator?", "To do simple linear regression from scratch for lab data (x, y), you‚Äôre fitting a line y = a + bx that minimizes the sum of squared vertical errors. Start by computing these summary values from your n data points: the means xÃÑ = (Œ£x)/n and »≥ = (Œ£y)/n, and the centered sums Sxx = Œ£(x ‚àí xÃÑ)¬≤ and Sxy = Œ£(x ‚àí xÃÑ)(y ‚àí »≥). The slope is b = Sxy/Sxx (this is ‚Äúrise over run‚Äù in a least-squares sense), and the intercept is a = »≥ ‚àí b xÃÑ, so your best-fit line is ≈∑ = a + bx. To get R¬≤, first compute the predicted values ≈∑i for each xi, then compute the total sum of squares SST = Œ£(yi ‚àí »≥)¬≤ and the residual sum of squares SSE = Œ£(yi ‚àí ≈∑i)¬≤; then R¬≤ = 1 ‚àí SSE/SST (it‚Äôs the fraction of the total variation in y explained by the line, with 1 meaning perfect fit and 0 meaning the line explains none). A handy equivalent check is that for simple linear regression, R¬≤ also equals r¬≤ where r = Sxy/‚àö(Sxx¬∑Syy) and Syy = Œ£(y ‚àí »≥)¬≤, so you can verify your arithmetic two ways. In practice, make a small table with columns x, y, (x ‚àí xÃÑ), (y ‚àí »≥), (x ‚àí xÃÑ)¬≤, and (x ‚àí xÃÑ)(y ‚àí »≥), sum the last two columns to get Sxx and Sxy, compute b and a, then compute ≈∑, residuals (y ‚àí ≈∑), SSE, SST, and finally R¬≤; if SSE is much smaller than SST, your line is doing a good job describing the data."),

