    ("Can you explain natural selection using a real example (like antibiotics or peppered moths) but in a way that‚Äôs not super long?", "Natural selection is when individuals in a population vary, and the ones with traits that help them survive and reproduce in a particular environment leave more offspring, so those helpful traits become more common over generations. A real example is antibiotics and bacteria: in any large group of bacteria, a few may happen to have a mutation that makes them less affected by an antibiotic, and when the antibiotic is used it kills most bacteria but the resistant ones survive, multiply, and pass on resistance, so the population becomes mostly antibiotic-resistant. This is why using antibiotics only when needed and finishing the prescribed course matters, because it reduces the chance that resistant bacteria are the ones left behind to spread."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 01:54 - Category: restful_services
    ("I need a quick walkthrough of RESTful services: what do GET vs POST vs PUT vs DELETE map to, and what‚Äôs the difference between path params and query params?", "In RESTful services, HTTP methods map to common CRUD actions on resources: GET retrieves a representation of a resource without changing it (safe and idempotent), POST creates a new resource under a collection or triggers a non-idempotent action (sending the same POST twice can create two items), PUT replaces or fully updates a resource at a known URI and is idempotent (PUT /users/123 with the same body repeatedly results in the same final state), and DELETE removes a resource and is typically idempotent (deleting the same resource twice should not create additional side effects beyond ‚Äúit‚Äôs gone‚Äù). Path parameters are part of the URL path and identify which specific resource you‚Äôre addressing, like /users/123/orders/456 where 123 and 456 are path params that locate the user and order, while query parameters come after a ? and refine how you fetch or search within resources, like /users/123/orders?status=shipped&limit=20 where status and limit filter, sort, paginate, or otherwise modify the retrieval without changing the resource identity. A quick rule of thumb is: use path params for ‚Äúwhich thing‚Äù (resource identity) and query params for ‚Äúwhich subset or view‚Äù (filters and options)."),

