    ("Physics: I‚Äôm confused about friction forces. If a box is on an incline, how do you know if it‚Äôs static or kinetic friction and which direction it points?", "On an incline, first decide whether the box is actually sliding relative to the surface: if it is sliding, the friction is kinetic; if it is not sliding (even if other forces are trying to make it slide), the friction is static. The direction of friction is always along the surface and always opposes the relative motion (for kinetic) or the impending motion (for static): for example, gravity has a component down the ramp equal to mg sin(theta), so if the box tends to slide down, friction points up the ramp; if something pulls the box up the ramp or it‚Äôs moving up, friction points down the ramp. To check whether it can stay at rest, compare the friction needed to prevent motion with the maximum possible static friction: the needed friction is whatever makes the net force along the ramp zero (often mg sin(theta) if nothing else acts along the ramp), and the maximum static friction is f_s,max = mu_s N with N = mg cos(theta); if the needed friction is less than or equal to mu_s N, the box can remain at rest and friction is static with magnitude ‚Äúwhatever is needed‚Äù up to that limit, but if the needed friction exceeds mu_s N then it must slip and the friction becomes kinetic with magnitude f_k = mu_k N, pointing opposite the direction of sliding."),

