    ("Database homework: design a simple schema for a campus tutoring app (students, tutors, sessions). Can you show tables with primary keys/foreign keys and give 2 example SQL queries?", "A simple campus tutoring app schema can use four tables: Students(student_id PK, name, email UNIQUE, major, year_level), Tutors(tutor_id PK, name, email UNIQUE, subject_area, hourly_rate), Sessions(session_id PK, student_id FK references Students(student_id), tutor_id FK references Tutors(tutor_id), start_time, end_time, location, status), and optionally Reviews(review_id PK, session_id FK references Sessions(session_id) UNIQUE, rating, comments, created_at) so each session links exactly one student to one tutor and a review (if used) belongs to one session. Example query 1 (list upcoming confirmed sessions for a given student, showing tutor name and time): SELECT s.session_id, t.name AS tutor_name, s.start_time, s.end_time, s.location FROM Sessions s JOIN Tutors t ON s.tutor_id = t.tutor_id WHERE s.student_id = 123 AND s.status = \'CONFIRMED\' AND s.start_time >= CURRENT_TIMESTAMP ORDER BY s.start_time; Example query 2 (find the most-booked tutors in the last 30 days): SELECT t.tutor_id, t.name, COUNT() AS session_count FROM Tutors t JOIN Sessions s ON s.tutor_id = t.tutor_id WHERE s.start_time >= CURRENT_DATE INTERVAL \'30\' DAY GROUP BY t.tutor_id, t.name ORDER BY session_count DESC;"),

