    ("High school calc: find the derivative of f(x)= (3x^2-5x+2)/(x-1) and tell me where it‚Äôs increasing/decreasing.", "For f(x) = (3x^2 ‚àí 5x + 2)/(x ‚àí 1), first note the domain excludes x = 1. You can simplify by dividing: 3x^2 ‚àí 5x + 2 = (x ‚àí 1)(3x ‚àí 2), so for x ‚â† 1 we have f(x) = 3x ‚àí 2 (it‚Äôs the same line everywhere except there‚Äôs a hole at x = 1). Therefore f‚Ä≤(x) = 3 for all x ‚â† 1 (equivalently, using the quotient rule gives f‚Ä≤(x) = [(6x ‚àí 5)(x ‚àí 1) ‚àí (3x^2 ‚àí 5x + 2)]/(x ‚àí 1)^2 = 3(x ‚àí 1)^2/(x ‚àí 1)^2 = 3, again for x ‚â† 1). Since the derivative is positive everywhere on its domain, the function is increasing on (‚àí‚àû, 1) and on (1, ‚àû), and it is decreasing on no interval; there are no critical points (f‚Ä≤ never equals 0), and x = 1 is not a critical point because the function is not defined there."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 01:58 - Category: inventors
    ("Who were the main inventors behind the light bulb and why is it not just one person? I keep seeing Edison but also other names.", "The ‚Äúlight bulb‚Äù wasn‚Äôt invented by just one person because it was a long, step-by-step engineering problem: people had to figure out how to make a filament glow brightly, keep it from burning up, and power it safely and cheaply, and different inventors solved different parts over decades. Humphry Davy showed the basic idea of electric light in the early 1800s with very bright arc lamps, but they weren‚Äôt practical for homes; in the 1840s Warren de la Rue tried a platinum filament in a vacuum (it worked but was far too expensive); in 1854 Heinrich G√∂bel is sometimes claimed to have made an early incandescent lamp, but the evidence is disputed; in the 1870s Joseph Swan in Britain made workable incandescent lamps using carbon filaments and improved vacuum techniques and demonstrated them publicly, lighting buildings in the UK; in 1874‚Äì1875 Henry Woodward and Mathew Evans in Canada patented a lamp design and later sold their patent rights; and in 1879‚Äì1880 Thomas Edison and his team in the United States developed a long-lasting, commercially practical incandescent lamp (famously using carbonized filament materials and better vacuum), patented it, and‚Äîjust as importantly‚Äîbuilt the whole system needed for everyday use, including generators, wiring, switches, meters, and power stations. That‚Äôs why you keep seeing multiple names: Edison was a key figure in making the light bulb reliable and widely used, but the invention was really the result of many inventors improving the idea and the technology over time, and even Edison and Swan ended up resolving patent conflicts and both are recognized for major contributions."),

