    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 01:58 - Category: rock_cycle
    ("What is the rock cycle? My teacher said there are 3 main rock types but I can‚Äôt remember how they change into each other.", "The rock cycle is the ongoing set of processes that constantly makes, breaks down, and changes rocks on Earth, and the three main rock types are igneous, sedimentary, and metamorphic. Igneous rock forms when melted rock (magma underground or lava at the surface) cools and hardens; sedimentary rock forms when older rocks are weathered and eroded into sediments, the sediments are carried by water or wind, then they are deposited in layers and compacted and cemented into rock; metamorphic rock forms when existing rock is changed by heat and pressure (and sometimes hot fluids) deep underground without melting. These types change into each other in several common pathways: any rock can be weathered into sediment that becomes sedimentary rock; sedimentary or igneous rock can be buried and squeezed/heated to become metamorphic rock; metamorphic (or any) rock can melt into magma and then cool to become igneous rock; and uplift can bring rocks back to the surface where weathering starts the cycle again, so the ‚Äúcycle‚Äù is really a loop with many possible routes driven by Earth‚Äôs internal heat and surface processes like water, wind, and ice."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 01:58 - Category: computer_networks
    ("College networking: what‚Äôs the difference between TCP and UDP and when would you use each? Real examples would help.", "TCP and UDP are two transport-layer protocols that sit on top of IP, but they make different tradeoffs. TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) is connection-oriented: before data flows it establishes a connection (a handshake), then it provides reliable, in-order delivery of a byte stream using sequence numbers, acknowledgments, retransmissions, and flow/congestion control, which means it adapts its sending rate to avoid overwhelming the network and the receiver. You use TCP when you care that every byte arrives correctly and in the right order, even if that adds latency, such as loading a web page over HTTP/1.1 or HTTP/2 (most commonly over TCP port 443 for HTTPS), downloading a file (FTP/SFTP/HTTPS), sending email (SMTP/IMAP), or using SSH‚Äîif a packet is lost, TCP will resend it and the application gets the complete data. UDP (User Datagram Protocol) is connectionless: it sends independent datagrams with minimal overhead and does not guarantee delivery, ordering, or duplicate protection; there‚Äôs no built-in retransmission or congestion control at the transport layer, so latency can be lower and the application can decide what ‚Äúgood enough‚Äù means. You use UDP when timeliness matters more than perfect reliability or when the application implements its own recovery, such as live voice/video (VoIP, video calls, streaming where a late packet is useless), online gaming (you‚Äôd rather drop an old position update than delay the newest one), DNS lookups (a small query/response where retrying is cheap), and many real-time protocols; a modern concrete example is QUIC, which powers HTTP/3 by running over UDP to get low-latency connection setup and avoid head-of-line blocking while still providing reliability and encryption at the application/QUIC layer. A simple way to remember the difference is that TCP is like a tracked, signed-for delivery service that guarantees the full package arrives in order, while UDP is like sending postcards: fast and lightweight, but you may lose some and they might arrive out of order, which is fine for things like ‚Äúcurrent state‚Äù updates where the newest message matters most."),

