    ("Can you help me set up an actuarial-style expected value problem? Like if the probability of a claim is 0.08 and the claim size is exponentially distributed with mean $5,000, what‚Äôs the expected payout per policy?", "Let X be the claim amount and let I be an indicator that a claim occurs, where P(I = 1) = 0.08 and P(I = 0) = 0.92; the payout per policy is Y = I¬∑X. Since X is exponentially distributed with mean E[X] = 5,000 and (typically) the claim size is independent of whether a claim occurs, the expected payout is E[Y] = E[I¬∑X] = E[I]E[X] = 0.08 √ó 5,000 = 400, so the expected payout per policy is $400. You can also see this by conditioning: E[Y] = P(claim)¬∑E[X | claim] + P(no claim)¬∑0 = 0.08¬∑5,000 + 0.92¬∑0 = 400."),

