    ("what is an ecosystem (like forest ecosystem) and who eats who? can you make it simple", "An ecosystem is a place where living things (plants, animals, fungi, and tiny microbes) interact with each other and with nonliving things like sunlight, water, air, soil, and temperature; a forest ecosystem includes trees, bushes, insects, birds, mammals, and decomposers all sharing the same home and depending on one another. ‚ÄúWho eats who‚Äù is called a food chain (or many connected food chains called a food web): plants such as trees and grasses make their own food using sunlight, plant-eaters like caterpillars, rabbits, and deer eat the plants, meat-eaters like frogs, snakes, owls, foxes, and wolves eat the plant-eaters (and sometimes other meat-eaters), and decomposers like fungi, bacteria, and earthworms break down dead plants and animals and return nutrients to the soil so plants can grow again. A simple forest example is: oak leaves are eaten by a caterpillar, the caterpillar is eaten by a bird, the bird is eaten by a hawk, and when any of them die, fungi and bacteria decompose them and feed the soil, which helps the oak tree grow more leaves."),

