    ("is evolution just like animals \"decide\" to change? my teacher said no but i don‚Äôt get it", "No, evolution is not animals deciding to change because they ‚Äúwant to‚Äù; individual animals are born with small random differences (mutations) in their DNA, and those differences can affect how well they survive and have babies in a particular environment. Natural selection is the simple idea that traits that help an organism leave more offspring tend to become more common over many generations, while traits that hurt survival or reproduction tend to become rarer, so the population changes even though no one is choosing it on purpose. For example, if some moths are born a bit darker and birds more easily spot light moths on dark tree bark, the darker moths are more likely to survive and reproduce, so after many generations the population becomes mostly darker; the moths didn‚Äôt decide to change color, the environment ‚Äúfiltered‚Äù which inherited traits got passed on. Individuals can still adjust during their lifetime (like getting stronger muscles from exercise), but that kind of change usually isn‚Äôt inherited, while evolution is specifically about inherited genetic changes in a population across generations."),

