    ("I need to write a basic REST API for a class project. What‚Äôs the difference between PUT vs PATCH, and what status codes should I return for validation errors vs not found?", "PUT and PATCH both update an existing resource, but they mean different things: PUT replaces the entire resource representation at that URL with what you send (think ‚Äúoverwrite‚Äù), so if you omit a field it‚Äôs typically treated as removed or reset to default, and PUT is intended to be idempotent (sending the same PUT multiple times should leave the resource in the same state). PATCH applies a partial update (think ‚Äúchange only these fields‚Äù), so you send only what you want to modify; PATCH is often idempotent in practice if you design it that way, but it depends on the patch format/semantics you choose. For status codes, return 404 Not Found when the resource identified by the URL doesn‚Äôt exist (for example, PUT /users/123 when user 123 isn‚Äôt present, unless your API explicitly supports ‚Äúupsert‚Äù with PUT), and return 400 Bad Request when the request is malformed (invalid JSON, wrong types, missing required fields for the operation) or 422 Unprocessable Content (commonly used in REST APIs) when the JSON is syntactically valid but fails business/validation rules (email not a valid format, string too long, value out of range); in both cases include a clear error body describing which fields failed and why. Common ‚Äúhappy path‚Äù codes are 200 OK (return updated representation), 204 No Content (update succeeded but you return no body), and 201 Created if a PUT creates a new resource at a client-chosen URL and you support that behavior."),

