    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:01 - Category: react_basics
    ("I‚Äôm building a small React app and keep getting the \'Too many re-renders\' error. Can you explain what usually causes that and show a clean pattern for fetching data with useEffect?", "‚ÄúToo many re-renders‚Äù almost always means your component is stuck in a render loop: something is causing state to update during rendering, which triggers another render, which updates state again, and so on until React stops it. The most common causes are calling a state setter directly in the component body (for example, doing setCount(count + 1) unconditionally while rendering), accidentally invoking a handler instead of passing a function (writing onClick={setOpen(true)} instead of onClick={() => setOpen(true)}), or having an effect that updates state but runs on every render because its dependency array is missing or unstable (for example, useEffect(() => { setData(...) }) with no dependency array, or including a freshly created object/function in the dependency list so the effect re-runs every time). A clean, safe pattern for fetching data is to start the fetch inside useEffect, depend only on the values that should actually trigger a refetch (like an id), track loading and error state, and ignore results if the component unmounts or the request becomes outdated; for example: function User({ userId }) { const [data, setData] = React.useState(null); const [loading, setLoading] = React.useState(true); const [error, setError] = React.useState(null); React.useEffect(() => { let cancelled = false; setLoading(true); setError(null); fetch(/api/users/${userId}) .then(r => { if (!r.ok) throw new Error(Request failed: ${r.status}); return r.json(); }) .then(json => { if (!cancelled) setData(json); }) .catch(e => { if (!cancelled) setError(e); }) .finally(() => { if (!cancelled) setLoading(false); }); return () => { cancelled = true; }; }, [userId]); if (loading) return \"Loading...\"; if (error) return Error: ${error.message}; return data ? data.name : \"No user\"; } This avoids re-render loops because state updates happen in an effect (not during render), and the effect only re-runs when userId changes, not on every render."),

