    ("Computer vision basics question: what‚Äôs the real difference between edge detection (like Sobel/Canny) and feature descriptors (SIFT/ORB)? I‚Äôm confused what each is used for.", "Edge detection and feature descriptors solve different problems: edge detection (Sobel, Canny) is about finding where image intensity changes sharply, producing an ‚Äúedge map‚Äù that highlights object boundaries and contours, which is useful for tasks like segmentation, shape/contour extraction, line detection, and as a simple preprocessing step; it tells you ‚Äúthese pixels likely lie on a boundary,‚Äù but it doesn‚Äôt by itself give a stable way to recognize the same place or object across different images. Feature methods like SIFT or ORB are about finding distinctive keypoints (corners/blobs) and then describing the local neighborhood around each keypoint with a compact vector so you can match the same physical point between images even if the camera moves, the object rotates, or the scale changes (SIFT is designed to be scale- and rotation-invariant; ORB is a fast binary alternative that is rotation-invariant and approximates scale invariance), which is why they‚Äôre used for image matching, panorama stitching, tracking, pose estimation, and SLAM. A good mental model is: edges are a dense, per-pixel ‚Äúwhere are the boundaries?‚Äù signal, while SIFT/ORB give you a sparse set of ‚Äúlandmarks‚Äù plus ‚Äúfingerprints‚Äù you can compare across images; you might use Canny to outline a stop sign in one image, but you‚Äôd use SIFT/ORB to reliably match that stop sign (or parts of it) between two different viewpoints to compute how the camera moved."),

