    ("what are the 3 branches of government and how do they stop each other from getting too much power", "In the United States, the three branches of government are the legislative branch (Congress), which makes laws; the executive branch (the President and the agencies), which carries out and enforces laws; and the judicial branch (the Supreme Court and other courts), which interprets laws and decides whether they follow the Constitution. They keep each other from getting too much power through ‚Äúchecks and balances‚Äù: Congress can pass laws and control spending, but the President can veto a law and Congress can override that veto with a two-thirds vote; the President chooses many top officials and federal judges, but the Senate must approve those choices; the courts can declare a law or a presidential action unconstitutional, but judges are nominated by the President and confirmed by the Senate; and Congress can investigate the executive branch and even impeach and remove a president or judge for serious wrongdoing. This system is meant to make the branches cooperate and argue in a healthy way so no single person or group can easily take over the whole government."),

