    ("For project management in my capstone, what‚Äôs the difference between a Gantt chart and a critical path diagram, and how do I figure out the critical path from a list of tasks?", "A Gantt chart and a critical path diagram both help you plan and track a project, but they emphasize different things: a Gantt chart is a time-based schedule that shows tasks as horizontal bars on a calendar (start date, finish date, overlap, and progress), which makes it great for communicating ‚Äúwhat happens when,‚Äù while a critical path diagram (often drawn as a network of boxes/arrows) focuses on task dependencies and identifies the longest chain of dependent work that determines the shortest possible project duration; tasks on that chain have zero slack (float), meaning if any of them slip, the whole project finish date slips. To find the critical path from a list of tasks, you need each task‚Äôs duration and its predecessors (what must finish before it can start), then do a forward pass to compute earliest start (ES) and earliest finish (EF) for every task by setting ES to the maximum EF of its predecessors and EF = ES + duration (start tasks have ES = 0 or the project start date), then do a backward pass starting from the project finish time (the maximum EF) to compute latest finish (LF) and latest start (LS) by setting LF to the minimum LS of its successors and LS = LF ‚àí duration (end tasks start with LF = project finish). Finally compute slack/float for each task as LS ‚àí ES (or LF ‚àí EF); the critical path is the continuous sequence of dependent tasks with slack = 0 from start to finish, and its total duration equals the project duration. For a quick mini-example: if A(3 days) starts the project, B(2) depends on A, C(4) depends on A, D(2) depends on B and C, and E(1) depends on D, then the paths are A‚ÜíB‚ÜíD‚ÜíE = 3+2+2+1 = 8 and A‚ÜíC‚ÜíD‚ÜíE = 3+4+2+1 = 10, so the critical path is A‚ÜíC‚ÜíD‚ÜíE (10 days) because it‚Äôs the longest dependent chain and those tasks will have zero slack."),

