    ("in geometry, how do you do a simple construction of a perpendicular bisector with a compass", "To construct the perpendicular bisector of a line segment AB using a compass (and a straightedge for drawing the final line), set the compass width to a little more than half the length of AB, place the compass point on A and draw an arc above and below the segment, then without changing the width place the compass point on B and draw arcs that cross the first pair of arcs; use the straightedge to draw the line through the two arc-intersection points. That line is the perpendicular bisector because every point where the arcs intersect is the same distance from A and from B, so the line through those intersections is the set of points equidistant from A and B, which must cross AB at its midpoint and at a right angle; you can quickly check by measuring that it meets AB at 90 degrees and splits AB into two equal parts."),

