    ("Geometry proof help: how do you prove two triangles are congruent if you only know two angles and a side? I always pick the wrong theorem.", "If you know two angles and a side, you use either ASA or AAS, and the key is deciding whether the known side is between the two known angles. ASA (Angle-Side-Angle) applies when the side you know is the included side between the two angles (for example, you know ‚à†A, side AB, and ‚à†B), while AAS (Angle-Angle-Side) applies when the known side is not between the two known angles (for example, you know ‚à†A, ‚à†B, and side AC). Both work because two angles fix the triangle‚Äôs shape (the third angle is forced by the Triangle Sum Theorem: ‚à†C = 180¬∞ ‚àí (‚à†A + ‚à†B)), and then a corresponding side fixes the scale, so there is only one possible triangle up to congruence; just be careful to match corresponding angles and the corresponding side in the two triangles. A common trap is thinking ‚ÄúSSA‚Äù (Side-Side-Angle) works the same way, but SSA is ambiguous and does not guarantee congruence, so if your given information is ‚Äútwo angles and a side,‚Äù you‚Äôre safe with ASA or AAS depending on whether the side is included."),

