    ("Physics question: what‚Äôs the Doppler effect and why does the pitch change more when the ambulance is moving fast?", "The Doppler effect is the change you hear in a sound‚Äôs pitch when the source of the sound and the listener are moving toward or away from each other, because the motion changes how frequently the sound waves reach your ears. When an ambulance is coming toward you, each new wave is emitted from a position slightly closer than the last one, so the waves get ‚Äúbunched up,‚Äù their wavelength becomes shorter, and the frequency you receive is higher, which sounds like a higher pitch; after it passes and moves away, the waves get ‚Äústretched out,‚Äù the wavelength becomes longer, and the frequency you receive is lower, which sounds like a lower pitch. The pitch changes more when the ambulance is moving fast because the amount of bunching or stretching depends on speed: a higher speed makes a bigger change in the spacing of the wavefronts, so the received frequency shifts more (for sound in still air, the shift grows roughly in proportion to the source speed compared with the speed of sound), which is why a fast-moving siren produces a more dramatic ‚Äúnee-naw‚Äù jump than a slow-moving one."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:04 - Category: federalism
    ("US gov: can you explain federalism in plain English and give a couple examples of powers reserved to states vs the federal government?", "Federalism is the U.S. system of sharing power between a national (federal) government and the state governments, so some decisions are made for the whole country while others are handled locally by each state; the Constitution gives certain ‚Äúenumerated‚Äù powers to the federal government, keeps other powers with the states (often called ‚Äúreserved powers‚Äù under the Tenth Amendment), and lets some powers be shared by both. Examples of federal powers include coining money, regulating trade between states and with other countries (interstate and foreign commerce), running the military, making treaties, and establishing rules for immigration and naturalization. Examples of powers mainly reserved to states include running public schools, setting most criminal laws and punishments, issuing driver‚Äôs licenses, conducting elections for state and local offices and managing many election rules, and regulating local matters like zoning and many business licensing rules; meanwhile, shared powers include things like collecting taxes, building roads, and making and enforcing laws, but if a state law conflicts with a valid federal law, the federal law generally wins under the Constitution‚Äôs Supremacy Clause."),

