    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:05 - Category: immigration_history
    ("US history question: what were the biggest causes of the Great Migration, and how did it change cities in the North?", "The Great Migration was the movement of about six million African Americans from the rural South to Northern, Midwestern, and Western cities, mainly between about 1916 and 1970, and its biggest causes were a mix of ‚Äúpush‚Äù factors in the South and ‚Äúpull‚Äù factors in the North. In the South, Jim Crow segregation, widespread racial violence and lynching, political disenfranchisement, and unfair economic systems like sharecropping kept many Black families poor and unsafe; on top of that, disasters such as the boll weevil infestation that devastated cotton crops starting in the 1890s and continuing into the early 1900s, plus floods and other hardships, made rural life even less sustainable. In the North, World War I created a huge demand for industrial labor just as immigration from Europe dropped sharply because of the war and later because of restrictive laws like the Immigration Act of 1924, so factories, railroads, and steel mills recruited Southern Black workers with the promise of better wages and more independence; newspapers such as the Chicago Defender also spread information about job opportunities and train routes, making migration more possible. Northern cities changed dramatically: places like Chicago, Detroit, Cleveland, Pittsburgh, New York, and Philadelphia grew quickly and developed large Black neighborhoods (for example, Chicago‚Äôs South Side and New York‚Äôs Harlem), which helped create strong community institutions such as churches, businesses, and civic organizations and fueled major cultural achievements like the Harlem Renaissance in the 1920s. At the same time, rapid growth and discrimination produced overcrowded housing, job competition, and segregation through practices like restrictive covenants and later redlining, and racial tensions sometimes exploded into violence, including the ‚ÄúRed Summer‚Äù riots of 1919 and the Chicago race riot of 1919. Over the long run, the Great Migration reshaped Northern politics and labor by increasing Black voting power, strengthening civil rights activism, and changing the workforce of key industries, while also transforming American music, literature, and social life in ways that still influence the country today."),

