    ("Why do ocean currents go in those big swirl patterns on maps? Is it because of Earth spinning or something?", "Those big swirl patterns are called ocean gyres, and yes, Earth‚Äôs spin is a major reason they form, but it works together with winds and the shapes of the continents. The Sun heats Earth unevenly, which helps create steady global wind belts (like the trade winds and westerlies) that push on the ocean surface and start large-scale flows; as that moving water travels, Earth‚Äôs rotation causes the Coriolis effect, which deflects motion to the right in the Northern Hemisphere and to the left in the Southern Hemisphere, so the wind-driven currents don‚Äôt go straight but curve. When those curved currents run into continents, they can‚Äôt keep going, so they turn and loop back, and the combination of wind pushing, Coriolis deflection, and continental boundaries closes the loop into a huge rotating system: clockwise gyres in the Northern Hemisphere and counterclockwise gyres in the Southern Hemisphere. Another key piece is that the Coriolis effect is stronger at higher latitudes than near the equator, which makes the circulating water ‚Äúpile up‚Äù slightly toward the center of a gyre; gravity then tries to pull that mound of water back down, and the balance between gravity pulling inward and Coriolis pushing sideways creates a stable circular flow around the mound (called geostrophic balance). So the swirls on maps aren‚Äôt just random spirals‚Äîthey‚Äôre the predictable result of wind-driven surface water being steered by Earth‚Äôs rotation and shaped by the continents, with smaller swirls (eddies) spinning off where currents meet or where the seafloor and coastlines create turbulence."),

