    ("We‚Äôre doing circles and I forgot the theorems‚Ä¶ how do you know an angle in a semicircle is 90 degrees?", "If you have a diameter AB of a circle and a point C anywhere on the circle, then the angle ACB is always 90¬∞, and the reason is a neat mix of ‚Äúradii are equal‚Äù and ‚Äúangles in a triangle add to 180¬∞.‚Äù Join the centre O to A, B, and C; OA, OB, and OC are all radii so OA = OC and OB = OC, which means triangles AOC and BOC are isosceles, so the base angles at C are equal to the angles at A and B in those triangles: let angle ACO = angle OAC = x and angle OCB = angle OBC = y. Now look at triangle ABC: angle ACB is x + y, angle CAB is x, and angle CBA is y, so x + y + x + y = 180¬∞, giving 2(x + y) = 180¬∞ and therefore x + y = 90¬∞, so angle ACB = 90¬∞. This is exactly what people mean by ‚Äúthe angle in a semicircle is a right angle‚Äù: the diameter forces the triangle to be right-angled at the point on the circle."),

