    ("How do I tell the difference between a square and a rectangle? Can you give me an easy trick?", "A rectangle is any four-sided shape with four right angles (each corner is 90¬∞), and opposite sides are the same length; a square is a special kind of rectangle that also has all four sides the same length. An easy trick is: first check the corners‚Äîif all four corners are right angles, it‚Äôs a rectangle-type shape; then check the side lengths‚Äîif all four sides match, it‚Äôs a square, and if only the opposite sides match (two long and two short), it‚Äôs a rectangle but not a square. For example, a 3 by 5 shape with four right angles is a rectangle, while a 4 by 4 shape with four right angles is a square."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:06 - Category: geometric_proofs
    ("How do you do a basic geometric proof? Like where do I even start if they give me triangles and some angles?", "Start by reading the ‚ÄúGiven‚Äù and ‚ÄúProve‚Äù and rewriting them in your own words, then draw a clean diagram (or mark up the one provided) and label every known angle, side, and any special facts like parallel lines, right angles, or equal segments. Next, decide what kind of conclusion you‚Äôre aiming for, because that tells you the tool to use: if you need two angles equal, look for angle facts (vertical angles, linear pairs, corresponding/alternate interior angles from parallel lines) or triangle angle sum; if you need two sides equal, look for shared sides, marked equal segments, or results from congruent triangles; if you need triangles congruent, try to collect one of the standard congruence packages (SSS, SAS, ASA, AAS, or HL for right triangles), and if you only need similarity, look for AA (two angles) first because it‚Äôs usually easiest. A practical way to ‚Äúget started‚Äù is to hunt for a small claim you can prove immediately from the picture‚Äîlike ‚Äúthese two angles are equal because they‚Äôre vertical‚Äù or ‚Äúthis angle is 180 minus the other two because angles in a triangle add to 180‚Äù‚Äîwrite that as your first step with a reason, and keep chaining facts until you can match a congruence or similarity criterion; once you prove triangles congruent/similar, you can use CPCTC (corresponding parts of congruent triangles are congruent) or proportional sides/angles from similarity to finish the original goal. For example, if a problem gives two triangles with one shared side and a pair of equal angles, you might prove a second angle pair equal (often from parallel lines or vertical angles), conclude ASA congruence, then immediately conclude the needed side or angle equality by CPCTC; the key is to work backward from what you‚Äôre trying to prove and forward from what you‚Äôre given until they meet in the middle, always writing each statement with a clear reason."),

