    ("Can you help with molar calculations? Like if I have 10 grams of NaCl, how many moles is that and how do I set it up?", "Yes‚Äîmoles are found by dividing the given mass by the substance‚Äôs molar mass: moles = grams √∑ (grams per mole). For NaCl, first compute the molar mass by adding atomic masses: Na is about 22.99 g/mol and Cl is about 35.45 g/mol, so NaCl is 22.99 + 35.45 = 58.44 g/mol. Now set it up with units so grams cancel: 10.0 g NaCl √ó (1 mol NaCl / 58.44 g NaCl) = 0.171 mol NaCl (to three significant figures), which you can sanity-check because 10 g is much less than 58.44 g, so the answer should be well under 1 mole."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:09 - Category: nodejs_basics
    ("I‚Äôm in intro CS and need Node.js basics: what‚Äôs the difference between require and import, and how do I run a simple server?", "In Node.js, require is the original CommonJS module system: you load modules with const express = require(\'express\') (or const fs = require(\'node:fs\') for built-ins), it works in every .js file by default, and it can be called conditionally at runtime; import is the newer ECMAScript Modules (ESM) syntax: you write import express from \'express\' or import { readFile } from \'node:fs\', it is resolved statically (so it‚Äôs easier for tooling and bundlers to analyze) and it‚Äôs the standard JavaScript module syntax used in browsers too. In Node, a file is treated as ESM if it ends in .mjs or if your package.json includes \"type\": \"module\" (otherwise .js is CommonJS), and the two systems interoperate but with rules: from ESM you can usually do import pkg from \'some-commonjs-package\' and get its module.exports as the default import, while from CommonJS you can load an ESM module only via dynamic import(\'some-esm-module\') (you can‚Äôt use require on an ESM-only module). To run a simple server without any libraries, create a file named server.js and put: const http = require(\'node:http\'); const server = http.createServer((req, res) => { res.statusCode = 200; res.setHeader(\'Content-Type\', \'text/plain; charset=utf-8\'); res.end(\'Hello from Node!\\n\'); }); server.listen(3000, () => console.log(\'Server running at http://localhost:3000\')); then start it with node server.js and visit http://localhost:3000 in your browser; stop it with Ctrl+C. If you want the same server using import, either rename the file to server.mjs or set \"type\": \"module\" in package.json, then write: import http from \'node:http\'; and keep the rest the same, run it with node server.mjs (or node server.js if your project is set to ESM)."),

