    ("In calculus, how do definite integrals actually relate to area, and what does the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus really say?", "A definite integral from a to b, written ‚à´[a to b] f(x) dx, is defined as the limit of Riemann sums: you split the interval [a, b] into many small subintervals of width Œîx, pick a sample point x in each one, add up f(x)Œîx, and then let the widths go to 0; this limit (when it exists) gives the net signed area between the graph y = f(x) and the x-axis from x = a to x = b, meaning regions where f(x) is above the x-axis contribute positive area and regions where f(x) is below contribute negative area, so the ordinary geometric area is instead ‚à´[a to b] |f(x)| dx (or you split at the zeros of f and add absolute values). The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus has two closely linked parts: first, if f is continuous on [a, b] and you define an ‚Äúaccumulation function‚Äù F(x) = ‚à´[a to x] f(t) dt, then F is differentiable and F‚Ä≤(x) = f(x), which says differentiation and integration are inverse processes in this precise sense; second, if f is continuous on [a, b] and A is any antiderivative of f (so A‚Ä≤ = f), then ‚à´[a to b] f(x) dx = A(b) ‚àí A(a), which is the practical rule for computing definite integrals by finding an antiderivative and evaluating it at the endpoints. For example, since an antiderivative of f(x) = x is A(x) = x¬≤/2, the integral ‚à´[0 to 2] x dx equals A(2) ‚àí A(0) = (4/2) ‚àí 0 = 2, matching the geometric area of a right triangle with base 2 and height 2, while if you integrate f(x) = ‚àí1 from 0 to 2 you get ‚à´[0 to 2] ‚àí1 dx = ‚àí2, showing the ‚Äúarea‚Äù is signed and records that the graph lies below the axis."),

