    ("We‚Äôre doing vectors in physics‚Äîcan you show me how to break a vector into x and y components if it‚Äôs 18 N at 35 degrees?", "To break an 18 N vector at 35 degrees into x and y components, treat it like the hypotenuse of a right triangle: the x-component is the adjacent side and the y-component is the opposite side, so Fx = F cos(Œ∏) and Fy = F sin(Œ∏) when the angle Œ∏ is measured from the +x axis. Plug in F = 18 N and Œ∏ = 35¬∞: Fx = 18 cos(35¬∞) ‚âà 18(0.819) ‚âà 14.7 N, and Fy = 18 sin(35¬∞) ‚âà 18(0.574) ‚âà 10.3 N, so the vector is about (14.7 N, 10.3 N). You can quickly check your work by recombining them: ‚àö(14.7¬≤ + 10.3¬≤) ‚âà 18 N, which matches the original magnitude (signs would change only if the vector pointed left or downward)."),

