    ("Can you help me do a basic probability question: what‚Äôs the chance of getting at least one 6 if I roll a die 4 times? Please show steps.", "To find the chance of getting at least one 6 in 4 rolls, it‚Äôs easiest to use the complement (the opposite event): ‚Äúat least one 6‚Äù = 1 ‚àí ‚Äúno 6s at all.‚Äù On one roll, the probability of not getting a 6 is 5/6, and because the rolls are independent, the probability of no 6s in 4 rolls is (5/6)^4 = 625/1296. Therefore the probability of at least one 6 is 1 ‚àí 625/1296 = 671/1296, which is about 0.5177, or about 51.8%. Quick check: since the chance is a bit more than 50%, that makes sense because you have four chances to roll a 6."),

