    ("We‚Äôre doing sports analytics in stats‚Äîhow would you test if a player‚Äôs free-throw % actually improved this season or if it‚Äôs just random?", "To test whether a player‚Äôs free-throw percentage truly improved (rather than just bouncing around due to randomness), treat each free throw as a make/miss trial and compare two proportions: last season‚Äôs makes out of attempts (x1 out of n1) versus this season‚Äôs (x2 out of n2). Set up hypotheses as H0: p2 = p1 (no real change) versus H1: p2 > p1 (improvement), then run a two-proportion z-test (or an equivalent chi-square test for a 2x2 table) using the pooled estimate pÃÇ = (x1 + x2)/(n1 + n2) and z = (pÃÇ2 ‚àí pÃÇ1)/sqrt(pÃÇ(1 ‚àí pÃÇ)(1/n1 + 1/n2)); a small p-value (like < 0.05) means the improvement is unlikely under ‚Äúno change.‚Äù Also report a confidence interval for the difference p2 ‚àí p1 (if the whole interval is above 0, that supports improvement) and check practical significance by asking whether the size of the increase matters in points per game. If sample sizes are small or you want fewer assumptions, do an exact test (Fisher‚Äôs exact) or a simple simulation/bootstrap: assume the old true rate p1, simulate n2 attempts many times, and see how often you‚Äôd get a percentage at least as high as the new one; that simulated probability is an intuitive p-value. Finally, be careful about context: free throws aren‚Äôt perfectly identical (injury, fatigue, shot mechanics, pressure), so if you have shot-level data you can model makes with logistic regression including a ‚Äúseason‚Äù indicator and other factors; the key idea is the same‚Äîestimate the change and test whether it‚Äôs bigger than what random variation would typically produce."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:12 - Category: local_government
    ("What does the mayor actually control in a city government vs the city council? Like who decides budgets and school stuff?", "In most U.S. cities, the city council is the main lawmaking body: it passes local laws (ordinances), approves the city budget, sets tax rates and big spending priorities, and often confirms certain appointments, while the mayor is the chief executive who runs day-to-day operations by managing city departments (like police, fire, public works), proposing a budget for the council to consider, hiring or supervising top staff (depending on the city), and carrying out the laws the council passes; who has more power depends on the system, because in a ‚Äústrong mayor‚Äù city the mayor has broader appointment and management authority and often a veto over council legislation (which the council may be able to override), while in a ‚Äúcouncil-manager‚Äù city the council hires a professional city manager to run daily operations and the mayor is often more of a chairperson and public spokesperson with limited independent power. For budgets, the common pattern is that the mayor (or city manager) drafts and proposes the budget, but the city council debates it, amends it, and must vote to adopt it, since spending public money usually requires council approval. For ‚Äúschool stuff,‚Äù it often is not controlled by the mayor or city council at all: public schools are typically run by a separate school district with its own elected or appointed school board and superintendent, with funding coming from a mix of local property taxes plus state and federal money, so decisions like curriculum, hiring teachers, and school policies are usually made by the school board and administrators, not city hall‚Äîthough in a few places the mayor has more direct influence (for example through appointing the school board or controlling parts of the school budget), so the most accurate answer for any specific city is to check its charter and whether its schools are governed by an independent district or the city."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:12 - Category: great_depression
    ("Can you summarize what caused the Great Depression in a way that‚Äôs not just a list of dates? I need it for a quiz.", "The Great Depression was caused by a chain reaction of weaknesses in the economy that turned a downturn into a long-lasting collapse: during the 1920s the U.S. economy looked strong, but much of the growth was uneven and fragile, with many people and businesses relying on easy credit and buying stocks on margin (borrowing to invest), while some industries such as farming and parts of manufacturing were already struggling with low prices and overproduction. When confidence broke and stock prices crashed in late 1929, it didn‚Äôt by itself ‚Äúcause‚Äù the whole Depression, but it wiped out wealth and, more importantly, scared consumers and investors into cutting spending and investment; as demand fell, companies reduced production and laid off workers, which reduced spending even more in a vicious cycle. The crisis deepened because the banking system was weak and poorly protected: waves of bank failures destroyed people‚Äôs savings and shrank the money supply, making it harder to get loans and pushing prices and wages downward, which increased the real burden of debts. Government and central-bank policies often made things worse at first, such as allowing the money supply to contract and raising trade barriers like the Smoot‚ÄìHawley Tariff, which contributed to a drop in international trade and spread the downturn globally, especially as countries tied to the gold standard had less flexibility to respond. In short, the Great Depression wasn‚Äôt one single event; it was a feedback loop where heavy debt, a financial panic, bank failures, falling spending, and policy mistakes reinforced each other until unemployment and poverty became widespread."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:12 - Category: us_government
    ("I don‚Äôt really get checks and balances‚Äîcan you give me a realistic example of how all three branches stop each other?", "Imagine Congress passes a law that says the government can ban certain kinds of social media posts nationwide, and the President signs it because they think it will reduce misinformation; that‚Äôs the legislative and executive branches working together to create and enforce a rule. People and groups who think the law violates the First Amendment sue in federal court, and judges can issue an order stopping the government from enforcing the law while the case is decided; if the courts ultimately rule the law unconstitutional, the judicial branch blocks it and the law can‚Äôt be used. Now flip it: if the President tries to act alone by issuing an executive order to do the same kind of speech ban without Congress, Congress can pass a law limiting or forbidding that action and can refuse to fund the program, and courts can also strike the order down if it exceeds the President‚Äôs constitutional authority. And if Congress passes a law the President thinks is harmful, the President can veto it, but Congress can override that veto with a two-thirds vote in both the House and Senate; even then, courts still have the power to review the law‚Äôs constitutionality, so each branch has tools that can stop the others from going too far."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:13 - Category: founding_documents
    ("For US history: what was the main idea behind the Federalist Papers, and who were they written for?", "The main idea behind the Federalist Papers was to explain and defend the new U.S. Constitution and to persuade Americans that a stronger national government under the Constitution would protect liberty better than the weak system under the Articles of Confederation, addressing worries about issues like too much federal power, the need for checks and balances, and how a large republic could control factions. They were written in 1787‚Äì1788 by Alexander Hamilton, James Madison, and John Jay under the pen name ‚ÄúPublius,‚Äù and they were aimed especially at the voters and leaders of New York (and more broadly the American public) to encourage ratification of the Constitution."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:13 - Category: bald_eagle
    ("Why is the bald eagle such a big American symbol? Was it always the national bird?", "The bald eagle became a major American symbol because it is native to North America, looks powerful and independent, and was seen by the founders as a fitting emblem for a new nation; it also appears on the Great Seal of the United States, which Congress approved on June 20, 1782, showing an eagle holding an olive branch for peace and arrows for defense, so it quickly became linked with national identity and government. It was not ‚Äúalways‚Äù officially the national bird in the sense of being named by a single early law, but it was chosen as the central national emblem on the Great Seal in 1782 and used that way for generations; much later, Congress formally declared the bald eagle the national bird of the United States in 1940. There was some disagreement at the start‚ÄîBenjamin Franklin famously complained in a letter that he thought the bald eagle had ‚Äúbad moral character‚Äù and joked he preferred the turkey‚Äîbut the eagle‚Äôs bold look and its long use on official symbols made it the enduring choice."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:13 - Category: territories
    ("What‚Äôs the deal with US territories‚Äîare people there US citizens and do they vote for president?", "U.S. territories are places under U.S. sovereignty that are not states, and that difference matters for both citizenship and presidential elections. Citizenship depends on which territory you mean: people born in Puerto Rico, Guam, the U.S. Virgin Islands, and the Northern Mariana Islands are U.S. citizens at birth under federal law, while people born in American Samoa are generally U.S. nationals (they owe permanent allegiance to the United States and can live and work anywhere in the U.S.) but are not automatically U.S. citizens unless they go through a naturalization process. As for voting for president, residents of territories do not vote in the general election for president because the Constitution gives Electoral College votes only to states (and Washington, D.C., via the 23rd Amendment), and territories have no electoral votes; territories also do not have voting members of Congress (they elect a nonvoting delegate or, for Puerto Rico, a resident commissioner). However, U.S. citizens from the territories can vote for president if they move to a state (and meet that state‚Äôs voting rules), and some U.S. citizens living in territories may be able to vote absentee in a state if they are eligible under that state‚Äôs laws based on prior residence. Territories do participate in presidential primaries and caucuses run by political parties, which helps choose the party nominees, but that is separate from the November presidential election."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:13 - Category: living_nonliving
    ("Science question: what‚Äôs the difference between living and nonliving things? Are viruses alive or not?", "Living things are made of one or more cells and carry out life processes: they use energy (metabolism), grow and develop, respond to their environment, maintain a stable internal condition (homeostasis), and reproduce, passing on genetic information; nonliving things may be made of matter and can change (like a rock breaking or a fire spreading), but they do not have cells, do not run their own metabolism, and do not maintain homeostasis or reproduce by themselves. Viruses are a special case because they have genetic material (DNA or RNA) and can evolve over time, but they are not made of cells and cannot use energy, grow, or reproduce on their own; instead, they must infect a living cell and use the cell‚Äôs machinery to make more viruses. Because they depend completely on a host cell for metabolism and reproduction, most scientists classify viruses as nonliving, or as ‚Äúon the border‚Äù between living and nonliving."),

