    ("In JavaScript, I keep getting \'undefined\' when I try to use a function‚Äîcan you look at this code and tell me what I‚Äôm doing wrong? function add(a,b){ return a+b } let total = add(3) console.log(total)", "Your add function expects two inputs, a and b, but you‚Äôre calling it with only one argument: add(3). In JavaScript, missing arguments become undefined, so inside the function a is 3 and b is undefined, and 3 + undefined evaluates to NaN (not a number), not a real total; if you‚Äôre seeing undefined in a similar situation, it‚Äôs usually because the function didn‚Äôt return anything or you forgot to pass required values. Fix it by passing both numbers, like let total = add(3, 4); console.log(total); which prints 7, or by giving b a default value so one-argument calls still work, like function add(a, b = 0) { return a + b; } so add(3) correctly returns 3."),

