    ("Immunology help: what‚Äôs the difference between MHC class I vs class II in terms of where the antigen comes from + which T cells get activated? I keep mixing it up on exams.", "MHC class I presents endogenous (inside-the-cell) antigens, meaning peptides made in the cytosol from proteins the cell itself is producing (for example viral proteins in an infected cell or abnormal proteins in a tumor cell); these peptides are loaded onto MHC I and displayed on almost all nucleated cells to activate CD8+ cytotoxic T cells, which can then kill the infected or malignant cell. MHC class II presents exogenous (from outside-the-cell) antigens, meaning proteins that were taken up by endocytosis/phagocytosis and processed in endosomes/lysosomes by professional antigen-presenting cells (dendritic cells, macrophages, B cells); these peptides are loaded onto MHC II and displayed to activate CD4+ helper T cells, which then coordinate immune responses (like helping B cells make antibodies and activating macrophages). A quick exam memory hook is ‚Äú1 is IN, 2 is OUT‚Äù: class I = INtracellular ‚Üí CD8, class II = OUTside ‚Üí CD4."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:16 - Category: chi_square_tests
    ("Can you help me debug my stats thinking: when would I use a chi-square test vs Fisher‚Äôs exact test? My prof says ‚Äòexpected counts‚Äô matter but I don‚Äôt know what that means.", "You use a chi-square test of independence (or homogeneity) when you have a contingency table of counts (for example, treatment vs outcome) and your sample is large enough that the chi-square approximation is reliable; you use Fisher‚Äôs exact test when the sample is small or the table is sparse so that the chi-square approximation can be inaccurate. ‚ÄúExpected counts‚Äù are the counts you would expect in each cell if there were truly no association between the variables, and they‚Äôre computed from the marginal totals as expected = (row total √ó column total) / grand total; for example, if 20 people are treated, 30 are controls, 10 have the outcome, and 40 do not (total 50), then the expected count in the treated-and-outcome cell is (20√ó10)/50 = 4, even if the observed count is something else. The rule-of-thumb your professor is pointing to is that chi-square works well when expected counts aren‚Äôt too small (commonly, all expected counts at least about 5, or at minimum no expected counts below 1 and at least 80% of cells with expected counts ‚â• 5), because the chi-square p-value relies on an approximation that breaks down with tiny expected values; Fisher‚Äôs exact test doesn‚Äôt rely on that approximation and instead calculates an exact p-value from the hypergeometric distribution given the fixed margins, so it‚Äôs preferred for 2√ó2 tables with small expected counts or any time you see very small expected values or zeros. In practice: if you have a reasonably large dataset and the expected counts look comfortably big, chi-square is fine and fast; if the table is small/sparse, especially a 2√ó2 with rare outcomes, use Fisher‚Äôs exact (or an exact/Monte Carlo version for larger tables), and if expected counts are small because categories are overly granular, another option is to combine sensible categories so expected counts increase."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:16 - Category: calculus_multivariable
    ("Multivariable calc: find the critical points and classify them for f(x,y)=x^3-3x+y^2-4y. I know it‚Äôs gradients/Hessian but I‚Äôm getting lost after setting partials = 0.", "To find critical points, compute the gradient and set it equal to zero: f(x,y)=x^3‚àí3x+y^2‚àí4y has partial derivatives f_x=3x^2‚àí3=3(x^2‚àí1) and f_y=2y‚àí4, so critical points satisfy 3(x^2‚àí1)=0 and 2y‚àí4=0, giving x=¬±1 and y=2, hence the two critical points are (1,2) and (‚àí1,2). To classify them, use the Hessian: f_xx=6x, f_yy=2, and f_xy=0, so the Hessian matrix is [[6x,0],[0,2]] with determinant D=f_xx f_yy‚àí(f_xy)^2=(6x)(2)=12x. At (1,2), D=12>0 and f_xx=6>0, so the Hessian is positive definite and (1,2) is a local minimum (in fact f(1,2)=1‚àí3+4‚àí8=‚àí6). At (‚àí1,2), D=‚àí12<0, so the Hessian is indefinite and (‚àí1,2) is a saddle point (and f(‚àí1,2)=‚àí1+3+4‚àí8=‚àí2). There is no local maximum because the only remaining critical point is a saddle, and along the x-direction the cubic term makes the function unbounded above and below."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:16 - Category: linear_algebra
    ("Linear algebra question‚Äîhow do I know if a set of vectors spans R^3 without doing a ton of work? If I give you v1=(1,2,0), v2=(2,4,1), v3=(0,1,1) can you show the quickest way?", "A quick way to check whether three vectors span R^3 is to put them as columns of a 3√ó3 matrix and check whether the determinant is nonzero (equivalently, whether the columns are linearly independent); if det ‚â† 0, they span all of R^3, and if det = 0, they don‚Äôt. Using v1=(1,2,0), v2=(2,4,1), v3=(0,1,1), form A = [[1,2,0],[2,4,1],[0,1,1]] with these as columns, then compute det(A) = 1¬∑det([[4,1],[1,1]]) ‚àí 2¬∑det([[2,1],[0,1]]) + 0¬∑(‚Ä¶) = 1¬∑(4¬∑1‚àí1¬∑1) ‚àí 2¬∑(2¬∑1‚àí1¬∑0) = 3 ‚àí 4 = ‚àí1, which is nonzero, so the vectors are linearly independent and therefore span R^3. As an even faster ‚Äúsanity check‚Äù intuition, notice v2 is almost 2v1 but has an extra 1 in the third component, and v3 has a different pattern as well, so it‚Äôs plausible they won‚Äôt lie in the same plane; the determinant calculation confirms it decisively."),

