    ("College bio/geology curiosity: how do fossils actually form, and why do we mostly find bones/shells instead of like soft tissue?", "Fossils form when an organism (or its traces, like footprints, burrows, or poop) gets buried quickly and then its remains are stabilized and turned into rock-like material over geologic time, usually in sedimentary settings such as river deltas, lake bottoms, floodplains, and shallow seas where mud, sand, or limey ooze can cover it before scavengers and decay destroy it. After burial, several different processes can preserve it: in permineralization, mineral-rich groundwater flows through pores in bone or wood and precipitates minerals (often silica, calcite, or iron minerals) that ‚Äúcement‚Äù the structure; in replacement, the original material (like shell aragonite) slowly dissolves and is replaced molecule-by-molecule by a more stable mineral (often calcite, silica, or pyrite) while keeping the shape; in molds and casts, the hard part dissolves leaving a cavity (mold) that later fills with sediment or minerals to make a cast; and in carbonization, pressure and heat drive off gases and liquids leaving a thin carbon film, common for plants and some soft-bodied organisms. We mostly find bones, teeth, and shells because they start out mineralized and durable (calcium phosphate in vertebrate bone and enamel, calcium carbonate in many shells), so they resist decay and can survive long enough to be buried and mineralized, whereas soft tissues are mostly water and proteins/lipids that are rapidly broken down by bacteria, oxygen-driven chemical reactions, and scavengers; even if buried, soft parts tend to collapse and rot before minerals can replicate them. Soft-tissue fossils do exist, but they require unusually protective conditions that shut down decay fast, such as very rapid burial in fine mud, low oxygen (anoxic) bottoms that limit scavengers and slow microbes, early mineral ‚Äúsealing‚Äù (for example phosphate or carbonate forming a protective coating), entombment in amber (tree resin), freezing, or extreme drying; famous examples include insects in amber, mammoths preserved in permafrost, and exceptionally preserved ‚ÄúLagerst√§tten‚Äù like the Burgess Shale where fine-grained sediments and low-oxygen conditions helped preserve outlines and even some internal details. In short, fossilization is a rare race between destruction and preservation, and hard parts usually win that race, which is why the fossil record is dominated by bones and shells rather than soft tissue."),

