    ("i have a question about animal groups: whats the difference between mammals and reptiles? examples please", "Mammals and reptiles are both vertebrates (animals with backbones), but they differ in how they regulate body temperature, how they reproduce, and what their skin is like. Mammals are warm-blooded, meaning they keep a fairly constant internal body temperature; they have hair or fur, and mother mammals produce milk from mammary glands to feed their babies, with most mammals giving live birth (though a few, like the platypus and echidnas, lay eggs). Examples of mammals include dogs, cats, humans, whales, bats, elephants, and kangaroos. Reptiles are cold-blooded (more accurately, ectothermic), meaning their body temperature changes with the environment, so they often bask in the sun to warm up; they have dry, scaly skin, and most lay leathery-shelled eggs on land (though some give live birth), and they do not make milk. Examples of reptiles include snakes, lizards, turtles and tortoises, and crocodiles and alligators. A quick way to remember it is: mammals have hair and feed milk to their young, while reptiles have scales and rely on external heat sources to stay warm."),

