    ("in chemistry, can you balance this equation: H2 + O2 -> H2O (and explain why the numbers change)", "To balance H2 + O2 -> H2O, you need the same number of each type of atom on both sides because atoms are not created or destroyed in a chemical reaction, they are only rearranged (this is conservation of mass). Start by counting atoms: on the left you have 2 hydrogen atoms (H2) and 2 oxygen atoms (O2), but on the right H2O has 2 hydrogen atoms and only 1 oxygen atom, so oxygen is unbalanced. Put a 2 in front of H2O to make 2 oxygen atoms on the right: H2 + O2 -> 2H2O; now the right side has 4 hydrogen atoms (because 2 times H2O contains 4 H total), so hydrogen is unbalanced. Fix that by putting a 2 in front of H2: 2H2 + O2 -> 2H2O, and now you can re-check: left has 4 H and 2 O, right has 4 H and 2 O, so it‚Äôs balanced. The numbers change because the coefficients (the big numbers in front) tell how many whole molecules react, and you are allowed to change those to match atom counts, but you should not change the small subscripts inside a formula (like the 2 in H2 or O2) because that would change what substance it is."),

