    ("i want to build a tiny project with a Raspberry Pi‚Äîwhat‚Äôs an easy first thing to try that isn‚Äôt super hard?", "A great first Raspberry Pi project that‚Äôs genuinely easy and very ‚Äúreal world‚Äù is turning it into a simple home network ad-blocker with Pi-hole, because it mostly involves following clear steps, you don‚Äôt need any soldering, and you end up with something useful right away. You‚Äôll need a Raspberry Pi (a Pi 3, 4, or 5 is ideal, but many models work), a microSD card, power, and an internet connection; install Raspberry Pi OS, update it, then install Pi-hole using the official one-line installer from pi-hole.net, and during setup choose a static IP address so your network can always find it. After it‚Äôs installed, you log into the Pi-hole web dashboard from another device on your network to see what it‚Äôs blocking, and the final step is telling your router (or each device) to use the Pi-hole‚Äôs IP address as the DNS server; once that‚Äôs set, many ads and tracking domains get blocked for your whole network automatically. If you want an even simpler ‚Äúfirst win‚Äù before that, try making the Pi a headless ‚Äúremote box‚Äù: enable SSH in Raspberry Pi OS, connect to it from your laptop with an SSH client, and practice basic commands (updating, checking disk space, editing a file), because those skills make every future Pi project easier."),

