    ("How do you find the volume of a triangular prism? Can you do one example with numbers so I can copy the steps?", "To find the volume of a triangular prism, you multiply the area of the triangular base by the length (or height) of the prism, so Volume = (area of triangle) √ó (prism length), and the triangle‚Äôs area is (1/2) √ó base √ó triangle height. Example: suppose the triangular base has base = 8 cm and triangle height = 5 cm, and the prism length is 12 cm; first find the triangle area: A = (1/2) √ó 8 √ó 5 = 20 cm¬≤, then multiply by the prism length: V = 20 √ó 12 = 240 cm¬≥, so the triangular prism‚Äôs volume is 240 cubic centimeters. You can always check your work by making sure you used square units for the base area and then multiplied by a length to get cubic units for volume."),

