    ("In physics, can you help me set up the equations for a cart being pushed with friction? I get lost on free body diagrams.", "Start by drawing the cart as a box and include only the forces acting on it: its weight mg straight down, the normal force N straight up from the floor, your applied push force F (often horizontal, but if you push at an angle Œ∏ above the horizontal then its components are F cosŒ∏ forward and F sinŒ∏ upward), and friction f along the surface opposing the direction of motion (if the cart is moving, use kinetic friction f = Œºk N; if it is not moving yet, static friction adjusts up to a maximum f ‚â§ Œºs N). Then write Newton‚Äôs 2nd law separately in each direction: in the vertical direction the cart usually has no acceleration so Œ£Fy = 0 gives N + F sinŒ∏ ‚àí mg = 0 (if the push is purely horizontal, this reduces to N ‚àí mg = 0), and in the horizontal direction Œ£Fx = ma gives F cosŒ∏ ‚àí f = ma (or just F ‚àí f = ma for a horizontal push). Substitute the friction model into the horizontal equation using the normal force from the vertical equation: for a horizontal push with kinetic friction you get N = mg, f = Œºk mg, and therefore a = (F ‚àí Œºk mg)/m; for an angled push you get N = mg ‚àí F sinŒ∏, f = Œºk(mg ‚àí F sinŒ∏), and a = (F cosŒ∏ ‚àí Œºk(mg ‚àí F sinŒ∏))/m, noting that pushing upward reduces N and friction while pushing downward increases them. A quick self-check is that if friction were zero (Œº = 0) your equation should reduce to a = F/m (or a = F cosŒ∏/m), and if the applied force is too small compared with the maximum static friction (F cosŒ∏ ‚â§ Œºs N) then the correct result is a = 0 because the cart does not start moving."),

