    ("I‚Äôm learning JavaScript and the DOM‚Äîhow do I add a click event to a button that changes the text on the page?", "In JavaScript you add a click event by first selecting the button element from the DOM, then attaching a listener that runs a function when the button is clicked, and inside that function you change the text of another element on the page. For example, if your HTML has <button id=\"changeBtn\">Change text</button> and <p id=\"message\">Original text</p>, your JavaScript can be: const btn = document.getElementById(\'changeBtn\'); const message = document.getElementById(\'message\'); btn.addEventListener(\'click\', () => { message.textContent = \'You clicked the button!\'; }); This works because addEventListener(\'click\', ...) tells the browser ‚Äúwhen a click happens on this button, run this code,‚Äù and textContent safely replaces the visible text inside the paragraph (if you needed to insert actual HTML tags, you‚Äôd use innerHTML instead)."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:30 - Category: neural_networks_intro
    ("For my intro ML class, can you explain what a neural network is using a super simple example? I don‚Äôt get what \'layers\' mean.", "A neural network is a machine-learning model that learns to turn inputs into an output by passing information through several stages of simple calculations, kind of like an assembly line for making a decision. A super simple example is predicting whether an email is ‚Äúspam‚Äù or ‚Äúnot spam‚Äù using a few input features like ‚Äúdoes the subject contain the word FREE?‚Äù, ‚Äúhow many links are in the email?‚Äù, and ‚Äúis the sender in your contacts?‚Äù; you can think of these as numbers you feed in (often 0/1 for no/yes, or a count). A layer is just a group of ‚Äúneurons‚Äù (tiny calculators) that all take in numbers, multiply them by learned weights (how important each input is), add a bias (a learned offset), and then apply a simple squashing function (an activation) to produce new numbers; the first layer is the input layer (it just holds the feature values), the middle layer(s) are hidden layers (they create useful intermediate signals like ‚Äúthis looks sales-y‚Äù by combining features), and the final layer is the output layer (it turns those signals into a final prediction like a probability of spam). During training, the network adjusts its weights and biases so that, for many labeled examples of emails, the final output matches the correct answer more often; ‚Äúmore layers‚Äù means more steps of transformation, which lets the model build more complex patterns from simple inputs, like combining ‚ÄúFREE‚Äù plus ‚Äúmany links‚Äù plus ‚Äúunknown sender‚Äù into a stronger spam signal than any one feature alone."),

