    ("AP Calc: can you show me how to do integration by parts on ‚à´ x e^(3x) dx? I keep mixing up u and dv.", "To do ‚à´ x e^(3x) dx with integration by parts, use the idea ‚Äúdifferentiate the algebraic part, integrate the exponential part,‚Äù so choose u = x (because it gets simpler when differentiated) and dv = e^(3x) dx (because it‚Äôs easy to integrate). Then du = dx and v = ‚à´ e^(3x) dx = (1/3)e^(3x). Apply the formula ‚à´ u dv = uv ‚àí ‚à´ v du: ‚à´ x e^(3x) dx = x¬∑(1/3)e^(3x) ‚àí ‚à´ (1/3)e^(3x)¬∑1 dx = (x/3)e^(3x) ‚àí (1/3)¬∑(1/3)e^(3x) + C = (e^(3x)/9)(3x ‚àí 1) + C. Quick check by differentiating: d/dx[(e^(3x)/9)(3x ‚àí 1)] = (1/9)[3e^(3x)(3x ‚àí 1) + e^(3x)¬∑3] = (1/9)[9x e^(3x)] = x e^(3x), so the antiderivative is correct; if you‚Äôre mixing up u and dv, a reliable habit is to pick u as the factor that becomes simpler when you differentiate (like x) and dv as the factor that stays manageable when you integrate (like e^(3x))."),

