    ("Chem: I‚Äôm confused on VSEPR. What shape is SF4 and why is it not tetrahedral?", "SF4 has five regions of electron density around the sulfur (four S‚ÄìF bonding pairs plus one lone pair), so by VSEPR its electron-domain geometry is trigonal bipyramidal, not tetrahedral (tetrahedral would require only four electron domains). In a trigonal bipyramidal arrangement there are two axial positions and three equatorial positions; the lone pair goes in an equatorial position because that minimizes repulsions (equatorial has fewer 90¬∞ interactions than axial), leaving two axial S‚ÄìF bonds and two equatorial S‚ÄìF bonds. With one equatorial position occupied by the lone pair, the molecular shape (the positions of the atoms only) is seesaw (also called disphenoidal), and the bond angles are distorted from the ideal 120¬∞ and 90¬∞ because lone pairs repel more strongly than bonding pairs."),

