    ("Physics help: a 2 kg block on a frictionless ramp (30¬∞) ‚Äî what‚Äôs the acceleration down the ramp and the normal force? Please do it step-by-step.", "On a frictionless ramp, the only forces on the 2 kg block are gravity (weight) straight down, W = mg, and the normal force N from the ramp perpendicular to the surface; choose axes with x along the ramp (downhill positive) and y perpendicular to the ramp. First compute the weight: mg = (2 kg)(9.8 m/s^2) = 19.6 N, then resolve it into components relative to the ramp: the component pulling the block down the ramp is mg sin(30¬∞) = 19.6(0.5) = 9.8 N, and the component pushing into the ramp is mg cos(30¬∞) = 19.6(0.866...) ‚âà 16.97 N. Along the ramp, Newton‚Äôs 2nd law gives Œ£F_x = ma, so 9.8 N = (2 kg)a, which means a = 9.8/2 = 4.9 m/s^2 down the ramp (equivalently a = g sin 30¬∞ = 9.8 √ó 0.5 = 4.9 m/s^2). Perpendicular to the ramp, the block does not accelerate into or away from the surface, so a_y = 0 and Œ£F_y = 0, which gives N ‚àí mg cos(30¬∞) = 0, so N = mg cos(30¬∞) ‚âà 16.97 N, usually reported as about 17.0 N. A quick check: the downhill component of gravity (9.8 N) is smaller than the full weight (19.6 N), so the acceleration (4.9 m/s^2) is less than g, and the normal force (‚âà17 N) is less than mg, which makes sense because some of gravity is ‚Äúused‚Äù to pull the block down the ramp."),

