    ("Can you check if my rational expression simplification is right? (x^2 9)/(x^2 6x + 9) ‚Üí (x+3)/(x-3). My teacher said there‚Äôs a domain issue?", "Factor first: x^2 ‚àí 9 is a difference of squares, so it becomes (x ‚àí 3)(x + 3), and x^2 ‚àí 6x + 9 is a perfect square trinomial, so it becomes (x ‚àí 3)^2. Then (x^2 ‚àí 9)/(x^2 ‚àí 6x + 9) = (x ‚àí 3)(x + 3)/(x ‚àí 3)^2, and you can cancel one factor of (x ‚àí 3) to get (x + 3)/(x ‚àí 3), so your simplification is algebraically correct. The domain issue is that the original expression is undefined when the denominator is zero: (x ‚àí 3)^2 = 0 happens at x = 3, so x cannot be 3; even though the simplified form also has x ‚àí 3 in the denominator, you must still state the restriction x ‚â† 3 because the original expression has a hole (a removable discontinuity) at x = 3 rather than being defined there."),

