    ("Bio/biochem: what‚Äôs the difference between competitive and noncompetitive enzyme inhibition, like what happens to Km and Vmax?", "Competitive inhibition happens when an inhibitor competes with the substrate for the enzyme‚Äôs active site, so you can overcome it by adding more substrate; this makes the apparent Km increase (it takes a higher substrate concentration to reach half of the original Vmax, meaning lower apparent affinity) while Vmax stays the same because at very high substrate the inhibitor is outcompeted and the enzyme can still reach its original maximum rate. Noncompetitive inhibition (in the classic ‚Äúpure‚Äù case) happens when an inhibitor binds at a different site (to E and/or ES) and reduces catalytic activity regardless of how much substrate is present, so it cannot be overcome by adding substrate; this lowers Vmax (fewer functional enzyme molecules or reduced turnover) while Km stays the same because substrate binding affinity is not changed in the pure noncompetitive model. A quick way to remember is ‚Äúcompetitive changes Km, noncompetitive changes Vmax,‚Äù with the logic that active-site competition affects how well substrate binds (apparent affinity), while allosteric inhibition affects how fast the enzyme can work even when substrate is bound."),

