    ("CS class: we‚Äôre learning databases. Can you explain what a primary key vs a foreign key is using a real example (like students/classes)?", "A primary key is a column (or set of columns) that uniquely identifies each row in a table, meaning no two rows can share the same value and it can‚Äôt be blank; for example, in a Students table you might have StudentID as the primary key because each student gets a unique ID even if two students share the same name. A foreign key is a column in one table that stores a value that points to (matches) a primary key in another table, creating a relationship between the tables; for example, you could have an Enrollments table with EnrollmentID as its primary key, plus StudentID and ClassID as foreign keys, where StudentID must match an existing Students.StudentID and ClassID must match an existing Classes.ClassID, so the database can enforce rules like ‚Äúyou can‚Äôt enroll a student who doesn‚Äôt exist‚Äù and ‚Äúyou can‚Äôt enroll anyone in a class that isn‚Äôt in the Classes table.‚Äù In short, primary keys identify a row inside their own table, while foreign keys connect rows across tables so the database can keep related data consistent."),

