    ("Intro cryptography question: how does a Caesar cipher get cracked with frequency analysis? Can you walk through a tiny example?", "A Caesar cipher shifts every letter by the same amount (for example, shifting by 3 turns A‚ÜíD, B‚ÜíE, ‚Ä¶), so it doesn‚Äôt hide the overall ‚Äúshape‚Äù of the language: common letters in the plaintext stay common in the ciphertext, just renamed. Frequency analysis cracks it by counting how often each ciphertext letter appears, guessing which plaintext letter it probably corresponds to (in English, E is usually most common, then T/A/O/I/N, etc.), and using that guess to infer the shift; you then test the shift by decrypting and seeing if the result looks like real words. Tiny example: suppose you intercept the ciphertext ‚ÄúKHOOR ZRUOG‚Äù and you count letters; O appears 3 times, which is the most frequent, so you try the common-English guess that this O might actually be plaintext E. If ciphertext O corresponds to plaintext E, the shift is +10 (because E shifted forward 10 gives O), so to decrypt you shift every letter back 10; applying that to KHOOR gives HELLO and to ZRUOG gives WORLD, yielding ‚ÄúHELLO WORLD,‚Äù which confirms the shift. In practice you don‚Äôt rely on a single letter for longer texts: you compare the whole frequency distribution (and common patterns like ‚ÄúTHE‚Äù or repeated double letters) across all 25 possible shifts, and the correct shift stands out because it produces readable English."),

