    ("Statistics: I have a scatterplot and I‚Äôm supposed to fit a regression line. How do I interpret r vs r^2 in normal words for my lab report?", "r (the correlation coefficient) tells you the direction and strength of the straight-line relationship between your x and y: it ranges from ‚àí1 to +1, where the sign tells direction (positive means y tends to increase as x increases; negative means y tends to decrease as x increases) and the size tells how tightly the points follow a line (values near 0 mean little to no linear pattern, values near 1 in magnitude mean a very strong linear pattern). r¬≤ (the coefficient of determination) is r multiplied by itself, so it is never negative, and it tells you how much of the variation in y is explained by the linear regression on x; in normal words for a lab report you can write something like ‚Äúr = 0.80 indicates a strong positive linear relationship‚Äù and ‚Äúr¬≤ = 0.64 means about 64% of the differences we see in y can be accounted for by a straight-line model using x, while the remaining 36% is due to other factors, noise, or a non-linear pattern.‚Äù A key practical point is that r is about direction plus strength, while r¬≤ is about explanatory power in percent-like terms, and r¬≤ does not tell you whether the slope is positive or negative (you need r or the slope sign for that); also, r and r¬≤ describe linear fit quality, so a curved pattern can give a low r even if x and y are strongly related in a non-linear way."),

