    ("Engineering elective: we‚Äôre doing a bridge design project. What are the main forces a truss bridge deals with (tension/compression) and how do you decide where to put supports?", "In a truss bridge, loads from the deck (people, cars, wind, the bridge‚Äôs own weight) get carried through straight members that mainly experience axial forces, meaning each member is either in tension (being pulled) or compression (being squeezed), with very little bending if the joints act like pins; typically the top chord is mostly in compression and the bottom chord is mostly in tension for a simply supported span under gravity loads, while the diagonals and verticals share the job of transferring shear so some go into tension and others into compression depending on the truss type and where the load sits (for example, in a Pratt truss the diagonals usually take tension under downward loads, while in a Howe truss the diagonals usually take compression). To decide where to put supports, start by thinking about the span you must cross and where the ground or structure can actually carry load, because supports are where the bridge pushes its forces into the earth; the most common, stable choice is a simply supported layout with one pin support (resists vertical and horizontal forces) and one roller support (resists vertical force but allows horizontal movement), usually placed at the ends of the span to minimize bending and keep the truss forces mostly axial, and the roller is important because it lets the bridge expand and contract with temperature without building up large unwanted forces. If you add an intermediate support (making multiple spans), you reduce member forces and deflection but you introduce new reaction forces and can create negative bending over the support, so you only add supports when the site allows it and when the design benefits outweigh the complexity; a good practical process is to sketch the span, choose realistic support locations, draw a free-body diagram of the whole bridge, compute the support reactions from equilibrium (sum of vertical forces equals zero and sum of moments equals zero, and horizontal forces if needed), then use a method like joints or sections to see which members are in tension or compression and adjust the truss geometry so long, slender members are mostly in tension (less buckling risk) and compression members are kept shorter or braced."),

