    ("College CS: I‚Äôm learning operating systems and I‚Äôm stuck ‚Äî what‚Äôs the difference between a process and a thread, and why does context switching have overhead?", "A process is an instance of a running program with its own private virtual address space and OS-managed resources such as an address-space layout, open file descriptors/handles, security credentials, and other kernel bookkeeping; threads are the units of execution that run inside a process, and multiple threads in the same process share that process‚Äôs code, heap, and open files but each thread has its own CPU execution state (program counter/instruction pointer, registers), its own stack, and typically thread-local storage, which is why threads are often called ‚Äúlightweight processes.‚Äù This distinction matters because isolation is different: separate processes are protected from each other by the memory-management hardware and the OS (one process generally can‚Äôt directly read/write another‚Äôs memory without explicit mechanisms), while threads can directly read/write the same memory, making communication faster but requiring synchronization (mutexes, semaphores, condition variables, atomics) to avoid races. Context switching has overhead because the CPU can only execute one thread at a time per core, so switching from one runnable thread/process to another requires the OS to save the current thread‚Äôs CPU state and restore the next thread‚Äôs state, update kernel scheduler data, and often change memory-mapping context; a thread switch within the same process may mostly be saving/restoring registers and switching stacks, but a process switch can additionally require changing the page-table base (address-space switch) and flushing or invalidating parts of the TLB (the cache of virtual-to-physical translations), which makes subsequent memory accesses slower until the TLB ‚Äúwarms up‚Äù again. There‚Äôs also indirect overhead: entering/exiting the kernel and touching scheduler structures can cause cache disruption, and the newly scheduled thread may have poor instruction/data cache locality compared to the one that was running, so even after the switch completes, the CPU may spend extra time waiting on memory while caches refill; that‚Äôs why excessive context switching (for example, too many runnable threads or very small time slices) can reduce throughput even though it improves responsiveness."),

