    ("For a class, I need to write a short proof: why does Dijkstra‚Äôs algorithm fail when there are negative edge weights? Can you explain the reasoning like I‚Äôm about to be tested on it?", "Dijkstra‚Äôs algorithm relies on a key invariant: when it selects (extracts) the unvisited vertex u with the smallest tentative distance d[u], that value is final and equals the true shortest-path distance from the source, because any alternative path to u would have to go through some other unvisited vertex v whose tentative distance is at least d[u], and then add a nonnegative edge weight to reach u, which cannot produce something smaller than d[u]. This ‚Äúgreedy choice is safe‚Äù step uses the assumption that all edge weights are nonnegative; with a negative edge, a vertex that looks optimal now can later be improved by a path that goes from the source to some other vertex x (possibly with a larger current tentative distance), and then takes a negative edge (or a sequence including a negative edge) into u, producing a new distance smaller than the one Dijkstra already finalized, which the algorithm will not correctly propagate because it never revisits finalized vertices. A concrete counterexample makes this airtight: let the source be s, with edges s‚Üíu of weight 1, s‚Üíx of weight 2, and x‚Üíu of weight ‚àí3; Dijkstra initializes d[u]=1 and d[x]=2, extracts u first (since 1<2) and finalizes it as distance 1, but the true shortest path is s‚Üíx‚Üíu with total cost 2+(‚àí3)=‚àí1, so the algorithm‚Äôs correctness proof breaks exactly at the step where it assumes ‚Äúany path reaching u later cannot be cheaper,‚Äù which is only guaranteed when all edge weights are ‚â• 0."),

