    ("Computer graphics question: can you explain barycentric coordinates and how they‚Äôre used for interpolating color/texture across a triangle in rasterization?", "Barycentric coordinates are a way to express any point P inside (or on the edges of) a triangle with vertices A, B, and C as a weighted combination of those vertices: P = wA¬∑A + wB¬∑B + wC¬∑C, where the weights wA, wB, wC sum to 1, and for points inside the triangle they are all between 0 and 1; geometrically, each weight tells you ‚Äúhow close‚Äù P is to the opposite vertex/edge, and a common intuition is that the weights are proportional to sub-triangle areas (for example, wA equals the area of triangle PBC divided by the area of triangle ABC). In rasterization, once you know the barycentric weights for a pixel center relative to the triangle‚Äôs three screen-space vertices, you can interpolate any per-vertex attribute linearly across the triangle by taking the same weighted sum, such as color(P) = wA¬∑colorA + wB¬∑colorB + wC¬∑colorC, or texture coordinates uv(P) = wA¬∑uvA + wB¬∑uvB + wC¬∑uvC; this is why barycentric coordinates are the standard tool for smooth gradients (Gouraud shading), interpolating normals for per-pixel lighting, and mapping textures. A crucial practical detail is perspective: barycentric interpolation is naturally linear in screen space, but attributes like texture coordinates are linear in camera (clip) space, so to avoid ‚Äúswimming‚Äù or distortion you typically do perspective-correct interpolation by interpolating u/w, v/w, and 1/w with the screen-space barycentric weights (where w here is the clip-space homogeneous w for each vertex), then recovering u and v at the pixel as u = (u_over_w)/(one_over_w) and v = (v_over_w)/(one_over_w); this makes textures look correct under perspective projection. Efficiently, rasterizers compute barycentric weights using edge functions (signed 2D cross products) that vary linearly across the screen, so as you step from pixel to pixel you can update the weights with simple additions, and the sign of the edge functions also provides the inside-triangle test."),

