    ("Circuits: I built an op-amp amplifier in lab and my output is saturating. How do I check if my gain is too high, and what does slew rate have to do with a distorted sine wave?", "If your op-amp output is saturating, first check whether the required output swing is larger than what the op-amp can actually deliver on your power supplies: compute the expected output amplitude from your closed-loop gain, Vout,peak = Av(closed-loop) √ó Vin,peak, and compare it to the maximum undistorted swing, which is usually a little less than the supply rails (for example, on ¬±5 V supplies a non-rail-to-rail op-amp might only swing to about ¬±3 to ¬±4 V depending on load, while a rail-to-rail part can get closer but still not exactly to the rails). If your calculated Vout exceeds that limit, the fix is to reduce the gain (change the feedback resistor ratio), reduce the input amplitude, increase the supply voltage (within ratings), or choose an op-amp with a wider output swing/rail-to-rail output and adequate output current for your load; also confirm you really built negative feedback (correct pinout and feedback path), because positive feedback or a missing ground reference can drive the output hard to a rail. Separately, slew rate distortion is a dynamic limit: even if the output amplitude is within the rails, a sine wave needs a maximum slope of 2œÄfVpeak, so the op-amp must have slew rate SR ‚â• 2œÄfVpeak; if SR is too low, the sine can‚Äôt change fast enough and the peaks turn into straight-line ramps, making the waveform look ‚Äútriangular‚Äù and adding high-frequency harmonics. A quick lab check is to lower the frequency or lower the output amplitude: if the distortion goes away when you reduce frequency (at the same amplitude), it points to slew rate; if it goes away when you reduce amplitude (at the same frequency) and the waveform was clipping flat at the top/bottom, it points to output swing saturation. Finally, remember gain-bandwidth can also matter: if the closed-loop gain is high, the op-amp‚Äôs bandwidth shrinks (approximately GBW/Av), causing amplitude roll-off and phase shift, but that usually looks like a smaller sine or ringing/instability rather than hard clipping at the rails."),

