    ("User-centered design: I have to propose usability testing for a campus app. How many users do we realistically need, and how do I write good tasks that don‚Äôt lead the participant?", "For a campus app usability test, you can get strong, realistic insights with about 5 participants per distinct user group (for example, undergraduates, graduate students, and staff) for a first round, because small tests quickly uncover the most common usability problems; if you have only one primary audience, 5‚Äì8 total is usually enough to find major issues, while 10‚Äì15 gives more confidence and helps you see less frequent problems, and you can run multiple rounds (test a few people, fix, then test again) rather than trying to ‚Äúsolve everything‚Äù in one big study. Write tasks as short, goal-based scenarios that match real reasons someone would use the app and avoid telling them exactly what to click; instead of ‚ÄúTap the Schedule button and find your class,‚Äù use something like ‚ÄúYou‚Äôre on your way to campus and want to confirm where your 10 a.m. class meets. Show me how you would find the building and room,‚Äù and instead of ‚ÄúUse the dining filter to find vegan options,‚Äù use ‚ÄúYou‚Äôre looking for a vegan lunch option near you right now. Find a place you‚Äôd consider eating and tell me why.‚Äù To keep tasks non-leading, don‚Äôt use the same labels as the interface when you can avoid it, don‚Äôt mention the feature you expect them to use, don‚Äôt hint that there‚Äôs a ‚Äúright‚Äù path, and don‚Äôt ask ‚ÄúWould you click X?‚Äù; ask them to do the goal, then follow up with neutral questions like ‚ÄúWhat are you thinking?‚Äù ‚ÄúWhat would you expect to happen next?‚Äù and ‚ÄúWas anything confusing?‚Äù and if they get stuck, use gentle prompts such as ‚ÄúWhat would you try next?‚Äù rather than directing them to a specific button."),

