    ("Calc 1: I get the power rule, but I don‚Äôt get WHY the derivative is like the slope of the tangent. Can you explain derivatives using the limit definition with a simple example?", "Think of a derivative as ‚Äúthe slope right here‚Äù on a curve, the same way a line has one constant slope everywhere: if you pick two points on a curve, the slope you can compute is the slope of the secant line, which is the average rate of change between those points, and the derivative is what you get when you slide the second point closer and closer until the secant line becomes the tangent line. Using the limit definition, the derivative of f at x is f\'(x) = lim(h‚Üí0) [f(x+h) ‚àí f(x)]/h, where h is the tiny horizontal step from x to x+h; this expression is exactly the slope formula ‚Äúrise/run‚Äù between (x, f(x)) and (x+h, f(x+h)), and taking the limit h‚Üí0 captures the slope at a single point. For a simple example, let f(x) = x^2 and look at x = 3: the secant slope from x=3 to x=3+h is [(3+h)^2 ‚àí 3^2]/h = (9 + 6h + h^2 ‚àí 9)/h = (6h + h^2)/h = 6 + h, and as h‚Üí0 this approaches 6, so the tangent slope at x=3 is 6; that matches the general derivative f\'(x) = lim(h‚Üí0) [(x+h)^2 ‚àí x^2]/h = lim(h‚Üí0) (2x + h) = 2x, and plugging in x=3 gives 2¬∑3 = 6. The key ‚Äúwhy‚Äù is that a tangent line is the best straight-line approximation to the curve at that point, and the limit process makes the secant line‚Äôs slope converge to the unique slope of that best local linear approximation, which is why the derivative represents the slope of the tangent and the instantaneous rate of change."),

