    ("Why does ice melt faster in warm water than in cold water? Is it just because it‚Äôs hotter or is there something else going on?", "Ice melts faster in warm water mainly because the temperature difference between the water and the ice is larger, so heat flows into the ice more quickly, and melting requires a lot of energy (the latent heat of fusion, about 334 joules per gram) even though the ice stays near 0 ¬∞C while it melts. But it‚Äôs not only ‚Äúbecause it‚Äôs hotter‚Äù: warm water also transfers heat to the ice more efficiently because it drives stronger convection currents, meaning warmer, less dense water rises and cooler, denser water sinks, constantly bringing fresh warm water into contact with the ice and carrying away the cold meltwater; in cold water those currents are weaker, and a chilly boundary layer can form around the ice that insulates it and slows heat transfer. So the faster melting comes from both a bigger temperature difference (more heat available per second) and faster heat transport (better mixing and less insulating cold layer), which is why stirring the water or breaking the ice into smaller pieces (more surface area) makes it melt even faster."),

