    ("I‚Äôm confused about electron configurations‚Äîwhy is it 4s filled before 3d, and how would you write the configuration for Fe and Fe2+?", "The reason 4s fills before 3d is that in neutral atoms the 4s orbital is usually slightly lower in energy than the 3d orbitals, so electrons occupy 4s first according to the Aufbau principle (electrons go into the lowest-energy available orbitals), but once the 3d subshell begins to fill the energy ordering becomes very close and can effectively switch, which is why when you form cations the 4s electrons are removed before the 3d electrons even though 4s was filled first. Iron has 26 electrons, so its ground-state electron configuration is [Ar] 4s2 3d6 (expanded: 1s2 2s2 2p6 3s2 3p6 4s2 3d6). For Fe2+, you remove two electrons from the highest-energy, outermost orbitals, which for transition metals means removing 4s before 3d, so Fe2+ is [Ar] 3d6 (expanded: 1s2 2s2 2p6 3s2 3p6 3d6)."),

