    ("AP Calc: can you find the derivative of f(x)= (x^2+1)/(x-3) and show the quotient rule steps? I keep messing up the minus signs.", "To differentiate f(x) = (x^2 + 1)/(x ‚àí 3), use the quotient rule: if f(x) = u(x)/v(x), then f‚Ä≤(x) = (v(x)u‚Ä≤(x) ‚àí u(x)v‚Ä≤(x)) / (v(x))^2, where the order v u‚Ä≤ minus u v‚Ä≤ is what helps keep the minus signs straight. Here u(x) = x^2 + 1 so u‚Ä≤(x) = 2x, and v(x) = x ‚àí 3 so v‚Ä≤(x) = 1; substitute carefully: f‚Ä≤(x) = ((x ‚àí 3)(2x) ‚àí (x^2 + 1)(1)) / (x ‚àí 3)^2. Now simplify the numerator step by step: (x ‚àí 3)(2x) = 2x^2 ‚àí 6x, then subtract (x^2 + 1): 2x^2 ‚àí 6x ‚àí x^2 ‚àí 1 = x^2 ‚àí 6x ‚àí 1, so the final derivative is f‚Ä≤(x) = (x^2 ‚àí 6x ‚àí 1)/(x ‚àí 3)^2 (valid for x ‚â† 3). A quick minus-sign check is to keep the numerator as ‚Äú(x ‚àí 3)(2x) ‚àí (x^2 + 1)‚Äù until the very end, and remember the subtraction distributes: ‚àí(x^2 + 1) becomes ‚àíx^2 ‚àí 1."),

