    ("In World History, can you summarize how the Industrial Revolution changed cities in the United States (like work, immigration, living conditions)? I need 3 main points for notes.", "First, the Industrial Revolution turned many U.S. cities into factory and transportation hubs, shifting lots of people from farm work to wage labor in mills, steel plants, meatpacking, and other mass-production jobs, with long hours, strict schedules, and new kinds of work tied to machines and assembly lines. Second, it drove rapid population growth through immigration and migration: millions of immigrants from Europe (and later other regions) moved to cities for industrial jobs, and many African Americans moved from the rural South to northern cities in the Great Migration starting in the 1910s, creating crowded ethnic neighborhoods and changing city culture, politics, and labor organizing. Third, living conditions often worsened at first because housing and services couldn‚Äôt keep up, leading to overcrowded tenements, poor sanitation, polluted air and water, and higher disease risk, though over time reform movements and city governments pushed improvements like building codes, sewers, clean water systems, and public health rules."),

