    ("I‚Äôm writing a short paper on the Cold War‚Äîwhat were 2 ways it impacted everyday life in the U.S. (not just foreign policy)?", "Two major ways the Cold War shaped everyday life in the United States were the constant presence of nuclear-war anxiety and the spread of anti-communism into schools, workplaces, and popular culture. First, because Americans were told that a Soviet nuclear attack could happen with little warning, daily routines included civil defense measures like ‚ÄúDuck and Cover‚Äù drills in classrooms, air-raid siren tests, fallout shelter signs in public buildings, and many families stocking emergency supplies or even building backyard shelters; this fear also influenced where people chose to live (some preferred suburbs farther from city targets) and what they watched and read, since news and films frequently focused on atomic threats. Second, anti-communist politics affected ordinary people‚Äôs jobs and community life through loyalty oaths for teachers and government workers, background checks, and investigations such as those led by the House Un-American Activities Committee and Senator Joseph McCarthy in the early 1950s, which could cost people employment or damage reputations based on suspected beliefs or associations; at the same time, schools emphasized patriotism and ‚ÄúAmericanism,‚Äù and entertainment and advertising often promoted traditional family roles and consumer prosperity as proof that U.S. capitalism was superior to communism."),

