    ("Why does a shadow get longer when the sun is lower? Is that like light moving different?", "A shadow gets longer when the Sun is lower because the light is coming in at a slant instead of from high overhead, so your body blocks the light and the ‚Äúblocked‚Äù region stretches farther along the ground; it‚Äôs the same reason a tall pole makes a short shadow at noon but a long shadow near sunset. You can picture it like shining a flashlight straight down at a toy (short shadow) versus shining it from the side (long shadow): the angle changes the shadow length. The light itself isn‚Äôt moving differently in the sense of speeding up or slowing down; sunlight still travels in straight lines at the same speed, but when the Sun is low the rays hit the ground at a smaller angle, so the geometry makes the shadow longer."),

