    ("What was the Cold War? My textbook is confusing and it‚Äôs due tomorrow.", "The Cold War was a long period of intense rivalry and tension after World War II, roughly from 1947 to 1991, mainly between the United States and its allies and the Soviet Union and its allies, but it was called ‚Äúcold‚Äù because the two superpowers never fought each other directly in a full-scale war; instead they competed through opposing political and economic systems (capitalist democracy versus communist one-party rule), a massive nuclear arms race, propaganda, spying, and ‚Äúproxy wars‚Äù where each side supported different countries or groups, such as the Korean War (1950‚Äì1953) and the Vietnam War (U.S. involvement escalated in the 1960s). Key moments included the division of Germany and Berlin after WWII, the Berlin Blockade and Airlift (1948‚Äì1949), the building of the Berlin Wall (1961), the Cuban Missile Crisis (1962), and periods of reduced tension called d√©tente in the 1970s, while alliances like NATO (formed 1949) and the Warsaw Pact (formed 1955) organized the two sides. The Cold War ended as communist governments in Eastern Europe fell in 1989, the Berlin Wall came down, and the Soviet Union dissolved in 1991, leaving the United States as the world‚Äôs only superpower; its lasting impact includes today‚Äôs NATO map, many modern conflicts shaped by earlier proxy struggles, and ongoing debates about nuclear weapons and international influence."),

