    ("In Python, how do I write a function that takes a list of numbers and returns the average? (I keep getting errors.)", "To compute an average in Python, write a function that accepts a list (or other iterable) of numbers, adds them up, and divides by how many items there are; you also need to handle the empty-list case to avoid a ‚Äúdivision by zero‚Äù error. For example: def average(nums): if not nums: raise ValueError(\"average() requires at least one number\") return sum(nums) / len(nums). If you‚Äôre seeing errors, the most common causes are passing something that isn‚Äôt a list of numbers (like strings), having an empty list, or accidentally using integer division in very old Python 2 code; in modern Python 3, sum(nums) / len(nums) returns a float average as expected, so average([1, 2, 3, 4]) gives 2.5."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:42 - Category: backend_basics
    ("Explain Big-O notation like I‚Äôm new to CS, and show why binary search is O(log n).", "Big-O notation is a way to describe how an algorithm‚Äôs running time (or memory use) grows as the input size n grows, focusing on the overall trend rather than exact seconds; it answers ‚Äúif I make the input 10 times bigger, how much more work will this do?‚Äù and it ignores constant factors and smaller terms because they matter less for large n (for example, 3n + 20 is O(n) since it grows roughly in proportion to n). Common growth rates are O(1) for constant work, O(n) for scanning everything once, O(n log n) for many efficient sorts, and O(n^2) for ‚Äúnested loop over all pairs‚Äù style work. Binary search is O(log n) because each comparison cuts the remaining search space in half: in a sorted array of n items, after 1 step you have at most n/2 candidates left, after 2 steps at most n/4, after k steps at most n/2^k, and you stop when the remaining range is about 1 item, meaning n/2^k ‚âà 1, so 2^k ‚âà n and therefore k ‚âà log2(n); that k is the number of steps in the worst case, so the time grows like log n. A concrete example makes it intuitive: with 1,000,000 sorted items, linear search might check up to 1,000,000 items (O(n)), but binary search needs only about log2(1,000,000) ‚âà 20 comparisons, and even if you double the data to 2,000,000, the work increases by only about one extra step because log2(2,000,000) ‚âà 21."),

