    ("In AP Calc, can you find the derivative of f(x)= (3x^2 5x + 2) / (x 1) and explain which rule you‚Äôre using?", "To find the derivative of f(x) = (3x^2 ‚àí 5x + 2)/(x ‚àí 1), you use the quotient rule because the function is a ratio of two differentiable functions: if f(x) = u(x)/v(x), then f\'(x) = (u\'(x)v(x) ‚àí u(x)v\'(x))/[v(x)]^2. Here u(x) = 3x^2 ‚àí 5x + 2 so u\'(x) = 6x ‚àí 5, and v(x) = x ‚àí 1 so v\'(x) = 1, giving f\'(x) = ((6x ‚àí 5)(x ‚àí 1) ‚àí (3x^2 ‚àí 5x + 2)(1))/(x ‚àí 1)^2; simplifying the numerator, (6x ‚àí 5)(x ‚àí 1) = 6x^2 ‚àí 11x + 5, and subtracting (3x^2 ‚àí 5x + 2) gives 3x^2 ‚àí 6x + 3 = 3(x ‚àí 1)^2, so f\'(x) = 3(x ‚àí 1)^2/(x ‚àí 1)^2 = 3 for x ‚â† 1 (and note the original function is undefined at x = 1). As a quick check, you can also do polynomial division first: (3x^2 ‚àí 5x + 2)/(x ‚àí 1) = 3x ‚àí 2 for x ‚â† 1, whose derivative is also 3, confirming the result."),

