    ("What‚Äôs the difference between a population and a sample? Like if I‚Äôm surveying my school about cafeteria food, what counts as what?", "A population is the entire group you want to understand, and a sample is the smaller group you actually collect data from to represent that population. In your cafeteria-food survey, the population would be everyone you want your results to apply to, such as all students at your school (or all students who eat cafeteria lunch, if that‚Äôs your real target), while the sample would be the specific students who end up answering your survey, like the 150 students you asked or the people who responded to your online form. For example, if your school has 1,200 students and you survey 200 of them, then 1,200 is the population and 200 is the sample; the goal is to choose the sample in a way that reflects the population fairly (not just your friends or only one grade), so your conclusions about cafeteria food are more trustworthy."),

