    ("Stats homework: what test am I supposed to use? We‚Äôre comparing the mean test scores of two classes (different students), and we have sample means + SDs. Is it a two-sample t-test and what assumptions do I check?", "Yes: if the two classes are different students and you want to compare their population mean test scores, the standard choice is an independent two-sample t-test (often called an unpaired t-test). You set up H0: Œº1 ‚àí Œº2 = 0 versus a two-sided or one-sided alternative depending on the question, and you choose between Welch‚Äôs two-sample t-test (recommended by default because it does not assume equal variances) and the ‚Äúpooled‚Äù two-sample t-test (only if equal variances is reasonable). The key assumptions to check are that the observations are independent within and between groups (different students, no pairing, and ideally random sampling/assignment), the outcome is approximately normal in each group or the sample sizes are large enough for the t-test to be robust (look for strong skew/outliers; with small n, normality matters more), and for the pooled version specifically you also need approximately equal population variances (you can compare SDs; if one SD is much larger than the other, use Welch). Also make sure the test scores are on an interval/ratio scale and measured the same way in both classes; if independence is violated (e.g., matched students or repeated measures) you‚Äôd use a paired t-test instead, and if distributions are extremely non-normal with small samples you might consider a nonparametric alternative like the Mann‚ÄìWhitney U test."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:46 - Category: limits_continuity
    ("Can you explain limits + continuity like I‚Äôm not dumb lol‚Äîwhat does it mean for a function to be continuous at x=2 and how do I check it quickly on a piecewise function?", "A limit is just ‚Äúwhat y-value the function is heading toward‚Äù as x gets close to a number, without caring what happens exactly at that number, so lim x‚Üí2 f(x) means the value f(x) approaches when you plug in numbers like 1.9, 1.99, 2.01, 2.1. A function is continuous at x=2 if three things all match: f(2) is actually defined, the limit as x approaches 2 exists (the left-hand limit from values less than 2 equals the right-hand limit from values greater than 2), and that common limit equals the actual value f(2); intuitively, you can draw the graph through x=2 without lifting your pencil, with no hole, jump, or vertical blow-up there. For a piecewise function, the quick check at x=2 is: compute the left-hand limit by using the piece whose rule applies for x<2 and plugging in x=2, compute the right-hand limit by using the piece for x>2 and plugging in x=2, compare them (if they‚Äôre different, it‚Äôs a jump and not continuous; if one doesn‚Äôt settle or goes to infinity, it‚Äôs not continuous), then compute f(2) using the piece that includes x=2 (often marked with ‚â§ or =) and make sure f(2) equals the shared limit; if the left and right limits match but f(2) is missing or different, that‚Äôs a removable discontinuity (a ‚Äúhole‚Äù you could fix by redefining f(2) to equal the limit)."),

