    ("ML basics question for a class project: what‚Äôs the difference between overfitting and underfitting, and how does train/validation split actually help?", "Underfitting and overfitting are two opposite ways a machine learning model can fail to generalize to new data: underfitting happens when the model is too simple (or not trained enough) to capture the real patterns in the training data, so it performs poorly on the training set and also poorly on new data, like trying to fit a straight line to data that clearly curves; overfitting happens when the model is too flexible (or trained too long) and starts ‚Äúmemorizing‚Äù noise and quirks in the training set, so it gets very low training error but worse performance on new data, like learning the exact answers to practice questions instead of the underlying concept. A train/validation split helps because it creates a clean test during development: you train the model only on the training set, then you evaluate it on the validation set, which the model did not see during training, so validation performance is a better estimate of how the model will do on truly unseen data. This comparison lets you diagnose problems: if both training and validation scores are bad, you‚Äôre likely underfitting and may need a more expressive model, better features, or more training; if training is great but validation is much worse, you‚Äôre likely overfitting and may need regularization (like L2/weight decay), a simpler model, early stopping, dropout (for neural nets), or more data/augmentation. In practice, the validation set is also what you use to choose hyperparameters (like model size, regularization strength, learning rate, tree depth, k in k-NN), because picking them based only on training performance would encourage overfitting; after you‚Äôve finalized choices using validation, you ideally do one final evaluation on a separate test set to get an unbiased estimate of real-world performance."),

