    ("APUSH: I‚Äôm confused about the Industrial Revolution in the US‚Äîwhat were the biggest changes for workers and cities, and what inventions mattered most?", "In the United States, the Industrial Revolution (especially from the early 1800s through the late 1800s) shifted work from small farms and artisan shops to wage labor in factories, which meant workers followed the clock, did repetitive tasks, and depended on employers for pay; this created new opportunities for some (including many young women in early textile mills like those at Lowell, Massachusetts) but also brought long hours, low wages, dangerous machinery, child labor, and frequent unemployment during downturns, which is why workers began forming unions and using strikes to demand shorter hours and safer conditions. Cities changed just as dramatically because factories, rail hubs, and ports pulled in huge numbers of people, including immigrants from Ireland and Germany in the mid-1800s and later from southern and eastern Europe, plus migrants from rural America; rapid urban growth produced crowded tenements, pollution, and disease, but also new services and infrastructure like streetcars, water and sewer systems, department stores, and a growing middle class of managers and clerks. The most important inventions and technologies were those that powered factories and connected markets: water-powered and then steam-powered machinery (including textile machines like the spinning jenny and power loom, even when first developed in Britain they became central in U.S. mills), the cotton gin (1793), which made short-staple cotton profitable and helped expand slavery in the South, interchangeable parts and the ‚ÄúAmerican System‚Äù of manufacturing (pioneered in arms production and later used widely), the telegraph (Samuel Morse, 1844) for rapid communication, the railroad and improved steam locomotives for fast, cheap transportation, the Bessemer process and other steelmaking advances that enabled skyscrapers, bridges, and rails, and later electricity and electric lighting (associated with Thomas Edison and others) that extended working hours and transformed urban life. Put together, these changes created a national industrial economy with bigger corporations and mass production, but they also intensified class conflict and made the problems of industrial labor and crowded cities central political issues in the late 1800s."),

