    ("Middle school science: what are the main parts of a cell and what does each part do? I mix up mitochondria and nucleus.", "Most cells have a few main parts that work together like a tiny factory: the cell membrane is the thin ‚Äúskin‚Äù that controls what enters and leaves the cell, the cytoplasm is the jelly-like fluid that fills the cell and is where many reactions happen, and ribosomes are tiny ‚Äúprotein builders‚Äù that make proteins the cell needs. The nucleus is the ‚Äúcontrol center‚Äù because it holds the DNA (the instructions for the cell) and helps direct cell activities; inside it, the nucleolus makes parts of ribosomes. Mitochondria are the ‚Äúpower plants‚Äù because they break down food molecules to release energy the cell can use, making most of the cell‚Äôs ATP (usable energy), so a quick way to remember the difference is: nucleus = instructions and control (DNA), mitochondria = energy production (ATP). In plant cells you also commonly learn extra parts: the cell wall is a stiff outer layer that supports and protects the cell, chloroplasts use sunlight to make sugar by photosynthesis, and a large central vacuole stores water and helps keep the plant cell firm."),

