    ("Middle school: can you explain photosynthesis and what the plant actually needs to do it? My teacher keeps saying ‚Äúglucose‚Äù and I‚Äôm lost.", "Photosynthesis is how plants make their own food: they use energy from sunlight to turn carbon dioxide from the air and water from the soil into a sugar called glucose, and they release oxygen as a leftover product. The plant needs light (captured by chlorophyll in the leaves), water (brought up from the roots), and carbon dioxide (taken in through tiny leaf openings called stomata) to do this; the overall idea is often written as 6 CO2 + 6 H2O + light energy ‚Üí C6H12O6 (glucose) + 6 O2. Glucose is not something the plant ‚Äúuses up‚Äù to do photosynthesis; it is the main product the plant makes, and then the plant uses that glucose as fuel for cellular respiration (to get usable energy), as building material to grow (for example turning it into cellulose for cell walls), or it stores it as starch for later."),

