    ("US History (middle school): what were the main causes of the Civil War? My notes are all over the place.", "The main causes of the American Civil War (1861‚Äì1865) were long-running conflicts between the North and the South over slavery and how much power the federal government should have compared with the states, and these tensions grew worse as the United States expanded westward. Slavery was the central issue because the Southern economy depended heavily on enslaved labor, while many Northerners opposed slavery‚Äôs spread (even when they did not support full equality), so every time a new territory might become a state, people argued over whether it would allow slavery and which side would gain more votes in Congress; major flashpoints included the Missouri Compromise (1820), the Compromise of 1850 and the Fugitive Slave Act, the Kansas‚ÄìNebraska Act (1854) which led to violent fighting in ‚ÄúBleeding Kansas,‚Äù and the Supreme Court‚Äôs Dred Scott decision (1857) which angered many in the North by saying Congress could not ban slavery in the territories. Political compromise broke down as new parties and movements formed, and Abraham Lincoln‚Äôs election in 1860, seen by many white Southerners as a threat to slavery‚Äôs future, led several Southern states to secede (leave the Union) and form the Confederate States of America; the immediate trigger for war came when Confederate forces fired on Fort Sumter in South Carolina in April 1861. In short, the war happened because the nation could not agree on whether slavery would continue and expand, and because the South chose secession to protect slavery and state power, while the North fought to preserve the Union."),

