    ("I‚Äôm in transportation engineering and I‚Äôm stuck: how do you derive the basic traffic flow model (q = kv) and explain what happens at capacity? If you can, walk through a simple example with numbers.", "The basic traffic flow identity q = k¬∑v comes directly from counting how many vehicles occupy a road segment and how fast they move: let k be density in vehicles per unit length (for example veh/km/lane), v be the space-mean speed in length per unit time (for example km/h), and q be flow in vehicles per unit time (veh/h/lane). If you look at a road segment of length L, the expected number of vehicles in it at an instant is N = kL; if those vehicles travel at average speed v, the average time to traverse the segment is T = L/v; flow is vehicles per time, so q = N/T = (kL)/(L/v) = k¬∑v, and the units check out because (veh/km)¬∑(km/h) = veh/h. ‚ÄúCapacity‚Äù is the maximum sustainable flow a facility can carry under prevailing conditions; on a fundamental diagram (flow vs density), as density increases from near zero, flow rises because there are more vehicles, but beyond a critical density kcrit drivers must slow and interact more, so speed drops faster than density rises and flow stops increasing; the peak flow qmax occurs at that critical point and is the capacity, and if density increases further (oversaturation) flow actually decreases and queues form, with speeds collapsing toward zero as density approaches jam density kjam. A simple numeric example: suppose a lane has density k = 20 veh/km and space-mean speed v = 90 km/h, then q = k¬∑v = 20¬∑90 = 1800 veh/h/lane; if demand rises and density increases to k = 30 veh/km but speed drops to v = 70 km/h due to closer spacing, then q = 30¬∑70 = 2100 veh/h/lane, which might be near capacity; if density rises further to k = 60 veh/km and speed falls to v = 25 km/h in congested conditions, then q = 60¬∑25 = 1500 veh/h/lane, showing the post-capacity regime where adding vehicles increases density but reduces throughput, so the excess arrivals accumulate as a growing queue upstream."),

