    ("Can you help me debug this C code? It compiles but segfaults when I try to insert nodes into my linked list. What‚Äôs the most likely pointer mistake and how do I test it step-by-step? (I can paste code after.)", "Yes‚Äîbefore you paste code, the single most common pointer mistake that compiles fine but segfaults during linked-list insertion is dereferencing an uninitialized or invalid pointer, especially the head pointer or the new node pointer (for example, doing new->next = head; when new was never allocated, or doing head->next = ... when head is NULL, or accidentally storing the address of a local stack variable as a node and then using it after the function returns). A close second is allocating the wrong size (malloc(sizeof(Node)) instead of malloc(sizeof(Node))), which can corrupt memory and crash later, and another frequent one is forgetting to set new->next (or setting it to garbage) so traversal eventually follows a junk pointer. To test step-by-step, first add very small, targeted checks and prints around every pointer you touch: right after malloc, verify new != NULL and print the addresses of new, head, and any next pointers you read or write; before dereferencing any pointer p, assert(p != NULL) (or at least if (!p) print a message and return) so you catch the exact first bad dereference; then run under a debugger like gdb by compiling with -g -O0 -Wall -Wextra -Wpedantic and running ‚Äúgdb ./a.out‚Äù, setting a breakpoint at your insert function, stepping line-by-line (step/next), and using ‚Äúprint head‚Äù, ‚Äúprint head‚Äù (only if head isn‚Äôt NULL), ‚Äúprint new‚Äù, and ‚Äúprint new->next‚Äù to watch when a pointer becomes NULL or nonsensical; finally, confirm with sanitizers/Valgrind because they pinpoint the real bug even if the crash happens later: rebuild with -fsanitize=address,undefined and run to get an immediate report like ‚Äúheap-use-after-free‚Äù, ‚Äústack-use-after-return‚Äù, or ‚Äúinvalid read‚Äù, which directly maps to the typical linked-list mistakes (using a freed node, returning a pointer to a local variable, or writing past an under-allocated struct). If you paste your node struct, how you initialize head, and your insert function, I can tell you exactly which line is wrong and what invariant (for example, ‚Äúhead is either NULL or points to a valid Node allocated with malloc, and every node‚Äôs next is either NULL or another valid Node‚Äù) is being violated."),

