    ("I‚Äôm trying to actually understand Big-O, not just memorize it. Why is binary search O(log n) and what changes if the array isn‚Äôt sorted?", "Big-O describes how the running time grows as the input size n grows, focusing on the dominant trend rather than exact seconds. Binary search is O(log n) because each comparison lets you throw away half of the remaining search space: you look at the middle element, decide whether the target must be on the left or right (which only works if the array is sorted), and then repeat on just that half. After 1 step you have at most n/2 candidates left, after 2 steps n/4, after k steps n/2^k; you stop when the remaining range is size 1, so you want n/2^k ‚âà 1, which means 2^k ‚âà n and therefore k ‚âà log2(n). That k is the number of iterations/comparisons in the worst case, so the time grows proportionally to log n (the base doesn‚Äôt matter in Big-O because changing bases only multiplies by a constant). If the array isn‚Äôt sorted, the ‚Äúgo left or right‚Äù decision is no longer valid because the target could be anywhere regardless of how it compares to the middle element, so you can‚Äôt safely discard half the elements; without extra structure you generally must check elements one by one until you find the target or exhaust the array, which is O(n) time. You can regain fast searching by sorting first, but sorting costs time (typically O(n log n)), after which each binary search is O(log n), so sorting is worth it when you‚Äôll do many searches on the same data, while for a single one-off search on unsorted data a linear scan is usually the right mental model."),

