    ("I have a stats homework question: a random variable X ~ Normal(Œº=50, œÉ=10). What‚Äôs P(X > 65) and how do I do it using z-scores?", "To find P(X > 65) when X ~ Normal(Œº = 50, œÉ = 10), convert 65 to a z-score using z = (x ‚àí Œº)/œÉ: z = (65 ‚àí 50)/10 = 1.5, so P(X > 65) = P(Z > 1.5) where Z ~ Standard Normal. From the standard normal table (or a calculator), Œ¶(1.5) = P(Z ‚â§ 1.5) ‚âà 0.9332, so P(Z > 1.5) = 1 ‚àí 0.9332 = 0.0668, meaning there‚Äôs about a 6.68% chance X exceeds 65; a quick sanity check is that 65 is 1.5 standard deviations above the mean, so the probability should be small but not tiny, which matches 0.0668."),

