    ("In abstract algebra, I don‚Äôt get why Z/nZ is a field only when n is prime. Can you explain with a concrete counterexample for n=6?", "In Z/nZ you can always add, subtract, and multiply classes mod n, but to be a field you also need every nonzero class to have a multiplicative inverse (so you can ‚Äúdivide‚Äù by any nonzero element). The key fact is that a class [a] has an inverse mod n exactly when gcd(a, n) = 1; if n is prime p, then every nonzero a = 1,2,‚Ä¶,p‚àí1 is automatically coprime to p, so every nonzero class is invertible and Z/pZ is a field. For a concrete counterexample with n = 6, look at the nonzero element [2] in Z/6Z: gcd(2,6) = 2, so it cannot have an inverse, and you can see this directly because 2¬∑1 ‚â° 2, 2¬∑2 ‚â° 4, 2¬∑3 ‚â° 0, 2¬∑4 ‚â° 2, 2¬∑5 ‚â° 4 (mod 6), so 2¬∑k is never congruent to 1 mod 6, meaning there is no [k] with [2][k] = [1]. Equivalently, Z/6Z has zero divisors, for example [2] ‚â† [0] and [3] ‚â† [0] but [2][3] = [6] = [0], and a field can‚Äôt have zero divisors because if ab = 0 with a ‚â† 0 then multiplying by a‚àí1 would force b = 0."),

