    ("Topology intro question: what does it mean for a set to be open vs closed in R, and why can a set be both? A couple examples would help.", "In the real line R with its usual topology (the one coming from the standard distance), a set U is called open if for every point x in U you can move a little bit left and right and still stay inside U, meaning there exists some radius r > 0 such that the entire interval (x ‚àí r, x + r) is contained in U; for example (0,1) is open because around any point strictly between 0 and 1 you can fit a small open interval that doesn‚Äôt reach the endpoints, and R itself is open because any small interval around any real number stays in R. A set F is called closed if it contains all its limit points (equivalently, if whenever a sequence of points in F converges in R, its limit is also in F), or, equivalently again, if its complement R \\ F is open; for example [0,1] is closed because any sequence in [0,1] that converges has a limit still between 0 and 1 inclusive, and {2} is closed because its complement is open (around any point not equal to 2 you can find a small interval avoiding 2). A set can be both open and closed (often called clopen) because ‚Äúopen‚Äù and ‚Äúclosed‚Äù are not opposites; the true opposite of ‚Äúopen‚Äù is ‚Äúnot open,‚Äù and the true opposite of ‚Äúclosed‚Äù is ‚Äúnot closed,‚Äù and in R the only clopen sets are the empty set ‚àÖ and the whole space R: ‚àÖ is open (the condition ‚Äúfor every x in ‚àÖ‚Äù is vacuously true) and closed (it contains all of its limit points, and its complement is R which is open), and R is open and closed because its complement is ‚àÖ which is open. This happens because R is connected, so there is no nontrivial subset that can be separated from the rest by a ‚Äúgap‚Äù; in other spaces that are not connected, like R with the point 0 removed, the set (‚àí‚àû,0) is both open and closed in that space because it is open there and its complement (0,‚àû) is also open there."),

