    ("Surveying homework: if I have two known points and measured angles/distances to a third point, how do I compute the coordinates of the unknown point? I‚Äôm confused about the trig setup.", "To compute the coordinates of an unknown point P from two known control points A(xA,yA) and B(xB,yB), you first form the baseline vector AB = (xB‚àíxA, yB‚àíyA) and its length c = sqrt((xB‚àíxA)^2 + (yB‚àíyA)^2), plus the baseline bearing (direction) Œ∏AB = atan2(yB‚àíyA, xB‚àíxA). Then use whichever measurements you actually have: if you measured distances AP = a and BP = b (trilateration), the triangle sides are a, b, c, so the angle at A between AB and AP is Œ± = arccos((a^2 + c^2 ‚àí b^2)/(2ac)); the direction from A to P is Œ∏AP = Œ∏AB ¬± Œ± (the ¬± gives the two mirror-image intersection points on either side of line AB). Finally compute P from A by xP = xA + a cos(Œ∏AP), yP = yA + a sin(Œ∏AP), and you can check by verifying that the computed distance from P to B equals b (within tolerance). If instead you measured angles at A and B to P (triangulation), let Œ± be the interior angle at A from AB to AP and Œ≤ be the interior angle at B from BA to BP (make sure they are interior angles of triangle ABP, not arbitrary instrument circle readings), then the third angle is Œ≥ = œÄ ‚àí Œ± ‚àí Œ≤ and by the law of sines AP = a = c sin(Œ≤)/sin(Œ≥) and BP = b = c sin(Œ±)/sin(Œ≥); once you have a, proceed exactly as above with Œ∏AP = Œ∏AB ¬± Œ± and xP,yP from A. A common trig setup mistake is mixing up which angle is referenced to which line: Œ± must be the angle at A between the baseline direction A‚ÜíB and the sightline A‚ÜíP, so if your instrument gives an absolute azimuth to P, you can set Œ∏AP directly and skip the ¬±, but if it gives a deflection/right angle from the baseline, convert it to a signed angle relative to Œ∏AB and keep track of whether P lies to the left or right of AB (that choice resolves the two-solution ambiguity)."),

