    ("What are the parts of a cell and what does the nucleus do? I have a quiz tomorrow and I‚Äôm kinda lost.", "Most cells have a few main parts you should know: the cell membrane is the thin ‚Äúskin‚Äù that surrounds the cell and controls what enters and leaves; the cytoplasm is the jelly-like fluid inside where many chemical reactions happen and where the organelles sit; and organelles are the tiny ‚Äúcell machines‚Äù that do specific jobs, like mitochondria that release energy from food (often taught as making ATP), ribosomes that build proteins, the endoplasmic reticulum and Golgi apparatus that help make, fold, and package proteins and lipids, lysosomes that break down waste (common in animal cells), and vacuoles that store water and materials (a very large central vacuole is typical in plant cells). Plant cells also have a rigid cell wall for support and protection and chloroplasts for photosynthesis, while animal cells do not. The nucleus is like the cell‚Äôs control center because it contains the DNA (the instructions for how the cell is built and how it works); it protects that DNA and uses it to direct cell activities by controlling which genes are turned on to make specific proteins, and it also helps with cell division when the cell copies and organizes DNA so each new cell gets the right genetic information. If you remember one sentence for your quiz, it‚Äôs this: the nucleus stores the cell‚Äôs DNA and uses it to run the cell by directing protein-making and growth."),

