    ("AP Physics question: using the work-energy theorem, how do I find the speed of a block after it slides down a ramp with friction? Can you set it up symbolically?", "Use the work‚Äìenergy theorem in the form Kf ‚àí Ki = Wnet, where the net work along the ramp comes from gravity (positive, because it helps the motion) and kinetic friction (negative, because it opposes the motion), while the normal force does zero work because it is perpendicular to the displacement. If the block of mass m slides a distance L down an incline at angle Œ∏, starting with speed v0, then Ki = (1/2)mv0^2 and Kf = (1/2)mv^2, the work by gravity is Wg = mgL sinŒ∏ (equivalently mgŒîh with Œîh = L sinŒ∏), and the work by kinetic friction is Wf = ‚àífk L = ‚àíŒºk N L = ‚àíŒºk (mg cosŒ∏)L. Putting this together gives (1/2)mv^2 ‚àí (1/2)mv0^2 = mgL sinŒ∏ ‚àí Œºk mgL cosŒ∏, so v^2 = v0^2 + 2gL(sinŒ∏ ‚àí Œºk cosŒ∏), and if it starts from rest then v = sqrt(2gL(sinŒ∏ ‚àí Œºk cosŒ∏)); this also shows the physical condition to actually speed up while sliding is sinŒ∏ > Œºk cosŒ∏ (otherwise friction is strong enough that it won‚Äôt accelerate, and it may not slide at all if static friction can hold it)."),

