    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:54 - Category: human_body_systems
    ("what is a body system? like what does the digestive system do and why do we need it?", "A body system is a group of organs and tissues that work together to do an important job that keeps you alive and healthy, kind of like a team where each player has a role but they all aim for the same goal. The digestive system‚Äôs job is to take the food and drinks you consume, break them down into tiny nutrients your body can absorb, and then get rid of what your body can‚Äôt use; you need it because your cells require nutrients for energy, growth, and repair. Digestion starts in the mouth where teeth chew and saliva begins breaking down food, then the esophagus moves it to the stomach where acids and enzymes help break it into a soupy mixture, the small intestine finishes digestion and absorbs most nutrients into the bloodstream (with help from the pancreas, which adds digestive enzymes, and the liver and gallbladder, which make and store bile to help digest fats), and the large intestine absorbs water and forms stool so waste can leave the body. Without a working digestive system, even if you ate plenty of food, your body wouldn‚Äôt be able to absorb enough nutrients and water to power your organs, build strong muscles and bones, and stay healthy."),

