    ("What‚Äôs the difference between potential energy and kinetic energy? My teacher mentioned the work-energy theorem and I‚Äôm lost.", "Kinetic energy is the energy an object has because it is moving, and for ordinary speeds it equals KE = (1/2)mv^2, so if you double the speed the kinetic energy becomes four times larger; potential energy is stored energy due to position or configuration, with gravitational potential energy near Earth often written as U = mgh (higher height h means more stored energy) and spring potential energy as U = (1/2)kx^2 (more stretch or compression x means more stored energy). The work-energy theorem connects force, motion, and energy by saying the net work done on an object equals the change in its kinetic energy: W_net = ŒîKE; ‚Äúwork‚Äù here means a force causing displacement, W = Fd cos(Œ∏), so if the net force does positive work the object speeds up (KE increases), and if it does negative work the object slows down (KE decreases). Potential energy fits in because many forces are conservative (like gravity and ideal springs), meaning the work they do can be accounted for by changes in potential energy: W_conservative = ‚àíŒîU, so combining this with the work-energy theorem gives a very useful form: ŒîKE + ŒîU = W_nonconservative (where nonconservative work includes things like friction or a motor), and in the special case with no nonconservative work you get conservation of mechanical energy, KE + U = constant; for example, a ball dropped from rest converts gravitational potential energy mgh into kinetic energy as it falls, and the work done by gravity equals the increase in KE while the potential energy decreases by the same amount."),

