    ("If I launch a ball at an angle, how do I figure out how far it goes? We‚Äôre doing projectile motion and I‚Äôm confused.", "To find how far a ball goes when you launch it at an angle (its horizontal range), you break the launch velocity into components and use the fact that gravity only changes the vertical motion. If the ball is launched from and lands at the same height and you ignore air resistance, start with the launch speed v0 and angle Œ∏: the horizontal speed is vx = v0 cos(Œ∏) and the vertical speed is vy = v0 sin(Œ∏). The time in the air comes from the vertical motion: y(t) = vy t ‚àí (1/2) g t^2, and setting y = 0 again (landing back at the start height) gives t = 0 or t = 2vy/g, so the flight time is T = 2v0 sin(Œ∏)/g. The horizontal distance is then range R = vx T = (v0 cos(Œ∏)) (2v0 sin(Œ∏)/g) = (v0^2 sin(2Œ∏))/g, where g ‚âà 9.8 m/s^2. This formula also shows a key idea: for a fixed speed, the maximum range happens at 45¬∞ because sin(2Œ∏) is biggest when 2Œ∏ = 90¬∞. If the ball lands at a different height than it was launched, you can‚Äôt use the simple range formula; instead solve the vertical equation y(t) = y0 + v0 sin(Œ∏) t ‚àí (1/2) g t^2 for the landing time T at the landing height, then plug that into x(t) = x0 + v0 cos(Œ∏) t to get R = v0 cos(Œ∏) ¬∑ T."),

