    ("What‚Äôs the carbon cycle, and how is it connected to climate change? I need it for an environmental science poster.", "The carbon cycle is the natural movement of carbon atoms through Earth‚Äôs major ‚Äústorage places‚Äù (the atmosphere, oceans, living things, soils, and rocks) and the processes that move carbon between them. Plants pull carbon dioxide (CO2) from the air during photosynthesis to build sugars and tissues, animals and microbes return carbon to the air as CO2 through respiration and decomposition, and some carbon is stored longer in soils, forests, and the ocean (where CO2 dissolves and can become bicarbonate and carbonate). Over very long timescales, carbon can be locked into sediments and rocks (like limestone) and later released by weathering and volcanoes; events like wildfires also quickly move stored carbon back to the atmosphere. The carbon cycle connects to climate change because CO2 and methane (CH4) are greenhouse gases that trap heat, and human activities are adding extra carbon to the atmosphere faster than natural processes can remove it: burning coal, oil, and natural gas releases carbon that was stored underground for millions of years, deforestation reduces the number of trees that can absorb CO2 and often releases carbon from wood and soils, and agriculture and fossil fuel production can increase methane. As greenhouse gas levels rise, Earth warms, which can further change the carbon cycle by increasing wildfire risk, thawing permafrost that releases CO2 and methane, and stressing forests, while the ocean absorbs some of the extra CO2 but becomes more acidic (ocean acidification), affecting marine life. In short, the carbon cycle is Earth‚Äôs carbon ‚Äúrecycling system,‚Äù and climate change happens when humans tip the balance by adding more greenhouse gases than the cycle can naturally store or remove."),

