    ("We‚Äôre learning DNA replication‚Äîcan you explain what helicase and DNA polymerase do without making it super confusing?", "Think of DNA like a twisted ladder with two matching sides stuck together; during replication, helicase is the ‚Äúunzipper‚Äù that opens the ladder by breaking the weak bonds between the base pairs, separating the two strands so they can be copied. Once the strands are open, DNA polymerase is the ‚Äúbuilder‚Äù that makes the new DNA by reading each old strand as a template and adding the correct matching DNA letters (A pairs with T, and C pairs with G) to grow a new strand. A key detail is that DNA polymerase can only add new letters onto the end of a growing strand (it can‚Äôt start from nothing), so the cell gives it a small starter piece first, and then polymerase keeps extending from there to produce an accurate copy."),

