    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 02:58 - Category: congress
    ("In the U.S. government, what‚Äôs the difference between the House and the Senate? I always mix them up.", "The House of Representatives and the Senate are the two chambers of the U.S. Congress, and they share the job of making federal laws, but they‚Äôre built to represent people in different ways. The House is designed to represent the population: it has 435 voting members divided among the states based on population, House members serve 2-year terms, and each representative speaks for a smaller district within a state, which tends to make the House more closely tied to current public opinion. The Senate is designed to represent the states equally: it has 100 members total, with 2 senators from each state no matter the state‚Äôs size, senators serve 6-year terms with elections staggered so only about one-third are up at a time, which makes the Senate more stable and slower-changing. Both chambers must pass the exact same bill for it to go to the President, but each has special powers: the House starts ‚Äúmoney bills‚Äù (taxing and spending bills) and can impeach federal officials (formally accuse them), while the Senate confirms many presidential appointments (like Cabinet members and federal judges), approves treaties by a two-thirds vote, and holds impeachment trials to decide whether to remove an impeached official. A quick memory trick is ‚ÄúHouse = population and shorter terms; Senate = states and longer terms,‚Äù and ‚ÄúHouse accuses, Senate decides‚Äù for impeachment."),

