    ("What does the Supreme Court do, and how do they decide cases? My teacher mentioned \'judicial review\' and I didn‚Äôt get it.", "The Supreme Court is the highest court in the United States, and its main job is to interpret the Constitution and make final decisions about what the law means when people disagree, especially in important cases about rights, federal laws, or conflicts between states or between a state and the federal government. Most of the time the Court does not hold a new trial with witnesses; instead, it reviews what happened in lower courts and reads written arguments called briefs from both sides (and sometimes from other interested groups), then the justices may hear oral arguments where lawyers answer the justices‚Äô questions, and afterward the justices meet privately, vote, and write an opinion explaining the decision, with the majority opinion becoming the official ruling and any justices who disagree writing dissents. Judicial review is the power of the Supreme Court (and other courts) to decide whether a law or government action violates the Constitution, and if it does, the Court can declare it unconstitutional, meaning it cannot be enforced; this idea was established in the 1803 case Marbury v. Madison and is important because it helps keep Congress and the President within the limits set by the Constitution."),

