    ("In AP Calc, how do you find the limit of (x^2 9)/(x 3) as x approaches 3? I know it‚Äôs not just plugging it in.", "When you plug in x = 3 you get (3^2 ‚àí 9)/(3 ‚àí 3) = 0/0, which is an indeterminate form, so you need to simplify first. Factor the numerator as a difference of squares: x^2 ‚àí 9 = (x ‚àí 3)(x + 3), so (x^2 ‚àí 9)/(x ‚àí 3) = (x ‚àí 3)(x + 3)/(x ‚àí 3) = x + 3 for all x ‚â† 3. Now take the limit by evaluating the simplified expression at x = 3: lim(x‚Üí3) (x + 3) = 3 + 3 = 6, and a quick check with nearby values like x = 2.9 gives about 5.9 and x = 3.1 gives about 6.1, confirming the limit is 6."),

