    ("Precalc help: what does it mean for a function to be continuous at x = 2? And can you do an example with a piecewise function?", "A function f(x) is continuous at x = 2 if three things are all true: first, f(2) is defined (you can actually plug in x = 2 and get a real value); second, the limit as x approaches 2 exists (the left-hand limit as x approaches 2 from values less than 2 equals the right-hand limit as x approaches 2 from values greater than 2); and third, that common limit equals the actual function value, meaning lim(x‚Üí2) f(x) = f(2). Here‚Äôs a clear piecewise example: define f(x) = x + 2 for x < 2, and f(x) = 2x for x ‚â• 2; then the left-hand limit at 2 is lim(x‚Üí2‚àí)(x+2) = 4, the right-hand limit at 2 is lim(x‚Üí2+)(2x) = 4, and f(2) uses the x ‚â• 2 rule so f(2) = 2¬∑2 = 4, so all three conditions match and the function is continuous at x = 2. For a contrasting example that is not continuous, define g(x) = x + 2 for x < 2, and g(x) = 2x + 1 for x ‚â• 2; then the left-hand limit at 2 is 4 but the right-hand limit is 5, so the limit does not exist and g is not continuous at x = 2 (this is a jump discontinuity)."),

