    ("Stats project: I have heights (in inches) from 28 students. What descriptive statistics should I report, and how do I explain what the standard deviation means in plain English?", "For a set of 28 student heights (in inches), you should report the sample size (n = 28) and clearly state the unit (inches), then summarize the center with the mean (average height) and the median (the middle height when ordered), summarize spread with the standard deviation (typical distance from the mean) and the range (max ‚àí min), and also include the five-number summary: minimum, first quartile (Q1), median, third quartile (Q3), and maximum; from that you can also report the interquartile range (IQR = Q3 ‚àí Q1), which describes the spread of the middle 50% and is especially helpful if there are outliers. It‚Äôs also good practice to mention the shape of the distribution (roughly symmetric, skewed left/right, or having outliers) and to show a simple graph such as a histogram or boxplot, because the graph helps readers see whether the mean and standard deviation are appropriate summaries (they work best when the data are roughly symmetric without extreme outliers). In plain English, the standard deviation tells you how much students‚Äô heights typically differ from the average height: if the mean height is, say, 66 inches and the standard deviation is 3 inches, then a ‚Äútypical‚Äù student is about 3 inches above or below 66 inches, and many students will fall within about 66 ¬± 3 inches (roughly 63 to 69) with fewer students farther away; a larger standard deviation means heights are more spread out, and a smaller standard deviation means heights are more similar to each other."),

