    ("I‚Äôm trying to understand machine learning basics for a CS club. What‚Äôs the difference between training vs testing data, and what is overfitting in plain English?", "Training data is the set of examples you let the model learn from: it repeatedly looks at those inputs (and usually the correct labels) and adjusts its internal ‚Äúknobs‚Äù so it gets better at predicting the training answers, like a student practicing with a worksheet that has solutions. Testing data is a separate set you keep hidden until the end and use only to check how well the finished model performs on new, unseen examples, like a final exam that tells you whether the student really learned the material rather than just memorizing the practice sheet. Overfitting is what happens when the model learns the training data too specifically, including noise and quirks that don‚Äôt generalize, so it scores very high on training examples but noticeably worse on the test set; in plain English, it‚Äôs like memorizing the exact questions and wording from the practice worksheet instead of learning the underlying concept, so you struggle when the exam asks the same idea in a slightly different way."),

