    ("For civics: what does the Supreme Court actually do, and how does a case even get there? Please keep it straightforward.", "The U.S. Supreme Court is the highest court in the federal system, and its main job is to interpret the Constitution and federal law by deciding real legal disputes, especially when people argue that a law or government action violates the Constitution or when different lower courts have reached different answers on the same legal question; when it rules, its decision sets a nationwide precedent that lower courts must follow, and it can uphold or strike down laws or government actions that conflict with the Constitution. A case usually gets to the Supreme Court after it has been decided in lower courts, most often starting in a federal district court, then going to a U.S. court of appeals, and then one side asks the Supreme Court to review the decision by filing a petition for a writ of certiorari; the Court chooses only a small fraction of requests, and it typically takes cases that raise important constitutional issues, involve federal law, or resolve splits where different appeals courts disagree. A smaller number of cases can come from a state‚Äôs highest court when a federal constitutional or federal-law issue is involved, and in rare situations the Court has ‚Äúoriginal jurisdiction‚Äù where a case can start there (for example, certain disputes between states), but most of the time the Court is not a place you automatically get to‚Äîit is a place you ask to review a case, and at least four of the nine justices must vote to take it."),

