    ("We‚Äôre doing the Civil War and I don‚Äôt get the difference between the Union‚Äôs main goals vs the Confederacy‚Äôs. Can you summarize it without sounding like a textbook?", "The Union (the United States government led by Abraham Lincoln) mainly fought to keep the country together, because Southern states were trying to leave and form a separate nation; at the start, Lincoln‚Äôs top priority was saving the Union, and as the war went on the Union also made ending slavery a central goal, especially after the Emancipation Proclamation in 1863 and then pushing for the 13th Amendment. The Confederacy (the breakaway Southern states) fought to become an independent country and to protect the system their economy and society were built on, which included slavery, and they argued that each state should be able to make its own decisions without the federal government stopping it. In everyday terms, the Union‚Äôs goal was ‚Äúwe‚Äôre staying one country,‚Äù while the Confederacy‚Äôs goal was ‚Äúwe‚Äôre leaving to run our own country our way,‚Äù and that ‚Äúway‚Äù was tightly tied to keeping slavery legal."),

