    ("What was the Cold War ‚Äúin one paragraph‚Äù and why were people so scared of nuclear war?", "The Cold War was a long period of intense rivalry after World War II, roughly from 1947 to 1991, when the United States and its allies (generally capitalist democracies) and the Soviet Union and its allies (communist one-party states) competed for global influence without fighting each other directly in a full-scale war; instead they used propaganda, spying, military buildups, nuclear threats, and ‚Äúproxy wars‚Äù in places like Korea, Vietnam, and Afghanistan, while crises such as the Berlin Blockade and the Cuban Missile Crisis brought the world close to open conflict. People were so scared of nuclear war because both superpowers built huge arsenals of atomic and hydrogen bombs and the missiles and bombers to deliver them, meaning a war could begin with little warning and kill millions in minutes, and because the strategy of ‚Äúmutually assured destruction‚Äù meant that if one side launched nuclear weapons the other could still retaliate, turning a conflict into a civilization-threatening catastrophe with long-term effects like radioactive fallout and potential global climate disruption. This fear shaped everyday life, leading to air-raid sirens, ‚Äúduck and cover‚Äù drills, fallout shelters, and constant anxiety that a political crisis or accident could trigger an unstoppable chain of nuclear escalation."),

