    ("Geometry help: a triangle has legs 9 and 12. What‚Äôs the hypotenuse? Also how do you know when to use the Pythagorean theorem?", "If a triangle has ‚Äúlegs,‚Äù that means it‚Äôs a right triangle and the legs are the two sides that meet to form the 90¬∞ angle, so you can use the Pythagorean theorem a^2 + b^2 = c^2 where c is the hypotenuse (the side opposite the right angle and the longest side). With legs 9 and 12, you get c^2 = 9^2 + 12^2 = 81 + 144 = 225, so c = ‚àö225 = 15, and you can verify it by checking that 15^2 = 225 matches 81 + 144. You use the Pythagorean theorem specifically when you know (or are told) the triangle is a right triangle, or you can identify a right angle in a diagram, and you want to find a missing side length (or check whether three side lengths could make a right triangle); if the triangle is not right, you would need a different method like the Law of Cosines."),

