    ("I‚Äôm in a college stats class and I‚Äôm stuck: when do you use a t-test vs a chi-square test vs ANOVA? I keep choosing the wrong one.", "Use the test that matches your outcome (response) variable type and how many groups/variables you‚Äôre comparing: t-tests and ANOVA are for a quantitative (numeric) outcome like height, exam score, or blood pressure, while chi-square tests are for categorical outcomes like yes/no, brand A/B/C, or political party. Use a t-test when you want to compare means between exactly two conditions: an independent-samples t-test compares two separate groups (mean score in Class A vs Class B), and a paired t-test compares two measurements on the same people or matched pairs (before vs after a program, or twins). Use ANOVA when you‚Äôre comparing means across three or more groups (mean score across majors A, B, C, D); it tests whether at least one group mean differs, and if it‚Äôs significant you typically follow with post-hoc comparisons (like Tukey) to see which groups differ; note that with exactly two groups, one-way ANOVA and the independent t-test give the same p-value, so the ‚Äúwrong test‚Äù is usually about recognizing the number of groups and the design (paired vs independent). Use a chi-square test when your data are counts in categories: chi-square goodness-of-fit checks whether one categorical variable‚Äôs observed counts match an expected distribution (for example, are M&M colors in the advertised proportions?), and chi-square test of independence checks whether two categorical variables are associated (for example, is voting preference related to gender in a contingency table); if expected cell counts are very small (a common rule is any expected count under 5), Fisher‚Äôs exact test is often preferred. A quick decision trick is: ask ‚ÄúAm I comparing means of a numeric outcome?‚Äù then it‚Äôs t-test (2 groups) or ANOVA (3+ groups); ask ‚ÄúAm I comparing proportions/relationships between categories using counts?‚Äù then it‚Äôs chi-square; and always check assumptions: independence of observations, roughly normal residuals and similar variances for t/ANOVA (or use Welch‚Äôs t/ANOVA if variances differ), and adequate expected counts for chi-square."),

