    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 03:04 - Category: statistical_analysis
    ("In stats, when should I use a t-test vs ANOVA vs chi-square? My professor just says ‚Äúdepends on the variables‚Äù and I‚Äôm confused.", "Use the test that matches your outcome (dependent) variable type and how many groups you‚Äôre comparing. Use a t-test when your outcome is quantitative (a number like height, test score, blood pressure) and you want to compare the mean between exactly two groups; if the two groups are independent (e.g., treatment vs control with different people) use an independent-samples t-test, and if the same people are measured twice (e.g., before vs after) use a paired t-test. Use ANOVA when your outcome is quantitative and you want to compare mean differences across three or more groups (e.g., mean exam score across 4 teaching methods); one-way ANOVA is for one categorical grouping variable, factorial ANOVA is for two or more categorical factors, and repeated-measures ANOVA is for the same subjects measured under multiple conditions. Use chi-square when your variables are categorical (counts in categories, like yes/no, smoker/non-smoker, party affiliation) and you‚Äôre testing whether proportions differ: chi-square test of independence checks whether two categorical variables are associated (e.g., smoking status by gender), and chi-square goodness-of-fit checks whether one categorical variable‚Äôs observed counts match an expected distribution (e.g., are colors equally common). A helpful shortcut is: numeric outcome and 2 groups means t-test; numeric outcome and 3+ groups means ANOVA; categorical outcome or two categorical variables means chi-square, and in all cases you should also check assumptions (independence of observations; for t-test/ANOVA roughly normal residuals and similar variances, with Welch‚Äôs t-test/Welch‚Äôs ANOVA as common alternatives when variances differ)."),

