    ("For machine learning basics: what‚Äôs the intuitive difference between training loss and validation loss, and what does it mean when validation loss starts going up?", "Training loss is the error your model makes on the same data it is allowed to learn from, so it measures how well the model is fitting the training set and it usually goes down as the optimizer adjusts the weights to better match those examples. Validation loss is the error on a separate ‚Äúheld-out‚Äù set that the model never uses to update its weights, so it estimates how well the model will generalize to new, unseen data rather than how well it can memorize the training set. When validation loss starts going up while training loss keeps going down, it typically means overfitting: the model is starting to learn training-specific quirks and noise that don‚Äôt transfer, so its real-world performance is getting worse; common responses are to stop training at the lowest validation loss (early stopping), add regularization like dropout or weight decay, reduce model complexity, or get more/cleaner training data."),

