    ("Computer architecture question: what‚Äôs the real difference between a cache miss and a page fault? Like what parts of the system are involved and why is one so much slower?", "A cache miss and a page fault are both ‚Äúthe data wasn‚Äôt where we hoped it would be‚Äù events, but they happen at very different layers of the memory system and trigger very different machinery. A cache miss is handled entirely within the CPU‚Äôs memory hierarchy: the core looks for a cache line (typically 64 bytes) in L1, then L2, then the last-level cache, and if it‚Äôs not there it fetches it from DRAM via the memory controller, filling the caches along the way; the program usually keeps running with the load just taking longer (or the core stalls waiting), and the operating system is not involved. A page fault happens at the virtual-memory layer: the CPU‚Äôs MMU translates a virtual address using page tables (with help from the TLB), and if the translation says the page is not currently mapped with the needed permissions or not present in physical memory, the CPU raises a page-fault exception, traps into the OS kernel, and the OS must resolve it (for a ‚Äúminor‚Äù fault it may just create/update page-table entries or map an already-in-RAM page; for a ‚Äúmajor‚Äù fault it must read the page from secondary storage like an SSD/HDD, possibly evicting another page, then update page tables and restart the faulting instruction). The speed difference comes from both the distance traveled and the work required: a cache miss might cost on the order of a few cycles (L1 hit) to tens of cycles (L2) to maybe ~50‚Äì200+ cycles for a DRAM access depending on the system, while a page fault includes an expensive privilege-level switch, kernel bookkeeping, and in the worst case a disk/SSD I/O that takes microseconds to milliseconds, which is millions of CPU cycles; that‚Äôs why cache misses are ‚Äúslow‚Äù but common and expected, while page faults are comparatively rare and can be catastrophically slow when they require going to storage. A good mental model is that a cache miss is ‚Äúthe data is in RAM but not in the CPU‚Äôs fast on-chip copies,‚Äù whereas a major page fault is ‚Äúthe data isn‚Äôt even in RAM right now, so the OS has to go fetch it and fix the mapping before the CPU can continue.‚Äù"),

