    ("I don‚Äôt get the Pythagorean theorem‚Äîcan you explain what a^2 + b^2 = c^2 actually means with a real example?", "The Pythagorean theorem is a rule that only works for a right triangle, which is a triangle with one 90-degree corner, and it says that if the two shorter sides that make the right angle are a and b, and the longest side across from the right angle (the hypotenuse) is c, then the area of a square built on side a plus the area of a square built on side b equals the area of a square built on side c, written as a^2 + b^2 = c^2. For a real example, imagine a ladder leaning against a wall: the distance from the wall to the bottom of the ladder is 3 feet (a = 3) and the height up the wall is 4 feet (b = 4), so the ladder length is c, and the theorem gives 3^2 + 4^2 = c^2, which is 9 + 16 = 25, so c = 5 feet. You can check it makes sense because the ladder (5 feet) must be longer than either the 3-foot distance on the ground or the 4-foot height on the wall, and this relationship lets you find a missing side any time you know the other two in a right triangle."),

