    ("What does the Supreme Court actually do day-to-day, and how does a case even get there?", "Day to day, the Supreme Court is less like a courtroom that is constantly holding trials and more like a small group of judges running a very selective review process: the justices and their law clerks read thousands of filings, study the records and legal arguments from lower courts, meet in private conferences to decide which cases to hear and later how to rule, hear oral arguments in a limited number of cases during the Court‚Äôs term (lawyers answer rapid-fire questions rather than presenting witnesses), and then spend weeks or months writing, editing, and negotiating opinions that explain the Court‚Äôs reasoning and set binding precedent on federal law and the U.S. Constitution; they also handle emergency requests and short orders, such as requests to pause a lower-court ruling while an appeal is pending, which can happen on a fast timeline. A case usually gets to the Court only after it has been decided below: most commonly it starts in a federal district court, goes to a U.S. court of appeals, and then the losing side files a petition for a writ of certiorari asking the Supreme Court to review it, or it comes from a state‚Äôs highest court if the decision turns on a federal constitutional or federal-law question; the Court is not required to take most cases and accepts only a small fraction, typically choosing ones that raise nationally important issues, resolve conflicts among different appellate courts (‚Äúcircuit splits‚Äù), or correct serious legal errors, and it takes a case when at least four justices vote to grant certiorari (the ‚Äúrule of four‚Äù). In a narrow set of situations the Court has original jurisdiction, meaning the case can begin there‚Äîmost famously certain disputes between states‚Äîbut even then the Court often appoints a special master to gather facts, because the Supreme Court‚Äôs main everyday work is deciding legal questions on appeal and explaining the rule that other courts must follow."),

