    ("What does \'mean\' and \'median\' mean? We did it with candy counts and I got mixed up.", "Mean and median are two ways to describe the ‚Äútypical‚Äù number in a set of data, like candy counts. The mean is the average: add up all the candy counts and divide by how many people there are; for example, if four people have 2, 3, 3, and 12 candies, the mean is (2+3+3+12) √∑ 4 = 20 √∑ 4 = 5. The median is the middle value when you put the counts in order from least to greatest; in that same ordered list 2, 3, 3, 12, the median is 3, and if there are two middle numbers (like 2, 3, 8, 12), you average those two to get the median (3+8) √∑ 2 = 5.5. A helpful way to remember the difference is that the mean can get pulled up or down by one unusually big or small candy count (like the 12), while the median usually stays closer to what most people have, so it‚Äôs often better when there‚Äôs an ‚Äúoutlier‚Äù or someone with way more candy than everyone else."),

