    ("I need a science fair experiment about plants or water that I can do at home. What should I test and how do I measure it?", "Try a simple, high-quality plant experiment: test how salt in water affects seed germination and early growth. Your question can be ‚ÄúHow does salt concentration in watering water change the percent of seeds that sprout and how fast seedlings grow?‚Äù Gather the same kind of seeds (radish or bean work well), identical cups or small pots, paper towels or potting soil, a ruler with millimeters, measuring spoons, and table salt; make three to five salt levels such as 0% (plain water), 0.5% (about 1/2 teaspoon salt in 1 cup/240 mL water), 1% (1 teaspoon per cup), and 2% (2 teaspoons per cup), and label everything clearly. Put the same number of seeds in each cup (for example 10 seeds per cup) and make at least three cups per salt level so results are more reliable; keep all other variables the same (same light, same temperature, same container, same amount of water added each day, and start all seeds at the same time). Measure germination by counting how many seeds sprout each day for a week and calculate percent germination as (number sprouted √∑ total seeds) √ó 100, then measure growth by using the ruler to record seedling height (soil line to top) in millimeters each day or every other day for 10‚Äì14 days; you can also measure root length at the end by gently rinsing roots and measuring the longest root. Record your data in a table with day number, salt level, number sprouted, and average height, then graph salt level on the x-axis and percent germination or average height on the y-axis to see the trend; a strong conclusion explains what happened, uses your numbers (for example, ‚Äú2% salt had 30% germination vs 90% in plain water‚Äù), and notes that salt makes it harder for seeds to take up water (osmosis), which can slow or prevent sprouting."),

