    ("What‚Äôs the difference between an SN1 and SN2 reaction and how can I predict which one happens on a test?", "SN1 and SN2 are two different nucleophilic substitution mechanisms: SN1 is ‚Äúsubstitution nucleophilic unimolecular,‚Äù meaning the rate-determining step involves only the substrate and happens in two steps (first the leaving group departs to form a carbocation, then the nucleophile attacks), while SN2 is ‚Äúsubstitution nucleophilic bimolecular,‚Äù meaning the nucleophile and substrate are both in the single, concerted rate-determining step (the nucleophile attacks as the leaving group leaves in one step). Because SN1 forms a carbocation intermediate, it is favored by substrates that can stabilize a carbocation (tertiary > secondary >> primary/methyl), by weak/neutral nucleophiles (water, alcohols can work), and by polar protic solvents (like water or ethanol) that stabilize ions; it also allows rearrangements (hydride or methyl shifts) and gives racemization at a chiral center (often a mix of inversion and retention) because the planar carbocation can be attacked from either side. SN2 is favored when the nucleophile can do a strong backside attack and steric hindrance is low (methyl > primary > secondary >> tertiary), with strong nucleophiles (like HO‚àí, RO‚àí, CN‚àí, N3‚àí, RS‚àí, I‚àí) and typically polar aprotic solvents (like DMSO, DMF, acetone, acetonitrile) that don‚Äôt ‚Äúcage‚Äù the nucleophile; SN2 gives a single stereochemical outcome called inversion of configuration (Walden inversion) and never rearranges because there is no carbocation. To predict quickly on a test, first look at the substrate: tertiary alkyl halides/tosylates almost always go SN1 (SN2 is blocked), methyl and most primary substrates go SN2 (SN1 carbocations are too unstable), and secondary substrates are the ‚Äúdecision point‚Äù where conditions matter; then check the nucleophile/solvent: strong nucleophile plus polar aprotic pushes SN2, while weak nucleophile plus polar protic pushes SN1. Also confirm the leaving group is good (I‚àí > Br‚àí > Cl‚àí >> F‚àí; sulfonates like OTs/OMs are excellent), and use stereochemistry/rearrangements as clues: inversion with no rearrangement suggests SN2, while racemization and possible rearrangement suggest SN1."),

