    ("I‚Äôm stuck on limits/continuity: does f(x)=|x| have a derivative at x=0? Can you explain without just saying \'cusp\'?", "No, f(x)=|x| is not differentiable at x=0, and you can see it directly from the definition of derivative as a limit: f\'(0)=lim(h‚Üí0) (|0+h|‚àí|0|)/h = lim(h‚Üí0) |h|/h. If h>0 then |h|/h = h/h = 1, so the right-hand limit (approaching 0 through positive h) equals 1; if h<0 then |h|/h = (‚àíh)/h = ‚àí1, so the left-hand limit (approaching 0 through negative h) equals ‚àí1. Because the two one-sided limits are different, the overall limit does not exist, so the derivative at 0 does not exist. It‚Äôs still continuous at 0 because lim(x‚Üí0)|x|=0=f(0), but differentiability is stricter than continuity: the function‚Äôs average rate of change near 0 approaches different values depending on whether you come from the left or the right, so there is no single slope you can assign at that point."),

