    ("I don‚Äôt get linear functions. What does y = 3x + 2 actually mean and how do you graph it without a calculator?", "y = 3x + 2 is a rule that tells you how to get y from x: you take your x value, multiply it by 3, then add 2, so every x you choose produces exactly one y and the set of all those (x, y) pairs makes a straight line. The ‚Äú3‚Äù is the slope, meaning y changes by 3 for every 1 step you move to the right in x (rise 3, run 1), and the ‚Äú+2‚Äù is the y-intercept, meaning when x = 0 the line crosses the y-axis at y = 2. To graph it without a calculator, first plot the y-intercept point (0, 2), then use the slope: from (0, 2) go right 1 and up 3 to get (1, 5), or go right 2 and up 6 to get (2, 8), or go left 1 and down 3 to get (-1, -1); once you have two or more points, draw a straight line through them and extend it. You can quickly check your graph by plugging in a point you drew, like x = 1 gives y = 3(1) + 2 = 5, so (1, 5) should be on the line, and you‚Äôll see the line always goes up as you move right because the slope 3 is positive."),

