    ("Can you explain the work-energy theorem like I‚Äôm in 7th grade? Like how does work turn into kinetic energy?", "The work-energy theorem says that when a force makes an object move, the work done on the object becomes a change in the object‚Äôs kinetic energy (its energy of motion): Work = change in kinetic energy, or W = ŒîKE. ‚ÄúWork‚Äù in science means you push or pull with a force and the object moves in the direction of that force, so you transfer energy into it; if you push a shopping cart and it rolls forward, your push does positive work and the cart speeds up because its kinetic energy increases. Kinetic energy is KE = 1/2 mv^2, so if the cart‚Äôs speed v goes up, KE goes up, and the theorem tells you exactly where that extra motion-energy came from: the work your force did over the distance. If the force points opposite the motion, like friction or braking, the work is negative, so kinetic energy decreases and the object slows down; that ‚Äúlost‚Äù kinetic energy usually turns into thermal energy (heat) in the tires, brakes, or ground. A simple way to picture it is like charging a battery: doing work is like ‚Äúpaying in‚Äù energy through a force over a distance, and the object ‚Äústores‚Äù that payment as more (or less) kinetic energy depending on whether the work is positive or negative."),

