    ("What‚Äôs the difference between an element, a compound, and a mixture? Can you give real-life examples (like soda or saltwater)?", "An element is a pure substance made of only one kind of atom and it cannot be broken down into simpler substances by ordinary chemical means; examples include oxygen (O2) in the air, iron (Fe) in nails, and gold (Au) in jewelry. A compound is a pure substance made when two or more different elements chemically bond in a fixed ratio, meaning it has its own properties and you can‚Äôt separate it by simple physical methods; examples include water (H2O), table salt (sodium chloride, NaCl), and carbon dioxide (CO2). A mixture is a physical combination of substances that are not chemically bonded, so the ingredients keep their own properties, the proportions can vary, and you can often separate them by physical methods like filtering or boiling; saltwater is a mixture because salt is dissolved in water and you can get the salt back by evaporating the water, and soda is also a mixture because it contains water, dissolved carbon dioxide gas, sugars or sweeteners, and flavorings (the bubbles are CO2 escaping), while air is another common mixture of gases like nitrogen and oxygen."),

