    ("Why does ice melt faster on metal than on plastic? We noticed it in class and I wanna know the science.", "Ice melts faster on metal than on plastic because metal is a much better conductor of heat, meaning it can move thermal energy from the warmer surroundings into the ice quickly, while plastic is an insulator that slows that energy transfer. When you place ice on a metal surface at room temperature, the metal near the ice cools down, but the rest of the metal quickly brings in more heat from deeper inside and from the air, so the ice keeps receiving energy and melting; with plastic, the top surface cools and then doesn‚Äôt ‚Äúdeliver‚Äù much more heat to the ice, so melting slows. A helpful way to picture it is that metal acts like a fast heat highway and plastic acts like a heat traffic jam, and that‚Äôs also why metal often feels colder than plastic even when both are the same room temperature: metal pulls heat out of your skin faster. (If the metal were already colder than the ice, it could actually slow melting or even freeze water, so the key idea is the rate of heat transfer, not that metal is magically ‚Äúhotter.‚Äù)"),

