    ("How do you tell what type of chemical reaction it is (synthesis, decomposition, single replacement, etc.)? Can you classify these 6 equations I have?", "You tell the reaction type by matching the equation to a few ‚Äúshapes‚Äù (patterns) based on how many reactants and products there are and whether atoms swap partners: if two or more reactants make one main product, A + B ‚Üí AB, it‚Äôs synthesis (combination); if one compound splits into simpler substances, AB ‚Üí A + B, it‚Äôs decomposition; if a free element kicks another element out of a compound, A + BC ‚Üí AC + B, it‚Äôs single replacement (single displacement), and you can often confirm it with the activity series for metals or halogens; if two ionic compounds exchange ions, AB + CD ‚Üí AD + CB, it‚Äôs double replacement (metathesis), and it‚Äôs especially likely if you form a precipitate (solid), water (in an acid‚Äìbase neutralization), or a gas; if a substance reacts with oxygen and releases energy, it‚Äôs combustion, and for hydrocarbons the products are typically CO2 and H2O (though some reactions can reasonably be described by more than one label, like ‚Äúsynthesis‚Äù and ‚Äúcombustion‚Äù for forming an oxide). I can absolutely classify your six equations, but I need you to paste all 6 balanced equations exactly as written (including states if you have them, like (s), (aq), (g), (l)), and I‚Äôll label each one and briefly point to the pattern that proves it; for example, 2H2 + O2 ‚Üí 2H2O matches A + B ‚Üí AB so it‚Äôs synthesis, and because it‚Äôs hydrogen reacting with oxygen releasing heat, it‚Äôs also commonly described as combustion of hydrogen."),

