    ("I‚Äôm starting limits in precalc/calc and I‚Äôm lost. What does it mean when x approaches 2 in lim(x->2) (x^2 4)/(x 2)?", "When you see lim(x‚Üí2) (x^2 ‚àí 4)/(x ‚àí 2), ‚Äúx approaches 2‚Äù means you let x get closer and closer to 2 (like 1.9, 1.99, 2.01, 2.001) and watch what the expression‚Äôs value is heading toward, without necessarily plugging in x = 2. If you try to substitute x = 2 directly you get (4 ‚àí 4)/(0) = 0/0, which is an indeterminate form that tells you you must simplify first: factor x^2 ‚àí 4 as (x ‚àí 2)(x + 2), cancel the common (x ‚àí 2) (this is allowed for x near 2 but not equal to 2), and the expression becomes x + 2. Now it‚Äôs clear what value it approaches as x gets close to 2: x + 2 approaches 4, so the limit is 4; the key idea is that a limit describes the value the function is approaching near a point, even if the original formula is undefined exactly at that point."),

