    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 03:14 - Category: dna_replication
    ("Bio question: what‚Äôs the difference between DNA replication and transcription? My teacher keeps saying ‚Äúsemi-conservative‚Äù and I don‚Äôt get it.", "DNA replication and transcription both use DNA as a template, but they have different goals, products, and enzymes. DNA replication happens before cell division and its job is to copy the entire genome so the cell can pass a complete set of DNA to each daughter cell; it uses DNA polymerase to make DNA, it copies both strands, and the result is two identical double-stranded DNA molecules. ‚ÄúSemi-conservative‚Äù describes how replication works: the two original DNA strands separate, and each original strand is used as a template to build a new complementary strand, so each finished DNA double helix contains one ‚Äúold‚Äù (parent) strand and one ‚Äúnew‚Äù strand‚Äîhalf old, half new. Transcription, in contrast, is used to express genes and make RNA (usually mRNA, but also rRNA and tRNA) from a specific gene or set of genes; it uses RNA polymerase, it copies only one DNA strand for that gene (the template strand), and the product is a single-stranded RNA molecule that is complementary to the DNA template (with U in RNA pairing with A instead of T). A quick way to remember the comparison is: replication is DNA ‚Üí DNA, whole genome, both strands, makes two double helices, and is semi-conservative; transcription is DNA ‚Üí RNA, one gene at a time, one strand as the template, makes one RNA strand, and it is not described as semi-conservative because it doesn‚Äôt produce a new DNA double helix that keeps an old strand."),

