    ("For my US History essay: did the Industrial Revolution mostly help or hurt workers in the U.S.? I need 3 specific examples I can cite.", "The Industrial Revolution in the United States mostly hurt workers in the short run (especially from the early 1800s through the late 1800s) because wages and output rose but working conditions were often dangerous, hours were long, and employers had far more power than individual workers; however, it also helped in the long run by creating more wage-paying jobs and eventually pushing reforms and unions that improved pay and safety. Three specific, citable examples are: first, the Lowell textile mills in Massachusetts (especially in the 1830s), where ‚ÄúLowell mill girls‚Äù worked tightly scheduled 12‚Äì14 hour days amid loud machinery and cotton dust, and their 1834 and 1836 strikes/petitions show how industrial discipline and wage cuts harmed workers even in a ‚Äúmodel‚Äù factory town; second, the Triangle Shirtwaist Factory fire in New York City in 1911, where 146 garment workers died because exits were locked and fire safety was inadequate, a clear example of how industrial workplaces could be deadly and how tragedy led to major factory-safety reforms; third, the Homestead Strike of 1892 at Carnegie‚Äôs steel works in Pennsylvania, where a bitter conflict over wages and union power turned violent (involving Pinkerton guards and state militia) and ended with the union defeated, illustrating how industrialization often meant harsh labor relations and limited bargaining power for workers. If your essay needs a clear thesis, you can argue that industrialization ‚Äúmostly hurt workers at first‚Äù using these examples as evidence, then briefly acknowledge the longer-term improvements that came later through labor organizing and government regulation."),

