    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 03:17 - Category: machine_learning_basics
    ("In machine learning, I get confused about bias vs variance ‚Äî could you explain it with a concrete example (like polynomial regression) and how regularization changes things?", "Bias and variance are two different reasons a model can make mistakes: bias is error from being too simple and systematically missing the true pattern (underfitting), while variance is error from being too sensitive to the particular training sample and showing lots of wobble from one dataset to another (overfitting). A concrete way to see this is polynomial regression on data generated by a smooth curve, for example y = sin(x) plus a little random noise: if you fit a degree-1 polynomial (a straight line), it can‚Äôt bend to match sin(x), so across many different training sets it will consistently be wrong in the same way (high bias, low variance); if you fit a very high-degree polynomial (say degree 15 or 20) with ordinary least squares, it can contort to pass near every noisy training point, so it may have tiny training error but its curve changes dramatically if you resample the data and it often predicts poorly between points or outside the training range (low bias, high variance). Regularization changes this by discouraging overly complex fits, effectively trading a bit more bias for less variance: with L2 regularization (ridge), you minimize squared error plus a penalty Œª times the sum of squared coefficients, which shrinks coefficients toward zero and makes the polynomial smoother and less wiggly; with a moderate Œª, a high-degree polynomial can behave more like a lower-degree, stable curve that generalizes better, while an extremely large Œª can overshrink and push you back toward underfitting. L1 regularization (lasso) uses a penalty on the sum of absolute coefficients, which can drive some coefficients exactly to zero, effectively selecting a simpler polynomial by removing unnecessary terms; in both cases, increasing regularization strength generally increases bias and decreases variance, and the ‚Äúbest‚Äù setting is usually found by validation or cross-validation because it depends on noise level, data size, and how complex the true relationship is."),

