    ("Help me debug this C segmentation fault ‚Äî I think it‚Äôs pointer math? Here‚Äôs the snippet: int a = malloc(5sizeof(int)); for(int i=0;i<=5;i++) a[i]=i; printf(\"%d\\n\", a[5]); Why does it crash sometimes and what‚Äôs the correct fix?", "It crashes ‚Äúsometimes‚Äù because the code writes and then reads past the end of the allocated block: malloc(5sizeof(int)) gives you space for exactly 5 ints with valid indices 0 through 4, but your loop uses i<=5 so it writes a[5], and then you also print a[5]; that out-of-bounds access is undefined behavior, meaning it might appear to work, might crash with a segmentation fault, or might corrupt other data depending on what happens to be in memory right after the allocation. The correct fix is to stay within bounds by changing the loop to for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) a[i] = i; and printing a[4] if you want the last element, or if you truly intend to store and print 6 values (0 through 5) then allocate 6 ints with malloc(6sizeof(int)) and keep indices 0..5; also, in real code you should check that malloc didn‚Äôt return NULL and call free(a) when you‚Äôre done."),

