    ("Stats question: what‚Äôs the difference between a confidence interval and a prediction interval, and when would you use each in regression?", "In regression, a confidence interval (CI) answers ‚Äúwhat is a plausible range for the true mean response?‚Äù while a prediction interval (PI) answers ‚Äúwhat is a plausible range for a single new observation?‚Äù Concretely, at a given predictor value x0, a CI is for the expected value E[Y|X = x0] (the regression line‚Äôs mean at x0), reflecting uncertainty in the estimated coefficients and shrinking with larger sample size; a PI is for an individual future Ynew at x0, which must include both the same coefficient-estimation uncertainty and the additional irreducible scatter of individual outcomes around the line (the error term), so it is always wider than the corresponding CI at the same x0. You use a confidence interval when you care about the average outcome at x0 (for example, the mean blood pressure for patients of a given age, or the mean sales at a given ad spend) or when reporting uncertainty in the fitted relationship; you use a prediction interval when you need to forecast an individual case (for example, the next patient‚Äôs blood pressure or next week‚Äôs sales for one store) and want a range that realistically captures typical observation-to-observation variability, noting that both types of intervals are usually narrowest near the center of the observed x values and widen as you extrapolate farther from the data."),

