    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 03:20 - Category: plate_boundaries
    ("How do tectonic plates make mountains and earthquakes? My teacher said \'plate boundaries\' but I don\'t get the difference between convergent and transform.", "Earth‚Äôs outer shell (the lithosphere) is broken into huge tectonic plates that slowly move a few centimeters per year on top of softer, hotter rock below, and most mountains and earthquakes happen where plates meet, which are called plate boundaries. At a convergent boundary, plates move toward each other: if two continents collide, the crust crumples and thickens like a car hood in a crash, pushing rock upward to build big mountain ranges (the Himalayas formed as India collided with Asia), and if an ocean plate meets a continent or another ocean plate, the denser ocean plate usually dives under the other in a process called subduction, which can create deep ocean trenches, volcanic mountain chains, and very powerful earthquakes; these earthquakes happen because the plates can get stuck from friction, stress builds up for years, and then the rocks suddenly slip, releasing energy as seismic waves. At a transform boundary, plates slide sideways past each other instead of crashing or pulling apart, so they usually do not make tall mountains or volcanoes, but they do make frequent earthquakes because the edges snag, bend, and then jerk forward when they finally overcome friction; the San Andreas Fault in California is a famous transform boundary. So the key difference is direction of motion: convergent means toward each other and often builds mountains (and can make huge quakes and volcanoes if subduction is involved), while transform means sliding past each other and mainly produces earthquakes from sudden sideways slipping."),

