    ("Physics projectile motion: if I launch a ball at 18 m/s at 35¬∞, how long is it in the air (assume flat ground, ignore air resistance)? Please show steps.", "To find the total time the ball is in the air on flat ground (same launch and landing height) with no air resistance, use the vertical motion. First split the launch speed into components: the initial vertical speed is v0y = v0 sin(Œ∏) = 18 sin(35¬∞). Since sin(35¬∞) ‚âà 0.5736, v0y ‚âà 18 √ó 0.5736 = 10.32 m/s. The vertical position is y(t) = v0y t ‚àí (1/2) g t^2, and the ball lands when y(t) returns to 0 (besides t = 0), so set 0 = v0y t ‚àí (1/2) g t^2 = t(v0y ‚àí (1/2) g t). The nonzero solution is t = 2v0y/g, so t = 2(10.32)/9.8 ‚âà 20.64/9.8 ‚âà 2.11 s. Therefore, the ball is in the air for about 2.1 seconds."),

