    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 03:22 - Category: activists
    ("who were Harriet Tubman and Martin Luther King Jr and why are they important", "Harriet Tubman (born around 1822, died 1913) was an African American abolitionist and freedom fighter who escaped slavery in Maryland and then repeatedly risked her life to help other enslaved people reach freedom through the Underground Railroad, later serving the Union during the American Civil War as a nurse, scout, and spy; she is important because her courage and leadership directly helped people gain freedom and made her a lasting symbol of resistance to slavery and injustice. Martin Luther King Jr. (1929‚Äì1968) was a Baptist minister and a central leader of the U.S. Civil Rights Movement who organized and inspired nonviolent protests against segregation and racial discrimination, including the 1955‚Äì56 Montgomery Bus Boycott, the 1963 March on Washington where he delivered his ‚ÄúI Have a Dream‚Äù speech, and the 1965 Selma voting-rights campaign; he is important because his leadership helped change U.S. laws and attitudes, contributing to major victories like the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and the Voting Rights Act of 1965, and he received the Nobel Peace Prize in 1964 for his commitment to nonviolent social change. Together, Tubman and King show how determined individuals can challenge unfair systems in different eras‚ÄîTubman fighting slavery in the 1800s and King fighting segregation and unequal rights in the 1900s‚Äîand why activism can shape history."),

