    ("Can you help me solve this? y = 3x 5 and y = 2x + 7. What‚Äôs the intersection point and how do I graph it?", "To find the intersection point, set the two expressions for y equal because at the intersection they have the same x and y: 3x ‚àí 5 = 2x + 7, then subtract 2x from both sides to get x ‚àí 5 = 7, add 5 to both sides to get x = 12, and plug x = 12 into either equation to find y, for example y = 2(12) + 7 = 31 (and checking in the other one gives y = 3(12) ‚àí 5 = 31 too), so the intersection point is (12, 31). To graph them, start by rewriting each in slope-intercept form (they already are): y = 3x ‚àí 5 has y-intercept ‚àí5 and slope 3, so plot (0, ‚àí5) then use the slope ‚Äúup 3, right 1‚Äù to get another point like (1, ‚àí2) and draw the line; y = 2x + 7 has y-intercept 7 and slope 2, so plot (0, 7) then go ‚Äúup 2, right 1‚Äù to get (1, 9) and draw that line, and where the two lines cross on your graph should be at (12, 31)."),

