    ("I‚Äôm doing a lab and my teacher said ‚Äúcontrol variables‚Äù and ‚Äúindependent variable‚Äù but I‚Äôm still confused. Can you explain using a simple example?", "In an experiment, the independent variable is the one thing you purposely change to see what effect it has, the dependent variable is what you measure as the result, and control variables are all the other factors you keep the same so the test is fair. For a simple example, imagine you‚Äôre testing whether the amount of sunlight affects how tall bean plants grow: the independent variable is the amount of sunlight each plant gets (like 2 hours, 6 hours, or 10 hours per day), the dependent variable is the plant‚Äôs growth (such as height in centimeters after two weeks), and the control variables are things you keep constant for every plant, like the type of bean seed, the soil, the pot size, the amount of water, the temperature, and how long you run the experiment. Keeping those control variables the same helps you be confident that any difference in plant height is due to sunlight (the independent variable) and not something else, like one plant getting more water or being in a bigger pot."),

