    ("Is this modular arithmetic thing basically like clock math? Can you explain what 47 mod 6 is and why?", "Yes, modular arithmetic is basically ‚Äúclock math‚Äù: you keep counting but whenever you reach the modulus (the number you‚Äôre modding by), you wrap back around to 0 and continue. To find 47 mod 6, you ask ‚Äúwhat is the remainder when 47 is divided by 6?‚Äù since mod means remainder after division; 6 goes into 47 seven times because 6 √ó 7 = 42, and 47 ‚àí 42 = 5, so 47 mod 6 = 5. You can also see it by repeatedly subtracting 6 from 47 (47 ‚Üí 41 ‚Üí 35 ‚Üí 29 ‚Üí 23 ‚Üí 17 ‚Üí 11 ‚Üí 5) and stopping when what‚Äôs left is less than 6, which again gives 5; it‚Äôs like a 6-hour clock where 47 hours lands on the same ‚Äúposition‚Äù as 5 hours."),

