    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 03:26 - Category: congress
    ("In the U.S. Constitution, what‚Äôs the difference between the House of Representatives and the Senate? Please explain like I‚Äôm in 5th grade.", "Congress has two parts, kind of like a school having two teams that must agree before a rule is made: the House of Representatives and the Senate. The House is based on population, so states with more people get more representatives, and House members serve 2-year terms; the Senate gives every state equal power, so each state gets 2 senators no matter how big or small it is, and senators serve 6-year terms. The House is meant to represent the people more directly, so it starts bills about taxes and spending and can accuse (impeach) a president or other officials, while the Senate is meant to be a steadier check, so it approves important presidential choices like judges and cabinet members, approves treaties, and holds the trial if someone is impeached; for a bill to become a law, both the House and the Senate have to pass the same bill."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 03:26 - Category: civil_war
    ("Can you summarize the causes of the Civil War in like 6-8 bullet points? My teacher said include slavery but also other reasons.", "Slavery was the central issue: Southern states wanted to protect and expand slavery, while many in the North opposed its expansion, and enslaved people resisted their bondage in countless ways. Deep economic differences increased tension: the South relied heavily on plantation agriculture and enslaved labor, while the North was more industrial and favored different policies on banking, internal improvements, and trade. Disputes over federal power versus states‚Äô rights: Southern leaders argued states could reject federal laws and later claimed a right to leave the Union, while many Northerners insisted the Constitution created a permanent national union. Expansion into western territories raised the question of whether new states would allow slavery, leading to repeated crises and compromises such as the Missouri Compromise (1820), the Compromise of 1850, and the Kansas‚ÄìNebraska Act (1854). Political breakdown and rising sectionalism: national parties weakened and new ones formed around slavery‚Äôs expansion (especially the Republican Party), making compromise harder and elections more ‚ÄúNorth vs. South.‚Äù Violence and radicalization: ‚ÄúBleeding Kansas‚Äù (mid-1850s) showed that the slavery question could turn into armed conflict, and John Brown‚Äôs raid on Harpers Ferry (1859) terrified many Southerners and energized some abolitionists. Key court and legal conflicts intensified mistrust: the Fugitive Slave Act (1850) angered many Northerners, and the Dred Scott decision (1857) convinced many that slavery might spread everywhere and that compromise was failing. The immediate trigger was secession after Abraham Lincoln‚Äôs election in 1860: several Southern states left the Union to protect slavery and their political power, and the war began when Confederate forces fired on Fort Sumter in April 1861."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 03:26 - Category: supreme_court
    ("What does the Supreme Court actually DO and how are justices chosen? I don‚Äôt really get why it‚Äôs so powerful.", "The U.S. Supreme Court is the highest court in the federal judiciary, and its main job is to interpret the U.S. Constitution and federal law by deciding real legal disputes that have worked their way up from lower courts; it does not write laws or run the government, but it can review actions by Congress, the President, and state governments and decide whether they are constitutional, which is why it can be so powerful. Most of the time the Court chooses which cases to hear (usually by granting a ‚Äúwrit of certiorari‚Äù), and it tends to take cases that raise big national questions or where different lower courts are interpreting the law differently; after hearing arguments and reviewing written briefs, the justices vote and issue opinions that become binding precedent for all lower federal courts and strongly influence state courts on federal issues. Its power comes largely from judicial review, the principle that courts can strike down laws or government actions that conflict with the Constitution; this was established early in U.S. history in Marbury v. Madison (1803), and because the Constitution is the top law of the land, the Court‚Äôs constitutional interpretations can shape what governments are allowed to do until a later Court changes course, Congress changes a statute (when the issue is statutory rather than constitutional), or the Constitution is amended (which is difficult). Justices are chosen through a two-step political process: the President nominates a candidate, and the U.S. Senate confirms or rejects the nominee by a majority vote; before the full Senate vote, the Senate Judiciary Committee typically holds hearings and then votes on whether to send the nomination to the full Senate. Supreme Court justices hold their offices during ‚Äúgood Behaviour,‚Äù which in practice means they serve for life unless they retire, resign, or are removed through impeachment by the House and conviction by the Senate, so a single appointment can influence the law for decades; there are nine justices by tradition and by federal statute, with one serving as Chief Justice and the others as Associate Justices. A simple way to think about it is that Congress makes laws, the President enforces them, and the Supreme Court decides what those laws and the Constitution mean when people disagree in court, and because its decisions are final for the federal courts and set nationwide rules, the Court can have enormous impact on rights, elections, criminal justice, and the balance of power between states and the federal government."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 03:26 - Category: amendments
    ("What are the 1st and 4th Amendments and examples of them in real life at school?", "The 1st Amendment protects five key freedoms: religion (you can practice a faith or choose not to), speech (you can express opinions), press (you can share information and ideas), assembly (you can gather peacefully), and petition (you can ask the government to change something). In school, this can look like students wearing a button or shirt supporting a cause, writing an opinion article for the school newspaper, starting a club that meets after school, or peacefully signing and delivering a petition to the principal or school board about a rule, as long as it doesn‚Äôt substantially disrupt class or threaten others. The 4th Amendment protects people from unreasonable searches and seizures by the government, and because public school officials are government employees, it applies at school too, but the rules are a bit different: school staff generally do not need a judge‚Äôs warrant, yet they must have a reasonable suspicion based on specific facts to search a student or a student‚Äôs belongings, and the search should be related to what they‚Äôre looking for and not more intrusive than necessary. Real-life examples include a principal searching a backpack after a teacher reports seeing a student put a vape or stolen phone inside, or checking a student‚Äôs pockets if there is a specific reason to believe the student has a prohibited item; in contrast, randomly searching one student‚Äôs backpack ‚Äújust because,‚Äù or searching a student in an overly invasive way without a strong, specific reason, can violate the 4th Amendment."),

