    ("I have a U.S. map quiz. What are the major mountain ranges (like Rockies/Appalachians) and which states do they go through?", "For a U.S. map quiz, the two biggest ‚Äúanchor‚Äù ranges are the Appalachian Mountains in the East and the Rocky Mountains in the West. The Appalachians run from Alabama through Georgia, Tennessee, North Carolina, South Carolina, Virginia, West Virginia, Kentucky, Maryland, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, New York, Connecticut, Massachusetts, Vermont, New Hampshire, and Maine (the Appalachian system continues into Canada). The Rockies run from New Mexico through Colorado, Wyoming, Montana, and Idaho (the Rocky Mountain system continues into Canada). Other major western ranges to know are the Sierra Nevada in California and Nevada; the Cascade Range in Washington, Oregon, and northern California; the Coast Ranges along the Pacific in California, Oregon, and Washington; the Basin and Range mountain belts that create many separate ranges across Nevada, western Utah, and parts of California, Arizona, New Mexico, Idaho, and Oregon; the Wasatch Range in Utah (with a small extension into Idaho); the Blue Mountains in northeastern Oregon and into southeastern Washington and western Idaho; the Bitterroot Range along the Idaho‚ÄìMontana border; the Teton Range mainly in Wyoming (with a small part in Idaho); the Alaska Range in Alaska; the Brooks Range across northern Alaska; and the Hawaiian volcanic mountain ranges on the islands of Hawaii (including Mauna Kea and Mauna Loa on the Big Island). If you want a quick memory trick: Appalachians hug the eastern side of the U.S., Rockies form the tall ‚Äúspine‚Äù of the interior West, and Sierra Nevada/Cascades/Coast Ranges line up near the Pacific."),

