    ("In stats, how do I know when to use mean vs median? And can you show a quick example where outliers mess up the mean?", "Use the mean when your data are roughly symmetric with no extreme outliers and you want an ‚Äúaverage‚Äù that uses every value (it‚Äôs especially appropriate for interval/ratio data like heights or test scores when the distribution is fairly balanced), but use the median when the data are skewed or contain outliers because the median depends only on the middle position and is resistant to extreme values (this is why medians are common for incomes, home prices, and wait times). A quick outlier example: compare the five values 10, 11, 12, 13, 14, where the mean is (10+11+12+13+14)/5 = 60/5 = 12 and the median is 12; now change just one value to create an outlier: 10, 11, 12, 13, 100, where the mean becomes (10+11+12+13+100)/5 = 146/5 = 29.2 even though four of the five values are still near 10‚Äì13, while the median stays 12, which better represents the ‚Äútypical‚Äù value in that set. In general, if you care about the total or want to do further calculations that rely on means (like variance/standard deviation) and the data are well-behaved, the mean is great; if you want a typical center that won‚Äôt be pulled around by a few unusual observations, the median is the safer choice."),

