    ("What are the main parts of a cell and what do they do? I always forget the difference between mitochondria and ribosomes", "Most cells have a few main parts that work together like a tiny factory: the cell membrane is the thin ‚Äúskin‚Äù that controls what enters and leaves; the cytoplasm is the jelly-like fluid where many reactions happen and where cell parts sit; and the nucleus (in plant and animal cells) is the control center that stores DNA and gives instructions for making proteins. The easiest way to remember mitochondria versus ribosomes is that mitochondria are the cell‚Äôs energy makers, turning energy from food into usable ATP through cellular respiration (so they help power everything the cell does), while ribosomes are the cell‚Äôs protein builders, reading the instructions from RNA and assembling amino acids into proteins (they can float in the cytoplasm or be attached to the rough endoplasmic reticulum). Other helpful parts to know are the endoplasmic reticulum, which is a folded membrane system that helps make and move proteins (rough ER) and lipids (smooth ER), the Golgi apparatus, which modifies, sorts, and ships proteins and lipids like a packaging center, lysosomes (common in animal cells), which break down waste and old cell parts, and in plant cells the cell wall for extra support and protection, chloroplasts for photosynthesis, and a large central vacuole for water storage and pressure that helps keep the plant rigid; a quick memory trick is ‚Äúmitochondria make energy‚Äù and ‚Äúribosomes make proteins,‚Äù so energy versus proteins is the key difference."),

