    ("For distributed systems, what‚Äôs the difference between consistency and availability in CAP theorem, and can you give a real-world example?", "In the CAP theorem, consistency means that after a successful write, every read from any node returns the same, most recent value (or an explicit error), so the system behaves like there is a single up-to-date copy of the data; availability means that every request to a non-failing node receives a non-error response in a reasonable time, even if that response might not reflect the latest write. CAP says that when a network partition happens (messages between some nodes are delayed or lost), a distributed system must choose between keeping consistency (rejecting or delaying some reads/writes until nodes can agree, which reduces availability) or keeping availability (continuing to serve requests on each side of the partition, which can return stale data and thus reduces consistency). A real-world example is an online shopping cart during a network split between two data centers: if the system prioritizes availability, each data center keeps accepting ‚Äúadd to cart‚Äù actions so the site stays responsive, but a user might briefly see different cart contents depending on which side they hit until the partition heals and the carts are reconciled; if it prioritizes consistency, the system might refuse cart updates or force the user to wait while it ensures a single agreed-upon cart state, preventing mismatches but potentially showing errors or timeouts during the partition."),

