    ("Can you summarize the main causes of the Civil War in like 5-7 bullet points that don‚Äôt sound like Wikipedia?", "Slavery was the core issue: the Southern economy and social order depended on enslaved labor, while many in the North wanted slavery stopped from spreading and, increasingly, ended altogether. The big fight was over power and expansion: every time the U.S. added new territory, people argued whether new states would be ‚Äúfree‚Äù or ‚Äúslave,‚Äù because that would decide who controlled Congress and the presidency. ‚ÄúStates‚Äô rights‚Äù mostly meant one specific right: Southern leaders argued states should be able to ignore federal limits and protect slavery, while the federal government and many Northerners pushed back on that idea. Compromises kept cracking: deals like the Missouri Compromise, the Compromise of 1850, and the Kansas‚ÄìNebraska Act were meant to calm things down, but they often just delayed the conflict and made both sides angrier. Violence and fear took over politics: ‚ÄúBleeding Kansas,‚Äù the beating of Senator Charles Sumner, and John Brown‚Äôs raid convinced many Americans that words and votes weren‚Äôt settling the slavery question anymore. The election of 1860 was the tipping point: Abraham Lincoln won without Southern electoral support, and many white Southerners saw his party as a direct threat to slavery, so several states chose secession. Secession turned the crisis into war: once Southern states left to form the Confederacy and the U.S. refused to accept it, the standoff became a shooting war starting with Fort Sumter in April 1861."),

