    ("Why are there checks and balances in the Constitution? Like what problem were they trying to solve?", "Checks and balances are in the Constitution because the people who wrote it in 1787 were trying to solve a very specific fear: that a stronger national government, which they knew the country needed after the weak Articles of Confederation, might turn into the same kind of concentrated power they had just fought against under the British king and Parliament. Their solution was to divide federal power among three branches with different jobs and different ways of being chosen, and then give each branch tools to stop the others from abusing power, so no single person, group, or branch could easily take over the whole government. For example, Congress makes laws but the president can veto them, Congress can override a veto and controls funding, the Senate must approve major appointments and treaties, courts can refuse to enforce laws that violate the Constitution, and Congress can impeach and remove officials; the goal was to prevent tyranny and protect liberty by forcing cooperation and slowing down rushed or extreme decisions."),

