    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 03:33 - Category: constitution
    ("For my civics class, can you explain what the Supreme Court actually does vs what Congress does? I keep mixing their powers up.", "Congress and the Supreme Court are in different branches and they do very different jobs: Congress is the lawmaking branch, while the Supreme Court is the highest court in the judicial branch that decides legal disputes and explains what the Constitution and federal laws mean. Congress (the House of Representatives and the Senate, in Article I of the Constitution) writes, debates, and passes bills that can become federal laws, controls federal spending and taxes, can declare war, can approve treaties and many presidential appointments through the Senate, and can investigate issues; Congress can also impeach and remove federal officials (the House impeaches, the Senate holds the trial). The Supreme Court (part of the federal courts described in Article III) does not write laws or vote on bills; instead, it hears certain cases and issues decisions that interpret the Constitution and federal law, including deciding whether a law or government action is unconstitutional, a power called judicial review (recognized in Marbury v. Madison in 1803). A helpful way to keep them straight is: Congress makes the rules, and the Supreme Court decides what the rules mean in real cases and whether the rules follow the Constitution; for example, Congress might pass a law about elections or speech, and if someone claims it violates the First Amendment, the Supreme Court can ultimately decide whether that law can stand. They also check each other: Congress can write new laws after a Court decision (as long as they follow the Constitution), can change a law the Court interpreted, can propose constitutional amendments to override a Court interpretation, and controls the Court‚Äôs budget and can set the number of justices by law, while the Court can strike down unconstitutional acts of Congress."),

