    ("High school US history: what were the MAIN causes of the Civil War? My teacher says it‚Äôs not just ‚Äústates‚Äô rights,‚Äù but I need details for my essay.", "The main cause of the Civil War was slavery and the conflict over whether it would expand and be protected in the United States, because the Southern economy and social order depended on enslaved labor while many Northerners increasingly opposed slavery‚Äôs spread and, in some cases, slavery itself; ‚Äústates‚Äô rights‚Äù mattered, but most often as the argument Southern leaders used to defend slavery and resist federal limits on it. Key long-term causes included the growing sectional divide between a more industrializing, free-labor North and an agricultural South dominated by plantation slavery; repeated political fights over slavery in the territories as the nation expanded westward, such as the Missouri Compromise (1820), the Compromise of 1850 (including a stricter Fugitive Slave Act), the Kansas‚ÄìNebraska Act (1854) and ‚ÄúBleeding Kansas,‚Äù and the Supreme Court‚Äôs Dred Scott decision (1857) that denied Congress could ban slavery in the territories; and rising abolitionist and anti-slavery activism that alarmed slaveholders. Key immediate triggers were Abraham Lincoln‚Äôs election in 1860 on a platform opposing the expansion of slavery (even though he did not campaign on immediately abolishing it everywhere), which convinced many Southern slaveholding elites that their power and slavery‚Äôs future were threatened, leading to secession beginning with South Carolina in December 1860; the formation of the Confederate States of America explicitly to protect slavery (as stated in secession documents and leaders‚Äô speeches); and the outbreak of fighting after Confederate forces fired on Fort Sumter in April 1861. For an essay, a strong thesis is that slavery was the central issue, and the other causes‚Äîstates‚Äô rights, economic differences, political breakdown, and cultural tensions‚Äîwere tightly connected to the struggle over slavery‚Äôs expansion and survival."),

