    ("What‚Äôs the Bill of Rights and why did we need amendments in the first place? I‚Äôm kinda confused about how amendments get added.", "The Bill of Rights is the name for the first ten amendments to the U.S. Constitution, added in 1791 to spell out specific freedoms and to limit what the federal government can do, because many people (often called Anti-Federalists) worried that the new Constitution created a strong national government but didn‚Äôt clearly protect individual rights the way some state constitutions did. Amendments were needed in the first place because the Constitution is meant to be a stable set of rules, but the country can change or discover problems over time, so the amendment process lets Americans fix, clarify, or expand the Constitution without rewriting the whole thing; the Bill of Rights was also a political promise that helped win support for ratifying the Constitution by adding protections like freedom of speech and religion (First Amendment), protection against unreasonable searches and seizures (Fourth Amendment, which generally requires a warrant supported by probable cause for many searches, with some exceptions), and fair-trial rights for people accused of crimes (Sixth Amendment). An amendment gets added through a deliberately hard process in Article V: first it must be proposed either by two-thirds of both the House and Senate or by a convention called by two-thirds of the state legislatures (this convention method has never been used), and then it must be ratified by three-fourths of the states, either by their legislatures or by state ratifying conventions, depending on the method Congress chooses, which is why amendments are rare and usually reflect broad national agreement."),

