    ("what‚Äôs the difference between mitosis and meiosis? i can‚Äôt remember which one makes babies", "Mitosis and meiosis are two different kinds of cell division with different jobs: mitosis is for growth, repair, and making identical body (somatic) cells, while meiosis is for making sex cells (gametes) that are used to make babies. In mitosis, one cell divides once to produce two genetically identical daughter cells with the same number of chromosomes as the original cell (in humans, 46), which is why your skin, muscle, and other tissues can grow and replace damaged cells without changing your DNA. In meiosis, one cell divides twice to produce four genetically different gametes (sperm or eggs) with half the usual number of chromosomes (in humans, 23), and those differences come from mixing and reshuffling DNA (crossing over and independent assortment); when an egg and sperm join at fertilization, the baby ends up back at 46 chromosomes, with a unique combination of traits from both parents. So the one that ‚Äúmakes babies‚Äù is meiosis, because it makes the sperm and eggs, and it‚Äôs also a key reason populations can evolve and form new species over time, since it creates genetic variation that natural selection can act on."),

