    ("We just started limits and continuity‚Äîwhat does it mean when a limit \'doesn‚Äôt exist\' even if the function has a value there?", "A limit is about what the function‚Äôs outputs are approaching as x gets close to a point, not about the function‚Äôs actual value at that point, so it can ‚Äúnot exist‚Äù even when f(a) is defined. The limit lim(x‚Üía) f(x) exists only if the values from the left and from the right both settle toward the same single number; if the left-hand and right-hand behaviors disagree, or the values grow without bound, or they keep oscillating without settling, then the limit does not exist. For example, define f(0) = 7 but f(x) = 1 for x > 0 and f(x) = ‚àí1 for x < 0; the function definitely has a value at 0 (it‚Äôs 7), yet as x approaches 0 from the right the outputs approach 1 and from the left they approach ‚àí1, so there is no single number the outputs are approaching, meaning lim(x‚Üí0) f(x) does not exist. This is why ‚Äúthe limit exists‚Äù and ‚Äúthe function has a value there‚Äù are separate ideas: continuity at a requires both that the limit exists and that it equals f(a), but you can have f(a) defined while the nearby behavior fails to agree on one value."),

