    ("I‚Äôm trying to graph y = 2x 3 and y = -x + 5‚Äîhow do I find where they cross? do I have to draw it?", "You don‚Äôt have to draw it to find where they cross; you can find the intersection exactly by setting the two y-expressions equal because at the crossing point they have the same y-value: 2x ‚àí 3 = ‚àíx + 5, then add x to both sides to get 3x ‚àí 3 = 5, add 3 to get 3x = 8, so x = 8/3. Substitute x = 8/3 into either equation to get y: using y = 2x ‚àí 3 gives y = 2(8/3) ‚àí 3 = 16/3 ‚àí 9/3 = 7/3, so the lines intersect at (8/3, 7/3). You can check by plugging x = 8/3 into y = ‚àíx + 5 to get y = ‚àí8/3 + 15/3 = 7/3, which matches, and if you do graph them, that point is exactly where the two lines meet."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 03:41 - Category: supreme_court
    ("what does the Supreme Court actually do and why do they get to ‚Äústrike down‚Äù laws? (civics test help pls)", "The U.S. Supreme Court is the highest court in the federal system, and its main job is to interpret the Constitution and federal law by deciding real legal disputes that come to it on appeal (and in a few special cases, directly). When the Court hears a case, it answers questions like whether a law or government action violates the Constitution, what a constitutional right means in a specific situation, or how a federal law should be applied; its decisions set binding precedent for all lower federal courts and usually influence state courts too. The reason it can ‚Äústrike down‚Äù laws is the principle of judicial review: if a law passed by Congress or a state conflicts with the U.S. Constitution, the Constitution is the ‚Äúsupreme law of the land,‚Äù so the Court will rule that the law can‚Äôt be enforced; this power isn‚Äôt written as the phrase ‚Äújudicial review‚Äù in the Constitution, but it has been accepted since the 1803 case Marbury v. Madison, and it fits the separation of powers and checks and balances by letting courts stop the other branches from enforcing unconstitutional laws. In practice, the Court doesn‚Äôt erase the law from the books like an eraser; it declares the law unconstitutional in a case, which prevents the government from using it, and then lawmakers can change the law or, very rarely, the Constitution can be amended."),

