    ("what‚Äôs 144 √∑ 12? and can you give me a trick to remember my multiplication tables better", "144 √∑ 12 = 12, because 12 √ó 12 = 144, so you‚Äôre asking ‚Äú12 goes into 144 how many times?‚Äù and the answer is 12. A great trick for remembering multiplication tables is to learn them as connected patterns instead of separate facts: start with easy anchors like 2s (just doubling), 5s (end in 0 or 5), and 10s (add a zero), then build harder ones from those, for example 6 √ó n is (5 √ó n) + n so 6 √ó 7 = 35 + 7 = 42, and 9 √ó n is (10 √ó n) ‚àí n so 9 √ó 8 = 80 ‚àí 8 = 72; also practice a tiny set every day by saying them out loud in order like a chant (for example the 12s: 12, 24, 36, 48, 60, 72, 84, 96, 108, 120, 132, 144) and then quiz yourself with mixed-up questions, because quick daily repetition plus patterns makes them stick much faster."),

