    ("For a robotics project, how do sensors and actuators work together? Like if I want a robot to stop before hitting a wall what parts do I need?", "Sensors and actuators work together in a feedback loop: sensors measure what‚Äôs happening in the world (like distance to a wall), a controller (your microcontroller and code) decides what to do with that information, and actuators carry out the decision by moving or stopping the robot (like slowing motors or applying a brake). To make a robot stop before hitting a wall, you need a distance sensor facing forward such as an ultrasonic sensor, infrared distance sensor, or a small LiDAR module; a controller such as an Arduino, Raspberry Pi, or similar board to read the sensor and run the logic; a motor driver (H-bridge or ESC, depending on your motors) because the controller can‚Äôt power motors directly; and the actuators themselves, usually DC motors or servos that drive the wheels. The basic behavior is: the sensor continuously reports distance, your code compares it to a safe threshold (for example, stop when distance is less than 20 cm), and then commands the motor driver to reduce speed to zero; for smoother stopping you can slow down when the robot is ‚Äúnear‚Äù (say 40 cm) and fully stop at the ‚Äústop‚Äù distance, and it‚Äôs wise to include a simple emergency backup like a bumper switch so the robot can cut power if it still makes contact."),

