    ("Computer engineering-ish: can you explain transistors like im a high schooler? i understand \"switch\" but not how that becomes 0s and 1s", "A transistor is like a tiny, controllable valve for electricity: it has a path where current wants to flow, and a separate ‚Äúcontrol‚Äù input that can either allow that flow or block it. In most modern chips the transistor is a MOSFET, where the control input (the gate) doesn‚Äôt need to send current through the main path; instead, a voltage on the gate creates an electric field that either opens a conductive channel between the other two terminals (source and drain) or keeps it closed. The reason this becomes 0s and 1s is that computers agree on two voltage ranges to represent two states, for example ‚Äúlow‚Äù (near 0 volts) means 0 and ‚Äúhigh‚Äù (near the supply voltage, like 1.0 V or 3.3 V depending on the technology) means 1; the exact numbers vary, but the key idea is that there‚Äôs a safe gap between what counts as low and what counts as high so small noise doesn‚Äôt flip the meaning. A single transistor can act like a switch, but the real magic comes from combining transistors into logic gates: for instance, an inverter (NOT gate) uses transistors so that when the input is high, the output is forced low, and when the input is low, the output is forced high, giving you a clean, reliable ‚Äúopposite‚Äù bit. Once you can build NOT, AND, and OR (or equivalent gates like NAND/NOR), you can build circuits that do arithmetic and make decisions, and you can also build memory: a simple memory cell stores a bit by using feedback so the circuit ‚Äúholds‚Äù either a stable low or a stable high even after the original input is removed. So 0s and 1s aren‚Äôt mysterious signals inside the chip; they‚Äôre just two agreed-upon voltage states, and transistors are the tiny devices that create, flip, combine, and store those states in a controlled way."),

