    ("Algebra 2: how do i tell if a polynomial function will have an even or odd end behavior? like why does the leading term matter", "To predict a polynomial‚Äôs end behavior (what happens to f(x) as x goes to positive or negative infinity), you only need the leading term, the term with the highest power, because for very large |x| that highest power grows so much faster than all the lower-power terms that it completely dominates the sum. For example, when x = 1,000, x^5 is 10^15 while x^2 is only 10^6, so the x^5 term controls the sign and size of the polynomial far out on the left and right. The ‚Äúeven or odd‚Äù part comes from the degree: if the degree is even, then x^n is positive for both large positive x and large negative x, so both ends of the graph go the same direction; if the leading coefficient is positive, both ends go up (f(x) ‚Üí +‚àû as x ‚Üí ¬±‚àû), and if the leading coefficient is negative, both ends go down (f(x) ‚Üí ‚àí‚àû as x ‚Üí ¬±‚àû). If the degree is odd, then x^n is positive for large positive x but negative for large negative x, so the ends go in opposite directions; with a positive leading coefficient the right end goes up and the left end goes down (as x ‚Üí +‚àû, f(x) ‚Üí +‚àû; as x ‚Üí ‚àí‚àû, f(x) ‚Üí ‚àí‚àû), and with a negative leading coefficient the right end goes down and the left end goes up. A quick check with examples: f(x) = 2x^4 ‚àí 3x + 1 has even degree and positive leading coefficient so both ends up, while g(x) = ‚àíx^3 + 5x^2 has odd degree and negative leading coefficient so left end up and right end down."),

