    ("For my circuits lab, can you explain how a MOSFET transistor actually works (like what‚Äôs happening in the channel) and why it‚Äôs used as a switch in digital logic?", "A MOSFET (metal‚Äìoxide‚Äìsemiconductor field-effect transistor) is a voltage-controlled device where the gate is separated from the semiconductor by a very thin insulating oxide, so applying a gate-to-source voltage creates an electric field that changes the charge distribution at the surface under the gate. In an n-channel enhancement MOSFET (the most common example for digital logic), with the source and body typically at the same potential, a positive gate voltage repels holes and attracts electrons to the surface of the p-type body; once the gate voltage exceeds the threshold voltage Vth, enough electrons accumulate to form an ‚Äúinversion layer‚Äù that becomes a conductive channel connecting source to drain, and then a drain-to-source voltage drives current through that channel. For small VDS the channel behaves roughly like a voltage-controlled resistor (the ‚Äúlinear/triode‚Äù region), but as VDS increases the channel charge near the drain is reduced until it pinches off; beyond that point the current is set mainly by how strongly the gate field creates channel charge (the ‚Äúsaturation‚Äù region), which is why MOSFETs can act as amplifiers too. MOSFETs are used as switches in digital logic because they naturally provide two well-separated operating states: with VGS below Vth there is ideally no inversion channel so only tiny leakage flows (OFF), and with VGS well above Vth a strong channel forms so the device has low on-resistance and can pass substantial current with a small voltage drop (ON). The insulated gate means essentially no steady DC gate current is needed (you mainly charge and discharge the gate capacitance during switching), which gives very low static power. In CMOS logic, an nMOS transistor pulls a node down to ground when ON while a pMOS transistor (which forms a hole channel when its gate is driven low relative to its source) pulls the node up to VDD when ON; arranging them as complementary pull-down and pull-up networks makes it so that in a stable logic 0 or 1 one side is OFF, so ideally there is no direct DC path from VDD to ground, giving high noise margins, rail-to-rail logic levels, and excellent energy efficiency, with most power consumed only during transitions when capacitances are being charged/discharged and briefly when both devices partially conduct."),

