    ("Stats question: I ran a t-test and got p = 0.03 but my prof keeps saying ‚Äúeffect size matters.‚Äù How do I report this properly, and what effect size should I calculate?", "A p-value of 0.03 from a t-test tells you that, if the null hypothesis of no mean difference were true, results at least this extreme would occur about 3% of the time, so you can report it as statistically significant at the 0.05 level, but your professor is right that you should also report the size of the difference because statistical significance depends on sample size and doesn‚Äôt tell readers whether the effect is trivial or practically important. Report the test in a complete sentence including the group means and standard deviations (or mean difference with a confidence interval), the t statistic with its degrees of freedom, the exact p-value, and an effect size with its confidence interval if you can; for example: ‚ÄúGroup A (M = ‚Ä¶, SD = ‚Ä¶) scored higher than Group B (M = ‚Ä¶, SD = ‚Ä¶), mean difference = ‚Ä¶, 95% CI [‚Ä¶, ‚Ä¶], t(df) = ‚Ä¶, p = .03, Cohen‚Äôs d = ‚Ä¶ (95% CI ‚Ä¶).‚Äù For effect size, the standard choice for an independent-samples t-test is Cohen‚Äôs d (standardized mean difference), but many instructors prefer Hedges‚Äô g because it applies a small-sample correction and is essentially the same as d in large samples; for paired/repeated-measures t-tests, use a paired-samples standardized mean difference such as dz (mean of the difference scores divided by the SD of the difference scores) or report the raw mean change with its CI plus an appropriate standardized measure. If you want an effect size that aligns directly with the t-test and is easy to interpret as ‚Äúvariance explained,‚Äù you can also report r (the point-biserial correlation equivalent) or eta-squared/partial eta-squared, which can be computed from t and df; whichever you choose, be explicit about which version you used and how it was computed, and interpret it in context (e.g., a small but reliable difference vs a large, practically meaningful difference), rather than relying on p alone."),

