    ("Can you show me how to sum this infinite series and say whether it converges: \\sum_{n=1}^{\\infty} 1/n^2? I know it converges but I don‚Äôt get why.", "The series sum from n = 1 to infinity of 1/n^2 converges because it is a p-series with p = 2, and every p-series sum 1/n^p converges when p > 1 (one way to see this is the integral test: the function 1/x^2 is positive and decreasing, and the improper integral from 1 to infinity of 1/x^2 dx equals 1, so the corresponding series must converge). To actually find its exact sum, a classic method uses the sine function: sin(x)/x has zeros at x = ¬±kœÄ for integers k ‚â• 1, and it has the Taylor expansion sin(x)/x = 1 ‚àí x^2/3! + x^4/5! ‚àí ¬∑¬∑¬∑ near 0; it also has an infinite product representation sin(x)/x = Œ†_{k=1}^‚àû (1 ‚àí x^2/(k^2œÄ^2)), and if you expand this product for small x the coefficient of x^2 is ‚àí(1/œÄ^2) times the sum from k = 1 to infinity of 1/k^2, while from the Taylor series the coefficient of x^2 is ‚àí1/6, so matching coefficients gives (1/œÄ^2) Œ£_{k=1}^‚àû 1/k^2 = 1/6 and therefore Œ£_{n=1}^‚àû 1/n^2 = œÄ^2/6. As a quick numerical check, the first few terms give 1 + 1/4 + 1/9 + 1/16 ‚âà 1.4236 and the full sum œÄ^2/6 ‚âà 1.6449, so the partial sums increase but level off toward a finite limit, which is exactly what convergence means."),

