    ("For brain/neuroscience, what‚Äôs the difference between an action potential and a graded potential? I keep mixing up where they happen and why they‚Äôre different.", "Graded potentials and action potentials are both changes in a neuron‚Äôs membrane voltage, but they differ in where they occur, how they‚Äôre generated, and how they travel. Graded potentials usually happen in the dendrites and cell body (soma) when neurotransmitters bind to receptors or when sensory stimuli open ligand-gated or mechanically gated ion channels; they are ‚Äúgraded‚Äù because their size varies with stimulus strength, they can be depolarizing (excitatory postsynaptic potentials, EPSPs) or hyperpolarizing (inhibitory postsynaptic potentials, IPSPs), they spread only a short distance and fade as they move (they‚Äôre decremental), and they can add together over space and time (summation) to influence whether the neuron will fire. An action potential usually starts at the axon initial segment (the ‚Äútrigger zone‚Äù near the axon hillock) because it has a high density of voltage-gated sodium channels; if the summed graded potentials depolarize this region to threshold, an all-or-none action potential is produced, meaning it has a stereotyped size and shape, it is regenerated along the axon by sequential opening of voltage-gated sodium channels (so it does not fade with distance), and it travels one direction because of the refractory period (voltage-gated sodium channels inactivate briefly after opening). A helpful way to remember it is that graded potentials are like a dimmer switch in the input region (dendrites/soma) that can be small or large and can add up, while an action potential is like a digital ‚Äúspike‚Äù that either happens or doesn‚Äôt and then reliably propagates down the axon to communicate with other cells."),

