    ("what is the carbon cycle? like where does the carbon go and how does it get back", "The carbon cycle is the way carbon atoms move over and over between the air, living things, water, and rocks, instead of staying in one place. In the air, carbon is often in a gas called carbon dioxide (CO2); plants take in CO2 during photosynthesis to build sugars and other body parts, then animals get that carbon by eating plants (or other animals), and both plants and animals return carbon to the air as CO2 when they breathe (respiration). When living things die, decomposers like bacteria and fungi break them down and release more CO2 (and sometimes methane in low-oxygen places like swamps), while some carbon can be stored in soils for a long time; in the ocean, CO2 dissolves into seawater and can be used by tiny organisms to make shells, and when those organisms die, some carbon sinks and can become sediments and eventually rock like limestone. Carbon also gets locked away for millions of years as fossil fuels (coal, oil, natural gas) and certain rocks, and it gets back into the air through burning (wildfires and people burning fossil fuels), through volcanoes, and through slow processes like weathering and the movement of carbon-rich ocean water; so carbon ‚Äúgoes‚Äù into plants, animals, soils, oceans, and rocks, and it ‚Äúgets back‚Äù mainly through breathing, decay, ocean release, and burning, completing the cycle."),

