    ("my code won\'t run and i can\'t find the bug. what are good debugging steps i should try before asking my teacher?", "Start by reproducing the problem on purpose: run the program again, note the exact error message and the line number, and copy it exactly (don‚Äôt paraphrase), because that text usually tells you what kind of mistake it is (syntax error, missing name/variable, wrong type, file not found, etc.). Then simplify and isolate: make sure the file you‚Äôre running is the one you think it is, save all files, restart the editor/interpreter, and comment out or temporarily remove big sections until the smallest piece that still crashes remains; once you have a tiny failing example, the bug is much easier to spot. Next, check the most common causes carefully: typos in variable/function names, missing parentheses/quotes/colons/brackets, wrong indentation (especially in Python), using a variable before it‚Äôs defined, off-by-one errors in loops, and incorrect input types (for example treating text as a number); also verify any filenames and paths are correct and that required libraries are installed and imported. Use targeted ‚Äúprint‚Äù or logging statements (or a debugger if you have one) to display key values right before the crash and at important steps, and compare what you expected to what you actually got; if a value is wrong, move the print earlier until you find where it first becomes wrong. If you‚Äôre using functions, test them one at a time with simple inputs you can predict, and if you changed something recently, undo that change to see if it fixes the issue (version history or git helps). Before asking your teacher, prepare a clear help request: include the smallest code snippet that still shows the bug, what you expected to happen, what actually happened, the full error message, what you already tried, and your environment (language/version and how you ran it), because that makes it much easier for someone to help quickly."),

