    ("what are the three branches of government and how do they \'check\' each other? i keep mixing them up", "In the U.S. federal government there are three branches: the Legislative branch (Congress: the House of Representatives and Senate) makes laws, the Executive branch (the President and the agencies) carries out and enforces laws, and the Judicial branch (the Supreme Court and other federal courts) interprets laws and decides whether they follow the Constitution; they ‚Äúcheck‚Äù each other so no one branch gets too powerful. Congress checks the President by passing laws and controlling spending, overriding a veto with a two-thirds vote, and approving or rejecting major appointments and treaties, and it can impeach and remove a president or judges; the President checks Congress by vetoing bills and can check the courts by appointing federal judges (with Senate approval), while the courts check both by judicial review, meaning they can strike down laws or executive actions that are unconstitutional. A quick way to remember is ‚Äúmake, take, and interpret‚Äù: Congress makes the laws, the President takes care that the laws are carried out, and the courts interpret what the laws mean and whether they fit the Constitution."),

