    ("can you explain machine learning basics like i\'m new to it, and then give me an example of classification vs regression?", "Machine learning is a way to teach a computer to learn patterns from examples instead of giving it a long list of hand-written rules: you collect data (called features, like size, color, or words in an email) along with the correct answers when you have them (called labels), you train a model to make predictions, and then you test it on new data it hasn‚Äôt seen to check how well it generalizes, because the goal is not memorizing but making good predictions on future cases. Two very common kinds of supervised machine learning are classification and regression, and the key difference is what you‚Äôre trying to predict: classification predicts a category from a fixed set of choices, while regression predicts a number on a continuous scale. For example, if you want to decide whether an email is ‚Äúspam‚Äù or ‚Äúnot spam,‚Äù that‚Äôs classification because the output is a label; the model might look at features like certain words, the sender, and the number of links and then output a probability of spam that you turn into a yes/no decision. If you want to predict the price of a house, that‚Äôs regression because the output is a number; the model might use features like square footage, number of bedrooms, and neighborhood to predict something like 425,000 dollars rather than a category."),

