    ("We did magnets in class but I still don‚Äôt get it‚Äîwhy do magnets repel sometimes and attract other times?", "Magnets have two ends called poles, a north pole and a south pole, and the basic rule is that opposite poles attract while like poles repel: north pulls toward south, but north pushes away from north and south pushes away from south. That happens because a magnet creates a magnetic field, and the fields ‚Äúline up‚Äù smoothly when opposite poles face each other (so the magnets snap together), but when the same poles face each other the fields clash and the magnets push apart, which you feel as repulsion. A helpful way to remember it is to imagine arrows: magnetic field lines leave the north pole and enter the south pole, so if you point a north toward a south the arrows connect, but if you point north toward north the arrows are trying to go the same way and they can‚Äôt easily connect, so the magnets resist being pushed together; if you try it with bar magnets, you‚Äôll notice that flipping one magnet around switches which pole is facing, and that‚Äôs why the same two magnets can attract in one orientation and repel in the other."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 03:59 - Category: projectile_motion
    ("If I roll a ball off a table, how do you figure out where it lands? Like the projectile motion stuff but in middle school terms.", "To figure out where a ball lands when it rolls off a table, think of the motion as two separate motions happening at the same time: sideways motion and up-and-down motion. Sideways, the ball keeps moving at about the same speed it had at the edge of the table (call that sideways speed v), because gravity doesn‚Äôt pull sideways much; up-and-down, gravity pulls it down faster and faster. First find how long it‚Äôs in the air using the table height h: it starts with zero up-and-down speed (it just rolls off), so the fall time is t = square root of (2h/g), where g is about 9.8 m/s¬≤ (you can use 10 m/s¬≤ for easy middle-school math). Then the landing distance from the table is just how far it goes sideways in that time: distance x = v √ó t. Example: if the table is 0.80 m high, t ‚âà sqrt(2√ó0.80/9.8) ‚âà sqrt(0.163) ‚âà 0.40 s; if the ball leaves the edge at 2.0 m/s sideways, then x = 2.0√ó0.40 = 0.80 m, so it lands about 0.8 m from the edge. A simple way to measure v is to let the ball roll on the tabletop for a known distance (like 0.50 m), time it with a stopwatch, and compute v = distance/time; then use the same v in x = v √ó sqrt(2h/g). This works best if the ball rolls smoothly off the edge (not launched upward), air resistance is small, and you measure from the edge of the table to the first spot it hits the floor."),

