    ("Why does ice melt faster when I put salt on it? We saw it on a video and I wanna know the science.", "Salt makes ice melt faster because it lowers water‚Äôs freezing point, which means the ice-and-water mixture can stay liquid at temperatures where pure water would still be frozen. On the surface of an ice cube there is always a super-thin layer of liquid water (even below 0¬∞C), and when you sprinkle salt on the ice, the salt dissolves into that layer and turns it into salty water; salty water needs a colder temperature to freeze (seawater freezes around ‚àí1.9¬∞C, and very salty brine can stay liquid down to about ‚àí21¬∞C), so the ice has to melt to make enough liquid water to dilute the salt. Melting requires energy (heat) called the latent heat of fusion, so the ice pulls that energy from its surroundings and from itself, which is why the salty, melting ice can get colder even while it‚Äôs melting; that‚Äôs also why salt helps de-ice roads, but it works best near 0¬∞C and becomes much less effective when it‚Äôs extremely cold (below about ‚àí10¬∞C to ‚àí15¬∞C, depending on how much salt is used)."),

