    ("In algebra 2, how do you tell if a polynomial has a factor? Like can you use the remainder theorem on this: f(x)=x^3-4x+3?", "To tell if a polynomial has a factor of the form (x ‚àí a), you use the Remainder Theorem: plug in a, and the remainder when dividing by (x ‚àí a) is f(a); if f(a) = 0, then the remainder is 0 and (x ‚àí a) really is a factor (this is also called the Factor Theorem). For f(x) = x^3 ‚àí 4x + 3, a good first step is to try possible rational zeros using the Rational Root Theorem: the only candidates are ¬±1 and ¬±3 (because they must divide the constant term 3). Evaluate: f(1) = 1 ‚àí 4 + 3 = 0, so (x ‚àí 1) is a factor; f(‚àí1) = ‚àí1 + 4 + 3 = 6, so (x + 1) is not a factor; f(3) = 27 ‚àí 12 + 3 = 18, so (x ‚àí 3) is not a factor; f(‚àí3) = ‚àí27 + 12 + 3 = ‚àí12, so (x + 3) is not a factor. Since (x ‚àí 1) is a factor, you can divide to factor completely: x^3 ‚àí 4x + 3 √∑ (x ‚àí 1) gives x^2 + x ‚àí 3, so f(x) = (x ‚àí 1)(x^2 + x ‚àí 3); the quadratic doesn‚Äôt factor nicely over integers, but it does have real roots (‚àí1 ¬± ‚àö13)/2 if you want the full factorization over the reals."),

