    ("In physics can you help me apply the work-energy theorem to a problem? A 2 kg object speeds up from 3 m/s to 9 m/s‚Äîhow much work was done?", "Use the work-energy theorem, which says the net work done on an object equals the change in its kinetic energy: W = ŒîK = (1/2)mvf^2 ‚àí (1/2)mvi^2. With m = 2 kg, vi = 3 m/s, and vf = 9 m/s, the initial kinetic energy is (1/2)(2)(3^2) = 9 J and the final kinetic energy is (1/2)(2)(9^2) = 81 J, so the change is 81 ‚àí 9 = 72 J. Therefore the net work done on the object is 72 joules (positive because it sped up)."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 04:02 - Category: transistors
    ("I‚Äôm learning about transistors in electronics‚Äîcan you explain what a transistor does in a circuit, like as a switch vs amplifier?", "A transistor is a three-terminal semiconductor device that lets a small input signal control a much larger current, so in circuits it‚Äôs mainly used as a switch or as an amplifier. As a switch, the transistor is driven into two ‚Äúend states‚Äù: off (it blocks current, like an open valve) and on (it allows current, like a closed valve); for example, in a common NPN BJT low-side switch, a small base current turns on a much larger collector-to-emitter current to power a load like an LED or motor, and in an N-channel MOSFET switch, a voltage on the gate creates a conductive channel from drain to source so the load current can flow, with the gate drawing almost no steady DC current. As an amplifier, the transistor is biased to sit in its active/linear region (not fully off or fully on) so small changes at the input cause proportional changes in output current; with a resistor (or other load) this changing current becomes a larger voltage swing, which is how a microphone‚Äôs tiny signal can be boosted in an audio amplifier or how radio signals are amplified. In short, switching uses the transistor‚Äôs cutoff and saturation (or off and fully enhanced) behavior for digital on/off control, while amplification uses a carefully set operating point so the output is a scaled version of the input rather than just 0 or 1."),

