    ("In discrete math, can you explain modular arithmetic like I‚Äôm new to it? How do you solve 7x ‚â° 1 (mod 26)?", "Modular arithmetic is ‚Äúclock arithmetic‚Äù: instead of numbers growing forever, you pick a modulus (here 26) and treat two numbers as equivalent if they differ by a multiple of 26, so 29 ‚â° 3 (mod 26) because 29 ‚àí 3 = 26; in the congruence 7x ‚â° 1 (mod 26) you are looking for the multiplicative inverse of 7 modulo 26, meaning a number x such that 7x leaves remainder 1 when divided by 26. To find it, use the extended Euclidean algorithm to solve 7x + 26y = 1: since 26 = 3¬∑7 + 5, 7 = 1¬∑5 + 2, 5 = 2¬∑2 + 1, back-substitute to express 1 as a combination of 7 and 26: 1 = 5 ‚àí 2¬∑2 = 5 ‚àí 2¬∑(7 ‚àí 1¬∑5) = 3¬∑5 ‚àí 2¬∑7 = 3¬∑(26 ‚àí 3¬∑7) ‚àí 2¬∑7 = 3¬∑26 ‚àí 11¬∑7, so ‚àí11¬∑7 + 3¬∑26 = 1, which means x ‚â° ‚àí11 (mod 26), and converting to a positive representative gives x ‚â° 15 (mod 26) because ‚àí11 + 26 = 15; quick check: 7¬∑15 = 105 and 105 = 4¬∑26 + 1, so the remainder is 1, confirming the solution x ‚â° 15 (mod 26)."),

