    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 04:04 - Category: limits_continuity
    ("I‚Äôm stuck on limits/continuity. Is f(x) = (x^2 1)/(x 1) continuous at x=1? Can you show it step by step (and why the hole thing happens)?", "To check continuity at x = 1 for f(x) = (x^2 ‚àí 1)/(x ‚àí 1), first notice that if you plug in x = 1 you get (1^2 ‚àí 1)/(1 ‚àí 1) = 0/0, which is undefined, so f(1) does not exist as written and the function cannot be continuous at 1 in its current form. Next, to understand what happens near 1, factor the numerator: x^2 ‚àí 1 is a difference of squares, so x^2 ‚àí 1 = (x ‚àí 1)(x + 1); then for x ‚â† 1 you can cancel the common factor (x ‚àí 1) and get f(x) = x + 1 (but this simplification is only valid when x is not exactly 1, because cancellation assumes you are not dividing by zero). Now compute the limit: lim(x‚Üí1) (x^2 ‚àí 1)/(x ‚àí 1) = lim(x‚Üí1) (x + 1) = 2, so the values of the function approach 2 as x gets close to 1 from either side. The ‚Äúhole‚Äù happens because the original formula is undefined at x = 1 even though the surrounding values line up perfectly with the simpler rule y = x + 1; graphically it looks like the line y = x + 1 with a missing point at (1, 2). Therefore f is not continuous at x = 1 because continuity requires three things: f(1) must be defined, the limit as x approaches 1 must exist, and they must be equal; here the limit exists and equals 2, but f(1) is undefined, so it fails. If you define a new function g(x) that equals (x^2 ‚àí 1)/(x ‚àí 1) for x ‚â† 1 and set g(1) = 2, then g would be continuous at x = 1 because you ‚Äúfill in‚Äù the hole with the limit value."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 04:04 - Category: work_energy_theorem
    ("Can you explain the work-energy theorem like I‚Äôm actually gonna remember it? Also do one example with numbers (like a block sliding with friction).", "The work-energy theorem is the ‚Äúenergy version‚Äù of Newton‚Äôs laws: the total (net) work done on an object equals the change in its kinetic energy, written as Wnet = ŒîK = (1/2)mvf^2 ‚àí (1/2)mvi^2, and the memory hook is ‚ÄúWork is the transfer that changes speed‚Äù (positive net work makes it speed up, negative net work makes it slow down). ‚ÄúWork‚Äù here means force along the direction of motion times distance, so if a force points opposite the motion (like friction), its work is negative and it steals kinetic energy. Example: a 2.0 kg block slides on a rough horizontal floor with initial speed 6.0 m/s and coefficient of kinetic friction Œºk = 0.20; the friction force is fk = Œºkmg = 0.20 √ó 2.0 √ó 9.8 = 3.92 N opposite the motion, so the net work over 5.0 m is Wnet = Wfric = ‚àífk d = ‚àí3.92 √ó 5.0 = ‚àí19.6 J, meaning the kinetic energy drops by 19.6 J. The initial kinetic energy is Ki = (1/2)mv^2 = 0.5 √ó 2.0 √ó 6.0^2 = 36 J, so Kf = Ki + Wnet = 36 ‚àí 19.6 = 16.4 J, and the final speed is vf = sqrt(2Kf/m) = sqrt(2 √ó 16.4 / 2.0) = sqrt(16.4) ‚âà 4.05 m/s; a quick check: since friction did negative work, the speed decreased from 6.0 m/s to about 4.1 m/s, which matches the idea you‚Äôre meant to remember."),

