    ("I have a weird bug in my Python code and idk how to debug it. What‚Äôs a good checklist for debugging? Like print statements vs using a debugger vs unit tests?", "Start by making the bug reproducible on demand: write down the exact steps, inputs, environment details (Python version, OS, package versions), and the full traceback or wrong output, then reduce the problem to the smallest snippet that still fails (often by deleting code until it breaks, or by isolating the function with a fixed input). Next, classify the failure: is it an exception, a hang, wrong results, or nondeterministic behavior; for exceptions, read the traceback from the bottom up to find the line that actually raised, and for wrong results, add quick ‚Äúsanity checks‚Äù (assert statements about shapes, types, ranges, invariants) right after key transformations to narrow where the state first becomes incorrect. Use print/logging when you need fast visibility into values and control flow, but prefer structured logging over scattered prints: log the inputs, key intermediate values, and branch decisions, include types and lengths (for lists/arrays), and keep logs consistent so you can compare a ‚Äúgood run‚Äù to a ‚Äúbad run‚Äù; if the bug is timing-related or too noisy for prints, switch to a debugger. Use a debugger (pdb, or your IDE‚Äôs debugger) when you need to step line-by-line, inspect variables, watch expressions, and understand why a branch is taken; set breakpoints at the point of failure and one or two steps earlier, use ‚Äústep into‚Äù for suspicious functions, and use conditional breakpoints when the bug only happens for certain inputs. Add unit tests when you want to prevent regressions and force clarity: once you‚Äôve found a failing case, turn it into a small test that asserts the correct behavior, then fix the code and keep the test; tests are especially valuable for edge cases (empty inputs, None, off-by-one boundaries, floating-point comparisons, time zones, encoding) and for refactors. A practical workflow is: reproduce and minimize, read the traceback or define the ‚Äúexpected vs actual,‚Äù add a couple of asserts/logs to locate the first bad state, use the debugger to understand the exact path and variable values, then write a unit test for the discovered case so the bug can‚Äôt come back; if the behavior is nondeterministic, also control randomness (set seeds), remove concurrency where possible, and verify you‚Äôre not mutating shared state unexpectedly."),

