    ("My teacher keeps saying transistors are like switches. How does a transistor actually work in a basic way, and how does that connect to 0s and 1s in computers?", "A transistor is a tiny electronic device that lets a small electrical signal control a larger one, so it can act like an on/off switch (and sometimes like a dimmer). In the most common kind used in computer chips, called a MOSFET, there are three main parts: the source and drain, which are like the two ends of a wire you want to connect, and the gate, which is like a handle that decides whether that connection exists. The gate is separated by a very thin insulating layer, so when you apply a voltage to the gate it creates an electric field that either allows charge to flow between source and drain (switch ‚Äúon‚Äù) or blocks it (switch ‚Äúoff‚Äù); importantly, the gate controls the flow without needing much current itself. Computers use billions of these transistors wired together so that ‚Äúoff‚Äù corresponds to a low voltage and ‚Äúon‚Äù corresponds to a higher voltage, and those two stable states are interpreted as the binary digits 0 and 1; by combining transistors into logic gates like NOT, AND, and OR, the chip can reliably compute with 0s and 1s, store bits in memory, and build up everything from simple decisions to full programs."),

