    ("For an intro machine learning assignment: can you explain what training vs testing data is, and what overfitting means, without being super jargon-y?", "Training data is the set of examples you show a machine learning model so it can learn a pattern, like giving it lots of labeled photos of cats and dogs so it can figure out what usually makes a cat look like a cat. Testing data is a separate set of examples you keep aside and do not let the model learn from; you use it at the end to check how well the model works on new, unseen cases, which is closer to what happens in real life. Overfitting is when the model learns the training data too specifically, almost like memorizing the answers (including quirks or noise) instead of learning the general idea, so it scores very high on training data but does noticeably worse on the testing data‚Äîfor example, it might ‚Äúlearn‚Äù that most cat photos in the training set happened to have a certain background and then rely on that background rather than the cat itself."),

