    ("APUSH: What were the biggest causes of the Civil War? I need like 3-4 main causes with evidence, not just \'slavery\' as one word.", "The Civil War had several major, connected causes, and the biggest was the expansion and protection of slavery, especially in the West: as the United States gained new territory, the North and South fought over whether slavery would be allowed there, shown by the Missouri Compromise (1820), the Compromise of 1850 (including the Fugitive Slave Act), the Kansas-Nebraska Act (1854) that led to ‚ÄúBleeding Kansas,‚Äù and the Dred Scott decision (1857) saying Congress could not ban slavery in the territories; Southern leaders repeatedly said they were seceding to protect slavery, as stated plainly in secession documents like South Carolina‚Äôs ‚ÄúDeclaration of the Immediate Causes‚Äù (1860) and Mississippi‚Äôs declaration (1861). A second major cause was the breakdown of the political system and the collapse of compromise as the nation‚Äôs parties realigned: the Whig Party fell apart, the Republican Party formed to oppose the spread of slavery, and events like the caning of Senator Charles Sumner (1856) and John Brown‚Äôs raid on Harpers Ferry (1859) showed how politics was turning violent and trust between sections was disappearing; Lincoln‚Äôs election in 1860 without carrying most Southern states convinced many white Southerners they had lost power in the federal government. A third cause was deep economic and social sectionalism that made each region fear the other‚Äôs future: the North was becoming more industrial and favored tariffs and internal improvements, while the South remained tied to plantation agriculture and cotton exports and worried that a stronger federal government and a growing free-state majority would threaten slavery and Southern wealth; arguments over ‚Äústates‚Äô rights‚Äù were often tied to protecting slavery, as seen in conflicts like South Carolina‚Äôs nullification crisis (1832‚Äì33) and later Southern demands for stronger federal enforcement of the Fugitive Slave Act. A fourth cause was the immediate secession crisis and the question of whether the Union was permanent: after Lincoln‚Äôs victory, seven Deep South states seceded before he even took office, formed the Confederacy, and the war began when Confederate forces fired on Fort Sumter in April 1861; Lincoln‚Äôs call for troops then pushed additional Upper South states to secede, turning a political crisis into full-scale war."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 04:06 - Category: cell_structure
    ("What are the main parts of a cell and what do they do? Like nucleus, mitochondria, cell membrane, etc.", "Most cells have several key parts (called organelles) that each do a specific job: the cell membrane is a thin, flexible ‚Äúskin‚Äù that surrounds the cell, controls what enters and leaves, and helps the cell communicate with its environment; the cytoplasm is the jelly-like fluid inside the membrane where many chemical reactions happen and where organelles sit; the nucleus is the control center in plant and animal cells because it holds the DNA (the instructions for building and running the cell) and is where DNA is copied, while the nucleolus inside the nucleus makes ribosomes; ribosomes are tiny ‚Äúprotein factories‚Äù that build proteins, either floating freely in the cytoplasm or attached to the rough endoplasmic reticulum (rough ER), which is a folded membrane system that helps make and fold proteins and often sends them onward; the smooth ER makes lipids (fats and oils used for membranes and hormones) and helps with detoxifying certain chemicals; the Golgi apparatus is like a packaging and shipping center that modifies, sorts, and packages proteins and lipids into vesicles for delivery to other parts of the cell or outside the cell; mitochondria are the ‚Äúpower plants‚Äù that release usable energy (ATP) from food during cellular respiration, which is why cells that need lots of energy (like muscle cells) tend to have many mitochondria; lysosomes (common in animal cells) are recycling centers filled with enzymes that break down worn-out cell parts and large molecules, while peroxisomes help break down fatty acids and safely handle harmful byproducts like hydrogen peroxide; the cytoskeleton is a network of protein fibers that gives the cell shape, helps it move, and acts like internal tracks for transporting materials; in plant cells specifically, chloroplasts capture sunlight to make sugar through photosynthesis, the cell wall is a sturdy outer layer (made mostly of cellulose) that supports and protects the cell, and a large central vacuole stores water and other materials and helps keep the plant cell firm; bacteria and other prokaryotes don‚Äôt have a nucleus or membrane-bound organelles, but they still have a cell membrane, cytoplasm, ribosomes, and DNA (usually in a region called the nucleoid), and many also have a cell wall for protection."),

