    ("Can you explain plate boundaries (convergent/divergent/transform) and what landforms they make? My test is tomorrow and I‚Äôm stressed.", "Plate boundaries are places where Earth‚Äôs tectonic plates meet, and the type of boundary tells you whether plates are colliding, pulling apart, or sliding past each other, which controls the landforms and hazards you see. At a convergent boundary, plates move toward each other: if an oceanic plate meets a continental plate, the denser oceanic plate subducts (dives) beneath the continent, forming a deep ocean trench offshore and a volcanic mountain chain on land (for example, the Andes and the Peru‚ÄìChile Trench), and producing strong earthquakes; if two oceanic plates converge, one subducts and you get a trench plus a curved chain of volcanic islands called an island arc (like Japan or the Aleutians); if two continental plates converge, neither subducts easily, so the crust crumples and thickens to build very high folded mountain ranges and plateaus with many earthquakes but little to no volcanism (like the Himalayas and the Tibetan Plateau). At a divergent boundary, plates move apart and new crust forms as magma rises to fill the gap: in the ocean this creates mid-ocean ridges (long underwater mountain chains with a central rift, like the Mid-Atlantic Ridge) and shallow earthquakes, while on continents it creates rift valleys with normal faults, volcanism, and eventually a new ocean basin if rifting continues (like the East African Rift). At a transform boundary, plates slide horizontally past each other, so crust is not created or destroyed; instead you get strike-slip faults, linear valleys, offset streams, and frequent shallow earthquakes, but usually little volcanism (a classic example is the San Andreas Fault in California). A quick way to remember is ‚Äúconvergent builds and subducts,‚Äù ‚Äúdivergent splits and makes new crust,‚Äù and ‚Äútransform slides and shakes,‚Äù and if you can match each to its signature landforms‚Äîtrenches and volcanoes or big folded mountains for convergent, ridges and rift valleys for divergent, and fault lines with earthquakes for transform‚Äîyou‚Äôll be ready for tomorrow‚Äôs test."),

