    ("How does a bill become a law in Congress, like the actual steps? I have a quiz and the flowchart is confusing.", "In Congress, a bill becomes a law through a specific sequence: first a member of the House or Senate introduces the bill (it‚Äôs ‚Äúintroduced‚Äù and given a number), then it is sent to the committee that handles that topic, where it may be studied in hearings, changed (‚Äúmarked up‚Äù), and then voted on; if the committee votes yes, it goes to the full chamber (House or Senate) for debate and a vote, and if it passes, it must go through the other chamber and pass there too in the same basic way (committee, then full-chamber vote). If the House and Senate pass different versions, a conference committee (members from both chambers) works out one compromise version, and both chambers must vote to approve that final identical version; then the bill goes to the President, who can sign it and it becomes law, veto it and send it back, or take no action‚Äîif Congress is in session and the President does nothing for 10 days (not counting Sundays) it becomes law without a signature, but if Congress has adjourned during that 10-day period it is a pocket veto and the bill fails. Congress can still make a vetoed bill become law by overriding the veto with a two-thirds vote in the House and a two-thirds vote in the Senate."),

