    ("What‚Äôs the Supreme Court and what does \'judicial review\' mean? Can you give an easy example?", "The Supreme Court is the highest court in the United States, meaning it is the final place people can go to settle big legal disagreements, especially about what the U.S. Constitution means; it has nine justices who hear important cases and their decisions set rules that all lower courts must follow. Judicial review is the Supreme Court‚Äôs power to examine a law or a government action and decide whether it violates the Constitution, and if it does, the Court can declare it unconstitutional so it can‚Äôt be enforced. An easy example is: if Congress passed a law saying ‚Äúpeople may not criticize the government,‚Äù someone could challenge it in court, and the Supreme Court could use judicial review to strike it down because the First Amendment protects free speech."),

