    ("For US history: what was the Industrial Revolution and how did it change life in the U.S.? I need like 5 impacts for a paragraph.", "The Industrial Revolution was the long shift in the late 1700s and 1800s from making goods by hand at home or in small shops to producing them with machines in factories, and in the United States it took off especially in the early 1800s with textile mills in New England and later spread with steam power, railroads, and mass production. It changed American life in many ways: it moved large numbers of people from farms into growing cities to work for wages in factories; it greatly increased how fast and cheaply goods could be made, so everyday items like cloth, tools, and later packaged foods became more available; it transformed transportation and trade as canals and especially railroads connected regions, sped up travel, and created a national market; it reshaped work and family life by replacing flexible farm or craft schedules with long factory hours, strict rules, and new jobs for women and children (which also led to reform movements and child labor laws); and it created big new economic differences and social changes, including the rise of large corporations and industrial ‚Äúcaptains of industry,‚Äù the growth of a working class, and the start of labor unions pushing for safer conditions and better pay."),

