    ("In computer architecture, I don‚Äôt get the difference between cache hit rate and AMAT. Can you explain how to compute AMAT with a real example (L1 miss -> L2 -> memory)?", "Cache hit rate is just a probability: the fraction of accesses that are found in a given cache level (for example, an L1 hit rate of 95% means 95 out of 100 loads/stores are served by L1 without going lower). AMAT, average memory access time, is the expected (average) time per access after you combine the fast-hit time with the extra penalties you pay on misses, weighted by how often those misses happen; in other words, hit rate tells you ‚Äúhow often,‚Äù while AMAT tells you ‚Äúhow long on average.‚Äù The standard way to compute it for an L1 backed by L2 backed by main memory is AMAT = L1 hit time + (L1 miss rate) √ó (L1 miss penalty), and the L1 miss penalty is itself an average: L2 hit time + (L2 miss rate) √ó (memory time). For a concrete example, suppose L1 hit time is 1 cycle and L1 hit rate is 95% (so L1 miss rate is 5%), L2 hit time (the extra time to access L2 once you‚Äôve missed in L1) is 8 cycles and L2 hit rate is 90% (so L2 miss rate is 10% of the L1 misses), and main memory time is 120 cycles. Then the average L1 miss penalty is 8 + 0.10 √ó 120 = 8 + 12 = 20 cycles, so AMAT = 1 + 0.05 √ó 20 = 1 + 1 = 2 cycles per access on average; you can sanity-check this by imagining 100 accesses: 95 take 1 cycle each (95 cycles total), 5 miss L1 and each costs 1 + 8 + (10% of the time an extra 120) which averages to 21 cycles each (105 cycles total), giving 200 cycles/100 accesses = 2 cycles."),

