    ("What does it mean for a function to be continuous? like what‚Äôs happening at the limit", "A function is continuous at a point x = a if there‚Äôs no ‚Äúbreak‚Äù in its graph there, meaning you can make f(x) as close as you want to f(a) by taking x close enough to a; formally, continuity at a requires three things: f(a) is defined, the limit lim(x‚Üía) f(x) exists (the left-hand and right-hand limits agree), and that limit equals the actual function value, lim(x‚Üía) f(x) = f(a). What‚Äôs ‚Äúhappening at the limit‚Äù is that you‚Äôre not plugging in x = a (unless you can); instead you‚Äôre watching the outputs f(x) as inputs x get arbitrarily close to a from both sides, and if those outputs settle toward a single number L, then the limit is L. If the function is continuous at a, that settling value is exactly the height of the function at a, so there‚Äôs no jump, hole, or mismatch; for example, f(x) = x^2 is continuous everywhere because as x approaches 2, f(x) approaches 4 and f(2) = 4, but if you define g(x) = (x^2 ‚àí 1)/(x ‚àí 1) for x ‚â† 1 and leave g(1) undefined, then lim(x‚Üí1) g(x) = 2 even though g(1) doesn‚Äôt exist, which creates a removable discontinuity (a ‚Äúhole‚Äù) at x = 1, and if you instead set g(1) = 2 you ‚Äúfill the hole‚Äù and make it continuous there."),

