    ("Prove that the sum from n=1 to infinity of 1/n^2 converges (you can use known results), and what it converges to if we‚Äôre allowed to say it", "To prove that the series sum from n=1 to infinity of 1/n^2 converges, you can use the p-series test: the series sum 1/n^p converges exactly when p>1, and here p=2>1, so it converges. If you want a direct comparison proof, group terms in blocks of powers of 2: 1/2^2+1/3^2+1/4^2 is less than 3¬∑(1/2^2), 1/5^2+‚Ä¶+1/8^2 is less than 4¬∑(1/4^2), and in general the block from n=2^k+1 to n=2^(k+1) has 2^k terms each at most 1/(2^k)^2, so that whole block is at most 2^k¬∑1/2^(2k)=1/2^k; therefore the tail is bounded by the geometric series 1+1/2+1/4+‚Ä¶ which converges, so by comparison the original series converges. If we‚Äôre allowed to state the value, the famous Basel problem result is that sum from n=1 to infinity of 1/n^2 equals pi^2/6 (approximately 1.644934)."),

