    ("I‚Äôm building a simple prototype for a class: what sensors and actuators would make sense for an automatic plant-watering system?", "For a simple automatic plant-watering prototype, the most useful sensors are a soil moisture sensor (capacitive types are usually more stable than cheap resistive probes because they corrode less), a water reservoir level sensor (a float switch or an ultrasonic sensor aimed at the tank) so you don‚Äôt run the pump dry, and optionally a light sensor (photoresistor or digital light sensor) plus a temperature/humidity sensor to log conditions and adjust watering rules; if you want to be safer, add a leak/drip sensor under the pot and a flow sensor in the tubing to confirm water actually moved. The key actuators are a small DC submersible pump or a peristaltic pump (peristaltic is great for precise dosing and prevents siphoning), controlled through a relay module or a MOSFET driver from your microcontroller, and you can also use a solenoid valve if you‚Äôre feeding from a pressurized source; adding a simple buzzer/LED or small display is helpful as an ‚Äúactuator‚Äù for alerts like ‚Äútank empty‚Äù or ‚Äúsensor disconnected.‚Äù A sensible starter setup for class is: capacitive soil moisture sensor in the pot, float switch in the reservoir, a small pump, and a relay/MOSFET driver, with tubing and a check valve or anti-siphon loop so the system doesn‚Äôt keep dripping after the pump turns off."),

