    ("I don‚Äôt really understand what the Supreme Court does, and what an \'amendment\' actually is. can you explain with an example?", "The Supreme Court is the highest court in the United States, and its main job is to decide how the U.S. Constitution applies when there‚Äôs a serious legal dispute, especially when different courts disagree or when a law might conflict with constitutional rights; if the Court decides a law violates the Constitution, it can stop that law from being enforced, a power called judicial review (famously recognized in the 1803 case Marbury v. Madison). An amendment is an official change or addition to the Constitution itself, which is harder to do than passing a regular law because it usually requires approval by two-thirds of both houses of Congress and then ratification by three-fourths of the states; once added, an amendment becomes part of the Constitution and can protect rights or change how government works. For example, the First Amendment says the government can‚Äôt make laws that take away freedom of speech, so if a city passed a rule saying ‚Äúno one may criticize the mayor,‚Äù someone could challenge it in court, and the Supreme Court could rule the rule unconstitutional because it violates the First Amendment; that shows the Court enforcing an amendment, while the amendment is the Constitution-level rule that sets the boundary the government must obey."),

