    ("What are the main parts of an animal cell and what do they do? My quiz is tomorrow and I can‚Äôt remember mitochondria vs nucleus stuff.", "An animal cell has several key parts (organelles) with specific jobs: the cell membrane is the thin, flexible ‚Äúskin‚Äù that controls what enters and leaves the cell; the cytoplasm is the jelly-like fluid where many reactions happen and where organelles sit; the nucleus is the control center that holds DNA (the instructions for the cell) and tells the cell what proteins to make, and the nucleolus inside it makes ribosomes; mitochondria are the ‚Äúpower plants‚Äù that release usable energy (ATP) from food during cellular respiration; ribosomes are tiny protein-making machines (found free in the cytoplasm or attached to rough ER); the rough endoplasmic reticulum (rough ER) is a folded membrane system with ribosomes that helps make and fold proteins, while smooth ER makes lipids (fats) and helps detoxify chemicals; the Golgi apparatus is the ‚Äúpost office‚Äù that modifies, sorts, and packages proteins and lipids into vesicles to ship them to where they‚Äôre needed or out of the cell; lysosomes are enzyme-filled ‚Äúrecycling centers‚Äù that break down old cell parts and germs; vesicles are small transport bubbles that move materials around; the cytoskeleton is a network of protein fibers that gives the cell shape and helps movement and internal transport; and centrioles (in the centrosome) help organize the cytoskeleton and pull chromosomes apart during cell division. To remember nucleus vs mitochondria: nucleus equals instructions and control (DNA), mitochondria equals energy production (ATP)."),

