    ("What does ‚Äúbalancing chemical equations‚Äù mean? Like can you balance this: Fe + O2 ‚Üí Fe2O3 (and explain it like I‚Äôm in 8th grade)?", "Balancing a chemical equation means making sure the same number of each type of atom appears on both sides of the arrow, because atoms aren‚Äôt created or destroyed in a reaction, they just get rearranged. In Fe + O2 ‚Üí Fe2O3, the product Fe2O3 has 2 iron atoms and 3 oxygen atoms in each formula unit, but oxygen on the left comes in pairs as O2, so we choose coefficients (big numbers in front) to make the counts match: put 2 in front of Fe2O3 to make 4 Fe and 6 O on the right, then put 4 in front of Fe to match the 4 Fe on the left, and put 3 in front of O2 to make 6 O on the left; the balanced equation is 4Fe + 3O2 ‚Üí 2Fe2O3. You can check it by counting: left side has 4 Fe atoms and 6 O atoms, and the right side also has 4 Fe atoms and 6 O atoms, so it‚Äôs balanced."),

