    ("My code won‚Äôt work and I don‚Äôt get why. In Scratch I made a loop but it keeps repeating forever. What‚Äôs a good way to debug step by step?", "When a Scratch loop repeats forever, the fastest way to debug is to slow the program down and watch exactly which condition never becomes true. First, add a temporary ‚Äúsay (variable)‚Äù or ‚Äúsay (join [state=] (state))‚Äù inside the loop to display the key variable(s) that should change, and also right-click the variable and choose ‚Äúshow‚Äù so you can see it on the Stage while the project runs; if the number never changes (or changes the wrong way), you‚Äôve found the problem. Next, use single-stepping by clicking the script itself (or individual blocks) instead of pressing the green flag, and turn on ‚ÄúTurbo Mode‚Äù off so it runs at normal speed; you can also insert a small ‚Äúwait (0.1) seconds‚Äù inside the loop to make changes visible. Then check the loop‚Äôs stopping rule: for a ‚Äúrepeat until <condition>‚Äù, temporarily say the condition result by using ‚Äúsay (<condition>)‚Äù (it will show true/false) and confirm the condition can ever become true; common mistakes are using ‚Äú< >‚Äù comparisons backwards, checking the wrong variable, or expecting equality when the value skips past it (for example, changing by 2 but checking ‚Äú= 5‚Äù). If it‚Äôs a ‚Äúforever‚Äù loop, make sure there is an ‚Äúif <stop condition> then stop [this script]‚Äù (or ‚Äústop [all]‚Äù if appropriate) inside it, and confirm that the stop condition depends on something that actually changes. Finally, isolate the bug by temporarily removing extra blocks: keep only the loop and the variable change, test, then add blocks back one at a time until it breaks again; this ‚Äúsimplify and rebuild‚Äù method makes it very clear which block or condition causes the infinite loop."),

