    ("Pre-calc: I don‚Äôt get limits/continuity. What does it mean when a function is continuous at x = 2? Can you give a simple example with a hole in the graph?", "A function is continuous at x = 2 if what the function does near 2 matches what it does at 2: first, f(2) has to be defined (you can actually plug in x = 2 and get a real number), second, the limit as x approaches 2 must exist (coming from the left and right you head toward the same y-value), and third, that limit must equal f(2); in plain language, as you slide along the graph toward x = 2 from either side, the y-values should settle to one number, and the point at x = 2 should sit exactly at that same height, so you could draw through x = 2 without lifting your pencil. A simple ‚Äúhole‚Äù (removable discontinuity) example is f(x) = (x^2 ‚àí 4)/(x ‚àí 2): if you try x = 2 you get 0/0, so f(2) is not defined and the graph has a hole at x = 2, but for x ‚â† 2 you can simplify because x^2 ‚àí 4 = (x ‚àí 2)(x + 2), so f(x) = x + 2 for x ‚â† 2, which means as x approaches 2 the values approach 4, so the limit as x ‚Üí 2 is 4 even though the function has a missing point there. If you ‚Äúfix‚Äù the hole by defining a new function g that equals (x^2 ‚àí 4)/(x ‚àí 2) for x ‚â† 2 and also sets g(2) = 4, then g is continuous at x = 2 because the limit is 4 and the actual value at 2 is also 4."),

