    ("Stats question for my project: what‚Äôs the difference between standard deviation and standard error, and when should I use each in a lab report?", "Standard deviation (SD) describes how spread out individual measurements are in your sample: it‚Äôs the typical distance of data points from the sample mean, reported in the same units as the measurement, so it answers ‚Äúhow variable were the trials/subjects?‚Äù Standard error (SE, usually the standard error of the mean, SEM) describes how precise your estimate of the population mean is: it is the standard deviation of the sampling distribution of the mean and, for independent observations, SEM = SD/‚àön, so it gets smaller as sample size increases even if the underlying variability stays the same; it answers ‚Äúhow precisely have we estimated the mean?‚Äù In a lab report, use SD (often written as mean ¬± SD) when you want to show the variability among repeated measurements or participants, and use SE mainly when you are doing inference about the mean (for example, to build a confidence interval or in a t-test/ANOVA context); for communicating uncertainty, it‚Äôs usually clearer to report a 95% confidence interval for the mean (mean ¬± t√óSE) rather than SE alone, because SD is about spread of data while SE/CI is about uncertainty in the mean."),

