    ("I got \\(z = 3 4i\\). How do I find its magnitude and write it in polar form? Also what does the angle represent?", "For z = 3 ‚àí 4i, the magnitude (also called modulus) is |z| = sqrt(3^2 + (‚àí4)^2) = sqrt(9 + 16) = 5, which is the distance from the origin to the point (3, ‚àí4) on the complex plane. To write z in polar form, find the argument (angle) Œ∏ made with the positive real axis: tan Œ∏ = (imaginary part)/(real part) = (‚àí4)/3, and since the point is in quadrant IV, Œ∏ = arctan(‚àí4/3) = ‚àíarctan(4/3) ‚âà ‚àí0.9273 radians (‚âà ‚àí53.13¬∞), or equivalently Œ∏ ‚âà 2œÄ ‚àí 0.9273 = 5.3559 radians (‚âà 306.87¬∞). Therefore z = 5(cos Œ∏ + i sin Œ∏) with Œ∏ as above, and you can also write z = 5e^{iŒ∏}; the angle represents the direction of the complex number (the direction of the vector from the origin to (3, ‚àí4)), and multiplying complex numbers adds these angles while multiplying their magnitudes."),

