    ("Bio question: can you compare mitosis vs meiosis like I‚Äôm studying for a test, but also include why meiosis increases genetic variation?", "Mitosis and meiosis are both ways cells divide, but they have different purposes and outcomes that you should memorize for a test. Mitosis is used for growth, repair, and asexual reproduction in many organisms: one diploid body cell (2n) divides once to produce two genetically identical diploid daughter cells (2n ‚Üí two 2n cells), keeping the chromosome number the same; DNA replicates once in S phase, then the cell goes through one division with homologous chromosomes not pairing up, and sister chromatids separate in anaphase. Meiosis is used to make gametes (sperm and eggs) for sexual reproduction: one diploid germ cell (2n) replicates its DNA once but divides twice (meiosis I and meiosis II) to produce four genetically unique haploid cells (2n ‚Üí four n cells); in meiosis I, homologous chromosomes pair up as tetrads and then homologs separate (this is the ‚Äúreduction division‚Äù that halves chromosome number), and in meiosis II, sister chromatids separate similar to mitosis. Meiosis increases genetic variation in three main ways that matter for speciation: crossing over (recombination) during prophase I swaps DNA between non-sister chromatids of homologous chromosomes, creating new allele combinations on the same chromosome; independent assortment during metaphase I means each homologous pair lines up randomly, so gametes get different mixes of maternal and paternal chromosomes (in humans this alone can produce 2^23, or about 8.4 million, possible chromosome combinations per gamete before even counting crossing over); and random fertilization then combines two unique gametes, multiplying variation even more. This genetic variation is the raw material for natural selection and can help populations diverge over time, which is why meiosis is tightly connected to speciation, while mitosis mainly preserves genetic consistency in body tissues."),

