    ("Physics: can you show how the work-energy theorem works on a block sliding down a ramp with friction? I don‚Äôt get where the negative work shows up.", "Take a block of mass m that slides a distance d down a ramp at angle Œ∏, starting with speed v0 and ending with speed v. The work‚Äìenergy theorem says the net work done on the block equals the change in kinetic energy: Wnet = ŒîK = (1/2)mv^2 ‚àí (1/2)mv0^2. Along the ramp, gravity has a component parallel to the surface mg sinŒ∏ that points downhill, so gravity does positive work Wg = (mg sinŒ∏)d because the force and the displacement point the same way. The normal force is perpendicular to the motion, so it does zero work. Kinetic friction has magnitude fk = ŒºkN = Œºk(mg cosŒ∏) and it points uphill, opposite the displacement, so its work is negative: Wf = fk d cos(180¬∞) = ‚àífk d = ‚àíŒºk(mg cosŒ∏)d; this ‚Äúnegative work‚Äù shows up because the dot product F ¬∑ d is negative when the force opposes the motion. Putting it together, Wnet = Wg + Wf = mgd sinŒ∏ ‚àí Œºkmgd cosŒ∏, so (1/2)mv^2 ‚àí (1/2)mv0^2 = mgd(sinŒ∏ ‚àí Œºk cosŒ∏), and you can solve for v; the friction term subtracts from the gravity term, meaning friction removes mechanical energy and turns it into thermal energy, which is why the block speeds up less than it would on a frictionless ramp (and if Œºk cosŒ∏ is bigger than sinŒ∏, the net work is negative and the block would slow down instead of speeding up)."),

