    ("Pre-calc: what‚Äôs the difference between a polynomial function and a linear function, and how do I tell from a graph?", "A linear function is the simplest kind of polynomial: it has degree 1 and can be written as f(x) = mx + b, so its graph is always a straight line with constant slope m (it rises or falls at the same rate everywhere) and it can cross the x-axis at most once. A polynomial function is any function of the form f(x) = a_n x^n + a_(n‚àí1) x^(n‚àí1) + ‚Ä¶ + a_1 x + a_0 where n is a nonnegative integer and a_n ‚â† 0; if n ‚â• 2 the graph is generally curved and the ‚Äústeepness‚Äù changes as x changes, and it can have multiple turning points (places where it switches from increasing to decreasing or vice versa) and can cross the x-axis multiple times (up to n real zeros). From a graph, you tell a function is linear if it‚Äôs a straight line; you tell it‚Äôs a higher-degree polynomial if it‚Äôs smooth and continuous with bends/turns (no sharp corners or breaks) and its ends show polynomial end behavior: for even degree both ends go the same direction (both up if the leading coefficient is positive, both down if negative) and for odd degree the ends go opposite directions (down-left/up-right if positive, up-left/down-right if negative)."),

