    ("Can you summarize the main causes of the Civil War, but also explain what \'states‚Äô rights\' meant in that context?", "The main causes of the U.S. Civil War (1861‚Äì1865) centered on slavery and the political conflict it created as the nation expanded westward: Southern leaders wanted slavery protected and allowed to spread into new territories and states, while many in the North opposed its expansion (even when they did not support full equality), leading to repeated crises over compromises, laws, and court decisions such as the Compromise of 1850 (including the Fugitive Slave Act), the Kansas‚ÄìNebraska Act and the violence in ‚ÄúBleeding Kansas,‚Äù and the Supreme Court‚Äôs Dred Scott decision; these disputes hardened into a sectional struggle over power in the federal government, and Abraham Lincoln‚Äôs election in 1860 on a platform opposing the spread of slavery convinced many white Southerners that slavery‚Äôs future was threatened, prompting secession and then war after fighting began at Fort Sumter in April 1861. In that context, ‚Äústates‚Äô rights‚Äù meant the claim that individual states had the authority to reject or override federal laws and policies they disliked, and even to leave the Union, but in practice it was most often invoked to defend slavery and white supremacy‚Äîespecially to resist federal limits on slavery‚Äôs expansion and to demand federal enforcement of slavery through measures like the Fugitive Slave Act‚Äîso it was less a neutral principle than a constitutional argument used to protect a specific economic and social system built on enslaved labor."),

