    ("Why did the Industrial Revolution change where people lived in the U.S.? Like what happened to cities and jobs?", "The Industrial Revolution changed where people lived in the U.S. because new machines and power sources (first water power, then steam and electricity) made it cheaper and faster to produce goods in factories, and factories needed lots of workers all in one place. Before this, many Americans lived on farms or in small towns and did work at home or on the land, but as textile mills, steel mills, meatpacking plants, and other factories grew in the 1800s and early 1900s, jobs shifted from farming and small workshops to wage-paying factory work, plus new city jobs like construction, transportation, and retail. Cities expanded quickly around factories, railroads, ports, and coal and iron regions; people moved from rural areas to urban neighborhoods, and many immigrants also arrived and settled near industrial jobs, which made cities larger, denser, and more diverse but also brought crowded housing and sanitation problems. In short, industry concentrated work in cities, so people followed the jobs, and the U.S. became much more urban as factory-based employment replaced many rural and home-based livelihoods."),

