    ("College math: I‚Äôm reviewing infinite series‚Äîhow do I know if \\(\\sum_{n=1}^{\\infty} \\frac{1}{n^2}\\) converges and what it converges to?", "The series sum from n = 1 to infinity of 1/n^2 converges because it is a p-series with p = 2, and every p-series sum 1/n^p converges when p > 1 (and diverges when p ‚â§ 1), so this one definitely converges. To find what it converges to, this is the classic Basel problem: Euler showed that sum from n = 1 to infinity of 1/n^2 equals pi^2/6, so the exact value of the infinite sum is pi^2/6 (approximately 1.644934). As a quick reasonableness check, the partial sums 1 + 1/4 + 1/9 + 1/16 + ‚Ä¶ increase but the terms shrink fast enough that the total levels off near 1.645, matching pi^2/6."),

