    ("Can you help me debug this? My C program for a cache simulator runs but the hit rate is wrong. What are the most common mistakes with set indexing + tag extraction?", "The most common reasons a cache simulator ‚Äúruns‚Äù but reports the wrong hit rate are off-by-some-bits errors in how you split an address into block offset, set index, and tag, plus subtle masking/shifting mistakes. Start by confirming you are using the correct number of offset bits b = log2(block_size_bytes) and set index bits s = log2(number_of_sets), and that you compute set_index = (address >> b) & ((1ULL << s) 1) and tag = address >> (b + s); a frequent bug is accidentally using the total cache size or associativity when computing s, or using bytes vs words inconsistently so b is wrong. Another very common mistake is using 32-bit types (unsigned int) for addresses on 64-bit traces, which truncates upper bits and makes tags collide, so use uint64_t/unsigned long long and 1ULL in masks; similarly, shifting by the wrong amount (using b+s-1, or forgetting parentheses) or building the mask with (1<<s) instead of (1ULL<<s) can silently overflow and produce a bad index. Also watch for mixing ‚Äúnumber of lines‚Äù with ‚Äúnumber of sets‚Äù (sets = lines / associativity), forgetting that block offset bits depend on block size not on cache size, and accidentally including the offset bits in the tag (tag should exclude both offset and index). Finally, ensure you are indexing sets with the post-offset bits (address >> b), not the raw address, and that you treat addresses as byte addresses (as most traces do); if your trace is in hex byte addresses but you assume word addresses, every access maps to the wrong set and tag and the hit rate will be consistently off. A quick sanity check is to print, for a few known addresses, the computed b, s, set_index, and tag and verify that two addresses within the same block differ only in offset, two addresses in different sets differ in index, and two addresses mapping to the same set but different blocks differ in tag."),

