    ("For stats, how do I decide whether to use a t-test, chi-square test, or ANOVA? I always freeze when I see the problem statement.", "Decide based on what kind of variables you have and what question you‚Äôre asking: if your outcome (dependent variable) is quantitative/continuous (like height, blood pressure, test score) and you want to compare average values between groups, use a t-test when there are exactly two groups (independent-samples t-test for two separate groups like treatment vs control, paired t-test for the same people measured twice like before vs after), and use ANOVA when there are three or more groups (one-way ANOVA for one grouping variable; it tests whether at least one group mean differs, and if it‚Äôs significant you typically follow with post-hoc comparisons like Tukey to see which groups differ). If your variables are categorical (like yes/no, smoker/non-smoker, party affiliation) and you‚Äôre comparing counts or proportions, use a chi-square test: chi-square test of independence for a contingency table (are two categorical variables associated?) and chi-square goodness-of-fit for one categorical variable (do observed counts match expected proportions?). A quick ‚Äúfreeze-proof‚Äù checklist is: ask ‚ÄúIs the outcome numeric or categorical?‚Äù Numeric points you toward t-test/ANOVA (means), categorical points you toward chi-square (counts/proportions); then ask ‚ÄúHow many groups or categories am I comparing?‚Äù Two groups suggests t-test, three or more suggests ANOVA, and for chi-square you‚Äôre usually looking at a table of counts across categories. Also sanity-check assumptions: t-tests/ANOVA assume independent observations, roughly normal residuals within groups (especially important for small samples), and similar variances across groups (Welch‚Äôs t-test or Welch‚Äôs ANOVA are good when variances differ), while chi-square assumes independent observations and expected cell counts that aren‚Äôt too small (a common rule of thumb is most expected counts at least 5; if not, consider Fisher‚Äôs exact test for a 2x2 table)."),

