    ("I need to compute the concentration after mixing two NaCl solutions (one is 0.20 M, one is 0.50 M) with different volumes. Can you walk me through the setup so I stop messing up the units?", "To find the concentration after mixing two NaCl solutions, the key idea is that moles add but molarities do not, so you convert each solution to moles, add them, then divide by the total final volume: moles1 = M1 √ó V1 and moles2 = M2 √ó V2, where V must be in liters (so if you‚Äôre given mL, divide by 1000 first), then Mfinal = (moles1 + moles2) / (V1 + V2). For your case, if the 0.20 M solution has volume V0.20 and the 0.50 M solution has volume V0.50 (both in liters), then Mfinal = (0.20√óV0.20 + 0.50√óV0.50)/(V0.20 + V0.50); for example, mixing 100 mL of 0.20 M with 250 mL of 0.50 M means V0.20 = 0.100 L and V0.50 = 0.250 L, so total moles = 0.20√ó0.100 + 0.50√ó0.250 = 0.020 + 0.125 = 0.145 mol and total volume = 0.100 + 0.250 = 0.350 L, giving Mfinal = 0.145/0.350 = 0.414 M (and the units work out because mol/L is M). A quick sanity check is that the final molarity must lie between 0.20 M and 0.50 M and be closer to the one with the larger volume; here it‚Äôs closer to 0.50 M because more of the 0.50 M solution was used."),

