    ("In distributed systems, what‚Äôs the difference between strong consistency and eventual consistency, like in plain terms but with an example scenario?", "Strong consistency means that after a write completes, every client reading the data from any replica will immediately see that same newest value, as if there were only one copy of the data; eventual consistency means replicas are allowed to be temporarily out of sync, so a read might return an older value for a while, but if no new updates happen the replicas will converge and eventually all reads will return the latest value. For example, imagine a bank balance stored on servers in two regions: with strong consistency, if you deposit $100 and the app says ‚Äúdeposit successful,‚Äù then checking your balance from any region right after will show the updated balance; with eventual consistency, the deposit might be recorded in one region first and copied to the other shortly afterward, so if you check immediately from the other region you might still see the old balance for a few seconds, and only later will both regions show the new balance. In plain terms, strong consistency prioritizes ‚Äúeveryone sees the same thing right now,‚Äù while eventual consistency prioritizes ‚Äúthe system stays fast and available even if different places briefly disagree, but they‚Äôll catch up.‚Äù"),

