    ("Can you explain how a transistor works at a high level (BJT vs MOSFET) and why people say MOSFETs are ‚Äúvoltage-controlled‚Äù?", "At a high level, a transistor is an electronic valve that lets a small input signal control a larger current between two terminals. In a BJT (bipolar junction transistor), the key idea is current control: a small base-emitter current forward-biases a junction and injects charge carriers, which allows a much larger collector-to-emitter current to flow; roughly, the collector current is proportional to base current (often described as Ic ‚âà Œ≤Ib in the active region), and because the base-emitter junction behaves like a diode, you typically need about 0.6‚Äì0.8 V across base-emitter for a silicon BJT to conduct appreciably, and you must keep supplying base current to keep it on. In a MOSFET (metal-oxide-semiconductor FET), the key idea is electric-field control: the gate is insulated from the channel by a thin oxide, so applying a gate-to-source voltage creates an electric field that attracts or repels carriers and forms (or enhances) a conductive channel between drain and source; once Vgs exceeds a threshold voltage (Vth), the device can conduct, and the drain current is mainly set by Vgs and the circuit conditions rather than by a steady gate current. People call MOSFETs ‚Äúvoltage-controlled‚Äù because, ideally, essentially no DC current flows into the gate due to the insulation, so the input is primarily a voltage that sets an electric field; in real life the gate still draws transient current when you change the voltage because you must charge and discharge the gate capacitance (and there can be small leakage), which is why MOSFETs are easy to drive for steady states but can require significant peak current for fast switching. By contrast, BJTs are often called ‚Äúcurrent-controlled‚Äù because the base-emitter junction must be forward-biased and continuously fed with base current to sustain conduction, even though the exact collector current also depends on base-emitter voltage and operating region; in short, BJTs use injected charge and base current to control conduction, while MOSFETs use an electric field from a gate voltage to control a channel with near-zero steady gate current."),

