    ("In Earth science, what causes tectonic plates to move and why do earthquakes happen mostly near plate boundaries?", "Tectonic plates move because Earth‚Äôs internal heat, left over from when the planet formed and continually produced by radioactive decay inside the mantle, makes the mantle‚Äôs hot rock slowly circulate like a very thick fluid; this circulation, along with gravity, pushes and pulls the rigid plates at the surface. Two key forces are ridge push, where new, hot, elevated crust forms at mid-ocean ridges and slides downhill under its own weight, and slab pull, where a cold, dense oceanic plate sinks at a subduction zone and drags the rest of the plate behind it. Earthquakes happen mostly near plate boundaries because that‚Äôs where plates interact by colliding, pulling apart, or sliding past each other, causing stress to build up as rocks lock due to friction; when the stress becomes too great, the rocks suddenly break or slip along faults, releasing stored energy as seismic waves. Plate interiors usually deform much more slowly and have fewer active faults, so large earthquakes are far less common there than at boundaries."),

