    ("Pre-calc question: what‚Äôs the difference between sine and cosine on the unit circle, and how do I remember which one is x and which is y?", "On the unit circle (a circle of radius 1 centered at the origin), an angle Œ∏ is measured from the positive x-axis, and the point where the terminal side of the angle hits the circle has coordinates (x, y) = (cos Œ∏, sin Œ∏). That means cosine is the x-coordinate (how far left/right the point is) and sine is the y-coordinate (how far up/down the point is), so the main ‚Äúdifference‚Äù on the unit circle is simply which coordinate each one gives you; both are ratios tied to the same angle, but cosine tracks horizontal position and sine tracks vertical position. A reliable way to remember is ‚Äúcos goes with x‚Äù because both start with a ‚Äúco‚Äù sound (cos‚Äìx is a common memory trick), or think ‚Äúsine is ‚Äòsin‚Äôking or rising‚Äù like vertical height, while cosine is the ‚Äúco‚Äùmpanion along the x-axis; you can also check quickly with Œ∏ = 0¬∞, where the point is (1, 0), so cos 0 = 1 and sin 0 = 0, confirming cosine is x and sine is y."),

