    ("US Gov: How does a bill actually become a law in Congress? Like what are the real steps it can get stuck on?", "A bill becomes a law through a series of gatekeeping steps where it can easily stall: first a member of the House or Senate introduces it and it is referred to one or more committees (often with subcommittees) that can hold hearings, rewrite it (‚Äúmark up‚Äù), or simply never schedule it, which is one of the most common ways bills die; if the committee approves it, it goes to the full chamber where the Rules Committee in the House can limit debate and amendments, while in the Senate debate is usually more open and a bill can get stuck in a filibuster unless 60 senators vote for cloture to end debate, and then the chamber votes to pass or reject it. If both chambers pass different versions, it must be reconciled (often in a conference committee) and then both the House and Senate must pass the same final text, which is another frequent sticking point; after that it goes to the President, who can sign it into law or veto it, and Congress can override a veto only with a two-thirds vote in both chambers, while if the President takes no action for 10 days (excluding Sundays) it becomes law unless Congress has adjourned, in which case it can be killed by a pocket veto. In real life, bills most often get stuck because committee leaders don‚Äôt move them, party leaders don‚Äôt schedule floor time, the Senate filibuster blocks them, the House and Senate can‚Äôt agree on a single version, or the President vetoes them."),

