    ("I‚Äôm confused about the Constitution: what‚Äôs the difference between federalism and separation of powers, and how are they shown in the U.S. system?", "Federalism and separation of powers are two different ways the Constitution prevents too much power from piling up in one place: federalism divides power vertically between levels of government, while separation of powers divides power horizontally within the national government. Federalism means the United States has a national (federal) government with certain enumerated powers, like regulating interstate and foreign commerce, coining money, and providing for national defense, while the states keep broad ‚Äúpolice powers‚Äù over most everyday matters like education, local law enforcement, and many health and safety rules; this is shown in the Constitution by Article I, Section 8 listing Congress‚Äôs powers, by the Supremacy Clause in Article VI making valid federal law the ‚Äúsupreme Law of the Land,‚Äù and by the Tenth Amendment emphasizing that powers not delegated to the United States nor prohibited to the states are reserved to the states or the people. Separation of powers means the federal government itself is split into three branches with different jobs so each can check the others: Article I creates Congress to make laws, Article II creates the President to enforce laws, and Article III creates the federal courts to interpret laws; you can see the checks and balances in features like presidential vetoes and Congress‚Äôs power to override them, the Senate‚Äôs role in confirming judges and top officials, Congress‚Äôs power of impeachment, and judicial review (recognized in Marbury v. Madison in 1803) allowing courts to strike down unconstitutional laws. In short, federalism answers ‚Äúwhich level of government‚Äîstate or national‚Äîgets this power?‚Äù while separation of powers answers ‚Äúwhich branch‚Äîlegislative, executive, or judicial‚Äîgets this power?‚Äù and the U.S. system uses both at the same time to protect liberty and limit government."),

