    ("i‚Äôm doing a poster about the carbon cycle. what even IS it and why do trees matter", "The carbon cycle is the continuous movement of carbon atoms between the air, living things, water, and rocks, and it matters because carbon is the backbone of life and also forms carbon dioxide (CO2), a greenhouse gas that affects Earth‚Äôs temperature. In the fast part of the cycle, plants take CO2 out of the atmosphere during photosynthesis and use the carbon to build sugars, wood, leaves, and roots; animals get that carbon by eating plants (or other animals), and both plants and animals return carbon to the air as CO2 through respiration, while decomposers like fungi and bacteria break down dead organisms and waste and release more CO2 (and sometimes methane in low-oxygen places like swamps). Carbon also moves into oceans where CO2 dissolves and can be used by marine life, and over very long timescales some carbon becomes locked away in sediments and rocks (like limestone) or stored underground as fossil fuels; volcanoes and the burning of fossil fuels return some of that long-stored carbon back to the atmosphere as CO2. Trees matter because they are powerful ‚Äúcarbon sinks‚Äù: as they grow, they pull CO2 from the air and store that carbon in their trunks, branches, roots, and in soils, often for decades to centuries, which helps lower the amount of CO2 in the atmosphere; when trees are cut down, burned, or decay, much of that stored carbon is released back as CO2, and losing forests also removes a major pathway for taking CO2 out of the air. For your poster, a simple way to remember it is ‚Äúphotosynthesis stores carbon, respiration and decay return it, oceans and rocks store it long-term, and human activities like deforestation and burning fossil fuels add extra CO2 faster than the natural cycle can remove it.‚Äù"),

