    ("We‚Äôre doing a design thinking project‚Äîcan you give brainstorming techniques that aren‚Äôt just ‚Äòwrite ideas‚Äô (like structured methods)?", "Try a few structured ideation methods that force new angles instead of ‚Äújust writing ideas‚Äù: start with Crazy 8s, where each person folds a page into eight panels and sketches eight different solutions in eight minutes to push past the obvious; use SCAMPER by taking an existing product or process and asking prompts like Substitute, Combine, Adapt, Modify/Magnify/Minify, Put to another use, Eliminate, and Reverse/Rearrange to systematically generate variants; do ‚ÄúHow Might We‚Äù reframing by turning insights into open-ended questions (for example, ‚ÄúHow might we help first-time users feel confident in 30 seconds?‚Äù) and then ideate specifically against each question; run a 6-3-5 brainwriting round where six people each sketch or describe three ideas in five minutes, then pass the sheet to build on others‚Äô ideas for several rounds; use the Lotus Blossom technique by placing a central challenge in the middle, surrounding it with eight related sub-themes, then expanding each sub-theme into eight more ideas to explore the space thoroughly; apply a Morphological Matrix by listing key dimensions of the solution (like user, channel, trigger, incentive, feedback) and multiple options for each, then mixing and matching combinations to create novel concepts; do Worst Possible Idea (and then invert it) to reduce fear of judgment and reveal hidden constraints, turning ‚Äúmake it confusing and slow‚Äù into concrete design principles like ‚Äúmake it instantly understandable and fast‚Äù; try role-storming by ideating as different personas (a child, an expert, a skeptical CFO, a customer support agent) to surface needs you‚Äôd miss; and finish with dot voting plus an ‚Äúimpact vs effort‚Äù sorting to converge, followed by a quick ‚Äúassumption smash‚Äù where you list what must be true for the top ideas and generate tests or tweaks to make them more feasible."),

