    ("We‚Äôre doing magnets in science‚Äîwhy do like poles repel but opposite poles attract? explain it like not too babyish lol", "Magnets create an invisible magnetic field around them, and the ‚Äúnorth‚Äù and ‚Äúsouth‚Äù labels really mean the field lines leave the magnet at the north pole and enter at the south pole. The field lines act like stretched rubber bands that prefer to connect smoothly from north to south, so when you bring opposite poles together (north facing south), the field lines can link up neatly and the magnets move together to lower the energy stored in the field, which we feel as attraction. When you bring like poles together (north facing north or south facing south), the field lines are trying to go the same direction in the space between the magnets, so they crowd and bend away from each other; that ‚Äúsqueezing‚Äù and distortion raises the field‚Äôs energy, and the magnets push apart to get to a lower-energy arrangement, which we feel as repulsion. A helpful way to picture it is that opposite poles let the field ‚Äúflow‚Äù smoothly between magnets, while like poles force the field to detour and spread out, and the magnets move in whatever direction makes the overall field pattern simpler and lower-energy."),

