    ("We started descriptive statistics‚Äîwhat‚Äôs the difference between mean, median, mode, and when should you use each?", "The mean, median, and mode are three different ways to describe the ‚Äúcenter‚Äù of a dataset, and they can give different answers depending on the shape of the data. The mean is the arithmetic average (add all values and divide by the number of values); it uses every data point, which makes it very useful for things like ‚Äúper person‚Äù totals and for further calculations, but it is sensitive to extreme values (outliers). The median is the middle value after sorting the data (or the average of the two middle values if there is an even number of observations); it is much more resistant to outliers and is usually the best single ‚Äútypical‚Äù value for skewed data like incomes, house prices, or waiting times. The mode is the most frequent value (or category) in the dataset; it is especially useful for categorical data where mean and median may not even make sense (for example, the most common shoe size sold, the most common blood type in a sample, or the most common response on a survey), and it can also be helpful for numerical data when you care about the most common outcome (like the most common number of calls per hour), noting that some datasets have no mode (all values occur once) or can be multimodal (two or more peaks). A quick way to choose is: use the mean for roughly symmetric distributions without extreme outliers and when you need an average that reflects totals; use the median when the distribution is skewed or has big outliers and you want a robust ‚Äútypical‚Äù value; use the mode when you want the most common value or you are working with categories. For example, with incomes 30k, 32k, 35k, 38k, and 300k, the mean is 87k (pulled up by the outlier), the median is 35k (more representative of most people), and the mode doesn‚Äôt exist because no value repeats; with values 1, 2, 2, 2, 10, the mean is 3.4, the median is 2, and the mode is 2, showing how the mode highlights the most common result while the mean is pulled upward by 10."),

