    ("i dont really understand what the Constitution DOES‚Ä¶ like why do we have it and what are amendments in normal words?", "The U.S. Constitution is basically the country‚Äôs rulebook for how the national government is built and what it is allowed to do: it creates the three branches (Congress makes laws, the President carries them out, and the courts interpret them), explains how leaders are chosen, and sets limits so no one part gets too powerful, which helps protect people‚Äôs freedom. We have it so the government can‚Äôt just change the rules whenever it wants; it gives a stable plan everyone can point to, and it also says some powers belong to the federal government while other powers are left to the states and the people. Amendments are official changes or additions to that rulebook, used because the country learns and grows over time; the first ten amendments are called the Bill of Rights (added in 1791) and they spell out important protections like freedom of speech and religion, fair rules for criminal cases, and limits on government searches, and later amendments did things like end slavery (13th, 1865), guarantee equal protection and due process (14th, 1868), and protect voting rights for more people (15th, 1870; 19th, 1920; 26th, 1971). An easy way to think of it is: the Constitution sets up the game and the referees, and amendments are the agreed-upon updates to the rules when the country decides the old rules need to be improved."),

