    ("What‚Äôs the difference between Congress and the Supreme Court? I keep mixing up what each one‚Äôs job is", "Congress and the Supreme Court are in two different branches of the U.S. government and they do different jobs: Congress is the lawmaking branch (the Legislative Branch), so its main role is to write, debate, and vote on bills that can become laws, approve the federal budget and taxes, and oversee the executive branch, while the Supreme Court is the highest court in the Judicial Branch, so its main role is to decide how the Constitution and federal laws should be interpreted when there‚Äôs a real legal case or controversy. A simple way to remember it is that Congress creates the rules for the country, and the Supreme Court answers questions like ‚ÄúWhat does this law mean?‚Äù or ‚ÄúDoes this law violate the Constitution?‚Äù, and if it does, the Court can strike it down, but it cannot write new laws the way Congress can. Congress has two parts, the House of Representatives and the Senate, with hundreds of elected members from states and districts, while the Supreme Court has nine justices who are nominated by the President and confirmed by the Senate and serve for life (unless they retire or are removed through impeachment)."),

