    ("What‚Äôs the difference between a strong acid and a weak acid (like HCl vs acetic acid) and how does that affect pH?", "A strong acid and a weak acid differ in how completely they ionize (dissociate) in water to produce hydronium ions, H3O+ (often written as H+). A strong acid like hydrochloric acid, HCl, is essentially 100% dissociated in dilute aqueous solution, so nearly every HCl formula unit produces an H3O+ and a Cl‚àí, which means the hydronium concentration is roughly equal to the acid‚Äôs initial concentration; for example, 0.10 M HCl gives about 0.10 M H3O+, so pH = ‚àílog(0.10) = 1.00. A weak acid like acetic acid, CH3COOH, only partially dissociates (CH3COOH + H2O ‚áå H3O+ + CH3COO‚àí), so at the same starting concentration it produces far fewer H3O+ ions and therefore has a higher pH; using Ka ‚âà 1.8 √ó 10‚àí5 for acetic acid, a 0.10 M solution has [H3O+] ‚âà ‚àö(Ka¬∑C) ‚âà ‚àö(1.8 √ó 10‚àí6) ‚âà 1.3 √ó 10‚àí3 M, giving pH ‚âà 2.87. The key pH effect is that, at equal molar concentration, strong acids drive [H3O+] much higher and pH much lower, while weak acids establish an equilibrium that limits [H3O+]; also, diluting any acid raises pH, but weak acids‚Äô pH changes in a way that depends on both concentration and Ka because the percent dissociation increases as you dilute."),

