    ("What does the Supreme Court actually do, and can you give a simple example of a case that changed students‚Äô rights?", "The U.S. Supreme Court is the highest court in the federal system, and what it actually does is decide a small number of real legal disputes that raise important questions about the U.S. Constitution or federal law; by interpreting what the Constitution and laws mean, it settles disagreements among lower courts, reviews whether government actions follow the Constitution, and its written decisions become precedents that lower federal courts must follow (and that state courts generally follow when federal rights are involved), which is why it can effectively change how rights work nationwide. A simple students‚Äô rights example is Tinker v. Des Moines Independent Community School District (1969): several students were suspended for wearing black armbands to school to protest the Vietnam War, and the Supreme Court ruled that students do not ‚Äúshed their constitutional rights to freedom of speech or expression at the schoolhouse gate,‚Äù meaning public schools can‚Äôt punish student expression just because they dislike the message, although schools may limit it if it would materially and substantially disrupt class or invade the rights of others. This case changed students‚Äô rights by making clear that student speech is protected under the First Amendment in public schools, setting a rule that schools still use today when deciding what kinds of student expression they can and cannot restrict."),

