    ("Can you explain the Bill of Rights like I‚Äôm not five but also not a lawyer? I need it for a civics quiz.", "The Bill of Rights is the name for the first ten amendments added to the U.S. Constitution in 1791, and its basic job is to limit what the federal government can do to people by protecting individual freedoms and setting rules for fair treatment. In plain language: the 1st Amendment protects freedom of religion (the government can‚Äôt force a religion or stop you from practicing one), speech, the press, peaceful assembly, and the right to petition the government; the 2nd involves the right to keep and bear arms; the 3rd stops the government from forcing people to house soldiers in their homes in peacetime; the 4th protects you from unreasonable searches and seizures and usually requires a warrant based on probable cause; the 5th says you can‚Äôt be tried twice for the same crime (double jeopardy), you can‚Äôt be forced to testify against yourself, you can‚Äôt be deprived of life, liberty, or property without due process of law, and the government must pay fair compensation if it takes private property for public use (eminent domain); the 6th guarantees key criminal trial rights like a speedy and public trial, an impartial jury, being told the charges, confronting witnesses, getting witnesses in your favor, and having a lawyer; the 7th preserves the right to a jury trial in many civil (non-criminal) lawsuits in federal court; the 8th bans excessive bail and fines and cruel and unusual punishments; the 9th says that just because some rights are listed doesn‚Äôt mean people have no other rights; and the 10th says powers not given to the federal government (and not forbidden to the states) are reserved to the states or the people. A helpful way to remember it is that the Bill of Rights is mostly about protecting personal freedoms (especially in the 1st), protecting privacy and fairness when the government investigates or prosecutes you (4th‚Äì8th), and reminding everyone that the federal government has limited powers and people keep many rights beyond what‚Äôs written down (9th‚Äì10th)."),

