    ("For US History, what were the biggest causes of the Civil War? My teacher said not just slavery but I‚Äôm confused.", "The biggest causes of the U.S. Civil War (1861‚Äì1865) all connect back to slavery, but it helps to see how slavery created several overlapping conflicts that finally broke the country apart. The central issue was slavery‚Äôs expansion: as the United States grew westward, Americans fought over whether new territories and future states would allow slavery, because that decision would determine political power in Congress and the long-term future of slavery itself; key flashpoints included the Missouri Compromise (1820), the Compromise of 1850 (including a stricter Fugitive Slave Act), the Kansas‚ÄìNebraska Act (1854) which led to violent ‚ÄúBleeding Kansas,‚Äù and the Dred Scott decision (1857) which said Congress could not ban slavery in the territories. A second major cause was the clash between Southern slaveholding states and the federal government over authority and rights: Southern leaders argued states could nullify federal laws or even secede, while many in the North argued the Union was permanent and federal law had to be enforced; this ‚Äústates‚Äô rights‚Äù debate mattered most because it was repeatedly used to defend slavery and protect it from national limits. A third cause was the growing economic and social divide between North and South: the North was becoming more industrial and urban with more wage labor, while the South‚Äôs economy depended heavily on plantation agriculture (especially cotton) and enslaved labor, leading to different views on tariffs, banking, and national policy, even though these disputes alone did not cause war without the slavery question underneath. Finally, the immediate triggers were political and sectional breakdown in the 1850s and the election of Abraham Lincoln in 1860 on a platform opposing the spread of slavery (not immediate abolition where it already existed); many Southern leaders saw this as a threat to slavery‚Äôs future and chose secession, forming the Confederate States of America, and the war began when Confederate forces fired on Fort Sumter in April 1861. So when teachers say ‚Äúnot just slavery,‚Äù they usually mean slavery was the core cause, but it produced multiple connected disputes‚Äîover expansion, political power, federal versus state authority, and sectional economies‚Äîthat together led to secession and war."),

