    ("Can you help me brainstorm techniques for studying for finals? I get overwhelmed and then I don‚Äôt start.", "When finals feel overwhelming, the goal is to make starting so small and clear that your brain doesn‚Äôt treat it like a threat. Try a ‚Äútiny start‚Äù rule: set a 5-minute timer and do only one micro-task such as opening your notes and writing a short list of what topics are on the exam, or doing just one practice problem; once you‚Äôve started, it‚Äôs much easier to keep going, and if you stop after 5 minutes you still succeeded. Next, turn ‚Äústudy‚Äù into a simple plan by doing a quick brain-dump of everything you think you need to cover, then circle the highest-impact items (what‚Äôs most likely on the test or what you‚Äôre weakest at) and pick just one for today; if it helps, use a ‚Äúnext action‚Äù list that‚Äôs specific like ‚Äúreview Chapter 5 vocab for 10 minutes‚Äù instead of ‚Äústudy biology.‚Äù Use short, repeatable work blocks such as 25 minutes on, 5 minutes off (or even 15/5 if you‚Äôre really stuck), and decide in advance what you‚Äôll do in that block so you don‚Äôt waste energy choosing. Make your studying active, because rereading feels safer but works less well: test yourself with practice questions, cover-and-recall (read a section, close it, explain it from memory), flashcards, or teaching the idea out loud as if you‚Äôre tutoring someone. If anxiety spikes, do a ‚Äúmessy first pass‚Äù: skim headings, look at past quizzes, and do easy questions first to build momentum, then return to harder ones; progress reduces overwhelm. Also reduce friction by setting up your environment before you start (water, charger, one tab open, phone in another room) and use a simple reward like ‚Äúafter one work block, I get a snack or a short walk.‚Äù If you tell me what subjects you‚Äôre studying, how many days you have, and what feels hardest (starting, focusing, or knowing what to do), I can help you turn this into a realistic schedule for the week."),

