    ("Can you help me debug this C code? My bitwise operations are giving weird results when I shift signed ints. What‚Äôs the difference between arithmetic vs logical shift in practice?", "In C, the ‚Äúweird‚Äù results usually come from the fact that right-shifting a signed negative int is not guaranteed to behave the same on every compiler/CPU: an arithmetic right shift copies the sign bit (the top bit) into the newly created high bits, so negative numbers stay negative (for example, on a typical 32-bit two‚Äôs-complement machine, -4 is 0xFFFFFFFC and (-4 >> 1) becomes 0xFFFFFFFE, which is -2), while a logical right shift always shifts in zeros (so 0xFFFFFFFC logically shifted right by 1 becomes 0x7FFFFFFE, a large positive number). In practice, most mainstream compilers on two‚Äôs-complement targets implement signed right shift as arithmetic, but the C standard says right shift of a negative signed value is implementation-defined, so you cannot rely on it being arithmetic everywhere; left shift of a signed value that overflows (or shifting a negative left) is undefined behavior, which can also produce ‚Äúimpossible‚Äù results under optimization. The reliable debugging rule is: if you want a logical shift, cast to an unsigned type before shifting (for example, (uint32_t)x >> n), and if you want an arithmetic shift, either ensure you‚Äôre on a platform where it‚Äôs defined the way you expect or implement it explicitly (for example, shift an unsigned value and then manually fill the top bits based on the original sign); also print values in hex (printf(\"%08x\", (uint32_t)x)) so you can see the actual bit patterns you‚Äôre manipulating."),

