    ("Can you show me how to prove this limit using epsilon-delta: lim(x‚Üí2) (3x + 1) = 7? I keep mixing up what I‚Äôm allowed to choose first.", "To prove lim(x‚Üí2) (3x + 1) = 7 using the epsilon-delta definition, you start by stating what you must show: for every Œµ > 0 (Œµ is chosen first by the person challenging the limit), you must find a Œ¥ > 0 (you are allowed to choose Œ¥ depending on Œµ) such that whenever 0 < |x ‚àí 2| < Œ¥, it follows that |(3x + 1) ‚àí 7| < Œµ. Now simplify the expression you need to control: |(3x + 1) ‚àí 7| = |3x + 1 ‚àí 7| = |3x ‚àí 6| = |3(x ‚àí 2)| = 3|x ‚àí 2|. So you want 3|x ‚àí 2| < Œµ, which will be guaranteed if you make |x ‚àí 2| < Œµ/3. This tells you exactly how to choose Œ¥: given any Œµ > 0, let Œ¥ = Œµ/3. Then if 0 < |x ‚àí 2| < Œ¥, you get |(3x + 1) ‚àí 7| = 3|x ‚àí 2| < 3Œ¥ = 3(Œµ/3) = Œµ, which is exactly the required inequality, so the limit is proven. The key ‚Äúwho chooses what first‚Äù rule is: Œµ is arbitrary and comes first, and Œ¥ is your response, chosen after seeing Œµ, to make the implication work."),

