    ("I‚Äôm doing descriptive stats for a psych experiment. What‚Äôs the difference between standard deviation and standard error, and when should I report each?", "Standard deviation (SD) describes how much individual observations vary around the sample mean, so it answers ‚Äúhow spread out are participants‚Äô scores (or trials)?‚Äù and is in the same units as the measure; for a sample it‚Äôs computed as s = sqrt(Œ£(x ‚àí xÃÑ)¬≤/(n ‚àí 1)). Standard error (SE), usually the standard error of the mean (SEM), describes how much the sample mean would vary from sample to sample if you repeated the experiment many times, so it answers ‚Äúhow precisely have I estimated the population mean?‚Äù and it shrinks as sample size grows; for the mean, SEM = s/‚àön (more generally, SE is the estimated standard deviation of an estimator). In a psych experiment, report SD when you want to describe the distribution/variability of the data (descriptive statistics, individual differences, plots of raw scores), and report SE when you are specifically communicating uncertainty/precision of an estimated mean (or other parameter), but for inference it‚Äôs usually clearer to report a confidence interval (for example, mean with a 95% CI, which is roughly mean ¬± t√óSE) rather than ‚Äúmean ¬± SE,‚Äù because SD and SE answer different questions and ‚Äú¬±SE‚Äù is often misread as showing data spread. A good rule of thumb is: SD = variability of the data; SE/CI = uncertainty about an estimate, so choose based on whether you‚Äôre describing participants‚Äô scores or the precision of your mean (or effect) estimate."),

