    ("In digital logic, I need to simplify this boolean expression and draw the circuit: F = (A + B)(A\' + C). Can you do it using algebra + Karnaugh map?", "Start by simplifying algebraically: F = (A + B)(A\' + C) = (A + B)A\' + (A + B)C = AA\' + BA\' + AC + BC = 0 + A\'B + AC + BC, and then use the consensus theorem XY + X\'Z + YZ = XY + X\'Z with X = A, Y = C, Z = B to drop the redundant term BC, giving the minimal form F = AC + A\'B. To confirm with a Karnaugh map, note this is a 3-variable function of A, B, C (no D): F = 1 when A = 0 and B = 1 (regardless of C), which are minterms m2 and m3, and when A = 1 and C = 1 (regardless of B), which are minterms m5 and m7, so the 1s are at m2, m3, m5, m7; on the 3-variable K-map (A as rows 0/1, BC as columns in Gray order 00, 01, 11, 10), you group m2‚Äìm3 as a pair to get A\'B and m5‚Äìm7 as a pair to get AC, yielding the same minimal SOP F = A\'B + AC (equivalently, it can be written as a 2:1 MUX form F = A\'B + AC = A ? C : B). The circuit is therefore two AND gates feeding one OR gate: one AND takes A and C to produce AC, the other AND takes NOT A and B to produce A\'B (so you need one inverter on A), and the OR gate combines them to output F; a compact implementation is also a 2-to-1 multiplexer with select A, where input 0 is B and input 1 is C."),

