    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 04:56 - Category: digital_logic
    ("I‚Äôm in a college intro CS class‚Äîcan you explain what a transistor does in a computer and how that connects to digital logic (AND/OR/NOT)?", "A transistor is a tiny electronic switch (or, in some circuits, an amplifier) that lets a small electrical signal control a larger current; in modern computers the key idea is switching, where the transistor is driven into one of two stable regions: ‚Äúoff‚Äù (it blocks current) or ‚Äúon‚Äù (it conducts). By choosing a voltage range to represent logic 0 and another range to represent logic 1, a transistor‚Äôs on/off behavior becomes a physical way to store and manipulate bits: a node pulled toward ground when a transistor turns on can represent 0, and a node pulled toward a supply voltage when a transistor turns off (letting a pull-up device act) can represent 1, or vice versa depending on the convention. Digital logic gates are built by wiring transistors so that the output voltage depends on the combination of input voltages: the simplest is NOT (an inverter), where one transistor network connects the output to ground when the input is 1, and another connects the output to the supply when the input is 0, flipping the bit. AND and OR are then made by combining transistor ‚Äúswitches‚Äù in series and parallel: in a common CMOS implementation, an AND function is often built as a NAND gate (series transistors in the pull-down path mean the output is pulled low only when both inputs are 1) followed by a NOT to invert it into AND, while an OR is often built as a NOR gate (parallel transistors in the pull-down path mean the output is pulled low when either input is 1) followed by a NOT to get OR. The big connection is that Boolean logic rules (AND/OR/NOT truth tables) map directly onto how series connections require multiple transistors to be on to create a conducting path, and parallel connections allow any one of several transistors to create that path; by composing these gates, billions of transistors can implement adders, registers, and ultimately the CPU operations your programs run."),

