    ("college stats: i have this dataset [4, 6, 6, 9, 12]. can you compute mean/median/standard deviation and explain what they tell me", "For the dataset [4, 6, 6, 9, 12], the mean (average) is (4+6+6+9+12)/5 = 37/5 = 7.4, which tells you the typical value if the total were shared evenly across all five observations. The median (middle value when sorted) is 6 because the ordered list is 4, 6, 6, 9, 12 and the third value is 6; the median tells you the central value and is less affected by unusually high or low numbers than the mean. For standard deviation, first find deviations from the mean 7.4: -3.4, -1.4, -1.4, 1.6, 4.6; square them: 11.56, 1.96, 1.96, 2.56, 21.16, which sum to 39.2; the population variance is 39.2/5 = 7.84 so the population standard deviation is sqrt(7.84) = 2.8, while the sample variance is 39.2/4 = 9.8 so the sample standard deviation is sqrt(9.8) ‚âà 3.13 (use this sample version if these five values are a sample from a larger group). Standard deviation measures spread around the mean, so a value around 2.8‚Äì3.13 means most data points are typically about 3 units away from 7.4; here the mean (7.4) is higher than the median (6), suggesting the larger values (9 and especially 12) pull the average upward."),

