    ("Why do magnets stick to some metals but not like aluminum? Also what‚Äôs the difference between north and south poles?", "Magnets ‚Äústick‚Äù well only to materials that are ferromagnetic, meaning they contain lots of atoms whose magnetic moments can group into regions called domains that can easily line up together; when a magnet is brought near iron, nickel, cobalt, and many (but not all) steels, it forces many domains to align, turning the metal into a strong temporary magnet and creating a strong pull, while most other metals don‚Äôt form domains that line up strongly, so the force is tiny. Aluminum is not ferromagnetic, so a normal magnet won‚Äôt stick to it; it is actually very weakly attracted (paramagnetic), but the effect is so small you usually can‚Äôt feel it unless you use a very strong magnet and special setups, and some materials are weakly repelled (diamagnetic) instead. Every magnet has two poles, called north and south, which are the two ends where the magnetic field is strongest; opposite poles attract (north pulls on south) and like poles repel (north pushes away north, south pushes away south), and the names come from how a freely suspended magnet points‚Äîits ‚Äúnorth‚Äù end points roughly toward Earth‚Äôs geographic North because it is attracted to Earth‚Äôs magnetic south-like region near the Arctic. Unlike electric charges, magnetic poles always come in pairs: if you cut a bar magnet in half, you don‚Äôt get a single north or a single south, you get two smaller magnets, each with its own north and south."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 04:58 - Category: carbon_cycle
    ("Can you explain the carbon cycle but like in a story/diagram way? I keep mixing it up with the water cycle", "Imagine carbon as a traveler named ‚ÄúC‚Äù who is always changing vehicles but never really disappears. C starts in the air as carbon dioxide (CO2), and plants are like restaurants that ‚Äúserve‚Äù CO2: using sunlight, they pull CO2 from the air and build it into sugars and plant tissue (this is photosynthesis). Then C rides through the food chain when animals eat plants (and other animals), and almost everyone‚Äîplants, animals, and microbes‚Äîbreathes out CO2 as they use food for energy (this is respiration), sending C back to the air. When living things die, decomposers break them down; during decomposition a lot of C returns to the air as CO2, but some carbon can stay stored in soils for a long time, and if it gets buried and compressed over millions of years it can become fossil fuels like coal, oil, and natural gas. C also visits the ocean: CO2 from the air dissolves into seawater, some becomes bicarbonate and carbonate, and marine organisms use it to build shells; when those organisms die, some carbon sinks and can become seafloor sediments and rocks like limestone, storing carbon for very long times, and later volcanoes and rock weathering can move carbon back toward the atmosphere. Humans create a shortcut by burning fossil fuels and cutting forests, which quickly releases long-stored carbon back into the air as CO2. A simple ‚Äúdiagram‚Äù to keep it straight is: Air (CO2) ‚Üí Plants (photosynthesis) ‚Üí Animals/food webs ‚Üí Air (respiration) and Dead matter ‚Üí Decomposers ‚Üí Air (decomposition), with side loops Air ‚Üî Ocean and long-term storage in Soil/Rocks/Fossil fuels ‚Üí Air (burning/volcanoes). The key difference from the water cycle is that the water cycle mostly moves the same H2O around by changing state (evaporation, condensation, precipitation), while the carbon cycle is about carbon being stored in living things, soils, oceans, and rocks and moving between them through chemical and biological processes like photosynthesis, respiration, decomposition, and combustion."),

