    ("Explain machine learning basics like I‚Äôm new: what‚Äôs the difference between training data and test data, and what is overfitting?", "Training data is the set of examples you show a machine-learning model while it is learning, so it can adjust its internal ‚Äúknobs‚Äù (parameters) to make its predictions match the correct answers, like a student practicing lots of homework problems with solutions. Test data is a separate set of examples you keep hidden until the very end, and you use it only to check how well the finished model works on new, unseen cases, like a final exam you don‚Äôt study from; keeping it separate matters because you want an honest score that reflects real-world performance. Overfitting is what happens when the model learns the training data too specifically, almost like memorizing the homework answers instead of learning the underlying ideas, so it gets very high accuracy on the training data but does noticeably worse on the test data because it has picked up noise and quirks (for example, it might ‚Äúlearn‚Äù that all photos of cats in the training set were taken on a couch and then struggle to recognize cats on grass)."),

