    ("For US history: what caused the Civil War besides ‚Äòslavery‚Äô‚Äîlike what were the arguments each side used?", "The Civil War had many causes, but slavery was the central issue that shaped the others; beyond simply saying ‚Äúslavery,‚Äù people at the time argued about political power, the economy, and the meaning of the Constitution. Many white Southerners said their states had the right to leave the Union (secession) and that the federal government should not restrict slavery in the territories; they framed this as ‚Äústates‚Äô rights,‚Äù but in practice the right they most wanted protected was the right to own enslaved people and to expand slavery westward, because their plantation economy depended on enslaved labor and they feared becoming a permanent minority in Congress as free states grew. They also argued that high tariffs and federal spending favored Northern industry, and they claimed the North was violating the Constitution by resisting the Fugitive Slave Act, while at the same time Southern leaders demanded strong federal enforcement to capture escaped enslaved people, showing that ‚Äústates‚Äô rights‚Äù was often used selectively. Many Northerners argued first for preserving the Union and the rule of law, saying no state could unilaterally break up the United States; over time, especially after the war began, more Northerners also argued that slavery was morally wrong and that it threatened ‚Äúfree labor,‚Äù meaning the idea that ordinary white workers should be able to work for wages and rise economically without competing against a system built on forced labor. The immediate political crisis came from repeated fights over whether new western territories would allow slavery, because that decision would shift the balance of power in the Senate and the Electoral College; key flashpoints included the Missouri Compromise (1820), the Compromise of 1850 and the Fugitive Slave Act, the Kansas‚ÄìNebraska Act (1854) and the violence in ‚ÄúBleeding Kansas,‚Äù the Dred Scott decision (1857) which said Congress could not ban slavery in the territories, John Brown‚Äôs raid (1859), and Abraham Lincoln‚Äôs election (1860), after which several Southern states seceded, explicitly citing the protection of slavery in their secession statements. So, when you ask what caused the war ‚Äúbesides slavery,‚Äù the best historical answer is that the other causes were tightly connected to slavery: disputes over states versus federal power, the expansion of slavery into new lands, economic systems and class power, and the fear on both sides that the other would control the national government and shape the country‚Äôs future."),

