    ("Can you explain limits vs continuity like I‚Äôm smart but tired? Also what does it mean when a function has a removable discontinuity?", "A limit is about what a function‚Äôs values are heading toward as x gets close to some number a, without requiring the function to actually be defined at a or to equal that value; for example, if f(x) gets closer and closer to 5 as x approaches 2 from both sides, then lim(x‚Üí2) f(x) = 5 even if f(2) is missing or different. Continuity is the stronger ‚Äúno break at that point‚Äù idea: a function is continuous at x = a exactly when three things line up at once‚Äîf(a) exists, the limit lim(x‚Üía) f(x) exists, and they are equal‚Äîso the graph can be drawn through x = a without lifting your pencil. A removable discontinuity is when the only thing preventing continuity is a single ‚Äúhole‚Äù: the two-sided limit exists (the function is clearly trying to approach one specific value), but the function either isn‚Äôt defined there or is defined to be the wrong value; classic example is f(x) = (x^2 ‚àí 1)/(x ‚àí 1), which simplifies to x + 1 for x ‚â† 1, so lim(x‚Üí1) f(x) = 2, but f(1) is undefined, creating a hole at (1, 2) that you can ‚Äúremove‚Äù by defining a new function g with g(1) = 2 (and g(x) = f(x) otherwise), making it continuous."),

