    ("What‚Äôs the difference between SN1 and SN2 reactions in a way that helps me predict which one happens? My teacher says ‚Äòsubstrate‚Äô and my brain shuts off.", "SN1 and SN2 are two different ways a nucleophile (the ‚Äúattacker‚Äù) replaces a leaving group on a carbon, and you can usually predict which happens by looking at how crowded that carbon is, how strong the nucleophile is, and what the solvent is doing. SN2 is ‚Äúone-step, backside attack‚Äù: the nucleophile attacks at the same time the leaving group leaves, so it needs easy access to the carbon; that means methyl and primary carbons strongly favor SN2, secondary can do SN2 if conditions help, and tertiary is basically too crowded for SN2. Because the nucleophile is part of the rate-determining step in SN2, stronger nucleophiles push SN2 (think negatively charged, not too bulky, like HO‚àí, RO‚àí, CN‚àí, N3‚àí), and polar aprotic solvents (like acetone, DMSO, DMF, acetonitrile) help SN2 by not ‚Äúcaging‚Äù the nucleophile; SN2 also flips the 3D arrangement at the reacting carbon (inversion). SN1 is ‚Äútwo-step, carbocation first‚Äù: the leaving group leaves first to make a carbocation, then the nucleophile attacks, so SN1 is favored when that carbocation would be stable; that means tertiary strongly favors SN1, secondary can do SN1 if conditions help, and primary/methyl almost never do SN1 (carbocations too unstable). Because the nucleophile attacks after the slow step in SN1, nucleophile strength matters less (even weak nucleophiles like water or alcohol can work), polar protic solvents (like water, methanol, ethanol) help SN1 by stabilizing ions, and SN1 often gives racemization (a mix of configurations) and can rearrange (hydride or methyl shifts) because carbocations can ‚Äúmove‚Äù to become more stable. A quick prediction shortcut is: if the reacting carbon is primary or methyl and you have a decent nucleophile in a polar aprotic solvent, expect SN2; if it‚Äôs tertiary in a polar protic solvent (often with a weak nucleophile), expect SN1; if it‚Äôs secondary, decide by conditions‚Äîstrong nucleophile/polar aprotic pushes SN2, while weak nucleophile/polar protic and a good leaving group pushes SN1 (and watch for rearrangements)."),

