    ("Machine learning basics: what‚Äôs the difference between training vs testing data, and why do people split like 80/20? I‚Äôm making a simple spam classifier for a class project.", "Training data is the set of labeled examples you let your model learn from (for a spam classifier, emails already tagged ‚Äúspam‚Äù or ‚Äúnot spam‚Äù), so the algorithm adjusts its internal parameters to fit patterns in that data, while testing data is a separate set of labeled examples you keep hidden during training and only use at the end to measure how well the trained model generalizes to new, unseen emails; if you tested on the same data you trained on, you could get an overly optimistic score because the model might partly ‚Äúmemorize‚Äù quirks of those specific messages rather than learning general spam cues. People often split something like 80/20 because it‚Äôs a practical compromise: you want most of your data (80%) to teach the model enough patterns, but you also need a meaningful chunk (20%) to get a trustworthy estimate of real-world performance; it‚Äôs not a magic rule, and the best split depends on dataset size and goals (with small datasets you might use a larger test fraction or, better, cross-validation, and with very large datasets you can often spare a smaller test set). For your spam project, make sure the split is random but keeps the spam/not-spam proportions similar in both sets (a ‚Äústratified‚Äù split), avoid letting near-duplicate emails leak into both sets, and evaluate with metrics beyond accuracy such as precision and recall, since missing spam and falsely flagging legitimate mail have different costs."),

