    ("How does Congress actually pass a bill? Like the step-by-step process but not the super boring version.", "A bill becomes a law through a predictable ‚Äúobstacle course‚Äù in Congress, with lots of chances for it to change or die. First, someone in the House or Senate introduces the bill (often after an idea comes from constituents, the President, or advocacy groups), and it gets a number like H.R. ___ or S. ___. Next it‚Äôs sent to the committee that handles that topic (like Agriculture or Judiciary), where most bills stall; the committee can hold hearings to gather information, then ‚Äúmark up‚Äù the text by debating and voting on amendments, and finally vote whether to send it to the full chamber. If it gets reported out, leaders decide whether it reaches the floor; in the House, the Rules Committee usually sets the debate time and what amendments are allowed, while in the Senate debate is looser and can be slowed or blocked by a filibuster unless 60 senators vote for cloture to end debate. Then the full House or Senate debates, may amend, and votes; if it passes one chamber, it goes to the other chamber and repeats the committee and floor steps there. Because the House and Senate often pass different versions, they must agree on identical text, usually by a conference committee or by one chamber voting to accept the other‚Äôs version; once both chambers pass the same final wording, Congress ‚Äúenrolls‚Äù the bill and sends it to the President. The President can sign it (it becomes law), veto it (Congress can still make it law by overriding with a two-thirds vote in both the House and Senate), or take no action; if Congress is in session for 10 days (not counting Sundays), it becomes law without a signature, but if Congress has adjourned and the President doesn‚Äôt sign within that period, it dies through a pocket veto. In short: introduce, committee work, floor debate and vote in each chamber, match the exact text, then the President decides‚Äîwith multiple off-ramps where the bill can be rewritten, delayed, or stopped."),

