    ("Supreme Court question: what‚Äôs the difference between original jurisdiction and appellate jurisdiction, and why does it matter?", "Original jurisdiction means a court is the very first place a case is filed and tried, with evidence presented and facts found; appellate jurisdiction means a court reviews a case that has already been decided by a lower court to decide whether the law was applied correctly (usually without re-trying the facts). For the U.S. Supreme Court, this distinction comes from Article III of the Constitution and is spelled out in 28 U.S.C. ¬ß 1251: the Court‚Äôs original jurisdiction is narrow and includes cases affecting ambassadors and other public ministers and consuls, and cases in which a state is a party, with exclusive original jurisdiction for controversies between two or more states; most of what the Supreme Court does is appellate review of federal courts of appeals and state supreme courts on federal questions, typically through discretionary certiorari. It matters because it determines where a lawsuit can start, what procedures apply, and how much choice the Supreme Court has about hearing it: original-jurisdiction cases can go straight to the Supreme Court (often using a special master to gather facts), while appellate cases usually reach the Court only if it agrees to take them, which shapes the Court‚Äôs workload and its power to focus on major national legal issues."),

