    ("Computer architecture thing: can you explain what the CPU cache does vs RAM, and why a cache miss slows everything down? I‚Äôm studying for a final.", "RAM (main memory) is where your program‚Äôs code and data live while it runs, and it‚Äôs relatively large but much slower to access than the CPU can execute instructions; the CPU cache is a much smaller memory built on the processor chip (typically split into L1, L2, and often L3) that keeps copies of the most recently used and most likely-to-be-used data and instructions so the CPU can get them in just a few cycles instead of waiting on RAM. The cache works because programs usually show locality: temporal locality means if you used a value recently you‚Äôll probably use it again soon, and spatial locality means if you used one address you‚Äôll likely use nearby addresses soon, so caches fetch and store data in fixed-size blocks called cache lines (often 64 bytes) to take advantage of that. A cache hit means the CPU finds what it needs in the cache and can keep its pipeline busy; a cache miss means the data isn‚Äôt there, so the CPU must fetch the whole cache line from the next level (L2/L3) or from RAM, and that extra latency is huge compared to CPU speed (roughly a few cycles for L1, tens for L2, tens to low hundreds for L3, and on the order of hundreds of cycles for DRAM), so the CPU often stalls waiting, doing little or no useful work during that time. Misses are especially painful when they happen repeatedly, like walking through a large array with a stride that skips around memory (poor spatial locality) or when many different addresses map to the same cache set (conflict misses), because the cache keeps evicting lines and reloading them; by contrast, tight loops and sequential array access tend to be fast because they reuse cached lines and let the hardware prefetcher pull in upcoming lines before the CPU needs them. In short, cache exists to hide RAM latency by keeping the working set close to the CPU, and a cache miss slows everything down because the CPU is forced to wait for much slower memory levels to deliver data before it can continue executing dependent instructions."),

