    ("I\'m stuck on a number theory proof: show that if gcd(a,n)=1 then a^{phi(n)} ‚â° 1 (mod n). I get the idea but I can\'t write it cleanly.", "Let n be a positive integer and let U be the set of reduced residue classes modulo n, meaning U = {x mod n : 1 ‚â§ x ‚â§ n and gcd(x,n)=1}; by definition |U| = œÜ(n). If gcd(a,n)=1, then multiplication by a permutes U: for any x in U we have gcd(ax,n)=1 so ax (mod n) is still in U, and if ax ‚â° ay (mod n) then n | a(x‚àíy), and since gcd(a,n)=1 we can cancel a to get n | (x‚àíy), hence x ‚â° y (mod n), so the map x ‚Ü¶ ax is injective and therefore bijective on the finite set U. Thus the multiset of residues in U is the same as the multiset {ax mod n : x in U}, so if we multiply all elements of U together we get (product over x in U of x) ‚â° (product over x in U of ax) ‚â° a^{œÜ(n)} (product over x in U of x) (mod n). Now the product P = product over x in U of x is itself coprime to n (it is a product of numbers each coprime to n), so gcd(P,n)=1 and P has a multiplicative inverse modulo n; multiplying both sides of P ‚â° a^{œÜ(n)}P (mod n) by P^{-1} gives a^{œÜ(n)} ‚â° 1 (mod n), which is Euler‚Äôs theorem."),

