    ("Stats question: I have a dataset with a mean of 72 and SD of 10. If the distribution is roughly normal, what percent of values are between 52 and 92? Please show the z-score steps.", "To find the percent of values between 52 and 92 in a roughly normal distribution with mean 72 and standard deviation 10, convert each endpoint to a z-score using z = (x ‚àí mean) / SD. For x = 52, z = (52 ‚àí 72) / 10 = ‚àí20/10 = ‚àí2.00, and for x = 92, z = (92 ‚àí 72) / 10 = 20/10 = 2.00, so the question becomes ‚Äúwhat proportion of a standard normal distribution lies between z = ‚àí2 and z = 2?‚Äù From the standard normal table, the area to the left of z = 2.00 is about 0.9772 and the area to the left of z = ‚àí2.00 is about 0.0228, so the area between them is 0.9772 ‚àí 0.0228 = 0.9544, which is 95.44% (about 95.4%); this also matches the Empirical Rule idea that about 95% of values lie within 2 standard deviations of the mean."),

