    ("Calc 2 homework: does the series Œ£_{n=1}^{‚àû} (n!/n^n) converge? I tried ratio test and got messy‚Äîcan you guide me without just dumping the final answer?", "Let a_n = n!/n^n, and try the ratio test in a clean way by writing a_{n+1} in terms of a_n: a_{n+1} = (n+1)!/(n+1)^{n+1} = (n+1)n!/(n+1)^{n+1} = n!/(n+1)^n, so a_{n+1}/a_n = (n!/(n+1)^n)/(n!/n^n) = (n^n)/(n+1)^n = (n/(n+1))^n = (1 1/(n+1))^n. Now you don‚Äôt need to expand anything; just take the limit: (1 1/(n+1))^n ‚Üí e^{-1} as n ‚Üí ‚àû (it‚Äôs the standard limit (1 1/m)^m ‚Üí e^{-1}, and here m = n+1 so (1 1/(n+1))^{n+1} ‚Üí e^{-1}, then dividing by one more factor (1 1/(n+1)) ‚Üí 1 doesn‚Äôt change the limit). Since the ratio limit is e^{-1} < 1, the ratio test says the series Œ£ n!/n^n converges absolutely. As a quick sanity check, e^{-1} ‚âà 0.367 means terms eventually shrink by about a factor of 0.367 each step, so the tail behaves roughly like a geometric series, which matches the convergence conclusion."),

