    ("what is the carbon cycle? is it like plants \"breathing\" or something", "The carbon cycle is the continuous movement of carbon atoms through Earth‚Äôs air, living things, oceans, and rocks, and it matters because carbon is a basic building block of life and also affects climate. It is a little like ‚Äúbreathing,‚Äù but the more accurate idea is that carbon is constantly being traded back and forth: plants take in carbon dioxide (CO2) from the air during photosynthesis and use the carbon to build sugars and plant tissue, then plants, animals, and microbes release CO2 back to the air when they do cellular respiration (using food for energy), which is like ‚Äúbreathing out‚Äù carbon dioxide. Carbon also moves when animals eat plants, when dead organisms decompose (releasing CO2 and sometimes methane), and when carbon gets stored for longer times in soils, the ocean (where CO2 dissolves and can become bicarbonate and carbonate), and in rocks and fossil fuels; burning fossil fuels and cutting forests quickly return long-stored carbon to the atmosphere as CO2. So yes, it connects to plants and breathing, but it‚Äôs bigger than that: it‚Äôs the whole Earth system recycling carbon between living things and the environment on timescales from days to millions of years."),

