    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 05:12 - Category: congress
    ("what does Congress actually do vs the Supreme Court? i need it for my gov class notes", "Congress and the Supreme Court are in different branches and do different jobs: Congress is the legislative branch, so its main role is to write, debate, and pass federal laws, and it also has major powers like controlling federal spending (passing the budget and taxes), declaring war, approving treaties and many top presidential appointments through the Senate, and providing oversight by holding hearings and investigations; it can also impeach and remove federal officials (the House impeaches, the Senate holds the trial). The Supreme Court is the highest court in the judicial branch, so it does not make laws; instead it decides legal cases and interprets what the Constitution and federal laws mean, including using judicial review to strike down a federal or state law or a government action if it violates the Constitution (this power comes from the 1803 case Marbury v. Madison). A helpful way to remember the difference is that Congress creates the rules for the whole country, while the Supreme Court decides what those rules mean in real disputes and whether the rules follow the Constitution; they also check each other because Congress can write new laws to respond to Court decisions, propose constitutional amendments to override a Court interpretation, and the Senate confirms Supreme Court justices, while the Court can invalidate laws Congress passes if they are unconstitutional."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 05:12 - Category: computer_architecture
    ("I\'m studying computer architecture‚Äîwhat\'s the difference between a CPU, RAM, and cache, and why is cache faster?", "A CPU (central processing unit) is the ‚Äúworker‚Äù that actually runs your program: it fetches instructions, performs arithmetic and logic, and controls data movement using internal registers and execution units. RAM (main memory) is the large, off-chip workspace where the program‚Äôs instructions and data live while the computer is running; it‚Äôs typically implemented as DRAM, which is dense and inexpensive per gigabyte but relatively slow to access because it needs row activation, sensing, and periodic refresh, and because the CPU must reach it over longer electrical paths through the memory controller and motherboard traces. Cache is a small amount of very fast memory placed on the CPU chip (usually split into levels like L1, L2, and a larger last-level cache) that automatically keeps copies of recently and frequently used instructions and data from RAM so the CPU can get them quickly; it‚Äôs faster mainly because it‚Äôs built from SRAM (which can be accessed in a few CPU cycles without refresh), it‚Äôs physically much closer to the CPU cores (shorter wires and fewer interfaces), and it‚Äôs smaller (so decoding and wiring delays are lower and it can be designed to meet tight timing). Caches speed programs up because of locality: programs tend to reuse the same instructions in loops and touch nearby data repeatedly, so if the ‚Äúworking set‚Äù fits in cache the CPU avoids waiting for RAM, but if it doesn‚Äôt, a cache miss forces a much slower fetch from RAM that can stall execution for many cycles."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 05:12 - Category: modular_arithmetic
    ("in number theory, how do modular arithmetic and remainders actually work? like what does 17 mod 5 mean and why is it useful", "Modular arithmetic is a way of doing arithmetic where you only care about the remainder after dividing by a fixed positive integer called the modulus; formally, when you work ‚Äúmod 5,‚Äù two integers are treated as equivalent if their difference is a multiple of 5, meaning they land on the same remainder when divided by 5. The expression 17 mod 5 means ‚Äúthe remainder when 17 is divided by 5‚Äù: since 17 = 5¬∑3 + 2, the remainder is 2, so 17 mod 5 = 2, and you can think of it like a clock with 5 positions labeled 0,1,2,3,4 where counting forward from 0 wraps around after 4 back to 0; in that picture, 17 steps lands on 2. This is useful because it lets you replace large numbers with small remainders while preserving addition, subtraction, and multiplication behavior: for example, mod 5 you have 17 ‚â° 2 and 23 ‚â° 3, so (17 + 23) mod 5 = 40 mod 5 = 0, and you get the same result by reducing first: (2 + 3) mod 5 = 5 mod 5 = 0; similarly, (17¬∑23) mod 5 can be found quickly as (2¬∑3) mod 5 = 6 mod 5 = 1. It‚Äôs also how you reason about ‚Äúlast digits‚Äù and divisibility patterns (working mod 10 tracks the last digit, mod 2 tracks even/odd, mod 9 explains the digit-sum test), how cyclic phenomena are modeled (days of the week are mod 7), and it powers many number-theory and computer-science tools, including fast error-checking with remainders and modern cryptography, where computations are done with huge integers but reduced mod a large number to keep them manageable and to exploit the predictable structure of remainders."),

