    ("Can you help me model this as a system of linear functions? I have a taxi fare: $3 base fee + $2.25 per mile, and a rideshare: $1.50 base + $2.75 per mile. At what distance are they the same and how do I show it on a graph?", "Let x be the distance in miles and y be the total cost in dollars. Then the taxi fare is the linear function y = 3 + 2.25x and the rideshare fare is y = 1.50 + 2.75x, which together form a system of two linear equations. To find where they cost the same, set them equal: 3 + 2.25x = 1.50 + 2.75x; subtract 2.25x from both sides to get 3 = 1.50 + 0.50x, subtract 1.50 to get 1.50 = 0.50x, and divide by 0.50 to get x = 3, so they are equal at 3 miles; plugging in gives y = 3 + 2.25(3) = 9.75 dollars (and 1.50 + 2.75(3) also equals 9.75), so the intersection point is (3, 9.75). To show this on a graph, put miles on the x-axis and cost on the y-axis, plot the taxi line using its y-intercept 3 and slope 2.25 (for example points (0,3) and (4,12)), plot the rideshare line using y-intercept 1.50 and slope 2.75 (for example points (0,1.5) and (4,12.5)), draw straight lines through each pair of points, and mark where they cross at (3, 9.75); you can also note that for distances less than 3 miles the rideshare is cheaper (lower line), and for distances greater than 3 miles the taxi is cheaper because it has the smaller per-mile rate."),

