    ("Can you explain the main reaction types (synthesis, decomposition, single replacement, double replacement, combustion) and then classify these 5 equations if I paste them?", "The five common reaction types are defined by what happens to the reactants: In a synthesis (also called combination) reaction, two or more simpler substances join to form one product, following the pattern A + B ‚Üí AB (for example, 2Na + Cl2 ‚Üí 2NaCl). In a decomposition reaction, one compound breaks apart into two or more simpler substances, AB ‚Üí A + B (for example, 2H2O2 ‚Üí 2H2O + O2). In a single replacement (single displacement) reaction, an element replaces another element in a compound, A + BC ‚Üí AC + B; this usually happens only if the free element is more reactive than the one it replaces (for example, Zn + 2HCl ‚Üí ZnCl2 + H2). In a double replacement (double displacement) reaction, ions in two compounds swap partners, AB + CD ‚Üí AD + CB; these often produce a precipitate (solid), a gas, or water (for example, AgNO3 + NaCl ‚Üí AgCl(s) + NaNO3, or HCl + NaOH ‚Üí NaCl + H2O). In a combustion reaction, a substance reacts rapidly with oxygen; for hydrocarbons the typical products are carbon dioxide and water, CxHy + O2 ‚Üí CO2 + H2O (for example, CH4 + 2O2 ‚Üí CO2 + 2H2O), and you can recognize it by O2 being a reactant and CO2 and H2O commonly appearing among the products. Paste your 5 balanced (or unbalanced) equations, and I‚Äôll label each one with its reaction type and briefly explain the pattern that matches it; if any equation could fit more than one category (like combustion that is also a synthesis in a broad sense), I‚Äôll tell you the most standard classification used in chemistry classes and why."),

