    ("Machine learning basics: can you explain training vs testing vs validation sets and what overfitting actually looks like? I‚Äôm doing a tiny image classifier in Python.", "When you build an image classifier, you split your labeled images into separate sets so you can measure how well the model learns and how well it generalizes to new images: the training set is the data the model actually learns from (it updates its weights to reduce loss on these examples), the validation set is a ‚Äúpractice exam‚Äù you do not train on but check during development to choose things like model architecture, learning rate, number of epochs, and when to stop training (early stopping), and the test set is the final ‚Äúreal exam‚Äù you keep untouched until the very end to get an unbiased estimate of real-world performance after all decisions are made. Overfitting is what happens when the model starts memorizing quirks of the training images instead of learning general patterns, and it looks like training accuracy keeps rising (and training loss keeps falling) while validation accuracy stops improving or gets worse (validation loss starts rising); for a tiny image dataset this can happen quickly, especially with a large model, and you might see the model do great on training images but misclassify slightly different new images (different lighting, backgrounds, rotations). A concrete example pattern is: after a few epochs both training and validation improve, then later training accuracy goes from, say, 95% to 99% while validation drops from 90% to 85%, which is a classic sign to stop earlier or add regularization; common fixes include using more data or augmentation (random crops/flips/color jitter), reducing model capacity, adding dropout or weight decay (L2 regularization), and making sure you split data correctly (for images, avoid near-duplicates or multiple shots of the same object appearing in both train and validation/test, and use stratified splits so each class is represented similarly)."),

