    ("I don‚Äôt get the Pythagorean theorem. If one side is 6 and the other is 8, how do I find the hypotenuse and why does it work?", "In a right triangle (one angle is exactly 90¬∞), the Pythagorean theorem says the two shorter sides, called legs, satisfy a¬≤ + b¬≤ = c¬≤, where c is the hypotenuse (the longest side opposite the 90¬∞ angle). If the legs are 6 and 8, you compute c = ‚àö(6¬≤ + 8¬≤) = ‚àö(36 + 64) = ‚àö100 = 10, so the hypotenuse is 10; you can quickly check it works because 6¬≤ + 8¬≤ = 36 + 64 = 100 and 10¬≤ = 100, so the equation balances. It works because in right triangles the area relationship between squares built on each side is always the same: if you draw a square on each side, the combined area of the two smaller squares exactly equals the area of the square on the hypotenuse, and that geometric fact leads directly to a¬≤ + b¬≤ = c¬≤."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 05:18 - Category: dna_replication
    ("What does ‚ÄúDNA replication is semiconservative‚Äù mean? And what do helicase and DNA polymerase actually do?", "‚ÄúSemi-conservative‚Äù DNA replication means that after DNA is copied, each daughter DNA double helix is made of one original (parental) strand that was already there and one newly synthesized strand, so the original information is ‚Äúconserved‚Äù by keeping half of the old molecule in each copy. Helicase is the enzyme that starts the process by unwinding the double helix and separating the two strands, mainly by breaking the hydrogen bonds between complementary bases, creating a replication fork where copying can occur. DNA polymerase is the enzyme that actually builds the new DNA strand by using each old strand as a template and adding matching nucleotides (A pairs with T, C pairs with G) to the growing strand; it can only add to an existing 3‚Ä≤ end, so it synthesizes DNA in the 5‚Ä≤‚Üí3‚Ä≤ direction, which is why one strand is made continuously (leading strand) and the other is made in short pieces (Okazaki fragments) that are later joined."),

