    ("Stats question: I have a dataset with a crazy outlier. Should I use mean/SD or median/IQR, and how do I justify it in a lab report without sounding like I‚Äôm cherry-picking?", "If your dataset has a ‚Äúcrazy‚Äù outlier, median and IQR are usually the better default for describing the typical value and spread because they are robust: one extreme point can pull the mean far away from where most observations lie and can inflate the SD dramatically, while the median and IQR change little unless a large fraction of the data are extreme. A clean way to justify this in a lab report without sounding like you‚Äôre cherry-picking is to predefine and explain your decision rule based on distribution shape and sensitivity to outliers, not on whether the result looks nicer: for example, state that you inspected the distribution (histogram/boxplot and, if relevant, a normality check) and found strong skew or an extreme value, so you summarized central tendency with the median and variability with the IQR because these statistics better represent the bulk of the data under non-normal or heavy-tailed conditions; then be transparent by also reporting the mean and SD as a sensitivity analysis (or in a supplement) and briefly noting how much they change when the outlier is included versus excluded. If you think the outlier might be an error, say exactly what you checked (units, data entry, instrument limits) and only exclude it if you have a documented, non-outcome-based reason; otherwise keep it, report robust summaries, and consider analyses that handle outliers (transformations like log for right-skewed data, or robust methods) so your choice is framed as good statistical practice rather than selective reporting."),

