    ("I need to prove a limit using epsilon-delta, but my professor‚Äôs examples feel like magic. Can you walk me through proving lim(x‚Üí2) (3x+1) = 7 step by step?", "To prove lim(x‚Üí2) (3x+1) = 7 using an epsilon-delta argument, you start by translating the limit statement into what you must show: for every Œµ > 0, you need to find a Œ¥ > 0 such that whenever 0 < |x ‚àí 2| < Œ¥, it follows that |(3x+1) ‚àí 7| < Œµ. Now simplify the expression inside the absolute value: |(3x+1) ‚àí 7| = |3x ‚àí 6| = |3(x ‚àí 2)| = 3|x ‚àí 2|. So the goal becomes making 3|x ‚àí 2| smaller than Œµ, and that‚Äôs easy if you force |x ‚àí 2| to be smaller than Œµ/3. Concretely, given any Œµ > 0, choose Œ¥ = Œµ/3; then whenever 0 < |x ‚àí 2| < Œ¥, you get |(3x+1) ‚àí 7| = 3|x ‚àí 2| < 3Œ¥ = 3(Œµ/3) = Œµ, which is exactly what the definition requires, so the limit is proven. The ‚Äúmagic‚Äù is really just this pattern: rewrite the difference between the function value and the claimed limit until it‚Äôs a constant times |x ‚àí a|, then pick Œ¥ to cancel that constant (here the constant is 3, so Œ¥ = Œµ/3)."),

