    ("Can you help me with projectile motion? A ball is launched at 20 m/s at 30¬∞. How do I find the time in the air and the max height?", "Yes. Ignore air resistance and take g = 9.8 m/s¬≤. First split the launch speed into components; for time in the air and maximum height you only need the vertical component: v0y = v0 sin(30¬∞) = 20(0.5) = 10 m/s. If the ball lands at the same height it was launched, the vertical motion is symmetric: at the top the vertical velocity is zero, so 0 = v0y ‚àí gt gives the time to reach the top t_up = v0y/g = 10/9.8 ‚âà 1.02 s, and the total time in the air is T = 2t_up ‚âà 2.04 s. The maximum height above the launch point comes from 0 = v0y¬≤ ‚àí 2gŒîy, so Œîy = v0y¬≤/(2g) = 100/(19.6) ‚âà 5.10 m; a quick check using Œîy = v0y t_up ‚àí (1/2)gt_up¬≤ gives 10(1.02) ‚àí 4.9(1.02¬≤) ‚âà 10.2 ‚àí 5.1 ‚âà 5.1 m, consistent. If it lands at a different height than it was launched, you‚Äôd instead solve y(t) = v0y t ‚àí (1/2)gt¬≤ for the landing time and then use the same max-height idea at v_y = 0."),

