    ("Pre-calc: how do I convert a point from rectangular coordinates to polar coordinates, and when is polar actually easier to use?", "To convert a point (x, y) in rectangular (Cartesian) coordinates to polar coordinates (r, Œ∏), you use r = ‚àö(x¬≤ + y¬≤) for the distance from the origin and Œ∏ as the angle measured from the positive x-axis to the point; a reliable way to get the correct angle in the correct quadrant is Œ∏ = arctan(y/x) adjusted for the quadrant (or, on many calculators, Œ∏ = atan2(y, x)), and you can always check your result by converting back with x = r cos Œ∏ and y = r sin Œ∏. For example, if (x, y) = (3, 3), then r = ‚àö(3¬≤ + 3¬≤) = ‚àö18 = 3‚àö2 and Œ∏ = arctan(3/3) = arctan(1) = 45¬∞ (or œÄ/4), so the polar form is (3‚àö2, 45¬∞); if (x, y) = (‚àí1, ‚àö3), then r = ‚àö((‚àí1)¬≤ + (‚àö3)¬≤) = ‚àö4 = 2 and arctan(‚àö3/‚àí1) gives a negative reference angle, but since the point is in Quadrant II the correct angle is 120¬∞ (or 2œÄ/3), so (2, 120¬∞). Polar is often easier when problems involve circles or rotation because r naturally represents distance from the origin and Œ∏ represents direction: equations like x¬≤ + y¬≤ = 9 become r = 3, lines through the origin become Œ∏ = constant, and many trig and calculus problems simplify because x = r cos Œ∏ and y = r sin Œ∏ turn expressions like x¬≤ + y¬≤ into r¬≤, making areas, arc lengths, and integrals with radial symmetry much cleaner."),

