    ("Middle school math: I don‚Äôt get why a negative times a negative is positive. Can you explain it without just saying ‚Äúbecause rules‚Äù?", "One good way to see why a negative times a negative must be positive is to use a pattern that comes from the distributive property, which is the idea that a(b + c) = ab + ac and works for all numbers. Start with something you already believe: 3 √ó 2 = 6, and if you decrease the second factor by 1 each time, the product should decrease by 3 each time because you‚Äôre taking away one group of 3: 3 √ó 2 = 6, 3 √ó 1 = 3, 3 √ó 0 = 0, 3 √ó (‚àí1) = ‚àí3, 3 √ó (‚àí2) = ‚àí6; that shows why a positive times a negative is negative without ‚Äújust rules,‚Äù it‚Äôs a consistent pattern. Now do the same idea but with a negative first factor: (‚àí3) √ó 2 = ‚àí6, (‚àí3) √ó 1 = ‚àí3, (‚àí3) √ó 0 = 0, and if you keep decreasing the second factor by 1, the product must keep changing by ‚àí3 each step (because you‚Äôre adding one more group of ‚àí3): (‚àí3) √ó (‚àí1) must be 3, and (‚àí3) √ó (‚àí2) must be 6, so a negative times a negative becomes positive. You can also see it directly from distributive property: 0 = (‚àí3) √ó 0 = (‚àí3) √ó (1 + (‚àí1)) = (‚àí3)√ó1 + (‚àí3)√ó(‚àí1) = ‚àí3 + (‚àí3)√ó(‚àí1), so to make the total 0, (‚àí3)√ó(‚àí1) has to be 3; the only way multiplication stays consistent with addition is if negative times negative is positive."),

