    ("Why do magnets stick to the fridge but not to a plastic toy? Is the fridge like‚Ä¶ special metal?", "Magnets stick to many fridge doors because the outer skin is often made of steel, and steel contains iron, which is a ‚Äúmagnet-friendly‚Äù material (ferromagnetic). Inside iron and steel are countless tiny regions called magnetic domains that can easily line up with the magnet‚Äôs field, turning the door into a temporary magnet and creating a strong pull that holds the magnet on. A plastic toy doesn‚Äôt have those magnetic domains at all, so the magnet‚Äôs field can‚Äôt make the plastic ‚Äújoin in,‚Äù and there‚Äôs essentially nothing for the magnet to grab onto, so it won‚Äôt stick. So yes, the fridge is ‚Äúspecial‚Äù in the sense that it‚Äôs made from an iron-based metal; not all metals are magnetic (for example aluminum and copper usually aren‚Äôt), but iron, steel, nickel, and cobalt are the common ones that magnets stick to strongly."),

