    ("Who are the Supreme Court people and what do they actually DO all day?", "In the United States, ‚Äúthe Supreme Court people‚Äù usually means the nine Supreme Court Justices (one Chief Justice and eight Associate Justices), who are judges appointed by the President and confirmed by the Senate to serve for life (unless they retire or are removed by impeachment), and their job is to decide important legal questions for the whole country by interpreting the U.S. Constitution and federal law. On a typical workday, they and their law clerks read written arguments (called briefs) from both sides of a case, study the record from the lower courts, research past decisions (precedent), and discuss how the law applies; when the Court hears oral arguments, the Justices sit in the courtroom, listen to lawyers, and ask tough questions to test each side‚Äôs reasoning. After that, they meet privately in a conference to vote on the outcome, one Justice is assigned to write the Court‚Äôs opinion explaining the decision, other Justices may write separate opinions if they agree for different reasons (concurring) or disagree (dissenting), and they spend a lot of time editing drafts to make the reasoning clear because their words guide every other court in the country; they also decide which cases to take in the first place by reviewing thousands of requests each year and choosing only a small number that raise big national issues or conflicts among lower courts. Supporting them are many other ‚ÄúSupreme Court people,‚Äù including law clerks (young lawyers who help with research and drafting), the Clerk of the Court (who manages filings and schedules), the Marshal (who handles security and courtroom order), and other staff, but the Justices‚Äô core ‚Äúall day‚Äù work is reading, thinking, questioning, debating, voting, and writing decisions that become the final legal rule for the nation unless changed by a later Court or by a constitutional amendment."),

