    ("I‚Äôm stuck balancing this equation for chem: Fe + O2 -> Fe2O3. Can you show how to do it step by step?", "To balance Fe + O2 -> Fe2O3, start by counting atoms on each side: on the left you have 1 Fe and 2 O, and on the right (Fe2O3) you have 2 Fe and 3 O. Because oxygen comes in pairs as O2, it helps to make the oxygen count on the product side even, so put a 2 in front of Fe2O3 to make 6 oxygen atoms on the right (2 x 3 = 6) and 4 iron atoms on the right (2 x 2 = 4). Now match oxygen by putting a 3 in front of O2 on the left to get 6 oxygen atoms (3 x 2 = 6). Finally match iron by putting a 4 in front of Fe on the left to get 4 iron atoms. The balanced equation is 4Fe + 3O2 -> 2Fe2O3, and you can quickly check it: left side has Fe = 4 and O = 6, right side has Fe = 4 and O = 6, so it‚Äôs balanced."),

