    ("Can you explain what a complex number actually means (like why i is useful) and then help me solve (3 2i)(4 + i)??", "A complex number a + bi is a way to represent two pieces of information at once: the ‚Äúreal‚Äù part a and the ‚Äúimaginary‚Äù part b, which you can picture as a point (a, b) on a plane where the horizontal axis is real and the vertical axis is imaginary; the special number i is defined so that i¬≤ = ‚àí1, which lets us extend ordinary number arithmetic to handle things like square roots of negative numbers in a consistent way. This is useful because many real-world systems naturally involve two coupled components that rotate and oscillate, and complex numbers make the math cleaner: for example, in electrical engineering AC circuits use complex numbers to combine resistance and reactance, in physics and signal processing they describe waves and phase shifts, and in mathematics they simplify solving polynomials and differential equations. To multiply (3 ‚àí 2i)(4 + i), distribute like FOIL: 3¬∑4 = 12, 3¬∑i = 3i, (‚àí2i)¬∑4 = ‚àí8i, and (‚àí2i)¬∑i = ‚àí2i¬≤; combine the imaginary terms 3i ‚àí 8i = ‚àí5i, and use i¬≤ = ‚àí1 so ‚àí2i¬≤ = ‚àí2(‚àí1) = +2, giving 12 + 2 ‚àí 5i = 14 ‚àí 5i. You can quickly sanity-check by treating them as (3, ‚àí2) and (4, 1): the real part should be 3¬∑4 ‚àí (‚àí2)¬∑1 = 12 + 2 = 14 and the imaginary part should be 3¬∑1 + (‚àí2)¬∑4 = 3 ‚àí 8 = ‚àí5, matching 14 ‚àí 5i."),

