    ("I‚Äôm stuck on limits/continuity: is f(x)=|x|/x continuous at 0? Can you walk me through the logic and not just give the answer.", "To decide whether f(x)=|x|/x is continuous at 0, start with the definition: a function is continuous at a point a only if (1) f(a) is defined, (2) the limit of f(x) as x approaches a exists, and (3) that limit equals f(a). Here, f(0) would be |0|/0 = 0/0, which is undefined, so condition (1) already fails and that alone means it cannot be continuous at 0. But it‚Äôs also helpful to check the limit behavior: for x>0, |x|=x so f(x)=x/x=1, meaning the right-hand limit as x‚Üí0+ is 1; for x<0, |x|=-x so f(x)=(-x)/x=-1, meaning the left-hand limit as x‚Üí0‚àí is -1. Since the left-hand and right-hand limits are different, the two-sided limit as x‚Üí0 does not exist, so condition (2) fails as well; this is a classic jump discontinuity. Putting it together, f(x)=|x|/x is not continuous at 0 because it isn‚Äôt even defined there, and even if you tried to ‚Äúpatch‚Äù it by assigning some value at 0, no single value could make it continuous because the function approaches -1 from the left and 1 from the right."),

