    ("Bio: what‚Äôs the difference between DNA replication and transcription? I keep mixing up leading/lagging strand and RNA stuff.", "DNA replication and transcription both use DNA as a template, but they have different goals, enzymes, and ‚Äústrand rules,‚Äù and that‚Äôs where leading/lagging comes in. Replication is DNA to DNA and happens before cell division to copy the entire genome once; helicase opens the double helix, primase lays short RNA primers, and DNA polymerase extends new DNA only in the 5‚Ä≤ to 3‚Ä≤ direction, using A-T and C-G pairing, to make two double-stranded DNA molecules (each with one old strand and one new strand). Because the two template strands run in opposite directions, replication at each fork makes a leading strand that can be synthesized continuously toward the fork (one primer, smooth copying) and a lagging strand that must be synthesized discontinuously away from the fork as Okazaki fragments (many primers); DNA polymerase makes the fragments, the RNA primers are removed and replaced with DNA, and DNA ligase ‚Äúglues‚Äù fragments together into one continuous strand. Transcription is DNA to RNA and happens when a cell needs to use a specific gene; RNA polymerase binds a promoter, unwinds a small region, reads only one DNA strand (the template strand) and builds a single-stranded RNA 5‚Ä≤ to 3‚Ä≤ using A-U and C-G pairing (RNA uses uracil, U, instead of thymine, T), and it stops at a terminator; there is no leading or lagging strand in transcription because RNA polymerase is making one continuous RNA copy from one template strand, not duplicating both strands of the whole genome at a fork. A quick way to keep it straight is: leading/lagging and Okazaki fragments belong to replication because DNA polymerase can only build 5‚Ä≤ to 3‚Ä≤ on two opposite templates at once, while ‚ÄúRNA stuff‚Äù (U instead of T, one gene at a time, RNA polymerase) belongs to transcription."),

