    ("Environmental science: can you explain the carbon cycle but also connect it to how burning fossil fuels changes atmospheric CO2? Like the ‚Äúso what‚Äù part.", "The carbon cycle is the constant movement of carbon among the atmosphere, living things, oceans, and rocks: plants pull carbon dioxide (CO2) out of the air during photosynthesis to build sugars and tissues, animals and microbes get that carbon by eating plants (or each other), and respiration and decomposition return much of it back to the air as CO2; at the same time, the ocean absorbs CO2 from the atmosphere and can also release it back, and over much longer timescales some carbon gets locked away in soils, ocean sediments, and rocks (including fossil fuels) through burial and chemical reactions, while volcanoes and rock weathering help move carbon between rocks, oceans, and the air. The ‚Äúso what‚Äù with burning fossil fuels is that coal, oil, and natural gas are ancient carbon that was stored underground for millions of years, and when we burn them we rapidly move that stored carbon into the atmosphere as CO2, adding extra CO2 faster than plants and oceans can remove it, so atmospheric CO2 rises and strengthens the greenhouse effect, trapping more heat and driving climate change; in other words, humans are short-circuiting the slow part of the carbon cycle by taking long-term storage and turning it into atmospheric CO2 on a timescale of decades. You can picture it like a bathtub where the drain (natural uptake by plants and oceans) is only so big: fossil-fuel burning is like turning on an extra faucet, so the water level (atmospheric CO2) climbs even if the drain is still working."),

