    ("Solve for x please: 3x + 7 = 22. And can you explain what I‚Äôm actually doing when I move numbers around?", "Start with the equation 3x + 7 = 22. Your goal is to get x by itself, so you ‚Äúundo‚Äù the operations that are happening to x, one at a time, using inverse operations while keeping the equation balanced. First undo the +7 by subtracting 7 from both sides: 3x + 7 ‚àí 7 = 22 ‚àí 7, which simplifies to 3x = 15. Then undo the ‚Äú3 times x‚Äù by dividing both sides by 3: 3x/3 = 15/3, so x = 5. What you‚Äôre actually doing when you ‚Äúmove numbers around‚Äù is not magically moving them; you‚Äôre performing the same operation to both sides of the equation (like subtracting 7 or dividing by 3) so the two sides stay equal, and that lets you peel away the extra parts until only x remains. Quick check: plug it back in: 3(5) + 7 = 15 + 7 = 22, which matches, so x = 5 is correct."),

