    ("I‚Äôm building a little Arduino project for an intro engineering class‚Äîwhat‚Äôs the difference between sensors and actuators, and can you suggest a simple setup for a door alarm?", "In an Arduino project, a sensor is an input device that measures something in the real world and turns it into a signal the Arduino can read (for example a door switch, a magnetic reed switch, a light sensor, or a motion sensor), while an actuator is an output device that the Arduino controls to make something happen (for example a buzzer, LED, relay, or motor). A simple door alarm setup is to use a magnetic reed switch as the sensor: mount the reed switch on the door frame and the matching magnet on the door so that when the door is closed the magnet keeps the switch closed, and when the door opens the switch changes state; wire one side of the reed switch to an Arduino digital input pin and the other side to ground, then enable the pin‚Äôs internal pull-up resistor in code so the input reads HIGH when the door is open and LOW when closed (or vice versa depending on wiring). For the actuator, connect a piezo buzzer (or an LED plus a resistor) to a digital output pin and ground, and in the sketch continuously read the reed switch; when the door-open condition is detected, turn on the buzzer/LED (optionally with a short delay and a latch so it keeps alarming until a reset button is pressed), and when the door is closed again, turn it off."),

