    ("Can you help me derive the work‚Äìenergy theorem from Newton‚Äôs 2nd law? My prof went too fast and I‚Äôm lost on the integral part.", "Start with Newton‚Äôs 2nd law for a particle of constant mass, F_net = m a, and take the dot product with the particle‚Äôs instantaneous displacement element d r along its path: F_net ¬∑ d r = m a ¬∑ d r. Now use the kinematics identity that makes the ‚Äúintegral part‚Äù work: v = d r/dt and a = d v/dt, so a ¬∑ d r = (d v/dt) ¬∑ (v dt) = (d v/dt) ¬∑ v dt = v ¬∑ d v (because dt cancels and the dot product is commutative), which is the key step that turns a time-dependent acceleration into something you can integrate with respect to velocity. Substitute that into the earlier equation to get F_net ¬∑ d r = m v ¬∑ d v, then integrate from the initial state to the final state along the actual motion: ‚à´(r_i‚Üír_f) F_net ¬∑ d r = ‚à´(v_i‚Üív_f) m v ¬∑ d v. The left-hand side is, by definition, the net work W_net done by the net force along the path, and the right-hand side is m ‚à´ v ¬∑ d v = m ‚à´ v dv = (1/2) m v^2 evaluated between v_i and v_f, giving W_net = (1/2) m v_f^2 ‚àí (1/2) m v_i^2 = ŒîK, which is the work‚Äìenergy theorem: net work equals the change in kinetic energy. If you want a quick check, in 1D with constant force F over distance Œîx, the theorem gives W = FŒîx = (1/2)m(v_f^2 ‚àí v_i^2), which matches the familiar constant-acceleration result v_f^2 = v_i^2 + 2aŒîx with a = F/m."),

