    ("I‚Äôm doing descriptive stats for a lab dataset‚Äîcan you explain when I should report mean/SD vs median/IQR, and how outliers change the story?", "Use mean and standard deviation when your variable is roughly symmetric and unimodal (often close to ‚Äúbell-shaped‚Äù) and you want to summarize the typical value and the spread in a way that matches methods that assume normality (like t-tests and linear models); in that situation, the mean is a good ‚Äúcenter of mass‚Äù and the SD describes typical deviation around it. Use median and interquartile range when the distribution is skewed, has a long tail, has clear outliers, or is ordinal, because the median (50th percentile) reflects the typical observation and the IQR (75th minus 25th percentile) captures the middle 50% without being pulled around by extreme values; a quick diagnostic is that if a histogram/boxplot shows skew or a few very large/small points, or if mean and median differ noticeably, median/IQR is usually the more honest summary. Outliers change the story because the mean and SD are not ‚Äúrobust‚Äù: a single extreme value can shift the mean toward it and inflate the SD, making the data look higher/lower and more variable than what most samples show, while the median and IQR often barely move; for example, if most measurements are around 10 but one is 100, the mean jumps upward and the SD balloons, but the median stays near 10 and the IQR still reflects the typical range. In lab reporting, it‚Äôs best to choose the summary that matches the distribution and the scientific question, and to be transparent: show a plot (dot plot/boxplot/histogram), report the sample size, and if outliers are present, state whether they are plausible biology/chemistry, a known measurement/entry error, or a separate subgroup; don‚Äôt delete them silently‚Äîeither correct obvious errors, analyze with and without them as a sensitivity check, or use robust summaries (median/IQR) and possibly robust methods, because outliers can represent real rare events that matter scientifically even if they distort mean/SD."),

