    ("For an infinite series, how do I decide between ratio test vs comparison test? Like, what clues should I look for just by staring at the terms?", "When you‚Äôre deciding by ‚Äústaring at the terms‚Äù of a series sum a_n, the ratio test is the first thing to try when the terms look like they have factorials (n!, (2n)!), exponentials (c^n), or products/powers that change a lot from n to n+1, because forming a_{n+1}/a_n usually cancels most of the mess and quickly reveals a limiting constant L; if L<1 the series converges absolutely, if L>1 it diverges, and if L=1 it tells you nothing (classic L=1 cases are harmonic-type terms like 1/n, p-series 1/n^p, and many ‚Äúpolynomial over polynomial‚Äù terms). The comparison test (direct or limit comparison) is the go-to when the term already resembles a known benchmark and doesn‚Äôt simplify nicely under a_{n+1}/a_n, especially when a_n is built from algebraic expressions like rational functions of n, roots, logs, or combinations that behave like a simple power of n; the clue is that you can estimate it above/below by something standard such as 1/n^p, 1/(n (log n)^q), or a geometric term r^n, or you can compute lim_{n‚Üí‚àû} a_n/b_n against a familiar b_n to transfer convergence. A practical rule of thumb is: if ‚Äúnext term over this term‚Äù collapses cleanly (factorials/exponentials), try ratio first; if ‚Äúthis term looks like a known template‚Äù (power/log behavior), try comparison first; and if ratio gives L=1, immediately switch to comparison (or another test) because L=1 is exactly where comparison with p-series, geometric series, or integral-test-type benchmarks usually decides the outcome."),

