    ("I don‚Äôt get cell structure‚Ä¶ what do the nucleus, mitochondria, and cell membrane actually DO?", "Think of a cell like a tiny, busy city: the nucleus is the control center that stores the cell‚Äôs DNA (the instruction manual) and uses it to direct what proteins get made and when, which is why it helps control growth, repair, and cell division; the mitochondria are the power plants that take energy from food molecules (like glucose) and convert it into ATP, the cell‚Äôs usable ‚Äúenergy currency,‚Äù through cellular respiration so the cell can do work like moving materials, building molecules, and sending signals; and the cell membrane is the flexible outer boundary that separates the inside from the outside and acts like a selective security gate, letting needed things (like oxygen, water, and nutrients) in, keeping many harmful or unnecessary things out, and helping the cell communicate with its environment using receptor proteins. In short, the nucleus gives instructions, mitochondria supply energy, and the cell membrane controls what enters and leaves while helping the cell interact with the world."),

