    ("Pre-calc: can you explain trig functions using the unit circle? I keep mixing up sine and cosine signs in different quadrants.", "On the unit circle (a circle of radius 1 centered at the origin), every angle Œ∏ in standard position lands on a point (x, y), and the key fact is that cos(Œ∏) = x and sin(Œ∏) = y, so cosine is the horizontal coordinate and sine is the vertical coordinate; that‚Äôs why the signs come straight from whether the point is to the right/left of the y-axis (x positive/negative) and above/below the x-axis (y positive/negative). This makes the quadrant sign pattern easy: in Quadrant I (top right) both x and y are positive so cos and sin are both positive; in Quadrant II (top left) x is negative but y is positive so cos is negative and sin is positive; in Quadrant III (bottom left) both are negative so cos and sin are both negative; in Quadrant IV (bottom right) x is positive but y is negative so cos is positive and sin is negative. A quick way to remember is ‚Äúcos = x, sin = y‚Äù plus ‚Äúright/left controls cosine, up/down controls sine,‚Äù and you can sanity-check with special angles: at 0¬∞ the point is (1, 0) so cos = 1 and sin = 0; at 90¬∞ it‚Äôs (0, 1) so cos = 0 and sin = 1; at 180¬∞ it‚Äôs (-1, 0) so cos = -1 and sin = 0; at 270¬∞ it‚Äôs (0, -1) so cos = 0 and sin = -1. If you also use tangent, tan(Œ∏) = sin(Œ∏)/cos(Œ∏) = y/x, so it‚Äôs positive when sine and cosine have the same sign (Quadrants I and III) and negative when they have opposite signs (Quadrants II and IV)."),

