    ("How does Congress actually pass a bill into law, and where can it get stopped along the way? Please keep it straight and not too wordy.", "A bill becomes a law through a series of required steps, and it can fail at many points: a member of the House or Senate introduces the bill, it is sent to one or more committees (and often a subcommittee) where it can be ignored, voted down, or changed; if the committee approves it, the full chamber debates it and votes, and it dies if it doesn‚Äôt get a majority. If it passes one chamber, it goes to the other chamber and must also pass there; if the second chamber changes it, both chambers must agree on the exact same text (often through a conference committee), and the bill can stall or fail if they can‚Äôt agree or if either chamber rejects the final version. After both chambers pass identical text, it goes to the President, who can sign it into law or veto it; Congress can still make it a law by overriding the veto with a two-thirds vote in both the House and the Senate, but if they can‚Äôt reach that threshold the bill stops. A bill can also be blocked by procedure, such as the Senate filibuster, which usually requires 60 senators to vote to end debate before a final vote can happen."),

