    ("Can you summarize the Industrial Revolution in the United States and list 3 ways it changed everyday life (good and bad)?", "The Industrial Revolution in the United States was the long shift, mainly from the early 1800s through the early 1900s, from an economy based on small farms and handcraft work to one powered by machines, factories, and new energy sources like water power, steam, and later electricity; it was driven by inventions and mass production, the growth of railroads and telegraphs that connected distant markets, and a huge rise in industrial cities and wage labor. One major everyday change was that many people moved from rural areas to towns and cities to work set hours for wages in mills and factories, which could bring steadier cash income and cheaper goods but also meant long hours, dangerous machinery, child labor in many places, and crowded housing and pollution. A second change was that mass production made items like cloth, clothing, tools, and later appliances more affordable and widely available, improving comfort and convenience for many families, but it also encouraged low-paid, repetitive work and made workers vulnerable to layoffs when factories slowed or closed. A third change was faster transportation and communication‚Äîrailroads, streetcars, and the telegraph (and later the telephone) made travel, news, and shipping much quicker, helping businesses and giving people more choices of jobs and products, while also bringing problems such as industrial accidents, the decline of some small local crafts and businesses, and a widening gap between wealthy industrialists and many low-wage workers that fueled labor conflicts and strikes."),

