    ("I‚Äôm writing a short response: what were the main causes of the Cold War, and how did it affect people in the US at home?", "The Cold War began after World War II because the United States and the Soviet Union emerged as rival superpowers with fundamentally different systems and goals: the US promoted democratic government and capitalism, while the USSR promoted one-party communist rule and a state-run economy, and each side feared the other would spread its system worldwide. Tensions grew from Soviet control of Eastern Europe, disagreements over Germany and Berlin, and a deep lack of trust made worse by nuclear weapons and an arms race; the US policy of ‚Äúcontainment‚Äù to stop communism (seen in events like the Truman Doctrine and Marshall Plan) and Soviet efforts to secure a buffer zone in Europe turned that mistrust into a long-term global standoff. At home in the US, the Cold War shaped daily life through constant anxiety about nuclear war, including ‚Äúduck and cover‚Äù drills in schools, fallout shelter planning, and civil defense warnings; it also fueled anti-communist investigations and loyalty programs that pressured people to prove they were not communist, with the Red Scare and McCarthy-era hearings leading to blacklists and lost jobs, especially in government, unions, and entertainment. The rivalry also affected the economy and society by boosting military spending and defense-related jobs, encouraging major investments in science and education (especially after the Soviet launch of Sputnik in 1957), and influencing culture and politics as Americans debated security versus civil liberties and watched international crises like the Berlin Blockade and the Cuban Missile Crisis with real fear that events overseas could quickly affect life at home."),

