    ("I don‚Äôt understand the work-energy theorem. Can you explain how work relates to kinetic energy with one simple example?", "The work-energy theorem says that the net work done on an object equals the change in its kinetic energy, written as Wnet = ŒîK = (1/2)mvf^2 ‚àí (1/2)mvi^2, where ‚Äúwork‚Äù means a force causing motion in the same direction (W = Fd when the force is constant and parallel to the motion). Here‚Äôs a simple example: imagine pushing a 2 kg box on a smooth, level floor (so friction is negligible) with a steady 10 N force for 3 m, starting from rest; the work you do is W = Fd = 10 √ó 3 = 30 J, so the box‚Äôs kinetic energy increases by 30 J. Since it started from rest, its initial kinetic energy is 0, so its final kinetic energy is 30 J, and you can even find the speed: (1/2)mv^2 = 30 ‚Üí (1/2)(2)v^2 = 30 ‚Üí v^2 = 30 ‚Üí v ‚âà 5.5 m/s; this shows the key idea that doing positive work transfers energy into the object‚Äôs motion, making it speed up (and if the net work were negative, like friction slowing it down, the kinetic energy would decrease by that amount)."),

