    ("What‚Äôs the Pythagorean theorem and how do I know when I‚Äôm allowed to use it on a triangle?", "The Pythagorean theorem is a rule for right triangles (triangles that have one 90¬∞ angle): if the two shorter sides that meet at the right angle are a and b (called the legs) and the side opposite the right angle is c (called the hypotenuse and it‚Äôs always the longest side), then a¬≤ + b¬≤ = c¬≤. You‚Äôre allowed to use it only when you know the triangle is a right triangle or you are trying to check whether it‚Äôs a right triangle; for example, if a triangle has side lengths 3, 4, and 5, you can test it by checking 3¬≤ + 4¬≤ = 9 + 16 = 25 = 5¬≤, which confirms it‚Äôs right, but if the triangle is not right (no 90¬∞ angle), the equation does not apply and you would need other tools like the Law of Cosines. A quick way to remember when it‚Äôs valid is: look for a right-angle marking in a diagram, wording like ‚Äúperpendicular,‚Äù ‚Äúsquare corner,‚Äù or ‚Äúheight/altitude to a base‚Äù that creates a right triangle, and make sure you label c as the side across from the 90¬∞ angle before plugging into the formula."),

