    ("I‚Äôm stuck on limits/continuity. How do you check if a piecewise function is continuous at x = 2?", "To check whether a piecewise function is continuous at x = 2, you need three things to match: the left-hand limit as x approaches 2, the right-hand limit as x approaches 2, and the actual function value at x = 2. First, find the expression that applies for x < 2 and compute lim x‚Üí2‚àí f(x) by plugging in 2 (or simplifying first if direct substitution gives something like 0/0); then find the expression that applies for x > 2 and compute lim x‚Üí2+ f(x) the same way. If those two one-sided limits are equal, the two-sided limit lim x‚Üí2 f(x) exists and equals that common number; next, compute f(2) using the piece that includes x = 2 (often the ‚Äúx = 2‚Äù or ‚Äúx ‚â• 2‚Äù branch). The function is continuous at x = 2 exactly when lim x‚Üí2‚àí f(x) = lim x‚Üí2+ f(x) = f(2); if the one-sided limits are different, you have a jump discontinuity, and if the limits match each other but don‚Äôt equal f(2) (or f(2) isn‚Äôt defined), you have a removable discontinuity (a ‚Äúhole‚Äù). For example, if f(x) = x + 1 for x < 2 and f(x) = 5 for x ‚â• 2, then the left-hand limit is 3, the right-hand limit is 5, so it‚Äôs not continuous at 2; but if the second piece were f(x) = x + 1 for x ‚â• 2 as well, then both limits and f(2) would be 3, so it would be continuous."),

