    ("Can you show me how limits work with a simple example? I don‚Äôt get what it means when x \'approaches\' something.", "When we say x ‚Äúapproaches‚Äù a number, we mean x gets closer and closer to that number without necessarily being equal to it, and a limit tells you what the function‚Äôs output gets closer and closer to as that happens. For a simple example, take f(x) = (x^2 ‚àí 1)/(x ‚àí 1) and ask what happens as x approaches 1: you can‚Äôt plug in x = 1 because you‚Äôd get 0/0, but you can simplify for x not equal to 1 by factoring x^2 ‚àí 1 into (x ‚àí 1)(x + 1), so f(x) = x + 1 whenever x ‚â† 1; now look at values near 1, like x = 0.9 gives f(x) = 1.9, x = 0.99 gives 1.99, x = 1.01 gives 2.01, and x = 1.001 gives 2.001, so as x gets closer to 1 from either side, f(x) gets closer to 2, which is why we write lim(x‚Üí1) (x^2 ‚àí 1)/(x ‚àí 1) = 2. The key idea is that the limit is about the trend of the outputs near the point, not necessarily the value at the point itself (in this example the function isn‚Äôt even defined at x = 1, yet the limit still exists and equals 2)."),

