    ("In computer science, what‚Äôs the difference between a transistor and a logic gate? I‚Äôm trying to understand how computers do \'1s and 0s.\'", "A transistor is a tiny electronic switch (or amplifier) made from semiconductor material that can let electric current flow or stop it, so in digital circuits we treat ‚Äúcurrent/voltage high‚Äù as a 1 and ‚Äúcurrent/voltage low‚Äù as a 0; by itself, a transistor is just one controllable on/off device. A logic gate is a small circuit built from multiple transistors (plus wiring) that performs a specific rule of Boolean logic on one or more input bits to produce an output bit, like an AND gate that outputs 1 only if both inputs are 1, an OR gate that outputs 1 if either input is 1, or a NOT gate that flips 1 to 0 and 0 to 1. In other words, transistors are the physical building blocks that switch electricity, while logic gates are the meaningful ‚Äúdecision-making‚Äù components made from transistors that combine and transform 1s and 0s; by connecting gates into larger circuits, computers create adders, memory, and processors that can do arithmetic and run programs."),

