    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 05:47 - Category: machine_learning_basics
    ("Machine learning basics: what‚Äôs the difference between training, validation, and test sets, and why can‚Äôt I just train on all my data?", "In supervised machine learning you usually split your labeled data into three roles because you need two different kinds of ‚Äúunseen‚Äù checks: the training set is the data the model is allowed to learn from, meaning it repeatedly looks at these examples and adjusts its parameters to reduce error; the validation set is a separate holdout you use during development to make decisions such as which model type to use, how strong regularization should be, how many training epochs to run, what probability threshold to pick, or which features to include, and it acts like a practice exam that guides tuning; the test set is a final, untouched holdout used once at the end to estimate how well the chosen, fully specified model will perform on truly new data, like a final exam that must stay secret to be an honest measure. You can‚Äôt ‚Äújust train on all your data‚Äù if you want a trustworthy performance estimate, because if the model (or you) uses every example for learning and tuning, you lose an independent yardstick and will almost always get an overly optimistic score, especially when overfitting happens (the model can partially memorize noise or quirks in the dataset), and even if you never explicitly train on the test set, repeatedly trying ideas and picking what looks best on the same data effectively leaks information and makes that score biased. A common workflow is to train on the training set, use validation results to choose settings and stop training before the model starts fitting noise, then lock everything and evaluate once on the test set; if data is scarce, cross-validation can rotate which data acts as validation while still keeping a final test set untouched for an unbiased last check."),

