    ("Number theory question: can you explain modular arithmetic like I‚Äôm in Algebra 2, and then solve 7x ‚â° 3 (mod 26)?", "Modular arithmetic is like doing arithmetic on a clock: working ‚Äúmod 26‚Äù means we only care about the remainder after dividing by 26, so two numbers are considered the same if they differ by a multiple of 26 (for example, 29 ‚â° 3 (mod 26) because 29 ‚àí 3 = 26), and you can add, subtract, and multiply as usual as long as you‚Äôre allowed to replace any number by an equivalent remainder at any time. To solve 7x ‚â° 3 (mod 26), we want to ‚Äúdivide by 7,‚Äù which in modular arithmetic means multiply by the modular inverse of 7 (a number y with 7y ‚â° 1 (mod 26)); since gcd(7,26)=1, an inverse exists, and using the Euclidean algorithm: 26 = 3¬∑7 + 5, 7 = 1¬∑5 + 2, 5 = 2¬∑2 + 1, then back-substitute to write 1 as a combination of 7 and 26: 1 = 5 ‚àí 2¬∑2 = 5 ‚àí 2¬∑(7 ‚àí 1¬∑5) = 3¬∑5 ‚àí 2¬∑7 = 3¬∑(26 ‚àí 3¬∑7) ‚àí 2¬∑7 = 3¬∑26 ‚àí 11¬∑7, so ‚àí11 is the inverse of 7 mod 26, meaning 7¬∑(‚àí11) ‚â° 1 (mod 26), and ‚àí11 ‚â° 15 (mod 26). Multiply both sides of 7x ‚â° 3 (mod 26) by 15 to get x ‚â° 15¬∑3 = 45 ‚â° 19 (mod 26), and you can check: 7¬∑19 = 133, and 133 ‚àí 3 = 130 is divisible by 26, so the solution is x ‚â° 19 (mod 26), meaning x = 19 + 26k for any integer k."),

