    ("Conic sections help: how do I tell if an equation is a circle vs ellipse vs parabola, and can you classify this one: 4x^2 + 9y^2 = 36?", "To tell conic sections apart from a general second-degree equation Ax^2 + Bxy + Cy^2 + Dx + Ey + F = 0, first look at the squared terms: if A and C are equal and have the same sign (and there is no Bxy term), it‚Äôs a circle; if A and C are both positive (or both negative) but not equal, it‚Äôs an ellipse; if one of A or C is zero (or, more generally, the squared terms have opposite signs), it‚Äôs a parabola (or a hyperbola when the signs are opposite). For 4x^2 + 9y^2 = 36, both x^2 and y^2 appear with positive coefficients and they are not equal, so it‚Äôs an ellipse; dividing by 36 gives x^2/9 + y^2/4 = 1, which is the standard ellipse centered at (0,0) with semi-axes 3 in the x-direction and 2 in the y-direction (so the major axis is horizontal)."),

