    ("APUSH help: what were the biggest causes of the Civil War, and can you give me a quick outline I could turn into a paragraph answer?", "The biggest causes of the Civil War centered on slavery and the power struggle it created: the Southern economy depended on enslaved labor and Southern leaders wanted slavery protected and expanded, while many in the North opposed its expansion (for moral reasons, for ‚Äúfree labor‚Äù economic opportunity, or both), and this disagreement turned into a political crisis over whether new western territories would be slave or free. Key flashpoints included the Missouri Compromise (1820) and then the breakdown of compromise after the Mexican‚ÄìAmerican War with the Compromise of 1850 and the Fugitive Slave Act, the Kansas‚ÄìNebraska Act (1854) and ‚ÄúBleeding Kansas,‚Äù the Dred Scott decision (1857) declaring Congress couldn‚Äôt ban slavery in the territories, John Brown‚Äôs raid (1859) heightening Southern fears of slave rebellion, and the election of Abraham Lincoln (1860) convincing many white Southerners that slavery‚Äôs future was threatened; secession followed, and the war began with Fort Sumter in April 1861. A quick outline you can turn into a paragraph is: start with a clear thesis that slavery was the central cause, then explain how westward expansion made slavery a national political fight, give 2‚Äì4 specific events showing compromise collapsing and tensions rising, and end by linking Lincoln‚Äôs election to secession and the outbreak of war."),

