    ("How does a bill become a law, but like specifically where Congress can kill it (committee, filibuster, veto, etc.)?", "A bill becomes a law only if it survives a long obstacle course, and Congress can ‚Äúkill‚Äù it at many points: a member introduces the bill in the House or Senate, and it is usually sent to a committee, where it can die if the chair refuses to take it up, if the committee never holds hearings, if it never gets a ‚Äúmarkup‚Äù meeting, or if the committee votes it down; even if the committee approves it, it often must pass the Rules Committee in the House (which can block it or set terms that make passage unlikely), and then it must pass the full chamber, where it can die by losing a vote, by leaders never scheduling it, or in the Senate by a filibuster (extended debate) unless supporters can get cloture, which takes three-fifths of the Senate, usually 60 votes, and even after cloture it can still fail on final passage. If it passes one chamber, it goes to the other, where the whole process repeats and it can be stopped again in committee, by not being brought up, by amendment fights, by a failed vote, or by a Senate filibuster; if the House and Senate pass different versions, they must agree on identical text, often through a conference committee or by one chamber accepting the other‚Äôs changes, and the bill can die if they cannot reach agreement or if either chamber rejects the compromise. If both chambers pass the same bill, it goes to the President, who can sign it into law or veto it; a veto kills it unless Congress overrides with a two-thirds vote in both the House and Senate, and even without a veto a bill can fail if the President takes no action and Congress adjourns during the 10-day window (a pocket veto). So the main ‚Äúkill points‚Äù are committee inaction or rejection, House scheduling and rules decisions, Senate filibusters and failed cloture, failed floor votes in either chamber, failure to reconcile House‚ÄìSenate differences, and a presidential veto that Congress cannot override."),

