    ("I\'m in intro ML and I\'m confused: can you explain bias vs variance in plain English and how it connects to overfitting? Like, what would I actually see on the training vs test curves?", "Bias and variance are two different ways a model can be wrong, and overfitting is what happens when variance gets too high. Bias is ‚Äúerror from being too simple‚Äù: the model has strong assumptions that don‚Äôt match the real pattern (like trying to fit a straight line to data that clearly curves), so it misses the signal; in practice you‚Äôll see both training and test performance are bad and fairly similar, meaning training error is high and test error is also high (this is underfitting). Variance is ‚Äúerror from being too sensitive‚Äù: the model can flex so much that it starts treating random noise in the training set as if it were real structure (like a very wiggly curve that goes through every training point), so training performance looks great but it doesn‚Äôt generalize; in practice you‚Äôll see training error keep dropping as the model gets more complex or you train longer, while test error drops at first but then bottoms out and starts rising, creating a widening gap between training and test curves‚Äîthis gap is the classic sign of overfitting. The bias‚Äìvariance tradeoff is that making a model more flexible usually lowers bias but raises variance, so the ‚Äúbest‚Äù point is often where test error is minimized: not too simple (high bias) and not too wiggly (high variance)."),

