    ("Can you walk me through using Bayes\' theorem for a medical test problem? Sensitivity = 0.98, specificity = 0.95, prevalence = 0.01. What\'s P(disease | positive) and why is it not close to 98%?", "Let D mean ‚Äúhas the disease‚Äù and + mean ‚Äútest is positive.‚Äù You‚Äôre given sensitivity P(+|D)=0.98, specificity P(‚àí|not D)=0.95 so the false positive rate is P(+|not D)=1‚àí0.95=0.05, and prevalence P(D)=0.01 so P(not D)=0.99. Bayes‚Äô theorem says P(D|+)=P(+|D)P(D) / [P(+|D)P(D)+P(+|not D)P(not D)] = (0.98√ó0.01) / [(0.98√ó0.01)+(0.05√ó0.99)] = 0.0098 / (0.0098+0.0495) = 0.0098/0.0593 ‚âà 0.165, so the chance you truly have the disease given a positive test is about 16.5%. It‚Äôs not close to 98% because 98% is the probability of testing positive if you already have the disease (sensitivity), not the probability of having the disease given a positive test; when the disease is rare (1% prevalence), there are many more healthy people than sick people, so even a modest false positive rate (5%) produces lots of false positives that can outnumber the true positives‚Äîfor example, out of 10,000 people you‚Äôd expect about 100 sick and 9,900 healthy, giving about 98 true positives (0.98√ó100) but about 495 false positives (0.05√ó9,900), so only 98 out of 593 positives are real, matching the ~16.5% result."),

