    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 05:50 - Category: computer_architecture
    ("CS systems question: can you explain what happens during a cache miss and how it impacts performance? If you can, connect it to spatial/temporal locality.", "A cache miss happens when the CPU looks for a needed piece of data or an instruction in a small, fast cache (like L1) and it isn‚Äôt there, so the processor must fetch it from a lower level of the memory hierarchy (L2, L3, or ultimately DRAM). Because each lower level is slower and farther away, the CPU often has to stall or do less useful work while waiting, which increases average memory access time and can dominate runtime in memory-bound programs; the miss penalty is the extra latency (and sometimes bandwidth use) incurred to bring the data in, typically by loading an entire cache line (a contiguous block of bytes) into the cache and possibly evicting another line. Spatial locality is why caches fetch a whole line: if a program accesses address X, it‚Äôs likely to soon access nearby addresses (like the next elements in an array), so pulling in adjacent bytes on a miss can turn future nearby accesses into cache hits; temporal locality is the idea that if a program uses something now, it‚Äôs likely to use it again soon (like a loop repeatedly reading the same variables), so keeping recently used lines in the cache reduces misses. When code has good spatial and temporal locality (sequential array traversal, tight loops reusing the same data), misses are rare and performance is high; when locality is poor (pointer-chasing through a linked structure with unpredictable addresses or working on a data set much larger than the cache), misses are frequent, the CPU spends more time waiting on memory, and overall performance drops."),

