    ("Chem help: I have to classify reaction types. How do I tell if something is precipitation vs acid-base vs redox? Example: Cu + 2AgNO3 -> Cu(NO3)2 + 2Ag", "To classify reactions, look for the key ‚Äúsignature‚Äù change: a precipitation reaction forms an insoluble solid (you‚Äôll see an (s) product that wasn‚Äôt there before, usually from mixing two aqueous ionic solutions and swapping ions), an acid‚Äìbase reaction transfers a proton H+ (often acid + base ‚Üí salt + water, or you can spot H+ moving from an acid like HCl to a base like OH‚àí or NH3), and a redox reaction involves electron transfer so oxidation numbers change (one species is oxidized, oxidation number increases; another is reduced, oxidation number decreases). For your example Cu + 2AgNO3 ‚Üí Cu(NO3)2 + 2Ag, it‚Äôs a redox single-displacement reaction: copper metal starts at oxidation state 0 and becomes Cu2+ in Cu(NO3)2 (oxidation number 0 to +2, so Cu is oxidized and loses 2 electrons), while Ag+ in AgNO3 goes from +1 to 0 in Ag(s) (reduced and gains electrons); nitrate NO3‚àí is a spectator ion that doesn‚Äôt change oxidation state, and it‚Äôs not precipitation because the driving force isn‚Äôt forming an insoluble salt from two aqueous solutions, and it‚Äôs not acid‚Äìbase because there‚Äôs no H+ transfer. A quick habit that works on most problems is: first check for H+ transfer (acid‚Äìbase), if not then check for oxidation-number changes (redox), and if neither happens but an insoluble solid forms from aqueous ions, it‚Äôs precipitation."),

