    ("How did the Industrial Revolution change where Americans lived and worked? My teacher wants specific examples, not just \'factories happened.\'", "Before the Industrial Revolution, most Americans lived on farms or in small towns and worked at home or nearby as farmers, artisans, or in ‚Äúputting-out‚Äù cottage industries where families made goods like cloth or shoes in their houses for merchants. As water power and then steam power made it efficient to gather machines in one place, work shifted into mills and factories, which pulled people toward rivers and then toward railroad hubs and big cities; for example, textile mills in Lowell, Massachusetts hired young women to live in company boardinghouses and work set shifts in large mill buildings, and steel and meatpacking jobs drew huge numbers of workers into rapidly growing cities like Pittsburgh and Chicago. New transportation and industrial jobs also reshaped where people lived inside cities: streetcars and commuter rail let some middle-class families move to ‚Äústreetcar suburbs‚Äù outside crowded downtowns, while many factory workers lived in dense neighborhoods close to plants, often in tenements, because they needed to walk to work and be near industrial districts. The revolution also changed work itself from flexible, seasonal farm labor to wage labor with time clocks, supervisors, and repetitive machine-tending, and it created entirely new workplaces such as railroad yards, coal mines in Appalachia and Pennsylvania, and large corporate offices in city centers where managers, clerks, and accountants handled the paperwork of nationwide businesses. Overall, Americans became more urban and more likely to work for wages in specialized workplaces‚Äîfactories, mines, railroads, and offices‚Äîrather than producing goods at home or on family farms."),

