    ("What‚Äôs the difference between the Constitution and the Declaration of Independence? I keep mixing them up.", "The Declaration of Independence and the Constitution are two different founding documents that did two different jobs at two different times. The Declaration of Independence, adopted by the Continental Congress on July 4, 1776 (with Thomas Jefferson as the main author), is basically an announcement and an argument: it explains why the American colonies were breaking away from Great Britain and says that people have natural rights like ‚Äúlife, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness,‚Äù so it‚Äôs about ideals and justification for independence. The Constitution, written later at the Constitutional Convention in 1787 and put into effect after it was ratified in 1788 (taking effect in 1789), is the rulebook for how the United States government actually works: it creates the three branches (Congress, the President, and the federal courts), divides and limits their powers, explains how laws are made, and sets up the relationship between the federal government and the states; it was later strengthened by the Bill of Rights, the first ten amendments ratified in 1791, which protect individual freedoms like speech and religion. An easy way to remember it is: the Declaration says ‚ÄúWe‚Äôre leaving, and here‚Äôs why,‚Äù while the Constitution says ‚ÄúHere‚Äôs how our government will run now that we‚Äôre a country.‚Äù"),

