    ("My science teacher said \'simple machines\'‚Ä¶ what are the 6 types and can you give me easy examples from my house?", "Simple machines are basic tools that make work easier by changing the size of a force or the direction you push or pull, and the six types are lever, wheel and axle, pulley, inclined plane, wedge, and screw. A lever is a rigid bar that pivots on a point, like a bottle opener, a hammer claw pulling out a nail, or a seesaw; a wheel and axle is a wheel attached to a rod that turns together, like a doorknob, a rolling office chair, or a pizza cutter; a pulley uses a grooved wheel and a rope to lift or move something, like the pulley on window blinds or a clothesline pulley. An inclined plane is a ramp that lets you raise things with less effort over a longer distance, like a ramp into a garage or even stairs acting like a stepped ramp; a wedge is like two inclined planes back-to-back that splits or cuts, like a kitchen knife, a doorstop, or an axe; and a screw is an inclined plane wrapped around a cylinder that turns to hold things tightly or lift, like jar lids, wood screws, or the threaded base of a light bulb. If you look around your house, you‚Äôll notice many objects combine simple machines, like scissors (two levers with wedges as blades) or a can opener (lever plus wheel and axle), which is why they make everyday tasks easier."),

