    ("In stats, what‚Äôs the difference between mean, median, and mode? Can you do a quick example with numbers?", "Mean, median, and mode are three common ways to describe the ‚Äúcenter‚Äù of a set of numbers, but they do it in different ways: the mean is the average (add all values and divide by how many values there are), the median is the middle value when the numbers are put in order (or the average of the two middle values if there‚Äôs an even count), and the mode is the value that appears most often. For example, with the numbers 2, 3, 3, 7, 10, the mean is (2+3+3+7+10)/5 = 25/5 = 5, the median is 3 because the ordered list is 2, 3, 3, 7, 10 and the middle number is 3, and the mode is also 3 because it occurs more than any other value. A helpful way to remember it is that mean uses all the numbers, median depends on the order and the middle, and mode depends on repeats, so they can be the same or different depending on the data."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 05:56 - Category: polynomial_functions
    ("In Algebra 2, what‚Äôs a polynomial function vs a linear function? Can you compare their graphs?", "A linear function is the simplest kind of polynomial function: it has the form f(x) = mx + b, where m and b are constants, and its highest power of x is 1; a polynomial function more generally has the form f(x) = anx^n + an‚àí1x^(n‚àí1) + ‚Ä¶ + a1x + a0 where n is a nonnegative integer and the coefficients are real numbers, so it can include quadratics (degree 2), cubics (degree 3), and higher degrees. On a graph, every linear function is a straight line with constant slope m (it rises or falls at the same rate everywhere) and crosses the y-axis at b, while polynomial graphs are smooth, continuous curves (no breaks or sharp corners) whose overall ‚Äúend behavior‚Äù depends on the leading term anx^n: if n is even, both ends go the same direction (up if an > 0, down if an < 0), and if n is odd, the ends go opposite directions (down-left/up-right if an > 0, up-left/down-right if an < 0). Another key graph difference is turning points: a line never turns, but a degree-n polynomial can have up to n‚àí1 turning points, so higher-degree polynomials can wiggle more; for example, y = x^2 is a U-shaped parabola with one turning point, and y = x^3 has an S-shape with a flattening point. Both types can cross the x-axis where f(x) = 0, but a polynomial can have multiple x-intercepts (up to its degree, counting multiplicity), whereas a non-vertical line has at most one x-intercept."),

