    ("Can you explain limits and continuity with an intuitive example? I get the math steps but not what it means.", "A limit is the value a function is heading toward when you get very close to an input, even if you never land exactly on it, and continuity means the function‚Äôs behavior has no ‚Äújump‚Äù or ‚Äúhole‚Äù at that point so you can draw the graph without lifting your pencil. An intuitive example is walking toward a door: if you start 10 meters away and each step halves the remaining distance (5 m, then 2.5 m, then 1.25 m, and so on), you keep getting closer to 0 meters away; the limit of your distance as the number of steps grows is 0, which captures the idea of ‚Äúapproaching‚Äù without needing to talk about the final step. For continuity, imagine a road that reaches a bridge: if the road meets the bridge smoothly, your position changes smoothly as you move (continuous), but if there‚Äôs a missing plank (a hole) you can get arbitrarily close to the gap from either side yet there‚Äôs no actual surface at that exact spot (a function can have a limit there but not be continuous), and if the bridge is suddenly shifted up or down (a jump) then as you approach the meeting point from the left you head toward one height while from the right you head toward a different height, so the limit doesn‚Äôt exist and the function is definitely not continuous. In symbols, a function is continuous at x = a when three things match up: f(a) is defined, the limit as x approaches a exists, and that limit equals f(a); intuitively, ‚Äúwhat you‚Äôre approaching‚Äù must equal ‚Äúwhat you get at the point,‚Äù with no gaps or jumps."),

