    ("How does DNA replication work in simple steps? Also what are the enzymes called again?", "DNA replication is how a cell copies its DNA before it divides, and it works like making a matching ‚Äúpartner strand‚Äù for each original strand. First, replication begins at an origin of replication, where helicase unwinds the double helix and separates the two strands by breaking the hydrogen bonds between base pairs, forming a replication fork; topoisomerase (also called DNA gyrase in many bacteria) relieves the twisting strain ahead of the fork, and single-strand binding proteins keep the separated strands from snapping back together. Next, primase makes short RNA primers because DNA polymerase cannot start from nothing; then DNA polymerase adds DNA nucleotides to the 3‚Ä≤ end of the primer, building new DNA only in the 5‚Ä≤‚Üí3‚Ä≤ direction by matching bases (A with T, C with G). Because the two template strands run in opposite directions, one new strand is made continuously toward the fork (the leading strand), while the other is made in short pieces away from the fork called Okazaki fragments (the lagging strand). After that, the RNA primers are removed and replaced with DNA (in bacteria this is mainly done by DNA polymerase I; in eukaryotes primer removal involves RNase H and FEN1, and filling is done by DNA polymerase), and finally DNA ligase seals the remaining ‚Äúnicks‚Äù in the sugar-phosphate backbone to make each strand continuous. The result is two identical DNA double helices, each with one original (parent) strand and one newly made strand, which is why replication is called semi-conservative."),

