    ("I‚Äôm doing a science fair thing. Can you help me design an experiment about plants + light? I need a hypothesis and variables and a control.", "You can do a clear, testable experiment by asking: ‚ÄúHow does the amount of light each day affect plant growth?‚Äù Hypothesis: If a plant gets more hours of light per day, then it will grow taller and produce more leaves over two to three weeks, because light provides the energy for photosynthesis. Independent variable (what you change): hours of light per day, for example 0 hours (dark), 4 hours, 8 hours, and 12 hours using the same lamp and keeping the lamp the same distance from each plant; dependent variables (what you measure): plant height in centimeters, number of leaves, and optionally leaf color or mass at the end; controlled variables (what you keep the same): plant species and starting size (use identical seeds or same-age seedlings), pot size, soil type and amount, watering amount and schedule, temperature, and where the plants sit so only light time differs. Control group: the ‚Äúnormal‚Äù condition you compare everything to, such as 8 hours of light per day (or whatever matches typical indoor growing), while the other groups are the experimental groups with less or more light. Procedure idea: plant the same number of seeds in identical pots, thin to one seedling per pot, assign at least 3 pots per light level to make results more reliable, water each pot with the same measured amount (like 20 mL) on the same days, measure height and leaf count at the same time every day or every two days, and record your data in a table and graph (light hours on the x-axis and average height or leaf number on the y-axis) to see the trend."),

