    ("Can you explain projectile motion with an example? Like if I throw a ball at 20 m/s at 30 degrees, how far does it go (ignore air resistance)?", "Projectile motion (ignoring air resistance) is just two simpler motions happening at the same time: horizontally the ball moves at a constant speed, and vertically it moves like any object under gravity, slowing down on the way up and speeding up on the way down; the key trick is to split the launch speed into components. For a throw at 20 m/s at 30¬∞ above horizontal, the horizontal component is vx = v cosŒ∏ = 20 cos30¬∞ = 20(0.8660) ‚âà 17.32 m/s, and the vertical component is vy = v sinŒ∏ = 20 sin30¬∞ = 20(0.5) = 10 m/s; gravity is g ‚âà 9.8 m/s¬≤ downward. If the ball lands at the same height it was thrown, the total time in the air comes from the vertical motion: time to go up is vy/g = 10/9.8 ‚âà 1.02 s, so the total time of flight is T = 2vy/g ‚âà 2.04 s. The horizontal range is then distance = vxT ‚âà 17.32 √ó 2.04 ‚âà 35.3 m; this matches the compact range formula R = (v¬≤ sin(2Œ∏))/g = (20¬≤ sin60¬∞)/9.8 = (400 √ó 0.8660)/9.8 ‚âà 35.3 m, so the ball goes about 35 meters horizontally under these assumptions."),

