    ("I don‚Äôt get limits/continuity. Is f(x) = (x^2-1)/(x-1) continuous at x=1? Can you explain without just saying ‚Äúcancel it‚Äù?", "To decide continuity at x = 1, you need two things: the function value f(1) must exist, and the limit as x approaches 1 must exist and equal that value. Here f(x) = (x^2 ‚àí 1)/(x ‚àí 1) is not even defined at x = 1 because the denominator becomes 0, so f(1) does not exist, which already means the function is not continuous at x = 1 as written. But you can still find the limit near 1 without ‚Äújust canceling‚Äù by using the idea that x^2 ‚àí 1 is the difference of squares: x^2 ‚àí 1 = (x ‚àí 1)(x + 1), so for x not equal to 1 the expression equals (x ‚àí 1)(x + 1)/(x ‚àí 1) = x + 1; this does not change the function at x = 1 because we never used x = 1, we only described what the function equals for nearby x values. Since near 1 the function behaves exactly like x + 1, the limit as x approaches 1 is the same as the limit of x + 1, which is 2; you can also see this by plugging in numbers close to 1, like x = 0.9 gives 1.9 and x = 1.1 gives 2.1, so the values squeeze toward 2. So the limit exists and equals 2, but the function has a ‚Äúhole‚Äù at x = 1 because f(1) is undefined, meaning it is not continuous there; if you define a new function g with g(x) = (x^2 ‚àí 1)/(x ‚àí 1) for x ‚â† 1 and set g(1) = 2, then g would be continuous at x = 1 (this is called a removable discontinuity)."),

