    ("In my CS class we started digital logic. Can you make a truth table for (A AND B) OR (NOT A) and then simplify it?", "To make the truth table for F = (A AND B) OR (NOT A), list all input pairs for A and B, compute A AND B, compute NOT A, then OR those two results: when A=0 and B=0, A AND B=0, NOT A=1, so F=1; when A=0 and B=1, A AND B=0, NOT A=1, so F=1; when A=1 and B=0, A AND B=0, NOT A=0, so F=0; when A=1 and B=1, A AND B=1, NOT A=0, so F=1. So the truth table outputs are (A,B)->F: (0,0)->1, (0,1)->1, (1,0)->0, (1,1)->1. To simplify, use the Boolean identity X + X‚ÄôY = X + Y (absorption), rewriting as (NOT A) + (A AND B) = (NOT A) + B, so the simplified expression is F = (NOT A) OR B, and you can verify it matches the table: it‚Äôs only 0 when A=1 and B=0, otherwise 1."),

