    ("I‚Äôm lost on distributed systems: what‚Äôs the difference between latency and throughput, and why do people talk about ‚Äúeventual consistency‚Äù?", "Latency and throughput measure different things in a distributed system: latency is how long one request takes from start to finish (the delay you feel for a single operation, often measured in milliseconds), while throughput is how much work the system can complete per unit time (how many requests per second it can handle overall). A helpful analogy is a grocery store: latency is how long you personally wait in line and get checked out, while throughput is how many customers the store can check out per minute; you can improve throughput by adding more cashiers, but your latency might still be high if your particular line is slow, and you can have low latency for one customer even if total throughput is low. People talk about eventual consistency because in distributed systems data is copied (replicated) across multiple machines for speed and reliability, and when you update one copy it takes time for that update to reach all the others; eventual consistency means the system allows those copies to be temporarily different, but guarantees that if no new updates happen, all replicas will converge to the same value later. This tradeoff is common because waiting for every replica to confirm every write can increase latency or reduce availability during network problems, so some systems choose faster responses and higher availability now, accepting that readers might briefly see old data (for example, you change your profile photo and one server shows the new one immediately while another still shows the old one for a few seconds) until the update finishes propagating."),

