    ("Can you explain transistors like I‚Äôm a beginner CS/EE student? Like how does a MOSFET actually act like a switch?", "A transistor is a controllable valve for electric current, and in digital electronics we use it mainly as an on/off switch; in a MOSFET (Metal-Oxide-Semiconductor Field-Effect Transistor), the ‚Äúcontrol knob‚Äù is the gate voltage, which creates an electric field that either allows or blocks current between the drain and source. Physically, the gate is separated from the semiconductor by a very thin insulating oxide, so ideally almost no DC current flows into the gate; instead, the gate voltage changes the charge distribution in the silicon underneath it. In an n-channel enhancement MOSFET (the most common type in logic), if the gate-to-source voltage VGS is below a threshold voltage VTH, there isn‚Äôt a continuous conductive path (a ‚Äúchannel‚Äù) between source and drain, so the device is off and the drain-source path looks like a very large resistance (aside from tiny leakage). When you raise VGS above VTH, electrons are attracted to the surface under the gate and form an inversion layer that connects source to drain; now the device is on and behaves like a small resistance RDS(on) when used as a switch, so current can flow from drain to source (or source to drain, depending on the circuit) with a small voltage drop. Thinking in switch terms: gate low means open switch, gate high means closed switch, but the ‚Äúclosed‚Äù switch is really a resistor whose value depends on VGS, device size, and temperature, and the ‚Äúopen‚Äù switch still has small leakage. In real circuits you also care about the MOSFET‚Äôs intrinsic body diode (from the body to the drain/source depending on type), which can conduct in one direction even when the MOSFET is off, and about switching speed: although the gate draws almost no steady current, it has capacitance, so you must charge and discharge that capacitance to turn the MOSFET on and off, which is why gate drivers and rise/fall times matter. Finally, in CMOS logic a p-channel MOSFET is the complement: it turns on when its gate is pulled low relative to its source, so pairing an nMOS (pull-down) and pMOS (pull-up) lets a logic gate strongly connect the output either to ground or to VDD with very little static power."),

