    ("Precalc: How do I know if a graph matches a polynomial function vs an exponential? Like what features should I look for?", "To tell whether a graph is more likely polynomial or exponential, look at end behavior, how fast it grows, and whether it has asymptotes. A polynomial y = a_n x^n + ‚Ä¶ is defined for all real x, is smooth with no breaks, and does not have a horizontal asymptote; as x goes to ¬±infinity the ends either both go the same way (even degree) or go opposite ways (odd degree), and any ‚Äúturning points‚Äù are limited (at most degree minus 1), so the graph can wiggle but only a finite number of times. Exponential functions like y = a¬∑b^x (with b > 0 and b ‚â† 1) typically have a horizontal asymptote (often y = 0 if there‚Äôs no vertical shift), stay on one side of that asymptote, and show growth or decay that becomes dramatically steeper in one direction; they also have a constant multiplicative change over equal x-steps (for example, multiplying by the same factor each time x increases by 1), whereas polynomials have changes that are not constant ratios and, for large |x|, grow much more slowly than exponentials (an exponential will eventually outgrow any polynomial). A quick practical check is to compare values at equally spaced x‚Äôs: if the ratios y(x+1)/y(x) are roughly constant, that suggests exponential; if instead the differences of some order become roughly constant (first differences for linear, second for quadratic, etc., when x-steps are equal), that suggests polynomial. Also watch for domain and intercept behavior: exponentials never cross their horizontal asymptote and often pass through (0, a) since b^0 = 1, while polynomials can cross the x-axis multiple times and have no ‚Äúleveling off‚Äù unless you‚Äôre only viewing a small window."),

