    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 06:03 - Category: carbon_cycle
    ("Can you explain the carbon cycle in a way that makes sense for a quiz? Like where does the carbon actually go?", "The carbon cycle is the movement of carbon atoms through Earth‚Äôs main ‚Äústorage places,‚Äù called reservoirs: the atmosphere (mostly as carbon dioxide, CO2), living things (as sugars, fats, proteins, and other organic molecules), the oceans (as dissolved CO2, carbonic acid, bicarbonate, and carbonate), soils and rocks (as organic matter and carbonate minerals like limestone), and fossil fuels (coal, oil, and natural gas). Carbon goes from the air into plants when they do photosynthesis, using CO2 to build biomass; then it moves through food webs when animals eat plants (and other animals), and it returns to the air when plants, animals, and microbes do cellular respiration, which releases CO2. When organisms die, decomposers break them down; that sends more carbon back to the atmosphere as CO2 (and sometimes methane, CH4, in low-oxygen places like wetlands), while some carbon stays in soils as organic matter for years to centuries. The ocean also absorbs CO2 directly from the air; some of that carbon is used by marine life, and some becomes carbonate that can form shells and skeletons, which may sink and eventually become seafloor sediments and carbonate rock, storing carbon for thousands to millions of years. Over very long times, plate tectonics and volcanism can return some of that rock-stored carbon to the atmosphere as CO2, and humans speed up the cycle by burning fossil fuels and cutting forests, which moves carbon that was stored underground or in biomass into the atmosphere mainly as CO2; for a quiz, remember the key ‚Äúwhere it goes‚Äù paths are air to plants (photosynthesis), living things to air (respiration), dead matter to air or soil (decomposition), air to ocean (dissolving), ocean to rocks (sediments/limestone), and fossil fuels/biomass to air (combustion)."),

