    ("Geometry help: I know the Pythagorean theorem is a^2+b^2=c^2, but how do I tell which side is c in a word problem?", "In the Pythagorean theorem, c is always the hypotenuse, meaning the side opposite the right angle (the 90¬∞ corner) and it is the longest side of the right triangle; the other two sides that form the right angle are a and b (the ‚Äúlegs‚Äù). In a word problem, first find or identify the right angle (sometimes it‚Äôs stated as ‚Äúright angle,‚Äù ‚Äúperpendicular,‚Äù or shown by a little square in a diagram); the side directly across from that right angle is c, and if the problem describes a ladder leaning on a wall, a diagonal across a rectangle, or the ‚Äústraight-line distance‚Äù between two points, that slanted/diagonal distance is usually c because it‚Äôs opposite the right angle formed by the horizontal and vertical directions. As a quick check, if you accidentally choose a shorter side as c, you‚Äôll often get something impossible like c coming out smaller than a or b, but the hypotenuse must be longer than either leg."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 06:04 - Category: simple_machines_intro
    ("In a simple machine, what‚Äôs mechanical advantage and why does a pulley make something ‚Äúeasier‚Äù even if you pull more rope?", "Mechanical advantage is how much a simple machine multiplies your input force, meaning it tells you how many times easier it is to lift or move something compared with pushing or lifting it directly; in an ideal machine it‚Äôs the ratio of the load force to the effort force, and for many simple machines it also matches how much farther you have to move your hand compared with how far the load moves. A pulley can make a job feel easier because it lets you trade distance for force: with a single fixed pulley you mostly just change the direction of your pull (so you can pull down instead of lifting up) and the mechanical advantage is about 1, but with a movable pulley or a block-and-tackle you support the load with multiple rope segments, so each segment shares the weight and you only need a fraction of the force (for example, two supporting rope segments gives a mechanical advantage of about 2, so a 100 N load needs about 50 N of pull). The reason you must pull more rope is energy conservation: the work you put in is force times distance, so if your force is cut in half, you have to pull about twice as far to do the same amount of work (ignoring friction), and real pulleys also have some friction so you may need a bit more force than the ideal calculation."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 06:04 - Category: congress
    ("Civics: What‚Äôs the difference between the House and the Senate and why do we have both? Please keep it clear, not super textbook-y.", "The House of Representatives and the Senate are the two parts of Congress, and they‚Äôre different on purpose. The House is meant to represent people more directly: each state gets a number of House members based on its population, so bigger states have more representatives, and House members serve 2-year terms, which keeps them closely tied to what voters want right now. The Senate is meant to represent the states equally: every state gets exactly two senators no matter how big or small it is, and senators serve 6-year terms, which helps the Senate be a steadier, slower-moving ‚Äúcooling off‚Äù place for big decisions. We have both because the U.S. wanted a balance between ‚Äúpower based on population‚Äù and ‚Äúequal voice for each state,‚Äù and because making a law requires both chambers to agree on the same bill, which forces compromise and helps prevent quick, extreme changes. In simple terms, the House is like the ‚Äúpeople‚Äôs side‚Äù that reacts faster, and the Senate is like the ‚Äústates‚Äô side‚Äù that takes a longer view, and together they‚Äôre designed to make laws carefully rather than too easily."),

