    ("How does the Supreme Court decide which cases it takes? What is certiorari in normal words?", "The Supreme Court gets thousands of requests each year but chooses only a small number to decide, so it mainly takes cases that raise important federal or constitutional questions, cases where different federal appeals courts or state supreme courts have reached conflicting answers on the same legal issue (so the law is applied differently in different places), or cases that have major national significance and need a clear, final rule. Most cases reach the Court through a petition for a writ of certiorari, which is simply a request asking the Supreme Court to review a lower court‚Äôs decision; in normal words, certiorari means ‚Äúplease take my case and look at it.‚Äù The Justices meet in private to discuss these petitions, and under the ‚ÄúRule of Four‚Äù the Court will agree to hear a case if at least four of the nine Justices vote to grant certiorari; if they deny certiorari, the lower court‚Äôs ruling stays in place and the Supreme Court usually does not explain why it declined."),

