    ("I‚Äôm stuck on this complex numbers question: write (3 4i) / (1 + 2i) in a + bi form, and then convert it to polar form. Show the steps so I can copy the method.", "To write (3 ‚àí 4i)/(1 + 2i) in a + bi form, multiply top and bottom by the conjugate of the denominator, 1 ‚àí 2i, so (3 ‚àí 4i)/(1 + 2i) = [(3 ‚àí 4i)(1 ‚àí 2i)]/[(1 + 2i)(1 ‚àí 2i)]; expand the numerator: (3 ‚àí 4i)(1 ‚àí 2i) = 3 ‚àí 6i ‚àí 4i + 8i^2 = 3 ‚àí 10i ‚àí 8 = ‚àí5 ‚àí 10i (since i^2 = ‚àí1), and the denominator is (1 + 2i)(1 ‚àí 2i) = 1 ‚àí (2i)^2 = 1 ‚àí 4i^2 = 1 + 4 = 5, so the result in a + bi form is (‚àí5 ‚àí 10i)/5 = ‚àí1 ‚àí 2i. For polar form, compute the modulus r = |‚àí1 ‚àí 2i| = sqrt((‚àí1)^2 + (‚àí2)^2) = sqrt(5), and find the argument Œ∏: tan Œ∏ = (imag/real) = (‚àí2)/(‚àí1) = 2, but since (‚àí1, ‚àí2) is in Quadrant III the angle is Œ∏ = œÄ + arctan(2) (equivalently Œ∏ = ‚àí(œÄ ‚àí arctan(2))), so the polar form is sqrt(5)(cos(œÄ + arctan(2)) + i sin(œÄ + arctan(2))); numerically, arctan(2) ‚âà 1.1071 rad, so Œ∏ ‚âà 4.2487 rad (or Œ∏ ‚âà ‚àí2.0344 rad), giving ‚àí1 ‚àí 2i = sqrt(5)(cos 4.2487 + i sin 4.2487)."),

