    ("Stats homework: given a dataset with a huge outlier, how do I decide between mean/SD vs median/IQR? Also how would that change a basic regression?", "If your dataset has a huge outlier, the key question is whether that extreme value is a real, meaningful part of the population you want to describe or a mistake/irrelevant case, because the mean and standard deviation are very sensitive to extreme values while the median and IQR are resistant. Use mean/SD when the distribution is roughly symmetric (often close to normal), the outlier is not dominating the scale, and you care about the arithmetic average (for example, total cost per person), but if the histogram/boxplot shows strong skew or one point pulls the mean far away from where most observations lie, median/IQR usually gives a more representative ‚Äútypical‚Äù value and spread for the bulk of the data; a practical check is to report both and see whether the mean shifts a lot relative to the median, and to verify whether the outlier is a data entry error (extra zero, wrong units) or a legitimate observation (a true rare event). For regression, an outlier can matter in two different ways: if it is an outlier in the response variable y but has an ordinary x value, it creates a large residual and can inflate the residual standard error and distort inference; if it is extreme in the predictor x (a high-leverage point), it can strongly change the fitted slope and intercept, especially if it also has a large residual (an influential point), so the ‚Äúbasic regression‚Äù line you get from ordinary least squares may tilt toward that one case. The standard approach is to fit the usual OLS model, then diagnose influence using residual plots plus leverage and influence measures (such as studentized residuals, hat values, and Cook‚Äôs distance), and if the outlier is an error you correct/remove it, while if it is real you either keep it but report robust summaries and a robust regression (for example, Huber or least absolute deviations/quantile regression), consider transforming variables (like logging a right-skewed outcome), or present a sensitivity analysis showing the regression with and without that point so the reader can see how dependent your conclusion is on the outlier."),

