    ("I‚Äôm confused: what‚Äôs the difference between the House and the Senate, and how does a bill become a law? Please keep it simple but accurate.", "The U.S. Congress has two chambers that share lawmaking power but are designed to represent people in different ways: the House of Representatives has 435 voting members, with each state‚Äôs number based on population, members serve 2-year terms, and it‚Äôs meant to reflect voters more quickly; the Senate has 100 members, with 2 senators from each state regardless of population, senators serve 6-year terms (staggered so about one-third are up every two years), and it‚Äôs meant to give states equal representation and be more stable. A bill becomes a law through several steps: someone in Congress introduces a bill in either the House or Senate (except money-raising bills must start in the House), it is sent to committees that study it and may change it, then the full chamber debates and votes; if it passes, it goes to the other chamber to go through the same process, and because the House and Senate often pass different versions, they must agree on the exact same text (often by negotiating a compromise). Once both chambers pass the same final version, the bill goes to the President, who can sign it into law or veto it; if vetoed, Congress can still make it a law by overriding the veto with a two-thirds vote in both the House and the Senate."),

