    ("What does ‚Äúmean‚Äù and ‚Äúmedian‚Äù mean? I‚Äôm in 4th grade and my teacher showed a chart and I got confused.", "Mean and median are two ways to describe what a ‚Äútypical‚Äù number is in a group of numbers. The mean is the average: you add all the numbers together and then divide by how many numbers there are; for example, if the numbers are 2, 4, and 9, the mean is (2 + 4 + 9) √∑ 3 = 15 √∑ 3 = 5. The median is the middle number when the numbers are put in order from least to greatest; for 2, 4, 9 the median is 4, and if there are an even number of numbers like 2, 4, 9, 10, the median is halfway between the two middle numbers (4 and 9), so it‚Äôs (4 + 9) √∑ 2 = 6.5. A helpful tip is that the mean can get pulled up or down by one really big or really small number, but the median usually stays closer to the ‚Äúmiddle,‚Äù so charts sometimes use the median when there‚Äôs an outlier (a number that‚Äôs far away from the others)."),

