    ("What does the Supreme Court do? I have to write 5 sentences and I don‚Äôt really get it.", "The Supreme Court is the highest court in the United States, and its main job is to decide what the Constitution and federal laws mean when there is a real legal disagreement. It does this by hearing a small number of important cases, usually after they have been decided in lower courts, and the justices read written arguments and listen to lawyers speak. The Court can say that a law or a government action is unconstitutional, which means it is not allowed because it conflicts with the Constitution. When the Supreme Court makes a decision, lower federal courts must follow it, and it often affects how laws are applied across the whole country. A helpful way to remember it is that Congress makes laws, the President carries them out, and the Supreme Court explains what the laws and the Constitution mean in court."),

