    ("I wrote a Scratch game but it won‚Äôt move my character right. What are good debugging steps to figure out what‚Äôs wrong?", "Start by making the problem super specific: does the sprite not move at all, move left instead of right, move only once, or move but then snap back, and does it happen with arrow keys, clicking a button, or automatic movement; then open the sprite‚Äôs scripts and find every place that changes x position, uses ‚Äúmove ( ) steps,‚Äù or sets direction, because the most common cause is that one script moves right while another script is constantly setting x back to a fixed value or forcing direction. Next, confirm the input is actually being detected by temporarily adding a ‚Äúsay‚Äù block like ‚Äúsay right‚Äù inside the ‚Äúif key (right arrow) pressed?‚Äù or right after the event block you expect to run, and also add a quick ‚Äúsay x: (x position)‚Äù after your movement block so you can see whether x is increasing; if the message never appears, the event isn‚Äôt firing (wrong key, code not under ‚Äúwhen green flag clicked,‚Äù or the script is on the wrong sprite), and if the message appears but x doesn‚Äôt change, the movement block isn‚Äôt being reached or is being canceled immediately. Then check for logic that prevents movement, such as an ‚Äúif touching color?‚Äù or ‚Äúif touching wall?‚Äù that is always true, a ‚Äúrepeat until‚Äù that never ends, or a ‚Äústop all‚Äù or ‚Äústop this script‚Äù that triggers; also look for direction issues like ‚Äúpoint in direction (-90)‚Äù (left) being used when you mean 90 (right), ‚Äúset rotation style [left-right]‚Äù versus ‚Äúall around,‚Äù and whether you‚Äôre using ‚Äúchange x by ( )‚Äù (best for pure left/right) versus ‚Äúmove ( ) steps‚Äù (which depends on direction). Finally, isolate and rebuild: make a tiny test script on the same sprite that only says ‚Äúwhen green flag clicked forever if key right arrow pressed then change x by 5,‚Äù see if that works, and if it does, add your original blocks back a few at a time until it breaks; the last block you added is usually the culprit, and fixing it often means removing the extra ‚Äúset x to ‚Ä¶‚Äù loop, moving code into the correct forever loop, or making sure only one script is controlling movement."),

