    ("What are the 3 main branches of the U.S. government and how do they ‚Äúcheck‚Äù each other? I need it for civics.", "The U.S. government has three main branches: the Legislative Branch (Congress‚ÄîHouse of Representatives and Senate) makes laws, the Executive Branch (the President and executive agencies) carries out and enforces laws, and the Judicial Branch (the Supreme Court and other federal courts) interprets laws and the Constitution. They ‚Äúcheck‚Äù each other through checks and balances so no one branch becomes too powerful: for example, Congress can pass laws, control government spending, and impeach and remove a president or federal judges, while the President can veto bills and appoint judges and other officials, and the courts can declare laws or executive actions unconstitutional through judicial review; in turn, Congress can override a presidential veto with a two-thirds vote in both houses and must approve many presidential appointments and treaties, and the President can nominate judges but the Senate must confirm them. Together, these powers force the branches to cooperate and limit each other, protecting liberty by preventing any single part of government from dominating."),

