    ("In physics, can you explain the work-energy theorem with a quick example problem? I get lost with the symbols.", "The work-energy theorem says that the net work done on an object equals the change in its kinetic energy: Wnet = ŒîK, where Wnet is the total work from all forces (in joules), K is kinetic energy, and ŒîK = Kfinal ‚àí Kinitial; kinetic energy is K = (1/2)mv^2, with m in kilograms and v in meters per second. ‚ÄúWork‚Äù for a constant force along the direction of motion is W = Fd, where F is force in newtons and d is distance in meters (if the force is at an angle, it‚Äôs W = Fd cosŒ∏, but we‚Äôll keep it straight-line here). Quick example: a 2.0 kg cart starts from rest and a constant 10 N horizontal push acts over 3.0 m on a frictionless floor; the net work is Wnet = Fd = (10 N)(3.0 m) = 30 J, so ŒîK = 30 J, and since it started from rest Kinitial = 0, we have Kfinal = 30 J = (1/2)mv^2 = (1/2)(2.0)v^2 = 1.0¬∑v^2, so v^2 = 30 and v = ‚àö30 ‚âà 5.48 m/s; a good check is that positive work increased the speed, which matches the result."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 06:12 - Category: transistors
    ("In computer architecture, what does a transistor actually do inside a CPU? I keep hearing ‚Äòswitch‚Äô but I want the real idea.", "Inside a CPU, a transistor is a tiny electrically controlled valve for current: a small voltage on its ‚Äúgate‚Äù (in modern CPUs this is usually a MOSFET) changes whether a conductive channel forms between two other terminals, so the transistor either allows current to flow easily (representing a logic 1 in many contexts) or blocks it (logic 0), but the ‚Äúreal idea‚Äù is that billions of these controlled valves are wired together to build logic gates and memory. When you connect transistors in specific patterns, they implement Boolean operations like NOT, AND, and OR; for example, a CMOS inverter uses two transistors so that when the input is low one transistor pulls the output up to the supply voltage, and when the input is high the other transistor pulls the output down to ground, giving a clean digital output while ideally drawing very little steady power except during switching. The same switching behavior also creates storage: cross-coupled inverters form a latch that can remember a bit, and in SRAM cells (used for CPU caches) a handful of transistors hold a 0 or 1 as long as power is applied, while other transistors act as access ‚Äúgates‚Äù to read or write that bit. So ‚Äúswitch‚Äù is accurate, but more precisely a transistor is a controllable current path that lets the CPU build reliable, noise-tolerant digital signals, amplify and restore those signals as they travel through many stages, and combine them into the arithmetic, control, and memory circuits that execute instructions."),

