    ("Can you walk me through proving a limit with epsilon-delta for f(x)=3x at x=2? I‚Äôm stuck on how to choose delta.", "To prove using the epsilon‚Äìdelta definition that lim(x‚Üí2) 3x = 6, you must show: for every Œµ > 0, there exists a Œ¥ > 0 such that if 0 < |x ‚àí 2| < Œ¥, then |3x ‚àí 6| < Œµ. Start by rewriting the difference in a way that involves |x ‚àí 2|: |3x ‚àí 6| = |3(x ‚àí 2)| = 3|x ‚àí 2|. Now you can see exactly how close x needs to be to 2 to make 3x close to 6: you want 3|x ‚àí 2| < Œµ, and dividing both sides by 3 gives |x ‚àí 2| < Œµ/3. That tells you how to choose Œ¥: let Œ¥ = Œµ/3. Then, whenever 0 < |x ‚àí 2| < Œ¥, you have |3x ‚àí 6| = 3|x ‚àí 2| < 3Œ¥ = 3(Œµ/3) = Œµ, which is exactly what the definition requires, so the limit is proven and the key idea is that you pick Œ¥ by solving the inequality you need, in this case Œ¥ = Œµ/3."),

