    ("I‚Äôm doing a lab in science class‚Äîhow do I write a good hypothesis and identify the independent/dependent variables for a paper towel absorbency experiment?", "For a paper towel absorbency lab, start by deciding exactly what question you‚Äôre testing, because your hypothesis and variables come directly from that question; a strong, ‚Äúgood‚Äù hypothesis is a specific, testable prediction that links what you change to what you measure and includes a brief scientific reason, often phrased as ‚ÄúIf‚Ä¶, then‚Ä¶, because‚Ä¶‚Äù. In an absorbency experiment, the independent variable is the factor you purposely change between trials, most commonly the brand or type of paper towel (Brand A vs Brand B vs Brand C), and the dependent variable is the outcome you measure to represent ‚Äúabsorbency,‚Äù such as how many milliliters of water a single sheet can absorb before it drips, or how much mass of water it absorbs calculated by weighing the towel dry and then wet (wet mass minus dry mass, in grams). Everything else should be controlled so the test is fair, meaning you keep it the same for every trial: the sheet size (for example, one full sheet or the same cut dimensions), number of sheets (one), water temperature, the amount of time you allow it to absorb, the way you add water (pouring rate or using a pipette), the container, and how you handle dripping (for example, letting it drip for the same number of seconds before weighing). A clear example hypothesis would be: ‚ÄúIf I test different brands of paper towels, then Brand X will absorb the greatest amount of water (measured in mL absorbed or grams gained) before dripping, because thicker towels with more fiber and air spaces can hold more water,‚Äù and you can double-check your variables by asking, ‚ÄúWhat am I changing on purpose?‚Äù (brand/type = independent) and ‚ÄúWhat number am I recording to compare absorbency?‚Äù (mL absorbed or grams of water absorbed = dependent)."),

