    ("Can you give me 10 brainstorming techniques for a school invention project? I keep getting stuck with boring ideas.", "Try ‚ÄúSCAMPER,‚Äù where you take any ordinary object and ask how you could Substitute a part, Combine it with something else, Adapt it for a new use, Modify or magnify it, Put it to another use, Eliminate something, or Reverse/rearrange it; use ‚ÄúMind mapping‚Äù by writing your project theme in the center and branching into users, places, problems, materials, and wild variations until a surprising connection appears; do ‚ÄúProblem safari‚Äù by walking around school for 10 minutes and writing down every tiny annoyance you notice (heavy doors, lost pencils, messy lockers, loud chairs) because great inventions often start as small fixes; use the ‚Äú5 Whys‚Äù by picking one annoyance and asking ‚ÄúWhy?‚Äù five times to uncover the real root cause you can design for; try ‚ÄúCrazy 8s‚Äù by folding paper into eight boxes and sketching eight different solutions in eight minutes so you can‚Äôt overthink; do ‚ÄúWorst idea first‚Äù by inventing the most terrible, inconvenient solution you can, then flipping each bad feature into a good one (too heavy becomes lightweight, too slow becomes instant, too expensive becomes made from recycled materials); use ‚ÄúAnalogies and biomimicry‚Äù by asking ‚ÄúHow would nature solve this?‚Äù or ‚ÄúHow would a restaurant/airport/hospital handle this?‚Äù and borrowing their strategies; try ‚ÄúConstraint brainstorming‚Äù by forcing limits like ‚Äúmust cost under $5,‚Äù ‚Äúmust fit in a backpack,‚Äù or ‚Äúmust use only cardboard and tape,‚Äù because constraints push you toward creative designs; do ‚ÄúRole-storming‚Äù by pretending you are different people (a kindergartener, a custodian, a teacher, a student with one hand injured) and inventing from their needs; and finish with ‚ÄúMash-up‚Äù by randomly combining two unrelated things (locker + timer, backpack + air pump, pencil + magnet) and asking what new invention could exist at that intersection‚Äîthen pick your top three ideas and quickly test them by asking, ‚ÄúWho would use this, what problem does it solve, and how could I build a simple prototype in one afternoon?‚Äù"),

