    ("Why do magnets stick to some things but not others? Like why does it work on my fridge but not a soda can?", "Magnets stick strongly only to certain materials called ferromagnets, mainly iron, steel (which is mostly iron), nickel, and cobalt, because inside those materials there are tiny magnetic regions (often called domains) that can line up with the magnet‚Äôs field and create a strong attraction; in most other materials the magnetic effects are too weak or cancel out, so you don‚Äôt feel a noticeable pull. Your fridge door is made of steel, so a magnet easily grabs it, but most soda cans are aluminum, and aluminum is not ferromagnetic, so a normal fridge magnet won‚Äôt stick (even though aluminum can interact very weakly with strong magnets in special situations). A quick way to predict what will happen is to ask ‚ÄúIs it iron or steel?‚Äù: paper, plastic, glass, wood, and most coins won‚Äôt stick, while things like a paperclip, nail, or many kitchen knives (if they‚Äôre steel) usually will."),

