    ("In Algebra 2, how do you factor x^2 5x + 6 and how do I check if I did it right?", "To factor x^2 ‚àí 5x + 6, look for two numbers that multiply to +6 and add to ‚àí5; those numbers are ‚àí2 and ‚àí3, so you split the middle term and factor: x^2 ‚àí 5x + 6 = x^2 ‚àí 2x ‚àí 3x + 6 = x(x ‚àí 2) ‚àí 3(x ‚àí 2) = (x ‚àí 2)(x ‚àí 3). To check, multiply the factors back out using FOIL: (x ‚àí 2)(x ‚àí 3) = x^2 ‚àí 3x ‚àí 2x + 6 = x^2 ‚àí 5x + 6, which matches the original polynomial, so the factoring is correct. Another quick check is to plug in x = 2 and x = 3: the original expression becomes 0 at both values, and the factored form also becomes 0 because one factor turns into zero, confirming the same roots."),

