    ("In trig, what‚Äôs the difference between sine and cosine, and why do they repeat in a cycle?", "Sine and cosine are two closely related trig functions that describe how a point on a circle (or a right triangle) is positioned: on the unit circle (a circle of radius 1 centered at the origin), cosine of an angle is the x-coordinate of the point where the angle‚Äôs terminal side hits the circle, and sine of the same angle is the y-coordinate; in a right triangle with angle Œ∏, cos(Œ∏) equals adjacent side over hypotenuse and sin(Œ∏) equals opposite side over hypotenuse, so cosine measures the ‚Äúhorizontal‚Äù part and sine measures the ‚Äúvertical‚Äù part of the same direction. They repeat in a cycle because rotating by a full turn brings you back to the exact same direction and the same point on the circle, so the x- and y-coordinates repeat: sin(Œ∏ + 2œÄ) = sin(Œ∏) and cos(Œ∏ + 2œÄ) = cos(Œ∏) (in degrees, 360¬∞ instead of 2œÄ radians). A helpful way to remember their relationship is that they are the same wave shifted in time: cos(Œ∏) = sin(Œ∏ + œÄ/2), which matches the idea that a quarter-turn (90¬∞) swaps which coordinate is ‚Äúleading‚Äù as you move around the circle."),

