    ("I‚Äôm confused about complex numbers. What does it mean to multiply by i and why is i^2 = -1 not just fake math?", "Multiplying by i is easiest to understand using the complex plane: think of an ordinary real number as a point on a horizontal number line, and think of a complex number a + bi as a point (a, b) in a 2D plane where the horizontal axis is ‚Äúreal‚Äù and the vertical axis is ‚Äúimaginary.‚Äù In that picture, multiplying a complex number by i doesn‚Äôt ‚Äúmake it fake,‚Äù it performs a specific geometric action: it rotates the point 90 degrees counterclockwise around the origin without changing its distance from the origin. You can see this from the rule i(a + bi) = ia + i¬∑bi = ai + b i^2 = ai ‚àí b, which is (a, b) turning into (‚àíb, a), exactly a 90-degree rotation. Then i^2 = ‚àí1 is not a random trick; it‚Äôs what must happen if you rotate by 90 degrees twice: two 90-degree rotations make a 180-degree rotation, and a 180-degree rotation sends every point to its opposite, which on the real line means x becomes ‚àíx, so the number that represents ‚Äúrotate by 90 degrees‚Äù must satisfy doing it twice equals multiplying by ‚àí1, hence i^2 = ‚àí1. Complex numbers are as consistent as real numbers because they follow clear rules (distributive, associative, etc.) and they model real phenomena: for example, engineers use i to represent phase shifts in AC circuits and waves, where multiplying by i corresponds to shifting a sine wave into a cosine wave (a quarter-cycle shift), which is the same ‚Äú90-degree rotation‚Äù idea in a different form. So i isn‚Äôt ‚Äúfake math‚Äù; it‚Äôs an extension of the number system that keeps all the usual algebra rules and adds a new operation that corresponds to rotation, letting us solve equations like x^2 + 1 = 0 and describe rotations and oscillations cleanly and reliably."),

