    ("I have to do a t-test vs chi-square for a stats project and I‚Äôm lost. How do I know which statistical test to use for different situations?", "To choose the right test, first identify what kind of variables you have and what question you‚Äôre asking: a t-test is for comparing the average (mean) of a numeric, continuous outcome between two groups, while a chi-square test is for comparing counts or proportions across categories. Use a t-test when your outcome is something measured on a number scale (like height, test score, blood pressure, time) and your predictor is a two-group category (like treatment vs control, male vs female); examples include ‚ÄúIs the mean exam score different between students who studied with flashcards vs not?‚Äù or ‚ÄúIs average blood pressure different between a medication group and a placebo group?‚Äù There are common t-test variants: an independent-samples t-test for two separate groups, a paired t-test for before/after measurements on the same people (or matched pairs), and Welch‚Äôs t-test (often the safest default for independent groups) when the two groups may have different variances; key assumptions are that observations are independent, the outcome is roughly normal within each group (or sample sizes are large enough for the mean to be approximately normal), and there aren‚Äôt extreme outliers driving the mean. Use a chi-square test when both variables are categorical and you‚Äôre analyzing a contingency table of frequencies, such as ‚ÄúIs smoking status (yes/no) associated with disease status (yes/no)?‚Äù or ‚ÄúDo the proportions of political party preference differ across age categories?‚Äù The most common is the chi-square test of independence (association between two categorical variables), and another is the chi-square goodness-of-fit test (whether one categorical variable‚Äôs observed counts match a claimed distribution); assumptions include independent observations and expected cell counts that aren‚Äôt too small (a common rule of thumb is most expected counts at least 5‚Äîif expected counts are small, especially in a 2x2 table, Fisher‚Äôs exact test is often better). A quick decision rule is: if you‚Äôre comparing means of a numeric variable between two groups, think t-test; if you‚Äôre comparing proportions or testing association using counts in categories, think chi-square; if you have more than two groups and a numeric outcome you‚Äôd typically use ANOVA instead of a t-test, and if you want to model a binary outcome you‚Äôd often use logistic regression, but for many class projects the t-test vs chi-square split is exactly ‚Äúmeans‚Äù versus ‚Äúcounts/proportions.‚Äù"),

