    ("What‚Äôs the difference between SN1 and SN2 reactions? My teacher went so fast and now the practice problems make no sense.", "SN1 and SN2 are two different ways a nucleophile can replace a leaving group (a substitution reaction), and the key difference is the number of steps and what controls the speed. SN2 is ‚Äúsubstitution nucleophilic bimolecular‚Äù: it happens in one single step where the nucleophile attacks the carbon at the same time the leaving group leaves, so the rate depends on both the substrate and the nucleophile (rate = k[substrate][nucleophile]); because the nucleophile must attack from the backside, SN2 causes inversion of configuration at a chiral center (like an umbrella flipping), it works best on less crowded carbons (methyl and primary are fastest, secondary can work, tertiary is essentially blocked), it is helped by strong nucleophiles, and it is favored by polar aprotic solvents like acetone, DMSO, DMF, or acetonitrile because they don‚Äôt ‚Äúcage‚Äù the nucleophile. SN1 is ‚Äúsubstitution nucleophilic unimolecular‚Äù: it happens in two main steps where the leaving group leaves first to form a carbocation (slow, rate-determining step), then the nucleophile attacks (fast), so the rate depends only on the substrate (rate = k[substrate]); because a carbocation is flat, the nucleophile can attack from either side, giving racemization (often a mix of retention and inversion) if the center is chiral, and rearrangements (hydride or methyl shifts) can happen because carbocations can rearrange to become more stable; SN1 is favored by more stable carbocations (tertiary best, secondary sometimes, primary and methyl usually don‚Äôt), by good leaving groups, by weaker/neutral nucleophiles (water, alcohols) since nucleophile strength doesn‚Äôt control the rate, and by polar protic solvents like water or alcohols that stabilize ions. A quick way to decide in practice problems is: if the carbon is tertiary and the solvent is polar protic, think SN1 (watch for rearrangements and racemization); if the carbon is methyl or primary and you have a strong nucleophile in a polar aprotic solvent, think SN2 (one-step backside attack with inversion); secondary substrates are the ‚Äúmixed‚Äù case where conditions matter, with strong nucleophile/polar aprotic pushing SN2 and weak nucleophile/polar protic pushing SN1."),

