    ("Bio question: can you walk me through DNA replication (like leading/lagging strand and what enzymes do what) without making it super confusing?", "DNA replication copies DNA before a cell divides, and the big ‚Äútrick‚Äù is that the two DNA strands run in opposite directions while DNA polymerase can only build new DNA in one direction: it can only add nucleotides to a free 3‚Ä≤ end, so it always synthesizes the new strand 5‚Ä≤‚Üí3‚Ä≤. It starts at an origin of replication where helicase unwinds the double helix by breaking the hydrogen bonds between base pairs, creating a replication fork; single-strand binding proteins hold the separated strands apart so they don‚Äôt re-zip, and topoisomerase (like DNA gyrase in bacteria) relieves the twisting strain ahead of the fork so the DNA doesn‚Äôt get overly wound up. Primase then lays down short RNA primers because DNA polymerase can‚Äôt start from scratch, and the main DNA polymerase extends from those primers by adding complementary bases (A with T, C with G). On the leading strand, the template is oriented so polymerase can follow the fork and synthesize continuously toward the fork from a single primer; on the lagging strand, the template faces the ‚Äúwrong way‚Äù for continuous copying, so primase has to keep making new primers as the fork opens and polymerase makes short stretches of DNA away from the fork called Okazaki fragments. After that, the RNA primers are removed and replaced with DNA (in bacteria this is done by DNA polymerase I; in eukaryotes enzymes like RNase H and FEN1 remove the RNA and a polymerase fills in the DNA), and DNA ligase seals the remaining ‚Äúnicks‚Äù in the sugar-phosphate backbone to join the fragments into one continuous strand. Many polymerases also proofread as they go (using 3‚Ä≤‚Üí5‚Ä≤ exonuclease activity) to fix most mistakes immediately, which is a big reason replication is so accurate."),

