    ("I don‚Äôt get cell parts. What do mitochondria and the nucleus do, and how are plant cells different from animal cells?", "Mitochondria are the cell‚Äôs energy makers: they take energy stored in food (like sugar) and, using oxygen, turn it into ATP, a usable ‚Äúenergy currency‚Äù the cell spends to do work such as moving materials, building molecules, and dividing. The nucleus is like the cell‚Äôs main office and library: it stores DNA, the instructions for how to build and run the cell, and it controls which instructions get used by sending out messages (RNA) that tell the rest of the cell which proteins to make; inside the nucleus, the nucleolus helps make ribosomes, the tiny machines that build proteins. Plant and animal cells share many parts (like a cell membrane, cytoplasm, mitochondria, and a nucleus), but plant cells have three big extras: a rigid cell wall made mostly of cellulose that acts like a sturdy box for support and protection, chloroplasts that capture sunlight to make sugar by photosynthesis, and a large central vacuole that stores water and helps keep the cell firm; animal cells do not have a cell wall or chloroplasts, usually have smaller vacuoles, and their cells are often more flexible in shape. A quick way to remember it is: nucleus equals instructions and control, mitochondria equals energy release from food, and plants have wall, chloroplasts, and a big vacuole."),

