    ("College CS: can you explain how transistors become logic gates and then a CPU? I‚Äôm trying to connect the hardware stuff to what code is doing.", "A transistor is basically an electrically controlled switch: in a common CMOS design you use two kinds (nMOS and pMOS) so that a small voltage on a ‚Äúgate‚Äù terminal can either connect or disconnect a path for current, letting a circuit represent bits as two voltage ranges (logic 0 near 0V and logic 1 near the supply voltage). By wiring transistors in specific patterns you get logic gates that implement Boolean functions: for example, a CMOS inverter (NOT) uses one pMOS to pull the output up to 1 when the input is 0, and one nMOS to pull the output down to 0 when the input is 1; combining these pull-up and pull-down networks gives NAND and NOR, and since NAND or NOR alone is functionally complete you can build any digital logic from them, including AND/OR/XOR and multiplexers. Gates become useful computation when you add memory: cross-coupled inverters form a stable latch, latches plus a clock form flip-flops, and many flip-flops together make registers that hold the CPU‚Äôs state (like the program counter and general-purpose registers). From there, a CPU is mainly two big pieces: the datapath, which moves and transforms bits (adders built from XOR/AND/OR, shifters, comparators, and an ALU that selects among these results with multiplexers), and the control unit, which decides what the datapath should do each clock cycle by asserting control signals (which register to read/write, which ALU operation to choose, whether to load the program counter, whether to access memory). When your code runs, it has been compiled into machine instructions; each instruction is just a pattern of bits stored in memory, and the CPU repeatedly performs the fetch‚Äìdecode‚Äìexecute loop: fetch reads the instruction at the address in the program counter, decode interprets fields like opcode and register numbers, execute uses the ALU and registers to do the operation, memory stages load/store data if needed, and writeback saves results into a register, then the program counter advances or jumps/branches. The key connection to code is that high-level statements become sequences of these simple bit operations and data moves, and the ‚Äúmagic‚Äù is that billions of transistors reliably implement switches, those switches form gates, gates form arithmetic and storage, and coordinated by a clock and control logic they carry out one tiny instruction step at a time extremely fast."),

