    ("US Gov: what‚Äôs the difference between the House and the Senate (like actual powers), and why do we have two chambers anyway?", "The House of Representatives and the Senate are the two chambers of Congress, and they share the main job of making federal laws, but the Constitution gives each some different powers and they represent people in different ways. The House is designed to be closer to the public: its members serve 2-year terms, seats are divided among the states by population, and it has the ‚Äúpower of the purse,‚Äù meaning all bills to raise revenue (tax bills) must start in the House; the House also has the sole power to impeach federal officials, which is like bringing formal charges. The Senate is designed to be more stable and to represent states equally: each state gets 2 senators regardless of population, senators serve 6-year terms with staggered elections, and the Senate has the sole power to hold impeachment trials and vote to convict and remove an official; the Senate also must approve major presidential actions, including confirming many top officials and all federal judges (including Supreme Court justices) and ratifying treaties by a two-thirds vote. We have two chambers because the framers wanted a balance between big states and small states (the ‚ÄúGreat Compromise‚Äù created a population-based House and an equal-state Senate), and because requiring both chambers to agree on the same bill makes lawmaking slower and more deliberative, acting as a check against sudden swings in public opinion and helping prevent any one group from gaining too much power too quickly."),

