    ("What did the Industrial Revolution change in the US day-to-day life? I need like 3 specific examples for an assignment.", "In the United States, the Industrial Revolution changed day-to-day life by shifting many people from farm and home-based work to wage work on a strict clock; for example, instead of doing tasks when daylight and seasons allowed, factory workers had set start times, long shifts, and rules enforced by bells and supervisors, so daily routines revolved around punctuality and timekeeping. It also changed what and how families bought and used goods; for example, mass production made items like ready-made clothing, canned foods, and factory-made tools cheaper and more widely available, so people increasingly shopped for standardized products in stores rather than making or repairing as much at home. A third everyday change was in household labor and living conditions as new technologies spread; for example, gas lighting and later electric lighting extended productive and leisure hours after dark, and indoor plumbing and sewer systems in many cities gradually reduced the need to haul water and dispose of waste by hand, changing basic daily chores and improving sanitation (though often unevenly by neighborhood and income)."),

