    ("Can you help me pick a baseline model for a text classification project? I have like 20k labeled reviews and need something simple to beat.", "With 20k labeled reviews, a strong, simple baseline to beat is a linear classifier on bag-of-words features, because it‚Äôs fast, hard to mess up, and surprisingly competitive for text. A very standard choice is TF-IDF vectorization (word unigrams, optionally add bigrams) feeding into a regularized linear model such as logistic regression or a linear SVM; both are ‚Äúlinear‚Äù in the sparse text feature space, train quickly, and usually outperform naive baselines by a lot, while still being easy to interpret by inspecting the highest-weighted words for each class. As even simpler reference points, you should also record a majority-class baseline (always predict the most common label) and a multinomial Naive Bayes model on count or TF-IDF features, since Naive Bayes is extremely fast and often decent on reviews; your ‚Äúreal‚Äù baseline to beat can be TF-IDF plus logistic regression with L2 regularization, tuned only lightly (for example, try a couple of C values and whether to include bigrams). To make the baseline meaningful, use a clean train/validation/test split (or cross-validation), keep preprocessing minimal and consistent (lowercasing, basic tokenization; avoid heavy feature engineering at first), and choose metrics that match the task (accuracy can be fine for balanced classes, but for imbalance prefer F1, precision/recall, and ROC-AUC for binary). If you want one baseline that is both simple and hard to beat, start with TF-IDF (1‚Äì2 grams) plus logistic regression, compare against Naive Bayes and majority-class, and only then move to more complex models like fine-tuned transformers once you know what ‚Äúgood‚Äù looks like on your dataset."),

