    ("Can you explain magnets like I‚Äôm in 7th grade? Like why do some things stick and other stuff doesn‚Äôt?", "Magnets create an invisible magnetic field that can push or pull on certain materials, and the reason only some things ‚Äústick‚Äù is that the material has to be magnetic in the right way. In most metals, the tiny magnetic effects of electrons cancel out, so the object doesn‚Äôt react much, but in ferromagnetic materials like iron, most steel, nickel, and cobalt, lots of atoms can line up their tiny magnetic directions into groups called domains; when a magnet is nearby, it makes many domains line up, turning the object into a temporary magnet so it gets pulled in and can stick. Things like aluminum, copper, gold, wood, plastic, glass, and paper don‚Äôt have domains that line up strongly, so they aren‚Äôt pulled much and won‚Äôt stick (even though some, like aluminum, can have very weak magnetic effects you usually can‚Äôt notice). A simple way to remember it is: magnets strongly attract iron and most steels because their domains can line up, but most everyday materials don‚Äôt have that kind of internal structure, so the magnetic field passes through without grabbing them."),

