    ("What was the Industrial Revolution and how did it change what jobs people had in the US?", "The Industrial Revolution was the long period in the late 1700s through the 1800s (and into the early 1900s in the United States) when new machines, new power sources like water and steam, and later electricity, plus better transportation such as canals and railroads, made it possible to produce goods much faster and cheaper in factories than by hand in small shops or at home. In the U.S., this changed jobs by shifting many people away from farming and skilled handcraft work toward wage-paying work for an employer: instead of a family making cloth, tools, or shoes at home or in a small workshop, more workers became factory operatives in textile mills and other manufacturing, miners digging coal and iron, and railroad and shipping workers moving raw materials and finished products. It also created and expanded new kinds of jobs needed by an industrial economy, including machinists and mechanics to build and repair equipment, clerks and accountants to manage large businesses, and many city service jobs such as construction, retail, and food processing, while at the same time some traditional artisan jobs declined or changed because machines could do parts of the work faster and with less training. Overall, the Industrial Revolution helped turn the United States from a mostly rural, farm-based economy into one where many more people earned regular wages in factories, transportation, and growing urban businesses."),

