    ("Can you explain limits and continuity like I‚Äôm trying to not fail pre-calc? Like what does it mean when a limit doesn‚Äôt exist?", "A limit is what a function is trying to approach as x gets close to some number, even if you never plug that exact number in; think ‚Äúnearby behavior,‚Äù not ‚Äúat the point.‚Äù For example, if f(x) = (x^2 ‚àí 1)/(x ‚àí 1), you can‚Äôt plug in x = 1 because you‚Äôd get 0/0, but if you simplify for x ‚â† 1 you get f(x) = x + 1, so as x gets close to 1 the outputs get close to 2, and we write lim(x‚Üí1) f(x) = 2; the limit exists even though f(1) is undefined, and you could ‚Äúfix‚Äù it by defining f(1) = 2. Continuity is basically ‚Äúno sudden break at that x-value,‚Äù and the official pre-calc checklist at x = a is: f(a) is defined, lim(x‚Üía) f(x) exists, and the limit equals the actual value f(a); if all three happen, the function is continuous at a. A limit does not exist when the function fails to settle on one single number as you approach from both sides: one common reason is a jump, like a piecewise function where approaching a from the left heads to 3 but from the right heads to 5, so there isn‚Äôt one agreed-upon value; another reason is an infinite limit, like 1/(x ‚àí 2) blowing up toward +‚àû from one side and ‚àí‚àû from the other; and a third reason is oscillation, like sin(1/x) near 0 bouncing forever between ‚àí1 and 1 without narrowing down. The key idea to not fail pre-calc is: to decide if lim(x‚Üía) f(x) exists, check whether the left-hand limit and right-hand limit both exist and are equal; if they match, the limit exists (even if f(a) is missing or different), and if they don‚Äôt match or the function shoots off or oscillates, the limit doesn‚Äôt exist."),

