    ("Can you show me how to do modular arithmetic? Like what is 17^3 mod 5 without a calculator (and why does it work)?", "Modular arithmetic means you only care about the remainder after division by a number (the modulus), so ‚Äúmod 5‚Äù means two numbers are considered the same if they differ by a multiple of 5; for example 17 ‚â° 2 (mod 5) because 17 ‚àí 2 = 15 is divisible by 5, and this replacement is valid inside addition and multiplication because if a ‚â° b (mod 5) then a = b + 5k for some integer k, so multiplying gives a¬∑c = (b + 5k)c = bc + 5(kc), which still differs from bc by a multiple of 5, meaning a¬∑c ‚â° b¬∑c (mod 5), and similarly for powers. To compute 17^3 mod 5 without a calculator, first reduce 17: since 17 ‚â° 2 (mod 5), we have 17^3 ‚â° 2^3 (mod 5); then 2^3 = 8, and 8 divided by 5 leaves remainder 3, so 8 ‚â° 3 (mod 5). Therefore 17^3 mod 5 = 3, and you can sanity-check it by noting 17^3 = 4913 and 4913 = 5¬∑982 + 3, so the remainder really is 3."),

