    ("Stats question: I have a dataset of 20 quiz scores. How do I compute mean, median, standard deviation, and IQR, and what does each one tell me?", "To compute these descriptive statistics for your 20 quiz scores, first sort all 20 scores from smallest to largest and keep that ordered list, because median and IQR depend on order. The mean is the average: add all 20 scores and divide by 20; it tells you the overall ‚Äúcenter of gravity‚Äù of the scores but can be pulled up or down by unusually high or low scores. The median is the middle value of the sorted list; with 20 scores (an even number), it is the average of the 10th and 11th scores in the sorted list, and it tells you the typical score in a way that is resistant to outliers (half the scores are at or below the median and half are at or above it). The (sample) standard deviation measures spread around the mean: compute each deviation (score ‚àí mean), square those deviations, add them up, divide by n ‚àí 1 = 19, and take the square root; it tells you a typical distance of scores from the mean (small SD means scores are tightly clustered, large SD means scores vary widely), and if the distribution is roughly bell-shaped then about 68% of scores fall within about 1 SD of the mean and about 95% within about 2 SDs. The interquartile range (IQR) measures the spread of the middle 50% of scores and is also resistant to outliers: after sorting, find Q1 (the first quartile) as the median of the lower half (the first 10 scores) and Q3 (the third quartile) as the median of the upper half (the last 10 scores); because each half has 10 values, Q1 is the average of the 5th and 6th scores in the lower half and Q3 is the average of the 5th and 6th scores in the upper half, then compute IQR = Q3 ‚àí Q1. Interpreting IQR is straightforward: it tells you how wide the middle half of the class‚Äôs scores is (for example, an IQR of 12 points means the central 50% of students are spread across a 12-point range), and it‚Äôs especially useful when the data are skewed or have outliers, where mean and standard deviation can be misleading."),

