    ("Chemistry: can you balance these equations and explain the steps? 1) C3H8 + O2 -> CO2 + H2O 2) Fe + O2 -> Fe2O3", "A good strategy for balancing is to change only coefficients (the big numbers in front), not subscripts, and to balance elements that appear in only one compound on each side first, leaving oxygen for last when it appears in multiple places. For 1) C3H8 + O2 -> CO2 + H2O, balance carbon: there are 3 C in C3H8, so make 3CO2; then balance hydrogen: there are 8 H in C3H8, so make 4H2O (because 4 √ó 2 = 8); now count oxygen on the products: 3CO2 has 6 O and 4H2O has 4 O, total 10 O, so you need 5O2 on the reactant side (because 5 √ó 2 = 10). The balanced equation is C3H8 + 5O2 -> 3CO2 + 4H2O, and checking confirms C 3=3, H 8=8, O 10=10. For 2) Fe + O2 -> Fe2O3, it helps to balance oxygen by making it an even number on the product side because O2 comes in pairs: Fe2O3 has 3 O, so put a 2 in front of Fe2O3 to make 6 O on the product side; that means you need 3O2 on the reactant side to supply 6 O. Now balance iron: 2Fe2O3 contains 4 Fe atoms, so put a 4 in front of Fe on the reactant side. The balanced equation is 4Fe + 3O2 -> 2Fe2O3, and checking confirms Fe 4=4 and O 6=6."),

