    ("Calc: I don‚Äôt get limits/continuity. How can a function be ‚Äòcontinuous‚Äô if it has a hole? Can you explain with an example like (x^2-1)/(x-1)?", "A function is continuous at a point a if three things all happen: f(a) is defined, the limit of f(x) as x approaches a exists, and that limit equals f(a); a ‚Äúhole‚Äù means the function is not defined at that x-value, so it is not continuous there even if the graph looks like it could be filled in. For your example f(x) = (x^2 ‚àí 1)/(x ‚àí 1), you can factor x^2 ‚àí 1 as (x ‚àí 1)(x + 1), so for every x not equal to 1 the function simplifies to f(x) = x + 1, which is a straight line; however at x = 1 the original formula gives 0/0, which is undefined, so there is a hole at x = 1 and the function is not continuous at 1. The limit still exists because as x gets close to 1, x + 1 gets close to 2, so lim(x‚Üí1) (x^2 ‚àí 1)/(x ‚àí 1) = 2; if you define a new function g that equals (x^2 ‚àí 1)/(x ‚àí 1) for x ‚â† 1 and also sets g(1) = 2, then g has no hole and is continuous at 1, which is why people say the original function has a ‚Äúremovable discontinuity‚Äù and can be made continuous by filling the hole with the limit value."),

