    ("Is the Cold War basically a ‚Äòwar‚Äô or not? My teacher says it wasn‚Äôt fighting like WW2 so I‚Äôm confused‚Äîwhat made it a war?", "The Cold War is called a ‚Äúwar‚Äù even though the United States and the Soviet Union almost never fought each other directly with their own armies, because it was a long, intense struggle for power and influence (roughly 1947 to 1991) where each side treated the other as a major enemy and prepared for the possibility of a real shooting war, especially a nuclear one. Instead of big head-to-head battles like World War II, the conflict was fought through constant military buildup and nuclear deterrence (both sides stockpiled weapons to scare the other from attacking), rival alliances (NATO vs. the Warsaw Pact), espionage and propaganda, economic pressure and competition, and ‚Äúproxy wars‚Äù where they supported opposite sides in other countries, such as Korea and Vietnam, plus crises that brought them close to direct conflict like the Berlin Blockade and the Cuban Missile Crisis. So it wasn‚Äôt a ‚Äúhot‚Äù war with continuous direct battles, but it was still a war in the sense of a sustained global confrontation where each side tried to defeat the other‚Äôs system and expand its influence, and millions of people were affected by the fear, spending, and indirect fighting it caused."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 06:36 - Category: magnets_basics
    ("Why do magnets stick to the fridge but not to a wooden table? I‚Äôm doing a science journal entry.", "Magnets stick to many fridge doors because the door is made of steel (or has a thin steel sheet under the paint), and steel is a ferromagnetic material, meaning its tiny magnetic regions inside (often called domains) can line up with the magnet‚Äôs field and get strongly attracted, so the magnet ‚Äúgrabs‚Äù onto the metal and stays there. A wooden table doesn‚Äôt stick because wood is not ferromagnetic; it‚Äôs mostly made of materials that are only very weakly affected by magnets, so there‚Äôs no strong attraction to hold the magnet up against gravity. A good note for your journal is that magnets don‚Äôt stick to all metals either: they usually stick to iron and most steels, and also to nickel and cobalt, but they won‚Äôt stick to metals like aluminum, copper, gold, or most stainless steel because those aren‚Äôt strongly magnetic. If you want to test this, try your magnet on different objects (a paperclip, an aluminum can, a coin, a spoon) and record which ones attract and which don‚Äôt, then connect your results to what the objects are made of."),

