    ("College calc: can you prove lim(x->0) sin(x)/x = 1 without just saying ‚Äòit‚Äôs a known limit‚Äô? My professor wants a real proof.", "Yes; a standard ‚Äúfirst principles‚Äù proof uses geometry and the squeeze theorem. Work in radians and take 0 < x < œÄ/2. On the unit circle, let A = (1,0), let B be the point reached by rotating counterclockwise by angle x, and let C be the point where the ray OB meets the vertical line x = 1 (so triangle OAC is right with angle x at O). Then the area of triangle OAB is (1/2)sin x (since OA = OB = 1 and the included angle is x), the area of sector AOB is x/2 (because a sector of angle x in a unit circle has area (1/2)¬∑1^2¬∑x), and the area of triangle OAC is (1/2)tan x (since base OA = 1 and height AC = tan x). Geometrically, triangle OAB lies inside the sector, which lies inside triangle OAC, so (1/2)sin x ‚â§ x/2 ‚â§ (1/2)tan x, hence sin x ‚â§ x ‚â§ tan x. Divide by sin x > 0 to get 1 ‚â§ x/sin x ‚â§ 1/ cos x, and invert (which reverses nothing here because all quantities are positive) to obtain cos x ‚â§ sin x / x ‚â§ 1 for 0 < x < œÄ/2. Now let x ‚Üí 0+: cos x ‚Üí 1, so by squeezing, sin x / x ‚Üí 1 as x ‚Üí 0+. For x < 0, use oddness: sin x / x = sin(‚àíx)/(‚àíx), so the left-hand limit equals the right-hand limit, giving lim(x‚Üí0) sin x / x = 1. The key point is that the inequalities come from comparing areas on the unit circle, and the step ‚Äúsector area = x/2‚Äù is exactly why angles must be measured in radians; in degrees the constant would not come out to 1."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 06:36 - Category: trigonometric_functions
    ("For trigonometry, when do I use sine vs cosine in right triangle word problems? I always pick the wrong one.", "In right-triangle word problems, you choose sine or cosine based on which sides you‚Äôre relating to the given angle: first label the angle you‚Äôre using (usually an acute angle), then name the sides relative to that angle‚Äîopposite is across from the angle, adjacent is the leg next to the angle (not the hypotenuse), and the hypotenuse is always the longest side across from the right angle; then use sine when your ratio involves opposite and hypotenuse (sin Œ∏ = opposite/hypotenuse) and use cosine when your ratio involves adjacent and hypotenuse (cos Œ∏ = adjacent/hypotenuse). A quick memory trick is SOH-CAH: Sine = Opposite over Hypotenuse, Cosine = Adjacent over Hypotenuse; for example, if you know an angle of elevation Œ∏ and the line of sight is the hypotenuse, then height (opposite) = (hypotenuse)¬∑sin Œ∏, but horizontal distance (adjacent) = (hypotenuse)¬∑cos Œ∏, and if you know the horizontal distance and want the height, you‚Äôd use tan Œ∏ = opposite/adjacent instead. To avoid picking the wrong one, always write the ratio with words first (opposite/hypotenuse or adjacent/hypotenuse), then match it to sin or cos, and do a quick reasonableness check: for a small angle, sin should be small (opposite is small compared to hypotenuse) and cos should be close to 1 (adjacent is almost the hypotenuse)."),

