    ("Can you help me understand modular arithmetic with a real example? Like why do we say -3 ‚â° 2 (mod 5) and how do you actually use that to solve equations?", "Modular arithmetic is ‚Äúclock arithmetic‚Äù: working with remainders after division by a number called the modulus, so mod 5 means we only care about what‚Äôs left over after dividing by 5, and numbers that differ by a multiple of 5 are considered equivalent. We say -3 ‚â° 2 (mod 5) because -3 and 2 are 5 apart: -3 ‚àí 2 = -5, which is a multiple of 5, and you can also see it by adding 5 to -3 until it lands in the usual 0‚Äì4 range: -3 + 5 = 2, so -3 has the same remainder as 2 when dividing by 5. A real example is days of the week: if today is Friday and you go back 3 days you get Tuesday; going back 3 is the same as going forward 4 because -3 ‚â° 4 (mod 7), and both moves land on the same weekday. To use congruences to solve equations, you replace numbers by equivalent, easier ones and use normal algebra rules (addition, subtraction, multiplication) while keeping ‚Äúmod 5‚Äù: for instance solve x ‚àí 3 ‚â° 1 (mod 5) by adding 3 to both sides to get x ‚â° 4 (mod 5), meaning x can be 4, 9, 14, ‚Ä¶; or solve 2x ‚â° 1 (mod 5) by finding the multiplicative inverse of 2 mod 5 (a number that makes 2¬∑? ‚â° 1), and since 2¬∑3 = 6 ‚â° 1 (mod 5), multiply both sides by 3 to get x ‚â° 3 (mod 5), which you can quickly check because 2¬∑3 = 6 leaves remainder 1 when divided by 5."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 06:38 - Category: machine_learning_basics
    ("In intro ML, I keep mixing up training/validation/test sets. Can you explain what each is for and how overfitting shows up in accuracy curves?", "The training set is the data you actually fit the model on, meaning the model‚Äôs parameters are adjusted to reduce error on these examples; the validation set is a separate ‚Äúpractice exam‚Äù you do not train on, used during development to choose things like model type, hyperparameters (learning rate, regularization strength, tree depth, number of layers), and when to stop training (early stopping), because it estimates how well the model generalizes while you‚Äôre still making decisions; the test set is a final ‚Äúsealed exam‚Äù you touch only once at the end, after all choices are locked in, to get an unbiased estimate of real-world performance (if you use the test set repeatedly to make decisions, it stops being a true test and effectively becomes another validation set). Overfitting shows up in accuracy (or loss) curves as a growing gap between training and validation: training accuracy keeps rising (or training loss keeps falling) as the model memorizes details and noise, but validation accuracy plateaus and then often starts to drop (or validation loss starts to rise), indicating worse generalization; in contrast, underfitting looks like both training and validation accuracy staying low and similar, and a well-fit model typically has both accuracies high with only a small gap. A common workflow is to train on the training set, monitor validation performance to pick hyperparameters and stop at the epoch with the best validation score, and then report the final number on the untouched test set."),

