    ("For work-energy theorem, if a block slides down a rough incline, how do you set up the energy equation with friction included? I keep getting the sign wrong.", "Use the work‚Äìenergy theorem as ‚Äúchange in kinetic energy equals the net work done by all forces along the motion‚Äù: Kf ‚àí Ki = Wgravity + Wnormal + Wfriction (and any other forces). For a block sliding a distance s down an incline of angle Œ∏, gravity does positive work along the slope, Wgravity = +mg s sinŒ∏, the normal force does zero work because it‚Äôs perpendicular to the motion, Wnormal = 0, and kinetic friction always does negative work because it opposes the direction of motion, Wfriction = ‚àífk s = ‚àíŒºk N s = ‚àíŒºk mg cosŒ∏ s (since N = mg cosŒ∏ on a simple incline). So the correct setup is Kf ‚àí Ki = mg s sinŒ∏ ‚àí Œºk mg cosŒ∏ s, or equivalently 1/2 m vf^2 = 1/2 m vi^2 + mg s sinŒ∏ ‚àí Œºk mg cosŒ∏ s; the sign ‚Äú‚àí‚Äù in the friction term is not chosen by the coordinate system but by the fact that friction points opposite the displacement, so its dot product with displacement is always negative."),

    # Auto-added 2025-12-26 06:39 - Category: computer_architecture
    ("Computer architecture question: what‚Äôs the difference between cache vs RAM, and how does locality (temporal/spatial) explain why caches help?", "RAM (main memory) is the computer‚Äôs large working storage where programs and data live while the CPU is running, but it has relatively high access latency compared with the CPU‚Äôs speed; cache is a much smaller, much faster memory built on the CPU chip (typically in levels like L1, L2, and often L3) that automatically keeps copies of recently used RAM data so the CPU can get it with far fewer cycles. The key idea is locality: temporal locality means if the CPU uses a piece of data or an instruction now, it‚Äôs likely to use the same thing again soon (for example, variables inside a loop or the next instruction in a tight loop), so keeping it in cache makes those repeated accesses fast; spatial locality means if the CPU accesses one address, it‚Äôs likely to access nearby addresses soon (for example, reading the next elements of an array or the next sequential instructions), so caches fetch and store data in fixed-size blocks called cache lines, bringing in neighboring bytes ‚Äúfor free‚Äù and speeding up the next nearby accesses. Caches help because most real programs repeatedly touch the same small ‚Äúhot‚Äù working set and often walk through memory in predictable patterns, so a high cache hit rate avoids slow trips to RAM, while a miss forces the cache to fetch the needed cache line from RAM, which is much slower."),

