    ("Can you help me test if a series converges: \\(\\sum_{n=1}^{\\infty} \\frac{(-1)^{n}}{\\sqrt{n}}\\)? I‚Äôm not sure when to use alternating series vs p-series.", "To test the series sum from n = 1 to infinity of (-1)^n / sqrt(n), notice it is alternating because of (-1)^n, so the alternating series test (Leibniz test) is the natural first choice: let b_n = 1/sqrt(n), then b_n is positive, decreases as n increases, and lim(n‚Üí‚àû) b_n = 0, so the alternating series converges. However, it does not converge absolutely, because the absolute-value series sum 1/sqrt(n) is a p-series with p = 1/2, and p-series converge only when p > 1, so sum 1/sqrt(n) diverges; therefore the original series is conditionally convergent. A good rule of thumb is: if you see (-1)^n (or cos(nœÄ)) making signs alternate, try the alternating series test for conditional convergence, and separately check absolute convergence by removing the sign and using a p-series or comparison test."),

