    ("We‚Äôre doing gas law problems and I keep messing up units. If 2.0 mol of an ideal gas is at 300 K and 1.5 atm in a 10 L container, what‚Äôs the pressure after compressing to 6 L (same temp)?", "Because the temperature stays the same, use Boyle‚Äôs law (P1V1 = P2V2), which is the constant-temperature form of the ideal gas law, so P2 = P1(V1/V2) = 1.5 atm √ó (10 L / 6 L) = 2.5 atm (to two significant figures). Notice the liters cancel in the ratio, so you don‚Äôt have to convert volume units as long as both volumes use the same unit; also, the given 2.0 mol and 300 K are consistent with the initial state but aren‚Äôt needed for this constant-T pressure change. Quick check: compressing from 10 L to 6 L makes the volume smaller by a factor of 10/6 ‚âà 1.67, so the pressure should increase by the same factor, and 1.5 √ó 1.67 ‚âà 2.5 atm, which matches."),

