    ("what are simple machines? is a can opener one? my teacher said something about levers", "Simple machines are basic tools that make work easier by changing the size of a force you apply, the direction you apply it, or the distance over which you apply it; the six classic simple machines are the lever, wheel and axle, pulley, inclined plane, wedge, and screw. A can opener is not usually just one simple machine by itself, but it uses simple machines inside it: the turning knob is a wheel and axle that helps you apply a small force over a longer distance, and the sharp cutting part acts like a wedge that splits the metal lid; many can openers also use a lever action when you clamp or squeeze the handles to grip and pierce the lid. So your teacher is right to mention levers, because parts of a can opener can work like levers, but overall a can opener is best described as a compound machine, meaning a tool made from two or more simple machines working together."),

