    ("My teacher said there are different reaction types‚Äîhow can I tell if something is synthesis vs decomposition vs replacement?", "You can usually tell reaction types by looking at the pattern of reactants and products. A synthesis (also called combination) reaction is when two or more simpler substances join to make one more complex product: A + B ‚Üí AB, like 2H2 + O2 ‚Üí 2H2O. A decomposition reaction is the opposite: one compound breaks into two or more simpler substances: AB ‚Üí A + B, like 2H2O2 ‚Üí 2H2O + O2 (often needs heat, light, or electricity). Replacement reactions make new substances by swapping partners, so you still end up with more than one product: in single replacement, an element replaces another element in a compound, A + BC ‚Üí AC + B, like Zn + CuSO4 ‚Üí ZnSO4 + Cu; in double replacement, two compounds exchange ions, AB + CD ‚Üí AD + CB, like AgNO3 + NaCl ‚Üí AgCl + NaNO3 (often you can spot these because a solid precipitate, water, or a gas forms). A quick checklist is: if the number of substances goes from many to one, it‚Äôs synthesis; from one to many, it‚Äôs decomposition; if it‚Äôs ‚Äúone element + one compound‚Äù producing ‚Äúone compound + one element,‚Äù it‚Äôs single replacement; and if it‚Äôs ‚Äútwo compounds‚Äù producing ‚Äútwo new compounds,‚Äù it‚Äôs double replacement."),

