    ("I‚Äôm trying to make a little cardboard bridge for tech class‚Äîwhat‚Äôs the best way to prototype it so it doesn‚Äôt collapse?", "Start by prototyping small and fast: sketch your bridge with the span length and where the load will sit, then build a simple test piece of each idea (a beam, a truss side, a deck) from the same cardboard you‚Äôll use in the final so your results are realistic. Cardboard is strongest when you take advantage of its shape, so fold it into tubes, box beams, or I-beams instead of using flat strips, and add triangles (trusses) along the sides because triangles stop the structure from ‚Äúracking‚Äù into a parallelogram; also keep the top and bottom ‚Äúchords‚Äù of the bridge continuous and connect them with diagonal members so the load has a clear path to the supports. Prototype in stages: first test one beam across two books and add weight gradually (coins, washers, or a water bottle) while watching where it bends, then improve that exact weak spot by adding depth (taller beam), adding a second layer with the corrugation running the other direction, or adding gusset plates (small flat patches) at joints; after that, build a half-length bridge section with the same joints and glue/tape you‚Äôll use, because most failures happen at joints, not in the middle of a piece. Use consistent, fair tests: same span, same load position, and add weight slowly while measuring deflection (how far it sags) and noting the failure mode (buckling at the top, tearing at a joint, twisting), then change only one variable at a time so you know what helped. Practical build tips that prevent collapse are to keep the bridge symmetrical, brace against twisting by adding cross-bracing between the two side trusses, avoid long unsupported flat areas, and let glue fully dry (tape can creep under load), and if your class allows it, laminating two pieces with corrugations perpendicular makes a much stiffer deck. When your prototype holds the target load with only a small sag, rebuild the final neatly with the same dimensions and reinforcements, because clean, tight joints and straight members usually matter as much as the design."),

