    ("How does DNA replication work but like in middle school words (and what do helicase and polymerase do)?", "DNA replication is how a cell makes an extra copy of its DNA before it divides, kind of like copying a zipper: first, an enzyme called helicase unzips the DNA by pulling the two strands apart so the ‚Äúletters‚Äù inside are exposed. Each old strand then acts like a template, and DNA polymerase is the enzyme that does the copying by sliding along the strand and adding the correct matching DNA pieces (A matches with T, and C matches with G) to build a new strand. When it‚Äôs done, you end up with two identical DNA molecules, and each one has one original strand and one newly made strand, which helps the cell keep the instructions the same in both copies."),

