    ("In earth science, what causes new species to form? Is speciation just like evolution happening fast?", "New species form through speciation, which happens when one population splits into groups that stop exchanging genes (stop interbreeding) and, over many generations, become genetically and reproductively different enough that they can no longer produce fertile offspring together; the main causes are isolation plus evolutionary change. Isolation can be geographic (a river changes course, a mountain range rises, glaciers advance, islands form, sea level rises and cuts off populations), ecological (groups use different habitats or foods in the same area), behavioral (different mating calls or courtship), temporal (breeding at different times), or genetic (especially in plants, polyploidy can create a new species in a single generation by doubling chromosome sets). Once gene flow is reduced, natural selection, mutation, and genetic drift push the separated groups in different directions, and reproductive barriers build up, such as mismatched mating signals, incompatible sperm and egg, or hybrids that are weak or sterile. Speciation is part of evolution, but it is not simply ‚Äúevolution happening fast‚Äù: it specifically refers to the origin of new species and usually requires the evolution of reproductive isolation, and it can be slow (thousands to millions of years) or sometimes relatively fast in special cases like polyploidy or strong selection in small isolated populations; so it‚Äôs better to think of speciation as the process of populations becoming unable to interbreed, not just a speed setting on evolution."),

