    ("Work-energy theorem confuses me. When do I use W = ŒîK instead of using kinematic equations?", "Use W = ŒîK when the problem is really about how forces change speed through energy, especially when you know (or can compute) the net work done along a path but you don‚Äôt care about the detailed time history. The work‚Äìenergy theorem says the net work done by all forces equals the change in kinetic energy: Wnet = Kf ‚àí Ki = (1/2)mvf^2 ‚àí (1/2)mvi^2, and since work is W = ‚à´F¬∑ds (or Fd cosŒ∏ for a constant force), it naturally connects forces and distances to speeds without needing time. This is often the cleanest choice when forces vary with position (like a spring force), when motion is along a curved path but you only need speed (because work depends on displacement along the path, not on how long it took), when friction or other non-constant forces do work over a distance, or when you‚Äôre asked for a speed after moving a certain distance under a known force. Kinematic equations are best when acceleration is constant (or can be treated as constant) and you want position, time, and velocity relationships like v = v0 + at or v^2 = v0^2 + 2aŒîx; they become awkward or unusable if acceleration changes with position or speed. A quick way to decide is: if you can easily write down a(x) as a constant and you need time or position explicitly, use kinematics; if you can more easily compute work from forces over a distance and you mainly want speed (or a stopping distance), use W = ŒîK. For example, if a block slides 5 m on a rough surface with kinetic friction Œºk, you can find the speed change from Wfric = ‚àíŒºkmgd = ŒîK without ever finding the time, while a spring problem (compressing a spring by x) is much simpler with work/energy because the force changes with x, making constant-acceleration kinematics invalid."),

