    ("For US history: what were the main causes of the Civil War, and can you separate economic vs political vs social causes?", "The U.S. Civil War (1861‚Äì1865) was caused by a long-running conflict over slavery and its expansion, which created deep economic, political, and social divisions between the North and the South; while many issues were involved, slavery was the central one that tied them together. Economically, the South‚Äôs plantation system depended heavily on enslaved labor to produce cash crops like cotton, and many white Southerners feared that restricting slavery‚Äôs expansion or ending it would destroy their wealth and way of life, while the North‚Äôs economy was more diversified (industry, small farms, wage labor) and often supported policies like protective tariffs and internal improvements that many Southerners opposed as favoring Northern interests; these differences sharpened sectional rivalry, but the key economic stake was the value and future of slave labor. Politically, the biggest fights were over whether slavery would be allowed to expand into new U.S. territories and states, because that would determine the balance of power in Congress and the Electoral College; major flashpoints included the Missouri Compromise (1820), the Compromise of 1850 (including the Fugitive Slave Act), the Kansas‚ÄìNebraska Act (1854) and ‚ÄúBleeding Kansas,‚Äù the Dred Scott decision (1857) declaring Congress could not ban slavery in the territories, and the collapse of national political parties into sectional ones, culminating in Abraham Lincoln‚Äôs election in 1860 on a platform opposing the expansion of slavery (not immediate abolition everywhere), which led many Southern leaders to choose secession to protect slavery and what they argued were states‚Äô rights. Socially, the nation was divided by fundamentally different beliefs about race, freedom, and the moral legitimacy of slavery: enslaved people resisted bondage in many ways, abolitionists in the North condemned slavery as immoral, many white Southerners defended it as necessary and feared racial equality and slave uprisings, and violent events like the caning of Senator Charles Sumner (1856) and John Brown‚Äôs raid on Harpers Ferry (1859) intensified fear and hatred; these social tensions made compromise harder and pushed both sides toward viewing the conflict as existential. In short, economic interests, political power struggles, and social/moral conflict all mattered, but they converged on the same core issue‚Äîslavery‚Äîespecially the question of whether it would expand and be protected, which ultimately triggered secession and war."),

