    ("Projectile motion question: If a ball is launched at 20 m/s at 35¬∞, how do I find time of flight and max height? Step-by-step please.", "Assume no air resistance and take g = 9.8 m/s¬≤, and also assume the ball lands at the same height it was launched (that‚Äôs the usual ‚Äútime of flight‚Äù setup unless stated otherwise). First resolve the launch speed into components: the vertical component is v0y = v0 sin(Œ∏) = 20 sin(35¬∞) ‚âà 20(0.5736) ‚âà 11.47 m/s (the horizontal component isn‚Äôt needed for time and max height). For time of flight, use vertical velocity v_y(t) = v0y ‚àí gt; at the top v_y = 0, so 0 = 11.47 ‚àí 9.8 t gives time to peak t_up = v0y/g ‚âà 11.47/9.8 ‚âà 1.17 s, and by symmetry the total time in the air is T = 2 t_up ‚âà 2(1.17) ‚âà 2.34 s. For maximum height above the launch point, use the kinematics relation at the top where v_y = 0: 0 = v0y¬≤ ‚àí 2gŒîy, so Œîy = v0y¬≤/(2g) ‚âà (11.47¬≤)/(19.6) ‚âà 131.6/19.6 ‚âà 6.71 m; you can verify with Œîy = v0y t_up ‚àí (1/2) g t_up¬≤ ‚âà 11.47(1.17) ‚àí 4.9(1.17¬≤) ‚âà 13.4 ‚àí 6.7 ‚âà 6.7 m, consistent. If the landing height is different, you would instead solve the vertical position equation y(t) = v0y t ‚àí (1/2)gt¬≤ (or y(t) = y0 + v0y t ‚àí (1/2)gt¬≤) for the landing time t, and the max height is still found by setting v_y = 0 to get t_up = v0y/g and then plugging into y(t) or using Œîy = v0y¬≤/(2g)."),

