    ("Stats help: What‚Äôs the difference between population vs sample standard deviation and when do I use each?", "Population standard deviation describes the spread of an entire population you fully have data for, and it uses the population mean Œº and divides by N: œÉ = sqrt( Œ£(xi ‚àí Œº)^2 / N ). Sample standard deviation describes the spread in a sample drawn from a larger population, and it uses the sample mean xÃÑ and divides by n ‚àí 1: s = sqrt( Œ£(xi ‚àí xÃÑ)^2 / (n ‚àí 1) ); the n ‚àí 1 is called Bessel‚Äôs correction and it‚Äôs used because xÃÑ is estimated from the same data, which makes the raw average squared deviations (dividing by n) systematically too small, so dividing by n ‚àí 1 makes s^2 an unbiased estimator of the population variance œÉ^2. Use the population standard deviation when your dataset is the whole group you care about (for example, the standard deviation of all 1,200 employees‚Äô salaries at a company if you have every salary), and use the sample standard deviation when your data are only a subset and you want to summarize variability while also supporting inference about the larger population (for example, salaries from 60 randomly sampled employees to learn about all employees). A quick rule of thumb is: if you could in principle collect more observations from the same process and you‚Äôre treating what you have as a sample from something bigger, use s with n ‚àí 1; if there is no ‚Äúbigger‚Äù group because you truly have everyone, use œÉ with N."),

