    ("Can you explain gas law problems in a way that makes sense? Like when to use PV=nRT vs combined gas law, with a quick example.", "Use PV = nRT (the ideal gas law) when the amount of gas can change or is given/asked for, because n (moles) is explicitly part of the relationship; use the combined gas law when you are told it‚Äôs the same sealed sample of gas (so n is constant) and you‚Äôre comparing two sets of conditions, which comes from PV = nRT by canceling nR to get P1V1/T1 = P2V2/T2 (temperatures must be in kelvins). A quick example: a rigid 2.0 L tank contains 0.50 mol of gas at 300 K; what is the pressure? Here n is given, so use PV = nRT: P = nRT/V = (0.50)(0.08206 L¬∑atm/mol¬∑K)(300 K)/(2.0 L) ‚âà 6.15 atm. For combined gas law, imagine a sealed syringe of gas has P1 = 1.0 atm, V1 = 3.0 L, T1 = 300 K and it‚Äôs warmed to T2 = 450 K while the pressure stays 1.0 atm; since it‚Äôs the same gas sample, use P1V1/T1 = P2V2/T2, so V2 = V1(T2/T1) = 3.0(450/300) = 4.5 L; the key decision is ‚Äúdoes n change?‚Äù‚Äîif yes or unknown, go with PV = nRT, and if the same trapped gas is just changing P, V, and/or T between two states, use the combined gas law."),

