    ("Civil War question: what were the main causes (not just \'slavery\') and what was the significance of the Emancipation Proclamation?", "The Civil War (1861‚Äì1865) was caused by a long buildup of conflicts between Northern and Southern states over how the United States would expand and be governed, with slavery at the center but expressed through several connected issues: whether slavery would be allowed to spread into new western territories (a fight that flared after the Mexican‚ÄìAmerican War and led to repeated political crises such as the Missouri Compromise, the Compromise of 1850, the Kansas‚ÄìNebraska Act and ‚ÄúBleeding Kansas,‚Äù and the Supreme Court‚Äôs Dred Scott decision), the balance of political power between free and slave states in Congress, deep economic differences (an industrializing North that generally supported protective tariffs and a plantation-based South tied to cotton exports and enslaved labor), and the argument over states‚Äô rights versus federal authority, especially the claim by many Southern leaders that states could nullify federal actions or secede; these tensions intensified with the rise of the Republican Party, violent conflict over slavery, and Abraham Lincoln‚Äôs election in 1860, after which eleven Southern states seceded and formed the Confederate States of America, leading to war. The Emancipation Proclamation was issued by President Lincoln on January 1, 1863 as a wartime order that declared enslaved people in areas ‚Äúin rebellion‚Äù against the United States to be free; it did not immediately free all enslaved people everywhere (it did not apply to loyal slaveholding border states or to Confederate areas already under Union control), but it was hugely significant because it made ending slavery an official Union war aim, discouraged European powers like Britain and France from supporting the Confederacy, authorized the enlistment of Black soldiers in the Union Army, and set the United States on a clear path toward the permanent abolition of slavery through the Thirteenth Amendment in 1865."),

