    ("I‚Äôm stuck on complex numbers‚Äîhow do I convert (3 4i) into polar form and then compute (3 4i)^5 without messing up the trig?", "To convert 3 ‚àí 4i to polar form, first find its modulus r = sqrt(3^2 + (‚àí4)^2) = sqrt(9 + 16) = 5, and its argument Œ∏ where tan Œ∏ = (‚àí4)/3; since the point (3, ‚àí4) is in quadrant IV, Œ∏ = arctan(‚àí4/3) = ‚àíarctan(4/3) (equivalently Œ∏ = 2œÄ ‚àí arctan(4/3)). So the polar (trig) form is 3 ‚àí 4i = 5(cos Œ∏ + i sin Œ∏) with Œ∏ = ‚àíarctan(4/3). To compute (3 ‚àí 4i)^5, use De Moivre‚Äôs theorem: (r(cos Œ∏ + i sin Œ∏))^5 = r^5(cos(5Œ∏) + i sin(5Œ∏)), giving (3 ‚àí 4i)^5 = 5^5(cos(5Œ∏) + i sin(5Œ∏)) = 3125(cos(‚àí5 arctan(4/3)) + i sin(‚àí5 arctan(4/3))). If you want the exact rectangular form without ‚Äúmessy trig,‚Äù it‚Äôs often easiest to multiply algebraically: (3 ‚àí 4i)^2 = 9 ‚àí 24i + 16i^2 = ‚àí7 ‚àí 24i, then (3 ‚àí 4i)^4 = (‚àí7 ‚àí 24i)^2 = 49 + 336i + 576i^2 = ‚àí527 + 336i, and finally (3 ‚àí 4i)^5 = (‚àí527 + 336i)(3 ‚àí 4i) = (‚àí1581 + 1344) + (2108 + 1008)i = ‚àí237 + 3116i; a quick check is that the modulus should be 5^5 = 3125, and indeed (‚àí237)^2 + (3116)^2 = 9,765,625 = 3125^2, so the result is consistent."),

