    ("In number theory, can you explain modular arithmetic like I‚Äôm not totally lost? Specifically: solve 17x ‚â° 5 (mod 31) and show how you find the inverse.", "Modular arithmetic just means you only care about remainders after dividing by some number (here 31), so 17x ‚â° 5 (mod 31) asks for an x such that 17x and 5 leave the same remainder when divided by 31; the standard way to solve it is to multiply both sides by the modular inverse of 17 modulo 31, meaning a number a with 17a ‚â° 1 (mod 31). To find that inverse, use the extended Euclidean algorithm: 31 = 1¬∑17 + 14, 17 = 1¬∑14 + 3, 14 = 4¬∑3 + 2, 3 = 1¬∑2 + 1, then back-substitute to write 1 as a combination of 17 and 31: 1 = 3 ‚àí 1¬∑2 = 3 ‚àí (14 ‚àí 4¬∑3) = 5¬∑3 ‚àí 1¬∑14 = 5¬∑(17 ‚àí 1¬∑14) ‚àí 1¬∑14 = 5¬∑17 ‚àí 6¬∑14 = 5¬∑17 ‚àí 6¬∑(31 ‚àí 1¬∑17) = 11¬∑17 ‚àí 6¬∑31, so 11¬∑17 ‚â° 1 (mod 31) and the inverse of 17 mod 31 is 11. Multiply the original congruence by 11 to get x ‚â° 11¬∑5 ‚â° 55 ‚â° 24 (mod 31), and you can quickly check: 17¬∑24 = 408, and 408 ‚àí 13¬∑31 = 408 ‚àí 403 = 5, so it really does give remainder 5 modulo 31."),

