    ("My intro ML class is talking about overfitting and regularization‚Äîcan you explain what L1 vs L2 regularization is doing intuitively, and when you‚Äôd pick each?", "Overfitting is when a model fits the training data ‚Äútoo well,‚Äù including noise, so it performs worse on new data; regularization fixes this by adding a penalty for large weights so the model is encouraged to stay simpler. L2 regularization (often called ridge, or ‚Äúweight decay‚Äù) adds a penalty proportional to the sum of squared weights, which gently shrinks all weights toward zero; intuitively it spreads influence across many features but keeps any single weight from getting huge, so it tends to produce stable models that work well when lots of features each have a small effect and when features are correlated (it will usually keep correlated features with similar, smaller weights rather than picking just one). L1 regularization (often called lasso) adds a penalty proportional to the sum of absolute values of the weights, which pushes many weights to exactly zero; intuitively it acts like an automatic feature selector, producing sparse models that are easier to interpret and can help when you believe only a small subset of features truly matters, especially in high-dimensional settings. In practice you‚Äôd pick L2 as a strong default for prediction and stability (common in linear/logistic regression and neural nets via weight decay), pick L1 when you want sparsity and interpretability or suspect many irrelevant features, and pick elastic net (a mix of L1 and L2) when you want some sparsity but also want the stability of L2, particularly with correlated features where pure L1 can behave unpredictably by selecting one feature and dropping the rest."),

