    ("I‚Äôm in calc 2 and infinite series are wrecking me‚Äîhow do you decide which convergence test to use, and can you test ‚àë_{n=1}^‚àû (n^2)/(3^n) as an example?", "When you‚Äôre choosing a convergence test, start by looking for the ‚Äúsignature‚Äù of the series: if terms look like a geometric series (something like r^n or 1/a^n), use geometric ideas; if you see factorials or powers like c^n, the Ratio Test is usually the fastest; if you see n-th powers without exponentials, try p-series/comparison; if it alternates, try the Alternating Series Test (and maybe absolute convergence); if it‚Äôs a complicated expression with n in exponents or roots, the Root Test can be clean; and if it resembles an integral-friendly function, the Integral Test can work. A good default decision rule is: exponentials and factorials usually dominate polynomials, so Ratio/Root tests tend to be decisive. For the example sum from n=1 to infinity of n^2/3^n, the presence of 3^n in the denominator screams ‚Äúexponential,‚Äù so use the Ratio Test: let a_n = n^2/3^n, then a_{n+1}/a_n = [(n+1)^2/3^{n+1}] / [n^2/3^n] = ((n+1)^2/n^2)¬∑(1/3) = (1 + 1/n)^2¬∑(1/3), and as n ‚Üí ‚àû this limit becomes 1¬∑(1/3) = 1/3, which is less than 1, so the series converges absolutely (and therefore converges). Intuitively, even though n^2 grows, 3^n grows much faster, so the terms shrink quickly enough for the infinite sum to settle to a finite value."),

