    ("How did the Supreme Court get the power of judicial review? Like what case started that and what was the reasoning?", "The Supreme Court‚Äôs power of judicial review‚Äîmeaning the authority to declare a law or government action unconstitutional‚Äîwas firmly established in 1803 in Marbury v. Madison, written by Chief Justice John Marshall. The case arose after William Marbury, who had been appointed a justice of the peace at the end of President John Adams‚Äôs term, asked the Court to order the new Secretary of State, James Madison, to deliver his commission; Marbury relied on a section of the Judiciary Act of 1789 that seemed to let the Supreme Court issue a writ of mandamus (a court order telling an official to do a required duty) in a case like his. Marshall‚Äôs reasoning was a careful chain: he said Marbury had a right to the commission and that a legal remedy generally exists when a right is violated, but the specific remedy Marbury wanted could not be granted because the part of the Judiciary Act that gave the Supreme Court original jurisdiction to issue that writ went beyond what Article III of the Constitution allows for the Court‚Äôs original jurisdiction. Because the Constitution is the ‚Äúsupreme law of the land,‚Äù Marshall argued that when an ordinary law conflicts with the Constitution, judges must follow the Constitution, and it is ‚Äúemphatically the province and duty of the judicial department to say what the law is,‚Äù so the Court could treat the conflicting statute as void; in other words, the Court denied Marbury what he asked for but, in doing so, asserted the lasting principle that federal courts can review laws and strike them down when they violate the Constitution."),

