    ("What is ARP spoofing and how to prevent it?",
     "ARP spoofing: attacker sends fake ARP messages to link their MAC with another IP (often gateway), enabling MITM attacks. Prevention: 1) Static ARP entries for critical hosts. 2) Dynamic ARP Inspection (DAI) on switches. 3) DHCP snooping. 4) ARP monitoring tools (arpwatch). 5) VPNs for sensitive traffic. 6) Network segmentation. 7) 802.1X port-based authentication. Detection: duplicate IP-MAC mappings, arpwatch alerts, IDS rules. On Linux: `arp -s gateway_ip gateway_mac`. [Generation: Network security - ARP spoofing]"),
    ("What is a Man-in-the-Middle attack?",
     "MITM attack: attacker intercepts communication between two parties, can read/modify traffic. Techniques: ARP spoofing, DNS spoofing, SSL stripping, rogue WiFi. Prevention: 1) Use HTTPS everywhere (HSTS). 2) Certificate pinning in apps. 3) VPNs on untrusted networks. 4) Verify certificate warnings. 5) ARP/DNS security measures. 6) Network monitoring for anomalies. Detection: unexpected certificate changes, unusual network behavior, ARP table anomalies. Tools for testing: Bettercap, mitmproxy, Ettercap. [Generation: Network security - MITM attacks]"),
    ("How do DDoS attacks work and how to mitigate them?",
     "DDoS types: 1) Volumetric: flood bandwidth (UDP flood, amplification). 2) Protocol: exhaust resources (SYN flood, Ping of Death). 3) Application: target app layer (HTTP flood, Slowloris). Mitigation: 1) CDN/DDoS protection services (Cloudflare, Akamai). 2) Rate limiting. 3) SYN cookies for SYN floods. 4) Anycast for distribution. 5) Blackhole routing for severe attacks. 6) Overprovision bandwidth. 7) WAF for application attacks. 8) BGP flowspec for network-level blocking. Have incident response plan ready. [Generation: Network security - DDoS mitigation]"),
    ("What is a SYN flood attack?",
     "SYN flood: attacker sends many SYN packets with spoofed source IPs, server responds with SYN-ACK and waits, exhausting connection table. Prevention: 1) SYN cookies - don't allocate state until ACK received (`sysctl net.ipv4.tcp_syncookies=1`). 2) Reduce SYN-RECEIVED timeout. 3) Increase backlog queue. 4) Rate limit SYN packets at firewall. 5) Use SYN proxy on load balancer. 6) DDoS mitigation service. Detection: many half-open connections, netstat shows SYN_RECV states. [Generation: Network security - SYN flood attacks]"),

